1. -- {Hello everyone!My name is Vjekoslav Nemec, I am a Candidate Master from Zagreb, Croatia, former Chessable Publishing Manager, and full-time chess coach and course author. I would like to welcome you all to my third-ever Chessable course! After devoting some attention to the White pieces in my previous one (titled Stomp The Sicilian), in this one I have decided to get back to my old habits of analyzing somewhat offbeat openings for the Black pieces in the form of the Alekhine Defence.When I first got into tournament chess(some 10 years ago), the Alekhine was my main opening against 1.e4. I don't really remember how I got the idea to start playing it, but I do remember I spent quite some time studying it with the help of the great book Play the Alekhine by Valentin Bogdanov(and Gambit Publishing).Initially, I justified my choice of a somewhat second-rate opening with the usual 'BuT eVeRyBoDy Is So WeLl PrEpArEd In ThE mAiNliNeS' argument(which is very flawed, in my opinion, but that is a discussion for some other time). But then I started playing it and realized I have pretty reasonable results. Sure, there were some bad losses and bad games. But overall, not many people turned out to be too well prepared against it - especially back in the pre-Chessable era.Thus, I continued playing it exclusively until a certain level(say 2100 FIDE). Once I got there and when it became much more known that this is my main and only opening - people started expecting it more and preparing better. I also experienced a certain crisis since I considered it quite tough to play for the win in certain variations(which is partly true for the Alekhine Defence, but also partly a consequence of my focus on opening preparation while my general chess knowledge is less developed). At some point, I decided to look for sharper options and switched almost exclusively to the Modern Defence.With that being said, the Alekhine was always 'out there somewhere'. I did keep analyzing it and continued playing it every now and then - especially in games with faster time control. Therefore, after I finished my last course, I asked myself: 'Which topic do I want to create a course on next?', 1.e4 Nf6 immediately came to the fore. Especially when Chessable mentioned that they have a new repertoire series titled '100 Repertoires'. Given that the Alekhine is NOT THAT theoretically demanding and relatively easy to pick up, I figured it would be a very good fit.Thus, the contract was signed and work soon started. I was very happy to do a very serious and thorough revision of my 'childhood' opening. I paid special attention to the line selection, as I wanted to go for the most combative variations - without necessarily crossing the threshold of reasonable risk.Even though this took me longer than expected, I can happily say I am very proud of the result. The last few months of analysis have rekindled my love for the opening again and I have started playing it much more frequently - and even using it in some of my own classical games.I do hope that this course will manage to convey my love for this opening and that it will entice you to try it out throughout your own chess journey.In ZagrebJuly 2023Vjekoslav Nemec} 
