[White "1) Introduction"]
[Black "Brief History Of The Alekhine"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6 {The Alekhine Defence was introduced in tournament practice by the fourth world champion Alexander Alekhine when he employed it in the Budapest 1921 tournament. According to the stories, he first observed a lower-rated player employ it in some tournament Alekhine was kibitzing - and it intrigued his imagination. It is not a coincidence it was played at a time when 'hypermodernists' were challenging the traditional school of chess and trying to find creative ways to violate established chess principles.At first glance, it looks crazy to allow the knight to be chased away by the pawns and allow White to establish a strong pawn center, but the situation is not so simple. Similarly as in some other provocative openings (such as the Pirc, or the Modern Defence), Black tries to claim that White has overextended and wants to create counter-attacking chances against the White's center.Ever since Alekhine first essayed it, the Alekhine Defence has been a very frequent guest in chess tournaments - at all levels! As we will see in this course, over the course of the last 100 years quite a few very strong players have employed it occasionally, such as Korchnoi, Larsen, and Shabalov. There are even some grandmasters like Lev Alburt who have employed it almost exclusively throughout their careers. Not to mention that the opening was even essayed in two games in the legendary Spassky - Fischer match by the versatile American.With that being said, in the last 10-15 years, the Alekhine is becoming less of a frequent guest at the top level - at least in the tournaments with classical time control. Even though it was employed in a few games even by Magnus Carlsen (which opening wasn't?), with the rise of modern engines and an increased level of preparation, it is simply considered too risky. Why bother playing it when there are safer options such as the Berlin or the Petrof?With that being said, there is also another side to the coin. While on the one hand, the engines have 'killed' several openings that were considered playable, they have also made some of the variations that weren't deemed viable fully playable. If we take a look at the high correspondence level, the Alekhine is employed every now and then - and Black does usually manage to hold a draw. If we dig very deep into certain opening variations, it is often possible to find very tenable and holdable positions, which probably confirms the notion that chess is, ultimately, a very drawish game.Of course, given that most of us are not top players and that we can't play like the engines, the objective theoretical status of the opening shouldn't concern us too much. At the club level, the Alekhine was - and still is - very much present and more than playable, as indirectly confirmed by the very reasonable results for the Black players employing it in the lichess database.I hope, therefore, that you will continue the tradition started by the fourth World Champion, dear students, and surprise your opponents with this extravagant knight move in your own games.} 
