[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6 {In a day and age where everyone is concerned with computer evaluations and the objective 'correctness' of the opening, it is very difficult to get some people to give some 'second-rate' openings a try.Considering you have already purchased this course, I have a feeling you are someone who is a bit more 'open-minded' and prone to experimenting and trying new things out. But just in case, I have decided to assemble a list of reasons why one should give the Alekhine (Or any opening, really) a shot, as can be found below:  
 It is fun!   It is still relatively rare compared to the other, more mainstream openings such as the Sicilian or 1.e4 e5, so your opponent might not be that well prepared/knowledgable.   It is fun!   If you play the Alekhine (semi)regularly, there are big chances you will have more experience and more 'feeling' for the position compared to your opponent.   It is fun!   It is very flexible, allowing Black to choose different setups and steer the game toward more tactical or positional waters. This allows you to dodge your opponent's preparation more easily and also to adjust the type of game you want to play to your opponent's strengths and weaknesses.   In many variations, White can't just make some natural-looking developing moves and put pressure on our position. In fact, if White plays on auto-pilot, it often allows Black to catch them off-guard and fight for the initiative.   It is fun!   It is objectively not such a bad opening (compared to, say, 1...b6 or 1...a6). As I try to demonstrate within the course, there are maybe only a couple of lines where White can obtain an objective advantage with some very precise opening play - and even in the worst case scenario the resulting positions are either very complicated and double-edged or simply quite holdable for Black.    It is fun!   The Alekhine is very provocative, which may induce your opponent to try and punish it and play in aggressive fashion, providing you with a lot of counterchances later down the road. Despite Fischer's famous claim, I do very much believe in psychology in chess. (And despite his claims, so does Fischer, as otherwise he wouldn't have employed the Alekhine himself in the 1972 World Championship Match)   Oh, have I mentioned it is very fun?} 
