 {When it comes to the creation of opening courses, apart from checking the engines and databases, one of the most important tasks the author should do is also check relevant publications(books and courses)that directly clash with the lines proposed in his/her repertoire.Of course, given the amount of publications out there on the market, it is virtually impossible to cover EVERYTHING that has ever been recommended. Still, while working on this repertoire, I tried to exercise my due dilligence to the best of my ability and check what other renowned authors have recommended against my proposed lines.The discoveries and clashes are presented here.} 1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6The Exchange Variation was the recommendation of Christof Sielecki in both of his famous courses, Keep It Simple 1.0 and Keep It Simple 2.0.5...cxd6A)6.Nc3g67.Be3Bg78.Rc1O-O9.b3This standard variation with the quick mobilization of the queenside was the main recommendation in the course Keep It Simple 1.0. In this course, I have refined the analysis provided by Christof and also given a shocking line he didn't analyze as the alternative.A1)9...d510.c5Nc6I also gave this shocking line, not mentioned in Keep It Simple 1.0, as the alternative.A2)9...e5This was the main move of my analysis.10.dxe5dxe511.Qxd8Rxd812.c5N6d713.Bc4Nc614.Nf3h615.Nb515...Bf8covering the d6 square. Black's position seems to be perfectly healthy in this line.B)6.Nf3g67.h3This venomous variation was Christof's recommendation in the newer version of the repertoire, Keep It Simple 2.0.7...Bg78.Nc3O-O9.Be2Nc610.O-OBf511.d5As I explain in the repertoire, this is already a rare move since it involves a pawn sacrifice. But it is arguably the most dangerous nevertheless.11...Na512.Nd4Naxc413.a4a514.Nxf5gxf5This whole variation is given in Keep It Simple 2.0, and I have also decide not to prolong it any further. While I don't disagree's with Christof's verdict that White is objectively better, I do disagree with the fact that this position is so easy to play. My suspicion is that Black's position is very tenable in practice - and some of my recent online games do demonstrate that verdict.} 
3. d6
4. Nf3 {The Modern variation was recommended in three Chessable courses I checked:   Wesley So's 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire, S.P. Sethuraman's 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire and Chessforlife's Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian.4.c4Nb65.f4The Four Pawns Attack was the main recommendation of several Chessable repertoires, such as Anish Giri's 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire Part 2, Adhiban Baskaran's 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire, Sebastian Mihajlov's The Energetic 1.e4, Gregorz Gajewski's 1.e4 Repertoire Part 2 and Till's Beat The Alekhine: The Four Pawns Attack   Alex Banzea's Ambush 1.e45...dxe56.fxe5Bf57.Nf3e68.Nc3Be79.Be3O-O10.Be2f611.exf6Bxf612.O-ONc6and now:A)13.b3was recommended by Alex Banzea, but here I have recommended the move13...Qe8Not mentioned by Banzea.B)13.Qd2Qe714.Rad1Rad815.Kh1Almost all of the courses mentioned above, apart from Banzea's course, do give this move as the main move in the position (Or, in the case of Till's course, we transpose to this variation later down the road) - which is not surprising, given that it is the first choice of the modern engines. I devoted a lot of attention to it and came up with a fairly fresh concept involving a surprising bishop move.15...h616.h3Bh7This move is not mentioned in the aforementioned repertoires, aside from Anish Giri's Lifetime one. Even though White is objectively somewhat better, the position is extremely fighting and double-edged and Black has quite a few resources. I think it is very tricky to handle it as White in a practical game.} 
4. g6
5. Bc4
5. Nb6
6. Bb3
6. Bg7
7. Ng5
7. e6
8. Qf3
8. Qe7
9. Ne4
9. dxe5
10. Bg5 {This bishop move, which consitutes the mainline, was recommended by Sethuraman and chessforlife.10.dxe5This rare recapture was Wesley So's recommendation in his Lifetime repertoire. Here I analyzed the variation that arises after10...h611.Nf6+Kf812.Qc3Nd513.Bxd5exd514.Be3Na615.O-Oc516.Nxd5Qxe517.Bxc5+Nxc518.Qxc5+All up to this point was mentioned by Wesley in his extensive and deep repertoire. I have concluded that Black has reasonable drawing chances in the resulting games with the bishop pair, despite the missing pawn. While it is somewhat unfortunate, but also quite expected, that deep computer analysis of slightly offbeat openings does find variations where White retains some advantage, I do think it is not 100% relevant for practical play. Even though I have been playing the Alekhine for more than 10 years, I have never encountered this variation over the board.} 
10. Qb4+
11. c3 {11.Nbd2This extremely rare and shocking moves was recommended by Sethuraman in his Lifetime Repertoire. Similarly as with chessforlife's line - while I do think it is objectively quite dangerous for Black, I also do think White needs to play like an engine to prove it. Both me and Sethu gave11...exd412.a3Qa513.Bf6O-O14.Bxg7Kxg715.Qf6+Kg816.Qxd4N8d717.O-O-OQe5and reach a position where the engine claims White has the compensation for the pawn, but where the correct continuation is not perfectly obvious. I think a position such as this one is perfectly playable for Black in practice - after all, when playing the Alekhine we do welcome provoking our opponent with open arms.} 
11. Qa5
12. dxe5 {This rare capture of the e5 pawn was recommended by chessforlife in his course. I have analyzed this position quite deeply and concluded that the line after} 
12. Nc6
13. Nbd2
13. Nxe5
14. Qg3
14. f5 {Is perfectly viable for practical play. White does need to memorize a lot of computer moves such as} 
15. O-O-O {and even if they do, all is not so bleak since I managed to find some high-level correspondence games where Black managed to draw with relative ease.} 
