1. e4
1. Nf6 {Hello dear students and welcome once again to the course. In this Quickstarter Guide chapter, I have selected 10 variations from the entire course that can be used a starting point for learning the Alekhine. The variations were selected on several criteria. Most of the time, I picked them because they are among the variations encountered most commonly in practice. But some of them I picked because they showcase a very typical Alekhine position or an important motif that is worth remembering.The idea is that this "crash course within the course" will provide you with a very quick and easy way to get the basic idea about the lines presented in the theoretical chapters and allow you to start employing the opening in your own games without going through the entire course.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rare 2nd Moves: 2.Nc3 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why a separate chapter is devoted to them. I thought it made a lot of sense to include one trainable in the Quickstarter too, because the following move is encountered very often in practice.} 
2. Nc3 {Out of all the options available to White on move 2, I have always found this one to be the most serious and most annoying to face. White is simply defending the pawn on e4 and bringing the knight into the game, either inviting Black to transpose to a different opening - or to try to cut the Gordian knot by striking in the center at once with d5.} 
2. d5 {Even though this might not be objectively the best move in the position, it is probably the most typical Alekhine move, striking in the center immediately and provoking the opponent once again by inviting them to advance the pawn to e5 once again. Deciding to recommend this move as a main option here was a difficult decision as I personally think it might not be the best, but the problem with the alternatives is that they allow White to transpose to a completely different opening.For example, the move2...d6would be a direct transposition to the Pirc defense after3.d4,while the move2...e6which is also a very creative possibility, allows White to transpose into one of the main positions of the French Defence after3.d4when we hardly have a better move than3...d5Last but not least, I personally think that the move2...e5is the healthiest move in this position, transposing to the Vienna opening. However, as an Alekhine player, you really don't want to be tricked into playing a variation of1.e4e5- even if it is not objectively the most dangerous one. Especially since I would expect people who respond with2.Nc3to be Vienna players and aware of this transposition.Thus, going for the text move seemed like the most logical option, even though it is worth keeping the afore-mentioned possibilities in mind if you want to expand your repertoire someday or surprise your opponent with an uncommon opening choice.} 
3. e5 {Apart from capturing on d5 with the pawn, White can also advance the pawn to e5, attack our knight on f6 and claim that now this advance happens under better circumstances as our knight can't go to d5 any longer.} 
3. Nfd7 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this provocative and challenging retreat, which is almost the exclusive choice of the blitz and bullet specialist Oleksandr Bortnyk - probably the leading Alekhine expert on the planet right now - a player who uses it regularly against the best players in the world. With this move, Black invites the opponent to either go for some sort of the French structure where Black will try to benefit from not playing the move e7-e6, or to immediately sacrifice the pawn with the push of the e5 pawn.The other possibility in this position is the move3...d4, which I used to play a lot in the past. The problem, however, is that after4.exf6dxc35.fxg7we are forced to go into a cheerless endgame that arises after5...cxd26.Qxd2Qxd27.Bxd2Bxg7where due to our worse pawn structure (3 pawn islands) we can only be worse and have to defend without any realistic winning prospects. Even though the results for both variations aren't too bad for Black according to the lichess database, I have personally never enjoyed playing this endgame.} 
4. e6 {First of all, let's ask ourselves - what happens if White tries to exploit the positioning of our knight on d7 (that is preventing the bishop on c8 from influencing the e6 square) by pushing the pawn to e6. This is a very typical pawn sacrifice with the help of which White tries to create weak doubled pawns on the semi-open e-file and disrupt Black's coordination and development and it needs to be taken seriously - especially since it is the third most common move played in this position.} 
4. fxe6 {Of course, Black more-or-less has to capture this pawn and accept the challenge.} 
5. d4 {The only move that really requires some analysis in this position. White clamps down on the position and tries to prevent the liberating e5 break. White's idea is to play slowly and obtain total control over the position with Nf3, Bd3, etc. They claim that the doubled e-pawns are a long-term weakness that is also hindering Black's natural development in this position. Now the question is - how should Black go about completing the development?} 
5. c5 {This move was recommended by Bryan Tillis in his excellent course on the Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. When I was first analyzing the position, I realized this is not the only possibility here and that5...g6might be a clever move order, keeping the option of playing for the Nc6-e5 plan. As a matter of fact, I completed all the analysis and annotations for this option and found no problem with it.However, then I realized that in the line after4.d4c55.e6is very much possible, when after5...fxe6we actually transpose to the text variation - but with White managing to avoid the 5...g6 option.I have to admit this realization made me very tilted, but I couldn't simply ignore this transposition. This is why I needed to go back to the drawing board and recommend the text move instead of 5...g6 in this position, in order to avoid having to learn two different setups against two different move orders.} 
6. dxc5 {The most critical option. White voluntarily removes the pawn from the center, but instead intends to control the central squares with the pieces and claims it is very difficult for Black to finish the development and obtain any sort of coordination between the pieces.If White tries to ignore the tension and play, say,6.Nf3then Black can follow the same scheme of development and go for6...g6when7.h4Bg78.h5Nc6creates a lot of pressure against the d4 pawn and probably forces a transposition to the game continuation with9.dxc5I should, perhaps, also mention that6.Bd3is tricky, as we shouldn't fall for6...cxd47.Qh5with a quick mate, but instead play6...g6when it turns out that White has committed the bishop to d3 a bit prematurely.} 
6. g6 {But this is my suggested deviation from the Tillis' course. I feel it is imperative for Black in this position to bring the bishop to g7 as soon as possible (which is why I also considered starting with 5...g6).Tillis recommended6...Nc6,but I am not 100% sure of the position that arises after7.Nf3g68.Nd4as now8...Nxc5is not possible with the knight on c6 due to9.Nxc6bxc610.Qd4winning. Black's position might still be playable, but given the choice, I would rather prevent White from having such options, especially since I don't think the early advance of the h-pawn is something we should be afraid of.Also note that6...Nxc5is bad as after7.Nf3White has a nice central control and can play Bf4 next. We don't really want to recapture on c5 too early and should instead focus on developing more pieces.} 
7. h4 {This is probably the most testing and also the most human continuation, trying to immediately exploit the target on g6 created by Black on the previous move. The idea is, obviously, to follow up with h5 and then claim that the g6 pawn will be a target. However, as it turns out, Black can simply ignore this idea and continue with the development, as even if we lose the g6 pawn with a check, it is not the end of the world.If White doesn't play in such an aggressive manner and tries to play natural moves such as7.Nf3Bg78.Be3Nc69.Qd2we can actually castle kingside as after9...O-O, Rxf3 and d4 is already a massive threat, while we also have ideas of Nde5, exchanging some pieces. Even though this position looks dangerous for Black, our bishop on g7 is quite powerful and we do have an extra pawn, so all three results are possible.} 
7. Bg7 {The natural move, developing the bishop to the powerful diagonal and also covering the h8 rook, in anticipation of White's next move.} 
8. h5 {The most logical follow-up to the previous move. As they say, once you have said A, you have to say B.} 
8. Nc6 {Still ignoring the situation on the kingside and continuing to bring more and more pieces into the action.} 
9. hxg6
9. hxg6
10. Rxh8+
10. Bxh8
11. Bd3 {And now comes the critical moment. White is threatening to take the pawn on g6 with check, which would be the triumph of their plan. But as it turns out, we are not at all concerned about this pawn and can play more aggressively instead.} 
11. Bxc3+ {A very creative and combative move. It looks crazy to give up such a nice bishop on g7, but given that it creates tripled isolated pawns on the c-file, the decision to give it up can be justified.It has to be said that this is not a must in this situation and that the more passive11...Nf8is also possible.} 
12. bxc3
12. Qa5 {This is the point of Black's play! Now the pawns on c3 and c5 are under attack and we have also vacated the d8 square for the king. It looks crazy to give up the g6 pawn just like that, but we will surely get at least one of the pawns on the c-file back.} 
13. Bxg6+
13. Kd8 {This is actually quite a standard procedure in positions where one side has a massive pawn chain in the center. The king feels quite secure behind the pawns on d5, e6 and e7 as they are very difficult to undermine - and there are also quite a few pieces around the king as well. Black will pick up some pawns next and is also ahead in development.Some ideas include Nxc5-Ne4 or even Nde5. The bishop on c8 can potentially be developed via b6-Ba6 and the king will feel quite secure on d7 for a while. The outcome of the game is completely unclear and both sides have winning (or losing) chances - which is precisely what an Alekhine player that employs this line is looking for.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves: 3.Nc3 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5 {This is the most natural and most common move, attacking the knight on f6, which you will encounter in the majority of your games.} 
2. Nd5 {The most natural reply, trying to keep the knight in the center of the board. It is true that the knight can be chased away further with the advance of the c-pawn, but   A) That is precisely the point of Black's provocative opening, as we are claiming that after the premature advance of the pawns, the opponent's structure will be vulnerable to counterattacks,and  B) Other knight movers such as2...Ng8or2...Ne4are hardly any better.Now, the main moves for White naturally involve moving one of the central pawns with3.c4or3.d4. But before we get there, let's take a moment to investigate some other options available to White at this particular moment. I believe there are two moves that need to be at least mentioned - the development of the bishop with3.Bc4and the development of the knight with3.Nc3We will do so in the current chapter.} 
3. Nc3 {Even though White most commonly pushes the c- or d-pawn forward on move 3, there are some alternatives that are examined in a separate chapter. Since this is by far the most serious 3rd move option at White's disposal, I thought it made sense to devote one trainable to it in the Quickstarter guide. White immediately challenges the knight on d5 and invites us to take on c3, when they would like to open up the d-file and the diagonal for their c1 bishop and then quickly go for the plan involving the queenside development.When I came back to the Alekhine after a long hiatus, this variation gave me problems, especially in games with faster time control.} 
3. Nxc3 {After analyzing various possibilities, I have concluded that there is nothing obviously wrong with this natural move, capturing the knight on c3 and doubling our opponent's pawns. It was also recommended by NM Bryan Tillis in his course The Dark Knight Rises here on Chessable.If you are searching for an alternative, the move3...e6was recommended by GM Roland Pruijssers in his excellent Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine course here on Chessable. But I am not 100% sure how much I like the position arising after4.Nxd5exd55.d4d66.Nf3- it seems to me it is a bit difficult for Black to generate real winning chances in this symmetrical structure, although Black has also probably equalized with ease.} 
4. dxc3 {The more common recapture in this position. White opens up the d-file and the diagonal for the c1 bishop and intends to quickly develop the forces with Bf4-Qd2 and then castle long. This idea of doubling the c-pawns in order to aim for rapid development is very standard and known from some other openings, such as the Nimzo-Sicilian1.e4c52.Nf3Nf63.e5Nd54.Nc3!?or the Vienna after1.e4e52.Nc3Nf63.f4d54.fxe5Nxe45.Qf3Nxc36.dxc3!?or the Petroff after1.e4e52.Nf3Nf63.Nxe5d64.Nf3Nxe45.Nc3Nxc36.dxc3} 
4. d6 {So how should Black best deal with White's idea of rapid development? Well, what we want to do is try to fight against the pawn on e5 that is providing White with a nice space advantage. If we manage to pressure that pawn or force White to make the exchange on d6, we should be reasonably happy as then our pieces would get more breathing room and our development would be more fluid.} 
5. Nf3 {The most natural move, defending the pawn and developing a knight. Note that5.exd6is precisely what we are aiming for as after5...cxd6(or even 5...Qxd6) we are more than happy with the elimination of the e5 pawn. We would also be more than happy to exchange queens and go in an endgame - as there White's worsened pawn structure might become a much more relevant factor. Note that here we are benefiting from having the knight on b8 as after6.Bd3we have6...Nd7with ideas of Ne5 and Nc5, eliminating the bishop on d3 and forcing the queen trade.Also - I don't really see a point in starting with5.Bc4as then after5...Nc6White either has to play6.Nf3transposing to text, or concede the pawn on e5 and play6.exd6Qxd6when Black has no problems as we have managed to eliminate the pawn on e5 which was restricting us severely.} 
5. Nc6 {A logical move, developing the knight and increasing the pressure on the e5 pawn, asking White a question - how do they want to deal with the increasing tension in the center?} 
6. Bb5 {This pinning move, trying to pressure the knight on c6 and indirectly defend the pawn on e5, is by far the most common move in the position - and the one you are very likely to encounter in your own games. Note that White should develop the bishop to b5 if they want to start by developing the light-squared bishop, as6.Bc4is not at all problematic as we can simply capture on e5 with6...dxe5and after7.Qe2play very greedily and try to preserve the pawn with7...f6Following8.Be3e69.Rd1we can play9...Bd6and are very solid, while preserving the extra pawn. Of course, White's play can be improved, but I don't see why they would allow us to capture on e5 just like that.} 
6. a6 {After analyzing the position for a bit, I realized I really like this move, attacking the bishop on b5 and basically forcing it to capture the knight on c6. In his course, Tillis only analyzed6...Bd7, but I feel this gives White precisely what they want as after7.Qe2a68.Bd3they are ready to go long castle next and create some attacking chances, while controlling the center thanks to the pawn on e5.Note, on the other hand, that the engine once again mentions the move6...Qd7as a possibility, but I really can't bring myself to recommend this move in a position and then explain this choice in human language.Finally, it has to be added that going for6...dxe5which was the prescription against 6.Bf4, is not that good here, as after7.Qxd8Kxd88.Bxc6bxc69.Nxe5our position is in ruins, our structure is horrible, the king is not ideal on d8 and we are losing a pawn due to the double attack. Not to be recommended.} 
7. Bxc6+ {Of course, White has to capture on c6 as otherwise, they would lose the pawn on e5 for nothing.} 
7. bxc6 {We have allowed our opponent to double our c-pawns, but in return, we have eliminated their bishop pair and also obtained the open b-file for the rook. Next, we are going to play Qd7 and f6 almost irrespective of what White does - and this combative plan was what attracted me to this variation in the first place.} 
8. O-O {This is the most logical and most common move in the position - but I think we are very happy when we manage to avoid setups with castling long in these positions where our opponent has voluntarily doubled the c-pawns earlier in the game. With that being said, any other moves would be met in a very similar fashion as the text move.For example, after8.Bf4we go8...Qd79.Qe2f6,just as after8.Be3Qd79.Qe2f6In either case, one of the possibilities is to play Qe6, e.g.10.O-O-OQe6when White is more or less forced to take on d6 and after11.exd6cxd6we are very happy to have our pawns and undoubled and to still have the bishop pair. Even if we are behind in development, we are claiming we are very solid and that there isn't an immediate way for White to exploit this factor.} 
8. Qd7 {My proposed solution. It looks a little bit artificial to block in the bishop on c8, but with this move, we are covering the e6 square and the c6 pawn and basically preparing to play f6 in the near future, given it is not so good to play it here due to8...f69.exf6gxf6when10.Nd4attacks the pawn on c6 and also threatens Qh5 ideas - which is definitely not very desirable. We will develop the bishop via b7 or a6 later in the game, anyway.I chose this idea in this particular position due to its universality - as we have seen, it is very much viable against other setups for White.} 
9. Re1 {Preventing Black's idea. Note that any other move would be met with the advance of the f-pawn, such as9.Bf4f6or9.Qe2f6} 
9. e6 {A necessary inclusion, preventing White from sticking the e6 pawn into our throat, as would be the case after9...f610.e6Now we are basically ready to play f6 on the next move.} 
10. Bf4 {A logical developing move. Other moves are met in a very similar manner.} 
10. f6 {This looks very 'ugly' at first glance and it also violates one of Ben Finegold's principles (never play 'f6'), but it is actually a very combative and sound idea. Black does everything possible to get rid of the strong pawn on e5 and emphasizes that White doesn't really have a way of getting at the king behind the central bulwark, due to the fact that White has no pawns to use as battering rams in the center.} 
11. exf6
11. gxf6 {And even though our construction with the 5 pawns on the 6th rank looks strange and loose and even though we apparently haven't yet developed a single piece - we are already somewhat better as our pawn mass in the center is very powerful. We will play e5-Be7-O-O next and easily catch up with the development - and there is nothing White can do to stop us. I would take the Black pieces here gladly as I feel our play is much easier!} 
