[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rare 4th moves after 3.d4: 4.Bc4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {So far in this course, we have covered all the possible variations that can arise via the 3.c4 move order (Which can in many cases transpose to the variations that arise via the 3.d4 move order, as we have seen in the case of the Four Pawns Attack or the Exchange Variation). In this varaition, we will cover the scenario where White refrains from moving the c-pawn early in the game and instead opts for the natural looking 3. d4. This is by far the most common variation you will encounter - both according to the lichess and masters' databases.The logic is simple - White refrains from advancing too many pawns early in the opening and overextending the forces, but tries to develop in a more harmonious and natural fashion, keeping the option of advancing the c-pawn in reserve. For a while, this has been regarded as the most critical test of the Alekhine defence. And even if the modern engines prefer the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I am also more afraid of, personally), 3.d4 is a very big and important line that needs to be taken seriously and studied in some detail.} 
3. d6 {The standard Alekhine response, creating the tension in the center and 'attacking' the e5 pawn. Now White can play4.c4and transpose to the Exchange Variation after4...Nb65.exd6or to the Four Pawns Attack after4...Nb65.f4, although the most common continuation is4.Nf3leading to the starting point of the Modern Variation. It will be analyzed later in the Quickstarter and in the final theoretical chapter of this course, but before we get there, it is necessary to complete the picture by mentioning other, rare 4th moves available to White in this position. In the Quickstarter Guide, we will mention the most common one.} 
4. Bc4 {Out of all the 4th moves considered in this chapter, this developing bishop move, hitting the d5 knight and also potentially eyeing the f7 pawn, is by far the most serious. It leads to a somewhat rare variation of the Alekhine defence that is not particularly dangerous, but which can be tricky to handle over the board without any prior analysis.} 
4. Nb6 {Almost an automatic move in the Alekhine defence when the bishop appears on c4 - we retreat the knight with the gain of tempo. In this particular case, since White refrained from developing the knight to f3, we will be able to capture on e5 on the very next move.} 
5. Bb3 {Of course, the bishop wasn't developed to c4 to immediately depart from the a2-g8 diagonal, so this is the only move really worth analyzing.} 
5. dxe5 {As mentioned above and as we have seen over and over agian in this chapter - since White refrained from reinforcing the e5 pawn on the previous move, we are more than happy to capture it, open the d-file and create a potential target on e5.} 
6. Qh5 {The main move in this position, eyeing the f7 pawn and also adding some control to the e5 square.} 
6. e6 {Dealing with the threat to the f7 pawn and restricting the bishop on b3. It is true that this also locks our bishop on c8, but there is no better way to deal with the threat to the f7 pawn. Besides, since White has violated the opening principles and moved the queen this early in the game, we can afford to play 'suboptimally' too, as we will have time to develop the bishop via d7 later in the game.} 
7. dxe5 {Recapturing on e5 with the pawn is the only sensible move, as7.Qxe5Nc6is not to be recommended.} 
7. a5 {As I mentioned in my notes to the 6.Qxd1 and 6.Qf3 variations, with the bishop on b3 and the knight on b6, I really like this thematic advance of the a-pawn, trying to gain some space on the queenside while harassing the bishop on b3 at the same time. a4 is now a very serious threat and White has to react to it.} 
8. a4 {The most common reaction in this position. White stops the a-pawn in its tracks and refuses to give Black more ground on the queenside. This is very sensible, but the problem is that now the pawn on a4 is a potential target. Black can start exploiting this immediately with the following knight move.Other ways of handling this position by White are given in the respective theoretical chapter.} 
8. Na6 {Slightly more flexible than going via the d7 route as it doesn't lock the bishop on c8 in, although both moves are more than fine. The knight is immediately heading toward the c5 square to put pressure on White's vulnerable queenside.} 
9. c3 {White can't really prevent the idea of Nc5 as9.Be3is met with9...Nd5and then Nc5 next, while the text move is even worse as it fatally weakens the d3 square.} 
9. Nc5
10. Bc2
10. Nd3+ {And now Black will get an even better version of the dominating position with the queen on d3 as White's light-squared bishop also gets eliminated along the way. Black is already positionally winning here.} 
