[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Four Pawns Attack #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {When it comes to the Four Pawns Attack which will be examined in this chapter, it is completely irrelevant whether White moves the c-pawn or the d-pawn first, as the same position is also reached after3.c4Nb64.d4d65.f4} 
3. d6
4. c4
4. Nb6
5. f4 {After we have covered some early deviations in earlier trainables, it is now time to turn our attention to more mainline options. We will start by examining the so-called Four Pawn Attack, featuring the early advance of the f-pawn on move 5.White's intention is clear - since we are refraining from contesting the center, they are trying to secure as much space as possible by fortifying their big and massive pawn chain, with the aim of using that very space advantage to slowly suffocate us - or even launch a direct attack on our king, depending on how we react.This attempt to basically directly refute the Alekhine defense has always been regarded as very dangerous - but this is especially so in our modern times, due to the following:   A) The variation is generally quite forcing and direct which makes it quite suitable for very deep computer analysis   B) The variation is objectively quite good and approved by these modern engines, essentially giving White a clear plus in almost all variations.It is not coincidence that no less than five Chessable authors - Giri, Adhiban, Mihajlov, Gajewski and till ( A community author and a master-level player ) give it as the main recommendation in their respective courses.On the other hand, even though it is a very challenging variation from the theoretical viewpoint, it has to be said that its practical results are far less impressive. According to the lichess database, Black has a positive score almost irrespective of the choice on move 5. Sure, any sort of statistic like this has to be taken 'cum grano salis' as it doesn't control for any sort of variable (say, the strength of the player). But I do think a lot of it has to be attributed to the character of the whole variation - such sharp and critical variations definitely involve some risk for the first player. Unless you are super-well prepared or a super-strong player, you can very easily slip and make the wrong move - which is often all Black needs to take over the initiative and punish you for your brave opening choice.Thus, working on the four pawns attack lead to some sort of conundrum - on one hand you are constantly looking at computer evaluations that are very much in White's favour, but on the other hand, I knew that the majority of these evaluations are not 100% relevant for practical play ( Something similar happened as I was working on my course on the Modern defence, although you could make an argument that the Four Pawns Attack is a more narrow battlefield than 1.e4 g6 ). I tried to take this into account when choosing my recommendation in this course and I have tried to find a good balance between what is objectively the best - and what I think can pose significant practical problems!} 
5. dxe5 {After very long consideration, I have decided to go for this typical 'Alekhine' capture on e5. However, whereas in other variations of the Alekhine defence this move is very helpful when it comes to destabilizing the White's center, this is not the case here as White has moved the f-pawn forward and the center is reinforced. Furthermore, once we capture on e5, White will not be forced to take with the d-pawn or the knight from f3, but can actually utilize the pawn on f4, open the f-file and keep the central pawn chain intact.With all that being said, you might be wondering - but why do we then take on e5 after all? That is a very good question that can't be explained very simply. The main point behind the early capture is to open up the d-file and make the pawns on e5 and d4 a little bit loose. Black subsequently wants to move the knight to c6, and after the exchange on e5, it is very hard for White to play d5 as the e5 pawn is hanging.For example, if Black tries to play with the immediate5...Bf5then6.Nc3e67.Nf3Nc6?!is faulty, as White has the option of going8.exd6cxd69.d5An idea like this one wouldn't have been available if the pawn was on e5 and unprotected, but here it works like a charm.That is why after5...Bf56.Nc3e67.Nf3, Black probably doesn't have anything better than transposing to our variation with7...dxe5With that being said, the line involving the capture on e5 is not the only way for Black to handle the Four Pawns Attack. In his Lifetime Repertoire, GM Roland Pruijssers recommended a very interesting variation starting with5...g6!?, with the main idea being6.Nc3Bg77.Be3Be6!?It is definitely a little bit less standard and creative, although the engine is not very optimistic about Black's chances after8.d5Since I personally never played this variation myself, I didn't feel like I have that much to add to Pruijssers' analysis anyway, so feel free to investigate this on your own if you are searching for an alternative!Last but not least, one hobby horse of mine that I like to play in blitz games is the move5...g5- which was employed by Magnus on a few (trolling) occasions - but needless to say, such a move is definitely not solid enough and way too crazy to be a serious recommendation in any repertoire.} 
6. fxe5 {Of course, recapturing with the f-pawn is THE main point of White's entire aggressive play. Going for6.dxe5is very faulty as Black would very much love to exchange the queens in a position with a lack of space. Moreover, after6.dxe5Qxd17.Kxd1White also loses castling rights and we are already winning after the natural move like7...Bf5,due to our major lead in development. The fact that White only advanced the pawns works against them as the brave peasants have left a lot of weaknesses behind!} 
6. Bf5 {After some contemplation, I have decided to recommend this move, developing the bishop to the natural square and not yet determining the position of the knight on b8. The downside of this move is that now it makes no longer sense to pin the knight on g4, but I personally don't think it is such a huge loss - because even if we don't move the bishop White wouldn't allow us to play Bg4 in one go. On the other hand, as we will soon see, there are some variations where it is super useful to not block the pawn on c7 and keep the option of playing c5, if required.I think this is the most flexible move and that its point might not be fully familiar to your opponents. For example, it was not at all considered by Adhiban in his 1.e4 LifetimeRepertoire, although ever-so-diligent Anish Giri did include it in his.With that being said, the main move here is the move6...Nc6Here, the idea is to be able to reply to7.Nf3with7...Bg4in one move, pressuring the center.However, after6...Nc6White will not oblige so easily and will play something like7.Be3when we hardly have anything better than to transpose to the main variation after7...Bf58.Nc3e69.Nf3with9...Be7, because in this exact position,9...Bb4has no purpose with the c-pawn blocked, and the variation with9...Qd7, intending long castling, is just too risky for Black (although there are some tricks that might work well - especially in faster time controls.).As we will see, against a very specific move order by White, even after6...Bf5we will transpose to the very same, main variation of the line. However, with 6...Bf5, we do land some mines along the way, which is why I ultimately decided to prefer it over 6...Nc6.- As for some other possibilities, the variation after6...c57.d5g6actually does super well in the lichess database, as Black wins 55% of the games. However, I do think that this is objectively quite dubious and I couldn't bring myself to recommend it in this course.} 
7. Be3 {One of the reasons why I am quite attracted to the variation with 6...Bf5 is this natural development of the bishop, defending the d4 pawn. As we have seen in the notes above, this move is the main response to 6...Nc6, as it makes a lot of sense to reinforce the center there. However, in this particular instance, this move is not very good as it allows Black to demonstrate why the knight was not developed in front of the c-pawn back on move 6.} 
7. e6 {A typical Alekhine move, opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop! Usually, this piece goes to e7 in these lines, but as we will see, here we have more ambitious plans! Also note that in some cases, now the Qh4 check might be on the agenda - especially if White plays a slow, non-developing move.} 
8. Nc3 {A standard Alekhine move, developing the knight and not yet committing the other knight to f3. White also adds more control to the d5 square, so advancing the c-pawn would now be met with d5.} 
8. Bb4 {At this point, Black can transpose to the mainline of the variation with either8...Be7or8...Nc6.However, I think that the text move, pinning the knight on c3, threatening to double the pawns and intending to play c5 next, is not only better, but also much more practical, as in the resulting position Black will end up having a considerable pressure on the White center. Furthermore, since now the e4 square is once again available to Black, Qh4 is an idea once again.} 
9. Nf3 {A natural developing move that also covers the h4 square. If9.a3then9...Bxc310.bxc3Qh4is very annoying for White. Remember this Qd8-Qh4 idea as it often comes useful in these positions if White is foolish enough to allow it.} 
9. c5 {The entire point of Black's play! Instead of moving the knight in front of the pawn, Black strikes in the center with c5 at the moment where White has insufficient control over the d5 square due to the pin on the knight on c3. In the Alekhine, Black has to try and undermine the center and here it is done in a very energetic and brutal fashion!} 
10. a3 {The best reply for White in this position, posing an immediate question to the bishop and prompting an exchange on c3, when the d4 pawn will acquire some additional protection. Moving the d-pawn is once again not particularly good, while not doing anything and continuing the development with something like10.Be2allows Black to take on d4 after, say,10...O-O11.O-Ocxd4when after12.Nxd4Bg6we have a very non-standard position in which White has the open f-file and more space due to the e5 pawn, but at the same time that e5 pawn is isolated and weak. I think Black is very close to full equality, but more importantly - I feel the position is much easier to play in practice - which is exactly what the Alekhine player is looking for.} 
10. Bxc3+ {Black is more-or-less forced to take, because after10...Ba5the pressure on the White center is significantly reduced because the c-pawn can virtually never capture on d4 due to b4, winning the piece. Black would have to lose time to move the knight from b6 and then potentially capture on d4, but this is obviously not very desirable.} 
11. bxc3
11. Nc6 {And now we have a very non-standard position where White has the bishop pair and more space, but where we have considerable pressure on the center and the structural advantage. Next, we want to castle and then try to pressure the pawns on the c-file with moves such as Na5-Rc8-cxd4-Nxc4. The engine still prefers White, but I don't think that this evaluation necessarily corresponds to practical play as Black has a clear plan ahead while White is the one who has to be creative and solve non-standard problems.Just in case, I did examine two continuations. The more natural12.Be2is apparently not particularly problematic due to12...O-O13.O-OBg6when Black is ready to start going for the aforementioned plan with Rc8, Na5 and so on.On the other hand,12.Bd3seems to be a better move, although it is really strange for a human to offer this exchange when they have the bishop pair and more space. However, the idea is to get the queen into play in one go and potentially eliminate the important defender of the kingside, so Black should not oblige and go for12...Bg4instead, pressuring the center and intending to capture on d4 next. White has some ultra-sophisticated prophylactic move in the form of13.Bf2here, with the idea of13...cxd414.cxd4Nxd415.c5!when Black can't really attack the bishop one3.Nevertheless, after13.Bf2Black can continue pursuing the plan with13...Rc8and suddenly the next move for White is not at all so obvious. I definitely wouldn't mind having this position in a practical game.} 
