[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange variation #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this trainable, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. exd6 {The capture on d6 leads to the so-called Exchange variation. White voluntarily releases the tension in the position and gets rid of the pawn on e5 that was securing them a lot of space. On the other hand, this pawn often turns out to be Black's main source of counterplay, so White is trying to make an argument that this exchange eliminates a potential target and provides White's center with some stability.Even though this solid approach is not the most critical or ambitious, it is very annoying to face in practice because it makes it quite difficult to play for the win (I have often jokingly referred to it as the 'Alapin of the Alekhine').} 
5. cxd6 {This is a big and important crossroad as it is possible to capture ond6with both pawns. The move5...exd6is generally regarded as the soundest and most solid way to deal with the exchange variation, but I have always found the resulting positions a bit dull, due to the symmetrical pawn structure. In this course, I will be, therefore, recommending the more ambitious, combative and risky approach, involving the capture with the c-pawn, simply because it leads to a more imbalanced position with an asymmetrical pawn structure.Also note that we can't really capture on d6 with the queen in 'Scandi' style, since5...Qxd66.c5Qe67.Be2is not very pleasant as our pieces are not really standing very well.} 
6. Nc3 {In this position, White has a vast choice, as there are many possible move orders available at our opponent's disposal. However, most commonly, White decides either to start by developing the kingside pieces and castling quickly or by developing the queenside pieces and trying to prevent Black's counterplay on that side of the board before proceeding with the kingside operations.Sure, these two plans/ schemes can be mixed and there are many move orders that lead to transpositions, but in principle, we will be focusing our attention on the moves6.Nc3and6.Nf3Not only because they follow the golden opening principle (Knights before bishops) or because this is the 100 Repertoires - but also because other moves such as6.Be3,6.Bd3or6.Be2are very likely to transpose.With that being said, you might be wondering - what exactly is the point of the text move? What are the benefits of starting with the queenside development? Well, as we will soon see, Black does have some ideas that involve generating counterplay in the center and on the queenside, so White quickly tries to mobilize the c1 bishop, the knight on b1 and the rook on c1 to avoid any issues. This is a very legitimate and serious way of handling this asymmetrical variation of the Exchange variation, so we should know what to do about it and how to handle it.} 
6. g6 {Of course, fianchettoing the bishop is the central theme of this entire chapter and we indeed go for it here, as well. Now White has quite a few options at their disposal.} 
7. Be3 {Last but not least, the most common move played in conjunction with 6.Nc3 is this move, developing the bishop and aiming to quickly mobilize the queenside with Rc1 and b3 next. The idea is to prevent any possible counterplay against the c4 and d4 pawns by removing the rook from the long diagonal and playing b3 before proceeding to develop the kingside.It has to be said that, apart from the moves covered so far, moves such as7.h3,7.Nf3,7.b3and even7.Bg5are also quite popular according to the lichess database, but they either transpose into lines examined via a different (6.Nf3) move order, or to the lines examined here (say, in the case of 7.b3). That is why they will not be covered separately.} 
7. Bg7 {The most natural move, fianchettoing the bishop and preparing to castle.} 
8. Rc1 {The point behind White's setup. White realizes that Black's idea is to play some sort of 8...d5 and 9...Nc4 combo (as is usually the case when White plays Be3 in the Alekhine) and takes measures against it.Moves such as8.Nf3or8.Be2are barely played and are also most likely to transpose to 6.Nf3 lines, so they will not be examined separately.} 
8. O-O {We have to castle here before doing anything else. In case you are wondering, the immediate8...d5doesn't quite work as after9.c5Nc410.Bxc4dxc4White has11.Qa4,picking up the pawn on c4 with a gain of time.} 
9. b3
9. e5 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this thematic central strike as the main option in this repertoire. This move was mentioned by both Roland Pruijssers and Bryan Tillis in their respective Alekhine repertoires here on Chessable, but it was dismissed as a bit too dry/non-combative. And while it is true that this allows White to exchange the pawns on e5 and essentially go for an endgame, I will try to make an argument that this endgame is not at all so simple or 'dry' as it looks at first glance.Besides, I am not 100% sure whether Black has a worthy alternative in this position. Both Tillis and Pruijssers gave9...Bf5as their main recommendation, but it seems to me that10.h3borderline refutes this attempt, as the main idea of10...d5is now met with11.g4Bd712.c5It is true that this whole h3-g4 is not the most easy to find over-the-board, but it is not that difficult to find at home when analyzing with the engine.On the other hand, the most common move in the position according to the lichess database is9...Nc6, but after10.d5White simply obtains a fantastic position and scores extremely well in practice (61% wins).On the other hand, when I analyzed this position some time ago, I discovered the amazing line that goes9...d510.c5e5Alas, even though it is extremely beautiful, it is not 100% sound, so I couldn't bring myself to give it as my main recommendation in this position (I have to mention that Pruijssers also gave it in his repertoire with a very similar verdict). However, I couldn't make a course on Alekhine and omit it completely, so this line will be provided as the alternative.(For the purposes of the Quickstarter, I think this is a good place to stop. The variation is analyzed in more details in the theoretical chapter.)} 
