[Black "Exchange variation #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this trainable, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. exd6 {The capture on d6 leads to the so-called Exchange variation. White voluntarily releases the tension in the position and gets rid of the pawn on e5 that was securing them a lot of space. On the other hand, this pawn often turns out to be Black's main source of counterplay, so White is trying to make an argument that this exchange eliminates a potential target and provides White's center with some stability.Even though this solid approach is not the most critical or ambitious, it is very annoying to face in practice because it makes it quite difficult to play for the win (I have often jokingly referred to it as the 'Alapin of the Alekhine').} 
5. cxd6 {This is a big and important crossroad as it is possible to capture ond6with both pawns. The move5...exd6is generally regarded as the soundest and most solid way to deal with the exchange variation, but I have always found the resulting positions a bit dull, due to the symmetrical pawn structure. In this course, I will be, therefore, recommending the more ambitious, combative and risky approach, involving the capture with the c-pawn, simply because it leads to a more imbalanced position with an asymmetrical pawn structure.Also note that we can't really capture on d6 with the queen in 'Scandi' style, since5...Qxd66.c5Qe67.Be2is not very pleasant as our pieces are not really standing very well.} 
6. Nf3 {Last but not least, even though the setup with Nc3-Be3-Rc1-b3 is very popular and testing, this natural developing move, aiming to mobilize the bishop and castle as quickly as possible, is still the most common move in the position - and arguably the most challenging. Some White players hesitate to make this move because it allows Black to pin the knight with Bg4, but as we will soon see, White doesn't really have to fear this early bishop move just yet.} 
6. g6 {Just like in the 6.Nc3 variation, we will aim for the fianchetto setup, aiming to bring the bishop to g7 from where it can influence the central e5 and d4 squares. It is important to mention that the pinning move6...Bg4is made automatically by many Alekhine players, but it really doesn't achieve anything in this position. For example, after7.h3Bh58.Nc3Black doesn't really have a reasonable continuation. For example, if8...e6then9.d5is already quite strong.While if7...Bg48.h3Bh59.Nc3Nc610.d5Bxf3(which is a standard idea in a number of Alekhine positions) then10.Qxf3Ne511.Qe4and White has everything protected, the bishop pair, more space and a completely winning position. We can conclude that the move Bg4 is much more powerful once the bishop has been developed to e2, because then White will have to recapture on f3 with the bishop and remove one of the defenders of the c4 pawn.After 6...g6, White has a wide array of options at their disposal.} 
7. h3 {This little pawn move, ruling out the move Bg4 once and for all, is arguably the most venomous move in the exchange variation. It might be a bit surprising considering that I just wrote above that the move Bg4 shouldn't be overestimated/underestimated.But as we have seen in the variation with7.Be2,Bg4might become quite strong at a later point, so it makes sense for White to prevent it, to begin with.Also note that White can also start with7.Nc3, but after7...Bg7they should probably go for8.h3anyway, which is why we will not separately examine this particular move order.} 
7. Bg7 {For the moment, we continue with the natural development.} 
8. Nc3 {Probably the best move, developing the knight and taking the e4 square under the control. White can't really go without placing the knight to c3 at some point, and probably it is better to do so sooner rather than later.For example, if8.Be2O-O9.O-OBlack has some additional options in the form of9...e5This move wouldn't be too good if the knight was already onc3, but here after10.Bg5f611.Be3there is11...e4as White doesn't have this square under control. Perhaps not the most significant nuance out there, but one that is kinda relevant.} 
8. O-O
9. Be2 {A very natural developing move, preparing to castle.} 
9. Nc6 {In this particular position, it is better to start with the development of the knight instead of striking in the center at once. The problem with9...e5is that after10.Bg5we are kinda left without a good reply and after10...f611.Be3we have violated one of the basic principles of Ben Finegold's teaching (never play f6) and limited our bishop on g7, which is clearly quite undesirable.} 
10. O-O {Note that here - in contrast to setups with Nc3-Be3-Rc1-b3, White can't really play10.d5as after10...Na5they have problems with the c4 pawn, and the b-pawn can't move as the knight on c3 is hanging. It is precisely these types of ideas that the setup starting with 6.Nc3 and 7.Be3 is aimed to avoid.} 
10. Bf5 {Black is in a bit of a conundrum here. We would very much like to gain some space and strike in the center, but the problem is that neither of the central pawn advances is particularly good.For example, after the thematic10...e511.Bg5is very annoying, as we really want to avoid a position such as11...f612.Be3. In case you are wondering,12...f5is not particularly great as after13.dxe5dxe514.Qb3our position is uncoordinated, weakened and we are lacking development and we might get punished for our overambitious play in the opening.Furthermore, without the bishop on e3, the other thematic strike10...d5has no sense, as after11.c5Nc412.b3we are in trouble as we can't exchange the knight for the bishop on e3. Instead, we develop our light-squared bishop and await further course of events. Now White has quite a few options available.} 
11. Be3 {First of all, this very natural move - which is the most common move in the position, is not particularly good for White, as it allows Black to execute a very thematic Alekhine idea in the form of d5 and Nc4.} 
11. d5 {Remember this idea. Whenever there is a bishop on e3, it should be on your radar! We have seen it executed in different shapes and forms throughout this chapter.} 
12. c5 {Very natural and most commonly played.12.b3might be better, but then Black is very happy to have gained a share of the central space and can consider taking on c4 or even the more creative12...Be4!?} 
12. Nc4 {The point of our play. We simultaneously hit the bishop on e3 and the pawn on b2 and we want to play b6 next, if allowed.} 
13. Bxc4
13. dxc4 {And despite the ugly pawn structure, this type of position is almost always fine for Black due to the light-square control and the counterplay against the pawn on d4. Black can play Bd3 or e5 next, while at some point the break with b6 should also be considered. The position is objectively close to being equal with a lot of play left, so Black shoulddefinitely be happy with the outcome of the opening.} 
