[White "2) Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Modern Line: Alburt Variation #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3 {Finally, after examining all the other possibilities available to White up to this point, we will examine this natural developing move of the knight, leading to the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. White's idea is simple - they are trying to keep the tension while developing a piece, intending to recapture on e5 with the knight, if allowed. They are also refraining from moving the c-pawn too early in order to prevent the overextension that can be so typical of the Alekhine Defence.For a long time, this was considered to be the best and most reliable way of meeting the Alekhine Defence. For example, if you enter these moves into lichess, you get an entry from Batsford Chess Openings/Wikipedia which states that 'While 4. c4 is tempting, the modern variation 4. Nf3 gets better results, making it harder for Black to equalize.'.There is no denying that 4.Nf3 is a variation that provides White with objective chances of seizing the advantage and that needs to be taken very seriously. However, in contrast, to, say, Four Pawns Attack, where the path is very narrow, the Modern Variation does offer Black a lot of flexibility in terms of possible setups. As we will soon see, there are many different possibilities available to Black starting from the very next move. In order for White to get an advantage against all these setups, they do need to be well-prepared and know a lot of details - which is not always the case, especially at lower levels.Therefore, even though the Modern variation is very solid, objectively very good and still very popular, I am personally a little bit less concerned about it compared to the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I do consider as the critical test of the Alekhine, as I mentioned there already).} 
4. g6 {As mentioned in my comment to White's previous move, there are many possibilities available to Black against the Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. After some consideration, I have decided to recommend the text move, leading to the so-called Alburt variation, named after the famous Ukrainian chess player and a great Alekhine specialist, Lev Alburt (who immigrated to the United States in 1979). The idea of this move is simple - Black decides to keep the tension, develop the bishop to g7, castle quickly and then play against White's center.I decided to go for this line because it is the most combative variation available to Black against the Modern variation, simply because it keeps the pawn structure asymmetrical. It is true that it involves some risk and that it might be less solid than some of the other options, but I do think it requires a bit more precision, concreteness, and knowledge from White. Besides, given that I have previously written a course on the Modern defence, it was only natural to try and develop the bishop to g7 at the first opportunity.With that being said, let's take a look at some of the other options available to Black on move 4.A) First of all, the old mainline is4...Bg4,pinning the knight on f3 and intending to play e6 next, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain. I have played this in some classical games in the past and recently in some high-rated rapid online games, but I am never too thrilled with the positions I get. Not only do I consider the mainline after5.Be2problematic for Black irrespective if we try5...e6or even5...c6,but I also feel that4...Bg45.c4Nb66.exd6cxd67.h3leads to a version of the exchange variation which is very reasonable for White, where I feel our development of the bishop to g4 was premature (as explained in the chapter dedicated to the Exchange variation).B) The other big variation that actually constitutes the mainline involves releasing the tension in the center with the move4...dxe5Then after the typical5.Nxe5, keeping the center fluid and activating the knight, Black again has quite a few options at the disposal.  B1) First of all, the move5...Nd7,immediately challenging the knight on e5, is played by some brave and bold Alekhine warriors. However, the problem is that it more or less loses by force to6.Nxf7It is true that this refutation is not at all that simple and that many White players don't actually go for it, after which Black's knight move is fully justified, but recommending a line that is objectively losing would be a little bit too hardcore even for an author of my standards who loves to go against the evaluation of the engine.B2) Secondly, after4...dxe55.Nxe5there is also the move5...g6,leading to the so-called Kengis variation, named after another great Alekhine expert Edvins Kengis, was recommended by Roland Pruijssers in the course Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. It is a very solid line, as exchanging on e5 removes the annoying pawn on e5 which often provides White with some nasty attacking opportunities, as we will see in our lines. However, the exchange on e5 also invites the knight on e5 - and also leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure. I am not even sure whether Black has full equality after, say,6.Bc4c67.O-OBg78.Re1,but more importantly - I feel it is very difficult to play for a win in a position like that one.B3) Last but not least, after4....dxe55.Nxe5the solid move5...c6,opening the potential c7 square for the knight on d5, overprotecting it, and also preparing to play with Bf5 and e6 next, is arguably the most reliable variation available to Black. It was recommended as the main option in the course The Dark Knight Rises by NM Bryan Tillis here on Chessable (with the move 4... g6 being recommended as the alternative). It is also the variation that is the choice of the strongest Alekhine practitioner, GM Oleksandr Bortnyk when he faces the Modern variation. I was considering recommending it, as well, but here again, I thought that Black has very little chance to play for a win in the main tabiya of the variation that arises after6.Be2Bf57.O-ONd78.Nf3e69.c4N5f610.Nh4Bg611.g3Still, this is a very solid setup, so if you want to keep things flexible and mix it up every now and then - I can only recommend you to check this variation in greater detail.} 
5. Bc4 {This is by far the main - and arguably the most dangerous move in the position. White develops the bishop to a very active diagonal, attacks our knight on d5 and also potentially eyes the pawn on f7. We will see that this early attack against the weakest point in the Black's pawn structure is actually quite relevant and venomous.} 
5. Nb6 {The most common and also natural move, retreating the knight and gaining a tempo for an attack on the bishop. Trying to preserve the knight on d5 doesn't work that well, say after5...dxe56.dxe5c6asnow the bishop is very active on c4 and some nasty ideas appear in the position, such as7.Nc3when7...Nxc3is not possible due to8.Bxf7winning on the spotOn the other hand, reinforcing the knight immediately with5...c6is sometimes played, but I really don't like the fact that this allows White to take on d6 with6.exd6at the moment when we are unable to recapture with the c-pawn, so we basically have to accept the transposition to some sort of symmetrical/Kengis variation where White has placed the bishop quite actively on c4.} 
6. Bb3 {Of course, White didn't bring the bishop all the way to c4 in order to retreat it to e2, and therefore retreats it to the active square b3, from where the bishop eyes the f7 square and exerts some pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.6.Be2would be very similar to the line with 5.Be2 after6...dxe57.Nxe5Bg7when the idea of c5 is already looming in the position.Also, note that6.Bxf7Kxf77.Ng5Kg8does lead to an extra piece for Black. There are minor inconveniences with the king, but objectively such a sacrifice shouldn't work and we are objectively winning.} 
6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. In the Quickstarter guide, I will be focusing on the main variation starting with7.Ng5Simply because it is by far most frequent and dangerous. Other possibilities on move 7 are covered in the corresponding theoretical chapter.} 
7. Ng5 {This knight jump, attacking the f7 pawn and making the way for the queen to join the action. It is true that this move violates the basic principles of the opening play (Don't move the same piece twice), but White claims it is justified because it creates immediate threats.This is a very serious option and arguably the main move in this position. Even though it is 'only' the 2nd most popular move in the lichess database, it is the 1st most popular move according to the masters' database - and is also the move that is often recommended as the 'refutation' of the Alburt line. It was, for example, recommended by Chessable author chessforlife in his course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian here on Chessable.Now, even though this move is theoretically very challenging, the fact that it is one of the main options for White in this variation was one of the reasons why I decided to recommend the Alburt variation with 4...g6 to begin with. I do think this move leads to some very sharp and combative lines where the price of a move is quite high and where Black can definitely get their fair share of winning chances. I also think very energetic and concrete play is required from White which makes the position somewhat difficult to handle - especially at lower levels. And even though White has relatively favourable results according to the lichess database (52% wins, 41% losses, 7% draws), in the very specific line I am going to recommend with 7...e6 and 8...Qe7, the situation is less clear (with wins for White and Black being tied at 47%, with 6 % draws).} 
7. e6 {This move, blocking the bishop onb3and preventing any sort of e6 nonsense is almost a must here, given that7...O-Oruns into8.e6which is very bad for Black. Now again White is at a crossroads and has to choose between two big options.} 
8. f4 {This relatively logical push of the f-pawn, reinforcing the e5 pawn and trying to hold on to the strong center in the style of the Four Pawns Attack, is not at all so silly or harmless as it looks. Since the knight has moved away, White tries to utilize the fact that the f-pawn is free. I faced this move for the first time in a rapid game online just as I started working on this course and immediately realized this is a relatively sensible option that does require some coverage. So let's take a look at how we should react.} 
8. dxe5 {When White places the pawns on d4, e5 and f4, it is better not to capture the pawn on e5 with the d-pawn, as after White almost certainly recaptures with the f-pawn, the f-file will be opened and our f7 pawn might come under pressure after White castles and places the rook on f1. However, with the bishop on g7, sometimes it is also very desirable for White to capture with the d-pawn, in order to maintain a strong point on e5 that restricts the fianchettoed bishop severely.In the given position, my suggestion is to capture on e5 at this particular moment when the opponent's queen is on d1, in order to 'force' White to capture with the f-pawn. The reason we want to keep the pawn on d4 is counterplay - after we castle, we want to play c5 and start undermining White's center, while claiming that the opening of the f-file is not at all so fatal, provided we do know what we are doing.It is also possible to castle, but I dislike the fact that8...O-O9.Qf3gives White some additional options, e.g. after9...dxe5they can play10.dxe5when the queen exchange has been avoided. It may not be the end of the world, but I would like to narrow their choice a little bit.} 
9. fxe5 {The most obvious and logical recapture. As I mentioned above,9.dxe5is not particularly desirable as after9...Qxd1we manage to exchange a pair of pieces - and queens no less - which is very much in our favour, given that we have less space in the position.} 
9. O-O {Now we finally castle and intend to start playing against the center with the c5 strike. But also - somewhat surprisingly - with the f6 pawn push, which turns out to be quite viable in this position.} 
10. O-O
10. c5 {Now we finally start chipping away at White's center and try to distract our opponent from attacking us on the kingside.} 
11. c3 {The only sensible move, reinforcing the d4 pawn and trying to maintain the long pawn chain. Taking on c5 is not desirable for White as after11.dxc5Qxd112.Rxd1N6d7both c5 and e5 are hanging and Black will regain a pawn with at least an equal position - although one that is much more pleasant to play in practice.} 
11. cxd4 {I think taking on d4 immediately is the most precise. Many games in the Lichess database saw11...Nc6but after12.Ne4cxd413.Bg5White gets a very strong - probably already winning - attack, e.g.13...Qd7?already fails to14.Nf6Bxf615.Bxf6when the weaknesses of the dark-squared complex turn out to be fatal, with Qc1-Qh6 incoming.} 
12. cxd4
12. Nc6 {Now we see one of the points of Black's idea - pressure against the d4 pawn. For the purposes of the Quickstarter Guide, this is a good moment to stop because the main idea involving the capture on d4 and creating play against d4 has been demonstrated. The variation is analyzed a bit deeper in the theoretical chapter.} 
