8. Qf3 {The most common and obvious move, utilizing the fact that the knight has created some space for the queen to join the action and currently threatening mate on f7.} 
8. Qe7 {This very provocative move is, in my opinion, the most combative and challenging option available at Black's disposal. Black defends the pawn on f7 and intends to play h6, kicking the knight from g5 away and also protecting the g5 square, which is important since White wants to play some sort of Ne4 and Bg5 combo next.In my distant youth, I once played8...O-O9.Qh3h6in a game against young and talented Croatian junior player and future IM Jadranko Plenča, but not only did I get absolutely crushed in that game - but this variation is also objectively very bad, irrespective if White decides to play the aggressive10.Ne4or more positional10.Nf3} 
9. Ne4 {This knight move, preparing Bg5 next and trying to utilize the dark squares on the kingside, is the only serious attempt for an advantage worth analyzing, as Black was threatening to take on e5, play h6, play Nc6 and castle. If Black obtains all that and gets a harmonious setup, then White's aggressive opening with Ng5 and Qf3 will make little sense - so the first player has to try and utilize their initiative while they still can. This is one of the critical positions of the entire Alburt variations and Black needs to be quite careful and knowledgable here in order not to lose at once.On a side note, maybe it is worth mentioning that9.exd6cxd610.Bf4,trying to invert the move order compared to the main line of the variation, doesn't quite work as after10...Nc6Black is ready to play e5 next and grab the initiative.} 
9. dxe5 {This is a very critical position for the entire variation with 4...g6 and I spent some time trying to decide which variation to recommend. Ultimately, I have decided to go for the most obvious move involving the capture on e5 as my main recommendation, mainly because it leads to sharp and irrational positions where both sides have to play accurately and have chances to win.However, since this continuation does force Black to play a non-standard and rugged position that can be tricky to navigate, and since White might objectively be better if they find all the best moves, this line might not be everybody's cup of tea. This is why I also decided to include the 'safer', but less exciting 9...h6 as the alternative in this course.} 
10. Bg5 {This developing move, temporarily sacrificing a pawn, is the most common move in this position. White attacks the queen on e7 and gets access to the f6 square. The downside is that Black now gets the opportunity to give a check on b4 and keep the e5 pawn protected, although Black shouldn't really aim to keep it and play this line too greedily, as we will soon see.} 
10. Qb4+ {This check is virtually the only move in this position, as the queen's best square is the one on a5.} 
11. c3
11. Qa5 {The key position of the entire 4...g6 variation. At first glance it looks crazy to allow a piece to jump to f6, but it turns out that this is not at all the end of the world for Black. And even though the computer claims some advantage for White, Black's practical results are actually quite good - Black scores 49% wins, 44% losses, with 7% of the games being drawn, according to the lichess database.For the purposes of the Quickstarter Guide, this seems like a good moment to stop as White has a wide array of possibilities. You just have to remember that both12.Nf6and12.Bf6don't yield White much. This crazy variation is the main reason why I picked the Alburt variation for this course.} 
