[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why we are going to cover them in this chapter.} 
2. Bc4 {First of all, allow me to start with this 'whacky' option that is seen occasionally. White develops the bishop and seemingly blunders the e4 pawn, but they are actually planning some Bxf7 and Qxh5 combo. This shouldn't be something that should concern an Alekhine player, but it is good to mention it exists so that you don't get surprised in one of your actual games.Funnily enough, other moves that leave the e4 pawn hanging such as2.Nf3Nxe4or2.d4Nxe4are also seen in numerous games of the lichess database. But since they are most probably the by-product of the era of the premoving rather than some sophisticated opening traps, I will refrain from devoting any attention to them, as we should be very happy to be a pawn up as Black on move 2.} 
2. Nxe4 {As they say - the best way of refuting a gambit is to accept it. We can happily capture the pawn on e4 and allow White to execute their tactical idea.} 
3. Bxf7+ {This is the point. White temporarily sacrifices the bishop but intends to play Qh5 and then follow it up with Qd5, winning back the knight on e4. This seems like a sensible idea since Black will also be deprived of the castling right, but it transpires that giving up the bishop pair and moving the queen three times afterward is not ideal. Black can already start fighting for the advantage here.} 
3. Kxf7
4. Qh5+ {Executing the afore-mentioned check and intending to play Qd5 next.} 
4. Kg8 {This is apparently a better move than the natural4...g6as now the king is immediately avoiding any subsequent checks, while in some positions after5.Qd5e66.Qxe4Bg7there might be some check on the f-file. This continuation is also probably more than sufficient for the human level, but ultra-precise engines do insist that retreating the king to g8 immediately is more precise - and who am I to oppose their verdict?} 
5. Qd5+
5. e6
6. Qxe4 {Thus White has regained a piece and deprived the Black king of castling rights, but in doing so they have lost a lot of time, given up the bishop pair, and exchanged an important central pawn on e4 for the pawn on f7. Furthermore, the queen on e4 is now exposed which allows Black to immediately expand in the center.} 
6. d5 {Moving a central pawn with a gain of tempo and getting some foothold in the center can't be too bad.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nc6 {And even though his king is temporarily on g8, shutting in the rook on h8, Black has a tremendous position. We have a nice central control, lead in development and no problems. Next, we want to play e5, Bd6 then develop the light-squared bishop, and then take it from there.We also have an option of going Nd4 if White doesn't prevent it and we can always play h6-Kh7 to include the rook on h8 into the game. Black should already be very comfortable and clearly better and this is definitely not a variation Alekhine players should particularly mind seeing on the board.} 
