1. e4
1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why we are going to cover them in this chapter.} 
2. d3 {With this move, White also defends the e4 pawn and indicates the willingness to go for some sort of system such as the King's Indian Attack, characterized by placing the knights on d2 and f3, the bishop on g2 or e2, castling and than taking it from there. Some players with the White pieces like to go for it almost irrespective of what Black does, but the problem is twofold:  A) It is objectively not the most critical or ambitious approach - as is usually the case when playing system-based openings.   B) In this particular situation, Black didn't yet place a pawn in the center and determine the pawn structure, which means that Black has a certain flexibility when it comes to reacting to what White does and choosing a preferred setup.} 
2. c5 {In my Modern defense course, I suggested going for the Sicilian setup whenever White does something weird early on - simply because I believe most of the anti-Sicilians available to the first player at worst allow us to equalize easily - and at best allow us to fight for the initiative from the early point in the game. In this particular case, we transpose to a favorable version of the so-called Closed Sicilian setup where White has played the move 2.d3 very early - which reduces their options significantly, as we will soon see.It may seem a bit inconsistent to recommend going for a completely different opening given that in some other variations, I advise against it - but in this particular case I consider this to be so good for Black that I can't go against it.With that being said, almost any sensible move for Black is good here. For example, if you play2...e5you end up in a very healthy version of the 1.e4 e5 system where White played the passive move d3 early on. On the other hand, the move2...d5has also been played here, but I feel it is better to wait with the confrontation in the center for the moment until we see what exactly White wants to do next.} 
3. f4 {This move is a very sensible option. White tries to benefit from not yet developing the knight to f3 to place the pawn on f4 in preparation for the future kingside attack. Now the game takes the shape of a Grand Prix Attack where we have managed to avoid some dangerous setups involving early Be3-Qd2 and where White is forced to keep the light-squared bishop passive on e2. With that being said, White doesn't really have time to prepare a more sophisticated setup due to the fact they have played the slow 2.d3 instead of, say, 2.Nc3 earlier.For example, if3.g3,intending to fianchetto the bishop to g2, we can already change the course and start preparing the central counterstrike with3...Nc64.Bg2d5!,obtaining a very good position, as we also want to play e5 next and completely take the center.Similarly,3.Nf3is met with3...Nc6while White still can't go for the fianchetto with4.g3due to the same4...d5!5.e5Nd7when the pawn on e5 is extremely weak (and we aren't at all worried if it goes to e6). In general, I don't think there is much sense in trying to prepare specific variations against these rare setups by White, as remembering some key ideas such as the aforementioned d5 push and playing relatively sensible chess in accordance to the regular principles (control the center, develop the pieces, etc.) should be more than sufficient to get a playable and healthy position.} 
3. Nc6 {We continue with our development. The knight hardly has a better square than c6, so we might as well immediately place it there.} 
4. Nf3 {White also continues with the development, so now we have to choose a setup. I would recommend going for the fianchetto in this position as I believe it is the best approach against the Closed Sicilian, too.} 
4. g6 {The idea behind this move is to simply fianchetto the bishop. Later down the road, Black intends to play on the queenside by pushing the queenside pawns, so having a bishop on g7 where it will exert influence over the queenside is very helpful. There are other possibilities here, as well, but as a Modern player, I have a soft spot for fianchettoing my bishop to g7 in all kinds of positions.} 
5. Be2 {Continuing the development. Note, btw, that5.e5is always met with5...Nd5It is true that the pawn on e5 is currently restricting our bishop on g7, but it will be very easy to undermine this pawn with d6 and open up the bishop's diagonal again.} 
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. c3 {A logical move, trying to exploit the fact that the knight hasn't occupied this square, to limit the bishop and to control the important d4 square. White would love to potentially play d4 at some point - but it is not so easy to do with the e4 pawn hanging.} 
7. d6 {Taking control over the e5 square finally, opening up the bishop and preparing to play on the queenside.} 
8. Qe1 {In these types of positions, trying to play Qe1-Qh4 and then to attack with f5-Bh6-Ng5 is a standard developing scheme. Many White players like to go for it almost automatically - but it is not something to be feared. Still, it is good to know how exactly to react to it and to emphasize its existence.If White tries to do anything else, say to play8.Kh1then we can immediately start our queenside expansion with8...b5when we intend to follow things up with a5-b4 and so on.On the other hand, if White tries to prevent this plan with8.a4then we can simply play8...a69.Kh1Rb8to insist on its implementation. Note that White can never block the queenside with the move a5 since our queen and knight are covering that square.} 
8. b5 {For the moment, we can ignore White's demonstration and can start our queenside expansion - a typical idea in these types of positions where the pawns on e4 and d3 are facing the pawns on c5 and d6.} 
9. Qh4 {White insists on executing the idea of f5-Bh6-Ng5 and so on.} 
9. e6 {A good defensive idea, covering the f5 square and eyeing the queen on h4 with our own queen, preparing to play Nd7 next. Next, we want to play moves such as a5 and b4 and open up the queenside and it is a big question what White should do next, given that10.f5is met with the simple10...exf5when White doesn't have any actual attack going.} 
