1. e4
1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why we are going to cover them in this chapter.} 
2. Nc3 {Out of all the options available to White on move 2, I have always found this one to be the most serious and most annoying to face. White is simply defending the pawn on e4 and bringing the knight into the game, either inviting Black to transpose to a different opening - or to try to cut the Gordian knot by striking in the center at once with d5.} 
2. d5 {Even though this might not be objectively the best move in the position, it is probably the most typical Alekhine move, striking in the center immediately and provoking the opponent once again by inviting them to advance the pawn to e5 once again. Deciding to recommend this move as a main option here was a difficult decision as I personally think it might not be the best, but the problem with the alternatives is that they allow White to transpose to a completely different opening.For example, the move2...d6would be a direct transposition to the Pirc defense after3.d4,while the move2...e6which is also a very creative possibility, allows White to transpose into one of the main positions of the French Defence after3.d4when we hardly have a better move than3...d5Last but not least, I personally think that the move2...e5is the healthiest move in this position, transposing to the Vienna opening. However, as an Alekhine player, you really don't want to be tricked into playing a variation of1.e4e5- even if it is not objectively the most dangerous one. Especially since I would expect people who respond with2.Nc3to be Vienna players and aware of this transposition.Thus, going for the text move seemed like the most logical option, even though it is worth keeping the afore-mentioned possibilities in mind if you want to expand your repertoire someday or surprise your opponent with an uncommon opening choice.} 
3. exd5 {White has two options in this position - capturing the pawn on d5 or advancing the pawn to e5. It goes without saying that the latter approach (which will be analyzed later in this chapter) is much more critical, as taking on d5 allows Black to capture on d5 with the knight and basically obtain a very reasonable version of the Scandinavian Defence!} 
3. Nxd5
4. Bc4 {The only move that tries to create some problems. White develops a piece with a gain of tempo, attacking the knight on d5. Taking on d5 with4.Nxd5would lead to a very good version of the Scandinavian for Black after4...Qxd5When the queen is sitting this comfortably in the center and White doesn't have the possibility of chasing it with a move like Nc3, it is usually very beneficial for Black.Also, a slow developing move such as4.Nf3would allow Black to continue with the development relatively easily - for example with4...Bf5,getting the bishop out of the pawn chain and then intending to calmly continue with e6-Be7-O-O and so on.} 
4. e6 {At this particular moment, Black is at a big juncture and has different ways of dealing with the pressure on the d5 knight. I personally think this move is the healthiest one, simply reinforcing the knight on d5 and restricting the bishop on c4, preventing some ideas associated with Qf3, as we will see shortly. It is true that this also limits our own light-squared bishop, but later down the road we can develop it via b6-Bb7 and it is not entirely clear why it would be placed any worse there.With that being said, let me briefly mention all the alternatives.A) Black can also reinforce the knight on d5 with the move4...c6However, here I dislike the fact that White has the option of playing5.Qf3and now the knight on d5 is unable to move due to the mating threats on f7. It is still very much playable for Black, but I would rather not allow our opponent that option.B ) Many players go for4...Nb6here, hitting the bishop immediately and intending to play5.Bb3c5, with the trap of attacking the bishop. I have tried this a few times in my own career, but I have realized that positions after6.d3are not at all so easy to handle in practice as it is somehow difficult to find a useful role for the light-squared bishop. Recommending it in this course definitely didn't appeal to me, although if you want to investigate setups where Black doesn't play 5...c5, feel free to do so.C) Last but not least, let me mention that4...Nxc3is not the best idea due to the intermediate5.Qf3!e66.dxc3!It is true that this doubles up White's c-pawns, but in return they open the diagonal for the bishop on c1 and the d-file, intending a very quick castling long. It is a standard procedure for White in many openings and I would rather not play the Black side in a position like this.} 
5. Nf3 {A logical developing move, bringing in the knight and preparing to castle next. Note that here5.Qf3is not as powerful as now we can play5...Nb6since mate on f7 is not threatened. After6.Bb3we can calmly continue with6...Nc6when Nd4 is already in the air and everyone is left wondering what exactly is the queen doing on f3. Black has absolutely no problems here.Also, let me mention that neither capture on d5 for White is particularly attractive, as5.Bxd5exd5loses the bishop pair while after5.Nxd5exd5the bishop has to move again, which causes White to lose some time for no good reason.} 
5. Be7 {Black also continues to develop normally and castle the king as soon as possible.} 
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. d4 {Sooner or later, White has to play this move and open up the bishop on c1. It is much more central and active to place the pawn on d4 rather than to advance it modestly to d3.} 
7. Nxc3 {Black has several options at their disposal here, but I like this idea of capturing on c3 at the moment where White is unable to recapture with the d-pawn and change the structure, saddling White with the doubled c-pawns.} 
8. bxc3 {It has to be mentioned that the weakness of these doubled pawns shouldn't be overestimated as it is not too easy to exploit it at this particular moment. Also, White has obtained the open b-file in return, allowing them to activate the rook on a1. Still, these pawns are a long-term static weakness that can be potentially exploited, say in some late endgame.} 
8. Nd7 {And now Black calmly develops the knight on a square where it helps prepare the thematic c5 break. Next on the cards is b6-Bb7 and then striking with the thematic c5 break. Black has obtained exactly what we wanted - an imbalanced, complicated position with very realistic chances for playing for a win, without risking too much (our position doesn't have any clear weaknesses).In the lichess database, Black's results are slightly more favourable, which is a good indication of the potential of our position and its practical value.} 
