1. e4
1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why we are going to cover them in this chapter.} 
2. Nc3 {Out of all the options available to White on move 2, I have always found this one to be the most serious and most annoying to face. White is simply defending the pawn on e4 and bringing the knight into the game, either inviting Black to transpose to a different opening - or to try to cut the Gordian knot by striking in the center at once with d5.} 
2. d5 {Even though this might not be objectively the best move in the position, it is probably the most typical Alekhine move, striking in the center immediately and provoking the opponent once again by inviting them to advance the pawn to e5 once again. Deciding to recommend this move as a main option here was a difficult decision as I personally think it might not be the best, but the problem with the alternatives is that they allow White to transpose to a completely different opening.For example, the move2...d6would be a direct transposition to the Pirc defense after3.d4,while the move2...e6which is also a very creative possibility, allows White to transpose into one of the main positions of the French Defence after3.d4when we hardly have a better move than3...d5Last but not least, I personally think that the move2...e5is the healthiest move in this position, transposing to the Vienna opening. However, as an Alekhine player, you really don't want to be tricked into playing a variation of1.e4e5- even if it is not objectively the most dangerous one. Especially since I would expect people who respond with2.Nc3to be Vienna players and aware of this transposition.Thus, going for the text move seemed like the most logical option, even though it is worth keeping the afore-mentioned possibilities in mind if you want to expand your repertoire someday or surprise your opponent with an uncommon opening choice.} 
3. e5 {Apart from capturing on d5 with the pawn, White can also advance the pawn to e5, attack our knight on f6 and claim that now this advance happens under better circumstances as our knight can't go to d5 any longer.} 
3. Nfd7 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this provocative and challenging retreat, which is almost the exclusive choice of the blitz and bullet specialist Oleksandr Bortnyk - probably the leading Alekhine expert on the planet right now - a player who uses it regularly against the best players in the world. With this move, Black invites the opponent to either go for some sort of the French structure where Black will try to benefit from not playing the move e7-e6, or to immediately sacrifice the pawn with the push of the e5 pawn.The other possibility in this position is the move3...d4, which I used to play a lot in the past. The problem, however, is that after4.exf6dxc35.fxg7we are forced to go into a cheerless endgame that arises after5...cxd26.Qxd2Qxd27.Bxd2Bxg7where due to our worse pawn structure (3 pawn islands) we can only be worse and have to defend without any realistic winning prospects. Even though the results for both variations aren't too bad for Black according to the lichess database, I have personally never enjoyed playing this endgame.} 
4. e6 {First of all, let's ask ourselves - what happens if White tries to exploit the positioning of our knight on d7 (that is preventing the bishop on c8 from influencing the e6 square) by pushing the pawn to e6. This is a very typical pawn sacrifice with the help of which White tries to create weak doubled pawns on the semi-open e-file and disrupt Black's coordination and development and it needs to be taken seriously - especially since it is the third most common move played in this position.} 
4. fxe6 {Of course, Black more-or-less has to capture this pawn and accept the challenge.} 
5. d4 {The only move that really requires some analysis in this position. White clamps down on the position and tries to prevent the liberating e5 break. White's idea is to play slowly and obtain total control over the position with Nf3, Bd3, etc. They claim that the doubled e-pawns are a long-term weakness that is also hindering Black's natural development in this position. Now the question is - how should Black go about completing the development?} 
5. c5 {This move was recommended by Bryan Tillis in his excellent course on the Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. When I was first analyzing the position, I realized this is not the only possibility here and that5...g6might be a clever move order, keeping the option of playing for the Nc6-e5 plan. As a matter of fact, I completed all the analysis and annotations for this option and found no problem with it.However, then I realized that in the line after4.d4c55.e6is very much possible, when after5...fxe6we actually transpose to the text variation - but with White managing to avoid the 5...g6 option.I have to admit this realization made me very tilted, but I couldn't simply ignore this transposition. This is why I needed to go back to the drawing board and recommend the text move instead of 5...g6 in this position, in order to avoid having to learn two different setups against two different move orders.} 
6. dxc5 {The most critical option. White voluntarily removes the pawn from the center, but instead intends to control the central squares with the pieces and claims it is very difficult for Black to finish the development and obtain any sort of coordination between the pieces.If White tries to ignore the tension and play, say,6.Nf3then Black can follow the same scheme of development and go for6...g6when7.h4Bg78.h5Nc6creates a lot of pressure against the d4 pawn and probably forces a transposition to the game continuation with9.dxc5I should, perhaps, also mention that6.Bd3is tricky, as we shouldn't fall for6...cxd47.Qh5with a quick mate, but instead play6...g6when it turns out that White has committed the bishop to d3 a bit prematurely.} 
6. g6 {But this is my suggested deviation from the Tillis' course. I feel it is imperative for Black in this position to bring the bishop to g7 as soon as possible (which is why I also considered starting with 5...g6).Tillis recommended6...Nc6,but I am not 100% sure of the position that arises after7.Nf3g68.Nd4as now8...Nxc5is not possible with the knight on c6 due to9.Nxc6bxc610.Qd4winning. Black's position might still be playable, but given the choice, I would rather prevent White from having such options, especially since I don't think the early advance of the h-pawn is something we should be afraid of.Also note that6...Nxc5is bad as after7.Nf3White has a nice central control and can play Bf4 next. We don't really want to recapture on c5 too early and should instead focus on developing more pieces.} 
7. h4 {This is probably the most testing and also the most human continuation, trying to immediately exploit the target on g6 created by Black on the previous move. The idea is, obviously, to follow up with h5 and then claim that the g6 pawn will be a target. However, as it turns out, Black can simply ignore this idea and continue with the development, as even if we lose the g6 pawn with a check, it is not the end of the world.If White doesn't play in such an aggressive manner and tries to play natural moves such as7.Nf3Bg78.Be3Nc69.Qd2we can actually castle kingside as after9...O-O, Rxf3 and d4 is already a massive threat, while we also have ideas of Nde5, exchanging some pieces. Even though this position looks dangerous for Black, our bishop on g7 is quite powerful and we do have an extra pawn, so all three results are possible.} 
7. Bg7 {The natural move, developing the bishop to the powerful diagonal and also covering the h8 rook, in anticipation of White's next move.} 
8. h5 {The most logical follow-up to the previous move. As they say, once you have said A, you have to say B.} 
8. Nc6 {Still ignoring the situation on the kingside and continuing to bring more and more pieces into the action.} 
9. hxg6
9. hxg6
10. Rxh8+
10. Bxh8
11. Bd3 {And now comes the critical moment. White is threatening to take the pawn on g6 with check, which would be the triumph of their plan. But as it turns out, we are not at all concerned about this pawn and can play more aggressively instead.} 
11. Bxc3+ {A very creative and combative move. It looks crazy to give up such a nice bishop on g7, but given that it creates tripled isolated pawns on the c-file, the decision to give it up can be justified.It has to be said that this is not a must in this situation and that the more passive11...Nf8is also possible.} 
12. bxc3
12. Qa5 {This is the point of Black's play! Now the pawns on c3 and c5 are under attack and we have also vacated the d8 square for the king. It looks crazy to give up the g6 pawn just like that, but we will surely get at least one of the pawns on the c-file back.} 
13. Bxg6+
13. Kd8 {This is actually quite a standard procedure in positions where one side has a massive pawn chain in the center. The king feels quite secure behind the pawns on d5, e6 and e7 as they are very difficult to undermine - and there are also quite a few pieces around the king as well. Black will pick up some pawns next and is also ahead in development.Some ideas include Nxc5-Ne4 or even Nde5. The bishop on c8 can potentially be developed via b6-Ba6 and the king will feel quite secure on d7 for a while. The outcome of the game is completely unclear and both sides have winning (or losing) chances - which is precisely what an Alekhine player that employs this line is looking for.} 
