4. f4 {Apart from playing with d4, White can also try to defend the e5 pawn with the f-pawn and play without including d4. It is very questionable whether such approach yields the first player any dividens in case Black decides to go for the very same setup with c5-Nc6, etc. But this also allows Black to play more ambitiously and advance the d-pawn at once - which will be what I will be recommending here.} 
4. d4 {Gaining some space in the center and kicking the knight away.} 
5. Ne4 {The only logical move, trying to keep the knight centralized and active.5.Nce2is very passive since after something like5...Nc66.d3Black can already start undermining the center with6...f6} 
5. f5 {A very strong move, harassing the knight on e4 further.} 
6. Ng5 {Again the best and most active move. White tries to place the knight on a very active square and create some threats associated with the Bc4-Qh5-e6 ideas. This is the only real try for a serious opening advantage, as the alternatives are quite meek.For example, if6.Nf2then6...e6leads to a perfectly reasonable position for Black where White's space on the kingside is counterbalanced by Black's space on the queenside and, as they say - we play chess from this point.Also note that taking en passant with6.exf6is not particularly threatening as after6...exf6we manage to eliminate the strong e5 pawn and have a very clear plan of playing Be7, castling short and then taking it from there.} 
6. Nb6 {Absolutely an essential move, preventing Bc4 and opening up the bishop on c8. Next, we want to play e6-Be7 and I guess we should ask ourselves here - what if White tries to prevent it in radical means?} 
7. e6 {Preventing Black from playing e6 and threatening Nf7. But this obviously involves a certain dose of risk as the pawn on e6 can become a potential target. Black does need to remember the following, very important, defensive move.} 
7. Qd5 {Very strong. Black activates the queen, eyes the e6 pawn, and also exerts influence on the kingside. I feel the position is already very difficult to play for White in practice.For example, if8.Nf7Qxe6wins on the spot.8.Qe2is not a concern as we can simply play8...g69.Nf7Rg8when the e6 pawn is hanging.Finally,8.Be2was played in a very high-profile game between Hikaru Nakamura and Oleksandr Bortnyk,  but after8...Nc69.Bf3Qd610.Ne2?!Bxe611.Nxe6Qxe6the strongest living practitioner of the Alekhine Defence was simply a pawn up, even though he did go on to lose the game in the end. But I think it is very heartening to see that even one of the best blitz players in the world can quickly lose his way in this variation - even if it was only a blitz game.} 
