1. Nf6 {In the majority of the games in which you employ the Alekhine, your opponent will move the e4 pawn and attack your knight on f6. However, there are some alternatives to this, the most obvious move, available to the first player on move 2. These deviations definitely aren't critical, but they are also not to be underestimated, which is why we are going to cover them in this chapter.} 
2. Nc3 {Out of all the options available to White on move 2, I have always found this one to be the most serious and most annoying to face. White is simply defending the pawn on e4 and bringing the knight into the game, either inviting Black to transpose to a different opening - or to try to cut the Gordian knot by striking in the center at once with d5.} 
2. d5 {Even though this might not be objectively the best move in the position, it is probably the most typical Alekhine move, striking in the center immediately and provoking the opponent once again by inviting them to advance the pawn to e5 once again. Deciding to recommend this move as a main option here was a difficult decision as I personally think it might not be the best, but the problem with the alternatives is that they allow White to transpose to a completely different opening.For example, the move2...d6would be a direct transposition to the Pirc defense after3.d4,while the move2...e6which is also a very creative possibility, allows White to transpose into one of the main positions of the French Defence after3.d4when we hardly have a better move than3...d5Last but not least, I personally think that the move2...e5is the healthiest move in this position, transposing to the Vienna opening. However, as an Alekhine player, you really don't want to be tricked into playing a variation of1.e4e5- even if it is not objectively the most dangerous one. Especially since I would expect people who respond with2.Nc3to be Vienna players and aware of this transposition.Thus, going for the text move seemed like the most logical option, even though it is worth keeping the afore-mentioned possibilities in mind if you want to expand your repertoire someday or surprise your opponent with an uncommon opening choice.} 
3. e5 {Apart from capturing on d5 with the pawn, White can also advance the pawn to e5, attack our knight on f6 and claim that now this advance happens under better circumstances as our knight can't go to d5 any longer.} 
3. Nfd7 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this provocative and challenging retreat, which is almost the exclusive choice of the blitz and bullet specialist Oleksandr Bortnyk - probably the leading Alekhine expert on the planet right now - a player who uses it regularly against the best players in the world. With this move, Black invites the opponent to either go for some sort of the French structure where Black will try to benefit from not playing the move e7-e6, or to immediately sacrifice the pawn with the push of the e5 pawn.The other possibility in this position is the move3...d4, which I used to play a lot in the past. The problem, however, is that after4.exf6dxc35.fxg7we are forced to go into a cheerless endgame that arises after5...cxd26.Qxd2Qxd27.Bxd2Bxg7where due to our worse pawn structure (3 pawn islands) we can only be worse and have to defend without any realistic winning prospects. Even though the results for both variations aren't too bad for Black according to the lichess database, I have personally never enjoyed playing this endgame.} 
4. d4 {The main move in the position. White simply moves the pawn to the center, defends the e5 pawn and transposes to some sort of the French/Caro Advance structure where Black didn't play either e6 or c6. Note that the d5 pawn is not really hanging as 4.Nxd5 Nxe5 is very much in Black's favour.} 
4. c5 {Black, in turn, doesn't waste time to defend the d5 pawn, but rather strikes in the center immediately. This is the favourite move of the Oleksandr Bortnyk and it scores extremely well in practice. In the lichess database, Black wins 56% of the games, while White wins only 41% (with the rest being drawn). Even in the Megadatabase, White scores only 38.5%.These numbers are far more relevant than the engine evaluation and are the best demonstration of the practical viability of this entire line.Note, btw, in passing, that Black can transpose to a variation of the French defence with4...e6,which may also be relevant in case you want to get your opponent out of their comfort zone and force them to play a position they don't usually play.} 
5. f4 {The most common and natural move in the position. White advances the f-pawn and reinforces the center, intending to develop the knight behind the pawn on f3 and handle the position in the same manner as they would handle the regular French defence.Let's quickly do a survey of other options:A) First of all, note that the capture on d5 is frequent - but also not ideal, as after5.Nxd5cxd4White can't go for the d4 pawn due to6.Qxd4Nb6!losing a piece. Note that 5.Nxd5 is the most common move in the lichess database.B) If5.dxc5, the easiest reply seems to be5...e6,going for a good version of the French defence where we will be able to collect the c5 pawn on the next move and then take it from there. It is true that some knowledge of the French structure/model games is helpful here, but overall, Black shouldn't have any particular problems in this variation.C) The same can be said about5.Nf3when5...e6seems to be a good idea, transposing to a big variation of the French where White didn't play f4. Our idea is to take on d4 next, play Nc6 and then take it from there.D) Finally,5.e6fxe6would transpose to the lines analyzed via 4.e6 move order.} 
5. cxd4 {I think this is the most challenging and tricky reply in this position. Black captures on d4 at the moment when there is no knight on f3 to recapture the pawn, forcing White to take a non-standard decision - to move the knight from c3 or to recapture on d4 with the queen.} 
6. Qxd4 {This is the most common move in the lichess database, which is quite expected as White recaptures the pawn immediately and also attacks the d5 pawn.} 
6. e6 {The natural response, defending the d5 pawn and intending to chase the queen away with Nc6 and/or Bc5.} 
7. Nf3 {The most common move in the position, simply developing the knight. However, it might not be the best move as now the queen will not be able to go to d2 as the bishop is still not on e3.7.Be3might be more precise, although after7...Nc68.Qd2Bc5White is lacking control of the d4 square as the knight is not yet on f3. Following9.Nf3Qb610.Bxc5Nxc5Blackhas a very reasonable position as the knight on c5 is quite nicely placed and can jump to e4 at some point in the future. Otherwise, Black can consider playing Bd7 and O-O-O and obtain a very healthy position without any weaknesses.Given that this is a 100 Repertoire and that 7.Be3 is only the third most common move in the lichess database, I figured it is okay to leave it as clickable, although I do want to emphasize it may be more precise than the text move.} 
7. Bc5 {Hitting the queen and developing with a tempo. In this particular case, I feel it is a tad more precise to start with the bishop, as after7...Nc6there is an option of going8.Qf2Bc59.Qg3which I would rather not have to deal with.} 
8. Qd1 {A logical move, preparing to play Bd3 and Qe2, then Bd2, castle long and then go for the kingside attack - a very typical French plan.Even though I have said that8.Qd2makes no sense with the bishop still on c1, the engine does suggest this is a playable option. But since no human will ever play, I think it can safely be ignored!} 
8. Nc6 {Now that we have forced the queen away from the f2 square, we continue with the natural development.} 
9. Bd3 {White also follows the aforementioned developing scheme and tries to mobilize the pieces and then to castle queenside.} 
9. a6 {A standard French plan, preparing the queenside expansion, gaining some space and anticipating that White will hide the king on that side of the board. Note that here we don't want to castle too quick as it would allow White an automatic and easy attack.} 
10. Qe2 {The queen is placed on e2 because there it reinforces the e5 pawn and prepares the f5 break. However, in contrast to regular variations of the French defence, White doesn't have such a good control of the d4 square which usually works in Black's favour as the knight on d4 would make the f5 attack even more deadly due to the pressure on e6.} 
10. b5
11. Bd2 {Both sides continue with their respective plans. Now it is not 100% clear what Black should do, but I really like the following regroup.} 
11. Bb6 {A very nice move, vacating the c5 square for the knight. Now Black will play Nc5 almost irrespective of what Black does.} 
12. O-O-O
12. Nc5 {Black has a good version of the French here. Some ideas involve playing b4-a5 and then Ba6, while alternatively, Nb4 with ideas of capturing on d3 is also in the air. Black probably wants to keep the king in the center for a while and focus on the queenside play. I feel a position like this offers Black good prospects - especially in a practical game.} 
