3. e5 {Apart from capturing on d5 with the pawn, White can also advance the pawn to e5, attack our knight on f6 and claim that now this advance happens under better circumstances as our knight can't go to d5 any longer.} 
3. Nfd7 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this provocative and challenging retreat, which is almost the exclusive choice of the blitz and bullet specialist Oleksandr Bortnyk - probably the leading Alekhine expert on the planet right now - a player who uses it regularly against the best players in the world. With this move, Black invites the opponent to either go for some sort of the French structure where Black will try to benefit from not playing the move e7-e6, or to immediately sacrifice the pawn with the push of the e5 pawn.The other possibility in this position is the move3...d4, which I used to play a lot in the past. The problem, however, is that after4.exf6dxc35.fxg7we are forced to go into a cheerless endgame that arises after5...cxd26.Qxd2Qxd27.Bxd2Bxg7where due to our worse pawn structure (3 pawn islands) we can only be worse and have to defend without any realistic winning prospects. Even though the results for both variations aren't too bad for Black according to the lichess database, I have personally never enjoyed playing this endgame.} 
4. d4 {The main move in the position. White simply moves the pawn to the center, defends the e5 pawn and transposes to some sort of the French/Caro Advance structure where Black didn't play either e6 or c6. Note that the d5 pawn is not really hanging as 4.Nxd5 Nxe5 is very much in Black's favour.} 
4. c5 {Black, in turn, doesn't waste time to defend the d5 pawn, but rather strikes in the center immediately. This is the favourite move of the Oleksandr Bortnyk and it scores extremely well in practice. In the lichess database, Black wins 56% of the games, while White wins only 41% (with the rest being drawn). Even in the Megadatabase, White scores only 38.5%.These numbers are far more relevant than the engine evaluation and are the best demonstration of the practical viability of this entire line.Note, btw, in passing, that Black can transpose to a variation of the French defence with4...e6,which may also be relevant in case you want to get your opponent out of their comfort zone and force them to play a position they don't usually play.} 
5. f4 {The most common and natural move in the position. White advances the f-pawn and reinforces the center, intending to develop the knight behind the pawn on f3 and handle the position in the same manner as they would handle the regular French defence.Let's quickly do a survey of other options:A) First of all, note that the capture on d5 is frequent - but also not ideal, as after5.Nxd5cxd4White can't go for the d4 pawn due to6.Qxd4Nb6!losing a piece. Note that 5.Nxd5 is the most common move in the lichess database.B) If5.dxc5, the easiest reply seems to be5...e6,going for a good version of the French defence where we will be able to collect the c5 pawn on the next move and then take it from there. It is true that some knowledge of the French structure/model games is helpful here, but overall, Black shouldn't have any particular problems in this variation.C) The same can be said about5.Nf3when5...e6seems to be a good idea, transposing to a big variation of the French where White didn't play f4. Our idea is to take on d4 next, play Nc6 and then take it from there.D) Finally,5.e6fxe6would transpose to the lines analyzed via 4.e6 move order.} 
5. cxd4 {I think this is the most challenging and tricky reply in this position. Black captures on d4 at the moment when there is no knight on f3 to recapture the pawn, forcing White to take a non-standard decision - to move the knight from c3 or to recapture on d4 with the queen.} 
6. Nb5 {Objectively speaking, this is the best move for White in the position. Our opponent refrains from capturing on d4 at once, but jumps with the knight in order to be able to recapture there with the piece and avoid having the queen harassed. This is the choice on the master level and above, although I wouldn't expect this move that often on lower levels.} 
6. Nc6 {For the moment, we continue developing normally and wait to see what White will do.} 
7. Nf3 {The point! Instead of capturing on d4 at once, White brings in the knight to f3 and attacks d4 one more time, in order to keep the knight on d4 after recapturing and avoid having the queen harassed, as would happen after the immediate7.Nxd4Nxd48.Qxd4e6when we are ready to go Bc5 next.} 
7. Nc5 {This seems to me to be the healthiest and most logical move in this position. Black activates the knight, eyeing the e4 square and also opens up the bishop to go to g4 and pin the knight on f3, thus trying to benefit from the fact that e6 was not played.I also looked at the move7...Qa5which is a valid alternative, but it does not score particularly well in the lichess database, so I thought it is not very practical.I should also mention that7...Ndb8has been played by the 'guru' himself - Oleksandr Bortnyk. The idea of this strange-looking move is to exchange one pair of knights and then to bring the other knight to c6, while also keeping the idea of Bg4 in the air. However, after8.Nbxd4I am not 100% sure in the position after either8...Nxd49.Nxd4Nc610.Be3, which seems like an inferior French,or8...Bg49.h3Nxd410.hxg4!when I feel Black's opening strategy has been a bit too slow to work.} 
8. Nbxd4 {The most natural recapture, bringing the knight from b5 closer to the center. The alternative 8.Nfxd4 is hardly ever played. On one hand, you might think it is sensible to try and avoid the pin via Bg4, but on the other hand, the construction with the knight on d4 and b5 is much less stable than the construction with the knights on f3 and d4.Black can emphasize it immediately with8...a6when9.Nxc6bxc610.Nd4Qb6is very nice for us, as we are pressuring the queenside and the knight on c5 is ready to jump to e4. At some future point, we will also play c6-c5 and kick the knight from d4 away and this whole line is not to be recommended for White.} 
8. Bg4 {A logical move, trying to utilize the absence of the pawn on e6 and to get the bishop outside of the pawn chain before locking things up by playing e6. Black goes for a good version of the French pawn structure where the main problem of the opening - the development of the light-squared bishop - is solved. And in contrast to, say, Caro-Kann, the bishop goes to g4 in one go, without first stopping on f5 and allowing some play on the kingside.} 
9. Be3 {In order to demonstrate a typical position that can arise in this variation, let's check this natural developing move as the main option. White moves the bishop to its lawful French post and eyes the c5 knight.It has to be said that the move9.Bb5,trying to pressure the c6 knight, might be more challenging. But first of all, it is really not the most obvious or common move in the position. And second of all, the consequences of it are not 100% clear. For example, after9...Rc810.O-Oe611.h3Bxf312.Qxf3Ne4was played in the game Perske - Kopylov, Playchess, 2021, where Black managed to outplay his GM opponent. Besides, instead of12...Ne4,12...g6seems to lead to a very unclear position where White will jump toe4at some point and where our structure is very solid and without any weaknesses, although White has the bishop pair and probably objectively somewhat better chances.} 
9. e6 {Now Black obtains a perfect version of the French defence with the light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain.} 
10. c3
10. Be7
11. Be2
11. O-O {And Black is very comfortable in this position. Some ideas include playing Ne4 and then Bc5, although it is also possible to slowly prepare the queenside expansion with a6-b5 and so on. Black does neet to be a little bit careful not to fall under some kingside attack with the timely f5, but all in all, the opening can be regarded as a big success as we managed to trick our opponent in an unfamiliar position and obtain a very complicated and playable middlegame - which is precisely what the Alekhine player is looking for.Conclusion: Rare 2nd move deviations against the Alekhine Defence are hardly the critical test of Black's provocative opening choice. The line with 2.Nc3, though, can be a little bit annoying as it makes it difficult for Black to play for the win without transposing to a completely different opening system. I think the line proposed in this chapter with 2...d5 3. e5 Nfd7 is very combative l and results in databases seem to confirm its practical value.} 
