1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5 {After covering all the possible rare 2nd moves in the previous chapter, it is now time to start focusing on this natural move, attacking the knight on f6 with a gain of tempo. It is indeed by far the main move in the position.} 
2. Nd5 {The most natural reply, trying to keep the knight in the center of the board. It is true that the knight can be chased away further with the advance of the c-pawn, but   A) That is precisely the point of Black's provocative opening, as we are claiming that after the premature advance of the pawns, the opponent's structure will be vulnerable to counterattacks,and  B) Other knight movers such as2...Ng8or2...Ne4are hardly any better.Now, the main moves for White naturally involve moving one of the central pawns with3.c4or3.d4. But before we get there, let's take a moment to investigate some other options available to White at this particular moment. I believe there are two moves that need to be at least mentioned - the development of the bishop with3.Bc4and the development of the knight with3.Nc3We will do so in the current chapter.} 
3. Bc4 {Apart from the move3.Nc3,which is by far the most serious deviation available to White on move 3, the text move is probably the only other 3rd move that needs to be analyzed to a certain extent. Similarly as in the 3.Nc3 lines, White tries to attack our knight on d5 with a piece instead of a pawn and avoid presenting us with a potential target in the center, aiming to control the center with the pieces and develop as quickly and rapidly as possible.On the other hand, with this move White does violate one of the basic principles (occupy the center first/develop your knights before the bishops), so it is not surprising that it provides Black with some additional options.} 
3. Nb6 {The most reasonable move, retreating the knight and attacking the bishop on c4 with a gain of tempo. This is quite a standard maneuver in the Alekhine's defence and there is absolutely no reason not to execute it here.I also briefly checked3...e6, but I really didn't like the positions arising after4.d4d65.Nf3,as I don't think moving the pawn to e6 is really beneficial in these typical Alekhine positions.} 
4. Bb3 {White naturally retreats the bishop. However, compared to the regular lines of the Alekhine defence, the bishop is somewhat exposed on b3. Furthermore, Black hasn't yet moved the d-pawn to d6, which gives the second player some additional options when it comes to choosing a setup.} 
4. d5 {This move, trying to transform the game into some sort of the French Defence. This is actually quite a standard Alekhine idea that can also be seen in some other variations - for example, in the position after1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.d4, the move3...Nb6is sometimes played, with the very same idea of playing d5 in one go, without wasting a tempo on d6.It has to be said that this is definitely not the only way of playing this position. In the lichess database, the best-scoring move is actually4...c5,trying to exploit the position of the bishop on b3. I was very tempted to give this move as the main option, but I ultimately decided against it due to the move5.c3- when quite a few lines actually transpose to the Alapin Sicilian. And even though the positions are harmless for Black, I couldn't bring myself to really recommend such a transposition, given that I am already highly annoyed when people play the Alapin against me via the regular Sicilian move order.I should also add that4...d6is a possible move order, but the positions after5.Nf3didn't really appeal to me, given that the engine suggests the move5...c5as the best possibility, once again allowing some transpositions to the Alapin Sicilian.} 
5. exd6 {Taking en passant on d6 is the most common move in this position, however, it is not a critical test of Black's position. It also gives us the option of recapturing with the queen, which we will happily do!'} 
5. Qxd6 {I think this is the simplest and healthiest way of recapturing in the given position - a method that is familiar from some variations of the Alapin Sicilian. Black basically gets a good version of the Scandinavian defence where we manage to put the queen on d6 without losing a tempo and being attacked by the knight on c3. We are also making an argument that the bishop on b3 is not ideally placed - and we also have the idea of exchanging it via Be6.It has to be said that capturing with any of the pawns would lead to a position resembling the regular Exchange variation, but if we have the opportunity to play a bit more creatively, yet very healthily - I believe we should take it.} 
6. d4 {The natural move, placing a pawn in the center of the board and gaining some space. Now Black has several options at disposal - and I really like the following suggestion.} 
6. a5 {Threatening a4. This is stronger than the immediate6...Qg6as without a5, White can ignore this and play7.Nf3when we do not dare to capture the pawn on g2 with7...Qxg2due to8.Rg1Qh39.Bxf7with a losing position.} 
7. a4 {An automatic reaction. One of the points behind Black's play can be seen if we consider what happens if White makes room for the bishop with7.c3Now we can indeed try to move the queen to g6 as after7...Qg68.Nf3we have8...a4!chasing the bishop from the ideal post.9.Bc2Qxg2when we win a pawn, for which White has to demonstrate the compensation.} 
7. Be6 {A nice idea. Now that the bishop on b3 has been somewhat destabilized, we propose an exchange and get rid of our bishop on c8 which can sometimes be short on squares in these structures. We have a very reasonable position and will follow up with moves such as Nc6-g6-Bg7.We will very likely castle short, although we can even consider castling long and it is clear why this shouldn't be one of the critical tests of the Alekhine.} 
