5. d4 {The most natural move, expanding in the center and reinforcing the e5 pawn. Now we can see that the game resembles some sort of Caro-Kann where we haven't spent time in playing c6, and where our knight is on b6 and the opponent's bishop is on b3.All in all, this should be a favourable version for us due to the saved tempo and due to the fact we can jump with the knight to c4 later on.} 
5. Bf5 {A natural move, placing the bishop outside of the pawn chain and intending to play e6 next.} 
6. c3 {Also a natural move, reinforcing the d4 pawn and forming a long pawn chain from c3 to e5, very typical of situations where White has pawns on d4 and e5 and anticipated that Black will try to undermine them with a timely c5.Note here that some immediate attacks on the kingside don't work, say after6.g4we can play6...Be4!to provoke the f-pawn to move and after7.f3Bg6we are happy with all the concessions and pawn moves White has made as8.h4h5is not at all problematic.} 
6. e6 {The logical continuation of the plan. Black places the pawn on e6 now that the bishop is outside of the pawn chain on f5 and clearly intends to follow up with c5 next.} 
7. Ne2 {Another very logical move. White develops the knight to e2 in order to later place it to g3, harassing the bishop on f5 and helping with the thematic f4-f5 ideas.Against the more natural move7.Nf3,we have an easy game as we can simply increase the pressure on the d4 pawn with natural moves such as7...c58.O-ONc6and now after9.Be3we can even consider moving the bishop again with9...Bg4,pinning the knight on f3 and increasing the pressure on d4 even further. Black basically has a very good version of the advance variation of the Caro-Kann here.} 
7. c5 {Nevertheless, we embark on this thematic pawn move, striking in the center and trying to create pressure against the base of the pawn chain - the pawn on d4.} 
8. Ng3 {A logical continuation, hitting the bishop and getting the knight to a square where it is helping with the potential kingside attack.Trying to keep the center intact instead does no good for White, for example,8.Nd2Nc69.Nf3Be710.Be3cxd4!Black already had a fine position with ideas of jumping with the knight to c4. White decided to take with the knight with11.Nexd4but after11...Bg6Black had no problems and his position could be even slightly more preferred due to the absence of weaknesses and very harmonious development. As a matter of fact, he did go on to beat his strong opponent in Nakamura - Zhalmakhanov, Chesscom, 2021.} 
8. Bg6
9. O-O
9. Nc6 {Increasing the pressure on d4 while continuing to develop.} 
10. f4 {The most logical continuation and one that looks very scary if you don't know what to do against it. White obviously wants to utilize the rook on f1 and the knight on g3 to execute a desired breakthrough with f5.Once again, if White tries to play more solidly and, say, focus on maintaining the d4 pawn, then after10.Be3cxd411.cxd4we can utilize the position of the knight on b6 to play11...Nc4,harassing the bishop on e3 and being more than prepared to recapture on c4 with the pawn should White take on c4. This variation illustrates why it is not at all so bad for Black to have the knight on b6 and is another reason why I consider these positions more favourable compared to the regular Caro-Kann.} 
10. Be7 {It turns out Black can simply ignore White's demonstration and finish with the development.} 
11. f5
11. exf5
12. Nxf5
12. O-O {And even though White can take our bishop pair with13.Nxe7after13...Qxe7we have no problems as we are still ahead in development and have some pressure on the central d4 pawn. Next, we can contemplate bringing the queenside rook into the game and then even opening the position further with f6.} 
