[White "4) Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves: 3.Qf3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5 {After covering all the possible rare 2nd moves in the previous chapter, it is now time to start focusing on this natural move, attacking the knight on f6 with a gain of tempo. It is indeed by far the main move in the position.} 
2. Nd5 {The most natural reply, trying to keep the knight in the center of the board. It is true that the knight can be chased away further with the advance of the c-pawn, but   A) That is precisely the point of Black's provocative opening, as we are claiming that after the premature advance of the pawns, the opponent's structure will be vulnerable to counterattacks,and  B) Other knight movers such as2...Ng8or2...Ne4are hardly any better.Now, the main moves for White naturally involve moving one of the central pawns with3.c4or3.d4. But before we get there, let's take a moment to investigate some other options available to White at this particular moment. I believe there are two moves that need to be at least mentioned - the development of the bishop with3.Bc4and the development of the knight with3.Nc3We will do so in the current chapter.} 
3. Qf3 {The following queen move was proposed in the course Grandmaster Gambits, Part 2: Aggressive Lines here on Chessable. While it is not at all so naive or silly as it looks, it is certainly not the critical test of the Alekhine and is rather more exotic and tricky than actually good. The idea is to attack the knight on d5 and then potentially to attack it with Nc3, seeking to develop quickly on the queenside.} 
3. e6 {A logical move. We defend the knight on e6 and intend to play d6 next, undermining the center in typical Alekhine style.} 
4. Nc3 {The point of White's play. They are trying to undermine the knight on d5 and open the d-file, quickly going for the queenside castling.} 
4. Nb4 {A very nice and somewhat unexpected resource, demonstrating the drawback of the early queen move. We avoid the threat of exchange on d5 with the gain of time and attack the pawn on c2. Note that there is nothing particularly wrong with4...Nxc3, but the text move seems simpler and more practical, as we refrain from giving White exactly what they want.} 
5. Qd1 {What else?5.Kd1is a bit too exotic to be seriously considered, but just in case - we can simply continue with5...d6and take it from there.It should also be mentioned that5.Qe4,defending the pawn c2 and attacking the knight on b4 doesn't work due to5...N8c66.a3d5!7.exd6f5!wins the pawn on c2 and the rook on a1. Note that the pawn on d6 is blocking the bishop from protecting the b4 knight, which is why 5...N8c6 defending it, was played.} 
5. d6 {Finally we undermine the center in typical Alekhine style.} 
6. a3 {The main line of Palliser and Simon's analysis and the most logical move, kicking the pesky knight away. Something like6.Nf3is met with6...dxe57.Nxe5N8c6with a perfectly reasonable game.} 
6. Nd5 {We don't really mind returning back to d5 now that the queen is back to d1 as we are no longer under the threat of losing a pawn.} 
7. Nf3 {If White takes on d5 we are not concerned as we will easily undouble our pawns after a subsequent capture on e5. We will see similar variations elsewhere in this chapter/course, so I wouldn't devote too much attention to 7.Nxd5. I would rather illustrate one important concept later in this line.} 
7. dxe5 {The whole point of playing d6 is to take on e5 and force White to capture with the piece.} 
8. Nxe5
8. Nxc3 {A nice idea. Now we no longer mind taking on c3 as White's idea of taking with the d-pawn and quickly going with the queenside castling is simply no longer viable.} 
9. bxc3 {Else we happily exchange queens and play the better endgame. But obviously, this is not what White wants when they play Nc3 in these positions.} 
9. Nd7 {Now we challenge the knight on e5 and have a very healthy, slightly more preferable position. Next on the cards is Be7 and castling, while later down the road we can also develop our light-squared bishop to b7 via b6-Bb7. Black doesn't have any particular problems in a position like this as we have no weaknesses, can develop freely, and don't even have significant lack of space.} 
