[Black "Rare 3rd Moves: 3.Nc3 with 4.bxc3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5 {After covering all the possible rare 2nd moves in the previous chapter, it is now time to start focusing on this natural move, attacking the knight on f6 with a gain of tempo. It is indeed by far the main move in the position.} 
2. Nd5 {The most natural reply, trying to keep the knight in the center of the board. It is true that the knight can be chased away further with the advance of the c-pawn, but   A) That is precisely the point of Black's provocative opening, as we are claiming that after the premature advance of the pawns, the opponent's structure will be vulnerable to counterattacks,and  B) Other knight movers such as2...Ng8or2...Ne4are hardly any better.Now, the main moves for White naturally involve moving one of the central pawns with3.c4or3.d4. But before we get there, let's take a moment to investigate some other options available to White at this particular moment. I believe there are two moves that need to be at least mentioned - the development of the bishop with3.Bc4and the development of the knight with3.Nc3We will do so in the current chapter.} 
3. Nc3 {Out of all the 3rd move options available, this one is arguably the most serious one. White immediately challenges the knight on d5 and invites us to take on c3, when they would like to open up the d-file and the diagonal for their c1 bishop and then quickly go for the plan involving the queenside development.When I came back to the Alekhine after a long hiatus, this variation gave me problems, especially in games with faster time control.} 
3. Nxc3 {After analyzing various possibilities, I have concluded that there is nothing obviously wrong with this natural move, capturing the knight on c3 and doubling our opponent's pawns. It was also recommended by NM Bryan Tillis in his course The Dark Knight Rises here on Chessable.If you are searching for an alternative, the move3...e6was recommended by GM Roland Pruijssers in his excellent Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine course here on Chessable. But I am not 100% sure how much I like the position arising after4.Nxd5exd55.d4d66.Nf3- it seems to me it is a bit difficult for Black to generate real winning chances in this symmetrical structure, although Black has also probably equalized with ease.} 
4. bxc3 {To be completely honest, at first I almost ignored this recapture with the b-pawn, as I can't recall if it was ever played against me - even in blitz online and bullet games. Still, it is a move that is both possible and played in practice, so I thought it might be sensible to devote it a trainable or two. Obviously, the idea here is to open the b-file and recapture toward the center, keeping the option of playing d4 later down the road. Let's see how we are supposed to deal with it.} 
4. e6 {I really like this strange-looking move, and allow me to explain why. Basically, in this type of position, we would very much like to transpose to the French structure by playing a setup with d5-c5-e6 and so on, as then we will very likely transpose to a position similar to the Winawer variation where White has the doubled c-pawns, but where we didn't give up our dark-squared bishop. The question, is, however, how to best go about it.The move4...d5seems a logical choice and was, in fact, recommended by Bryan Tillis in his Chessable course, but I really didn't like that White can refrain from playing d4 and go for something like5.Ba3or5.a4The move4...c5is also an attempt to transpose to similar positions with5.d4d5, but it also does allow some extra options such as6.exd6which I wanted to avoid. Thus, the text move seemed like a logical choice - especially when I realized that d4 is the most common move in this position.Allow me also to add that the standard Alekhine play doesn't seem ideal since after something like4...d65.f4I feel it is a bit difficult to create pressure against White's center. Here we will not be playing against the pawn on e5 - but rather the one on d4 and c3!} 
5. d4 {The most common and natural move, advancing the pawn in the center now that White kept it on d2. White can also try to avoid playing with d4 here and play, say,5.f4, but this is not such a problem, in my opinion. We continue in a very similar manner and go for the French structure with5...c56.Nf3d57.Be2Nc68.O-OBe7and next on the table is castling short and then either playing f6 to undermine the structure or f5 to block it completely.It is true that our bishop on c8 is passive for the moment due to the fact we played e6 quite early in the game, but we have kept our dark-squared bishop and White does have the doubled c-pawns, which means we have a better version of the regular French positions.} 
5. d5 {This is the point! In these variations, we are not trying to play against the e5 pawn, but rather transpose to the French structure where White will have the doubled and weak c-pawns, while we will have kept our bishop on f8 (which is usually the piece being exchanged for the knight on c3 to create the weakness).} 
6. Nf3
6. c5 {A logical French move, creating pressure on the pawn on d4. Although, in this particular case, we will not be maintaining that pressure for long. Instead, we will rapidly close down the position.} 
7. Be2 {A better square for the bishop than d3 as after7.Bd3we are more than happy to play7...c4- given that we will do so even with the bishop on e2.} 
7. Nc6
8. O-O
8. c4 {An important strategical concept. Black decides to close the structure and release the tension in the center. At first glance, it looks strange, but even in regular French, this idea is sometimes executed - and here it makes a lot of sense because we still have our dark-squared bishop, so the weakness of the a3-f8 diagonal is non-existent. Black's plan is to play the moves Qa5-Bd7 and then actually castle long, planning to execute kingside operations in the future.} 
9. a4 {This is a standard move in these positions. But usually, it is followed by Ba3 when the bishop is dominating on this diagonal. But here, this maneuver is not as powerful given that our bishop is still on f8 - a subtle, yet major difference.} 
9. Qa5 {A logical move, attacking the c3 pawn and blocking the a-pawn. Optionally, the computer recommends9...a5, intending to play b5 to create a passed pawn on the a-file. In this case, Black could castle kingside. Still, I propose a more natural and human way of playing.} 
10. Qd2 {A more logical move than10.Bd2when we would continue in a very similar manner with10...Bd7} 
10. Bd7 {We don't care at all for White's demonstration and are preparing to castle long.} 
11. Ba3 {A logical maneuver, trying to exchange the dark-squared bishops. But this just doesn't have the same impact because we have a dark-squared bishop to contest the f8-a3 diagonal as compared to the French Winawer.} 
11. Bxa3
12. Rxa3
12. O-O-O {Black is perfectly happy with this position. White's pieces are not ideally placed and it is hard for them to create threats on either side of the board. We can always play h6 to safeguard the kingside, can contemplate opening the kingside with f6, and can even put the king on a8, the rook on b8, and then contemplate opening the queenside with b5. In any case, we can face the future with optimism and I feel this entire variation showcases some very typical ideas for this line with 4.bxc3.} 
