4. dxc3 {The more common recapture in this position. White opens up the d-file and the diagonal for the c1 bishop and intends to quickly develop the forces with Bf4-Qd2 and then castle long. This idea of doubling the c-pawns in order to aim for rapid development is very standard and known from some other openings, such as the Nimzo-Sicilian1.e4c52.Nf3Nf63.e5Nd54.Nc3!?or the Vienna after1.e4e52.Nc3Nf63.f4d54.fxe5Nxe45.Qf3Nxc36.dxc3!?or the Petroff after1.e4e52.Nf3Nf63.Nxe5d64.Nf3Nxe45.Nc3Nxc36.dxc3} 
4. d6 {So how should Black best deal with White's idea of rapid development? Well, what we want to do is try to fight against the pawn on e5 that is providing White with a nice space advantage. If we manage to pressure that pawn or force White to make the exchange on d6, we should be reasonably happy as then our pieces would get more breathing room and our development would be more fluid.} 
5. Nf3 {The most natural move, defending the pawn and developing a knight. Note that5.exd6is precisely what we are aiming for as after5...cxd6(or even 5...Qxd6) we are more than happy with the elimination of the e5 pawn. We would also be more than happy to exchange queens and go in an endgame - as there White's worsened pawn structure might become a much more relevant factor. Note that here we are benefiting from having the knight on b8 as after6.Bd3we have6...Nd7with ideas of Ne5 and Nc5, eliminating the bishop on d3 and forcing the queen trade.Also - I don't really see a point in starting with5.Bc4as then after5...Nc6White either has to play6.Nf3transposing to text, or concede the pawn on e5 and play6.exd6Qxd6when Black has no problems as we have managed to eliminate the pawn on e5 which was restricting us severely.} 
5. Nc6 {A logical move, developing the knight and increasing the pressure on the e5 pawn, asking White a question - how do they want to deal with the increasing tension in the center?} 
6. Bb5 {This pinning move, trying to pressure the knight on c6 and indirectly defend the pawn on e5, is by far the most common move in the position - and the one you are very likely to encounter in your own games. Note that White should develop the bishop to b5 if they want to start by developing the light-squared bishop, as6.Bc4is not at all problematic as we can simply capture on e5 with6...dxe5and after7.Qe2play very greedily and try to preserve the pawn with7...f6Following8.Be3e69.Rd1we can play9...Bd6and are very solid, while preserving the extra pawn. Of course, White's play can be improved, but I don't see why they would allow us to capture on e5 just like that.} 
6. a6 {After analyzing the position for a bit, I realized I really like this move, attacking the bishop on b5 and basically forcing it to capture the knight on c6. In his course, Tillis only analyzed6...Bd7, but I feel this gives White precisely what they want as after7.Qe2a68.Bd3they are ready to go long castle next and create some attacking chances, while controlling the center thanks to the pawn on e5.Note, on the other hand, that the engine once again mentions the move6...Qd7as a possibility, but I really can't bring myself to recommend this move in a position and then explain this choice in human language.Finally, it has to be added that going for6...dxe5which was the prescription against 6.Bf4, is not that good here, as after7.Qxd8Kxd88.Bxc6bxc69.Nxe5our position is in ruins, our structure is horrible, the king is not ideal on d8 and we are losing a pawn due to the double attack. Not to be recommended.} 
7. Bxc6+ {Of course, White has to capture on c6 as otherwise, they would lose the pawn on e5 for nothing.} 
7. bxc6 {We have allowed our opponent to double our c-pawns, but in return, we have eliminated their bishop pair and also obtained the open b-file for the rook. Next, we are going to play Qd7 and f6 almost irrespective of what White does - and this combative plan was what attracted me to this variation in the first place.} 
8. O-O {This is the most logical and most common move in the position - but I think we are very happy when we manage to avoid setups with castling long in these positions where our opponent has voluntarily doubled the c-pawns earlier in the game. With that being said, any other moves would be met in a very similar fashion as the text move.For example, after8.Bf4we go8...Qd79.Qe2f6,just as after8.Be3Qd79.Qe2f6In either case, one of the possibilities is to play Qe6, e.g.10.O-O-OQe6when White is more or less forced to take on d6 and after11.exd6cxd6we are very happy to have our pawns and undoubled and to still have the bishop pair. Even if we are behind in development, we are claiming we are very solid and that there isn't an immediate way for White to exploit this factor.} 
8. Qd7 {My proposed solution. It looks a little bit artificial to block in the bishop on c8, but with this move, we are covering the e6 square and the c6 pawn and basically preparing to play f6 in the near future, given it is not so good to play it here due to8...f69.exf6gxf6when10.Nd4attacks the pawn on c6 and also threatens Qh5 ideas - which is definitely not very desirable. We will develop the bishop via b7 or a6 later in the game, anyway.I chose this idea in this particular position due to its universality - as we have seen, it is very much viable against other setups for White.} 
9. Re1 {Preventing Black's idea. Note that any other move would be met with the advance of the f-pawn, such as9.Bf4f6or9.Qe2f6} 
9. e6 {A necessary inclusion, preventing White from sticking the e6 pawn into our throat, as would be the case after9...f610.e6Now we are basically ready to play f6 on the next move.} 
10. Bf4 {A logical developing move. Other moves are met in a very similar manner.} 
10. f6 {This looks very 'ugly' at first glance and it also violates one of Ben Finegold's principles (never play 'f6'), but it is actually a very combative and sound idea. Black does everything possible to get rid of the strong pawn on e5 and emphasizes that White doesn't really have a way of getting at the king behind the central bulwark, due to the fact that White has no pawns to use as battering rams in the center.} 
11. exf6
11. gxf6 {And even though our construction with the 5 pawns on the 6th rank looks strange and loose and even though we apparently haven't yet developed a single piece - we are already somewhat better as our pawn mass in the center is very powerful. We will play e5-Be7-O-O next and easily catch up with the development - and there is nothing White can do to stop us. I would take the Black pieces here gladly as I feel our play is much easier!} 
