[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves: 3.Nc3 with 4.dxc3 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5 {After covering all the possible rare 2nd moves in the previous chapter, it is now time to start focusing on this natural move, attacking the knight on f6 with a gain of tempo. It is indeed by far the main move in the position.} 
2. Nd5 {The most natural reply, trying to keep the knight in the center of the board. It is true that the knight can be chased away further with the advance of the c-pawn, but   A) That is precisely the point of Black's provocative opening, as we are claiming that after the premature advance of the pawns, the opponent's structure will be vulnerable to counterattacks,and  B) Other knight movers such as2...Ng8or2...Ne4are hardly any better.Now, the main moves for White naturally involve moving one of the central pawns with3.c4or3.d4. But before we get there, let's take a moment to investigate some other options available to White at this particular moment. I believe there are two moves that need to be at least mentioned - the development of the bishop with3.Bc4and the development of the knight with3.Nc3We will do so in the current chapter.} 
3. Nc3 {Out of all the 3rd move options available, this one is arguably the most serious one. White immediately challenges the knight on d5 and invites us to take on c3, when they would like to open up the d-file and the diagonal for their c1 bishop and then quickly go for the plan involving the queenside development.When I came back to the Alekhine after a long hiatus, this variation gave me problems, especially in games with faster time control.} 
3. Nxc3 {After analyzing various possibilities, I have concluded that there is nothing obviously wrong with this natural move, capturing the knight on c3 and doubling our opponent's pawns. It was also recommended by NM Bryan Tillis in his course The Dark Knight Rises here on Chessable.If you are searching for an alternative, the move3...e6was recommended by GM Roland Pruijssers in his excellent Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine course here on Chessable. But I am not 100% sure how much I like the position arising after4.Nxd5exd55.d4d66.Nf3- it seems to me it is a bit difficult for Black to generate real winning chances in this symmetrical structure, although Black has also probably equalized with ease.} 
4. dxc3 {The more common recapture in this position. White opens up the d-file and the diagonal for the c1 bishop and intends to quickly develop the forces with Bf4-Qd2 and then castle long. This idea of doubling the c-pawns in order to aim for rapid development is very standard and known from some other openings, such as the Nimzo-Sicilian1.e4c52.Nf3Nf63.e5Nd54.Nc3!?or the Vienna after1.e4e52.Nc3Nf63.f4d54.fxe5Nxe45.Qf3Nxc36.dxc3!?or the Petroff after1.e4e52.Nf3Nf63.Nxe5d64.Nf3Nxe45.Nc3Nxc36.dxc3} 
4. d6 {So how should Black best deal with White's idea of rapid development? Well, what we want to do is try to fight against the pawn on e5 that is providing White with a nice space advantage. If we manage to pressure that pawn or force White to make the exchange on d6, we should be reasonably happy as then our pieces would get more breathing room and our development would be more fluid.} 
5. Nf3 {The most natural move, defending the pawn and developing a knight. Note that5.exd6is precisely what we are aiming for as after5...cxd6(or even 5...Qxd6) we are more than happy with the elimination of the e5 pawn. We would also be more than happy to exchange queens and go in an endgame - as there White's worsened pawn structure might become a much more relevant factor. Note that here we are benefiting from having the knight on b8 as after6.Bd3we have6...Nd7with ideas of Ne5 and Nc5, eliminating the bishop on d3 and forcing the queen trade.Also - I don't really see a point in starting with5.Bc4as then after5...Nc6White either has to play6.Nf3transposing to text, or concede the pawn on e5 and play6.exd6Qxd6when Black has no problems as we have managed to eliminate the pawn on e5 which was restricting us severely.} 
5. Nc6 {A logical move, developing the knight and increasing the pressure on the e5 pawn, asking White a question - how do they want to deal with the increasing tension in the center?} 
6. exd6 {Last but not least - let me cover this move which, is not the most popular in this position, but which actually provided me quite a headache. White tries to exchange on d6 at the moment where we have committed our knight to c6, claiming that the absence of the Nd7-Nc5 resource is significantly in their favour. This move was not covered in Bryan Tillis' course, but I feel it is not at all so naive and silly as it looks at the first glance!} 
6. Qxd6 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this move. I do have to mention that the move6...exd6would actually transpose to a very theoretical variation of the Petroff defence (?!), which is obviously not what we are aiming for as Alekhine players.On the other hand, I was considering the move6...cxd6, but I didn't find a good way of stopping the plan of7.Be3, intending castling long. The engine suggested some strange7...Qc78.Qd2e5!?,but I feel it is really not practical or natural to play in such a manner.} 
7. Bd3 {A logical move for White, preventing us from exchanging queens and intending to execute the desired plan with Be3-Qd2/Qe2 and O-O-O, which is especially potent now that we don't have Nd7-Nc5 resources and that our queen is somewhat exposed on d6.} 
7. g6 {This move will be my recommendation. This is a natural move in this structure that keeps the option of playing Bg7 open. But quite importantly - the move also prepares the move Bf5, eliminating the bishop on d3 and nipping the dangerous plan with castling long in the bud.This move is technically a novelty. In practical games, only7...Bg4was seen, but after8.h3Bh59.Qe2I really don't like the fact that O-O-O is coming and that we have to react by moving our queen away. It might still be playable, but if given the choice, I would rather prevent this plan altogether.} 
8. Be3 {The most logical and dangerous move, preparing either Qd2/Qe2 and then castling long. If White decides to castle short - we will have no problems.Say after8.O-OBg79.Qe2O-ONow White can't go for the kingside attack so easily and it is harder for them to justify the weakening of the pawn structure on the queenside (although their position is quite healthy and solid, of course).} 
8. Bf5 {This is the idea! We are trying to ease our position by exchanging some pieces, thus avoiding the dangerous plan involving the castling long. It may look a bit artificial to double our pawns voluntarily, but if White captures on f5, we do get the opportunity to exchange queens - and also open the g-file.} 
9. Bxf5 {This is the move I would expect the majority of human opponents to make  (it is hard to say as the position hasn't yet been tested in practice). What can be more logical than exchanging on the spot and doubling the f-pawns?Objectively, though, a move like9.Qe2might be a bit more combative, although even there, I don't think Black has any particular problems after the bishop exchange, say after9...Bxd310.cxd3e5Next, we want to play Bg7 and can also choose to castle either way.} 
9. Qxd1+ {Of course, this is one of the points. We gladly take the opportunity to exchange the queens in this position.} 
10. Rxd1
10. gxf5 {I think this endgame is equal, as both sides have doubled pawns, but no particularly obvious weaknesses. Black wants to play e6-Be7 next and then potentially utilize the g-file with Rg8. We can consider playing h5-h4 at some point and if necessary, we can defend the c7 pawn with Rc8 if White attacks it. Later down the road, we also want to reroute the knight from c6 to greener pastures - potentially via e7 and g6.In any case, I think our position is quite healthy and I would consider our opening a success - especially since I wouldn't expect White to capture on d6 on move 6 in the majority of your games.Conclusion: Out of all White's 3rd move alternatives against the Alekhine Defence, the move 3. Nc3 is by far the most serious and tricky to handle. I think that my proposed solution involving the capture on c3 and then playing against the e5 pawn is the cleanest attempt to achieve equality. As usual with sidelines - we objectively shouldn't experience serious problems - provided we do know a few details.} 
