[White "5) 3.c4: Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "3.c4 4.b3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. c4 {After examining all the possible deviations and sidelines by White on move three (and also two), in the previous two chapters, it is now time to start covering the more mainstream (and objectively - more dangerous options), available on move 3 (and onward).Now, for a long time, this logical move of the c-pawn, attacking the exposed knight on d5 with the gain of tempo, was considered to be the main line - and is indeed one of the main options available to White even today.However, in modern times, there is a solid argument to be made for3.d4, withholding the advance of the c-pawn for the moment. To be fair, the moves have a big transpositional value, as after the most common move3...d6(which will be the recommendation of this repertoire) White can still play4.c4and basically transpose to the3.c4move order.However, after3.d4d6, White more commonly plays without the advance of the c-pawn with4.Nf3With that being said, the move-order3.c4also has some peculiarities, most notably when White refrains from advancing the d-pawn on the next move. For simplicity's sake, I have decided to first cover all possible lines via this move-order - and then conclude the course with the coverage of 3.d4 variations. In the process, I will try my best to point out all the possible instances when 3.c4 and 3.d4 move orders transpose to each other.} 
3. Nb6 {The only sensible move by the knight.3...Nf4is bad for very obvious reasons after4.d4(development with a tempo),while some people have tried3...Nb4when after4.d4the knight will very likely end up on a6 at some point, where it is almost certainly placed even worse than on b6. Would not recommend.After3...Nb6the move4.d4is by far the most common and natural reply, which will be examined in great depth in later chapters. However, White does have a few other 4th move options available at their disposal, that are perhaps not objectively the best, but that can be very tricky and venomous if faced without any knowledge. In this chapter, we will cover them in some depth and ensure that we are not surprised when they appear in our own games.} 
4. b3 {This quiet move, trying to defend the c4 pawn, limit the knight on b6 and develop the bishop to b2 is sometimes played, but it is definitely not critical as White is not taking the center and trying to punish us for our provocative play.} 
4. d6 {As usual in the Alekhine, we immediately challenge the center and the pawn on e5.} 
5. exd6 {Since White refrained from placing the pawn on d4 earlier, now they have to give up the center as otherwise Black will gladly take on e5 and blast the center open.Note that something like5.Nf3doesn't work as after5...dxe56.Nxe5we even have6...Qd4with a double attack on the rook and the knight. Not that I expect such variations to ever appear on the board.} 
5. Qxd6 {The most ambitious. In the regular exchange variation with the knight on b6, this is usually not possible due to some potential c5 forks, but here Black can get away with this ambitious queen recapture due to White's very slow move b3 earlier. In general, Black likes to capture on d6 with the queen in the Alekhine when possible, in order to activate the piece and keep the d-file open.} 
6. d4 {The most logical move, seemingly challenging Black's entire setup due to the potential c5 fork. But one discovery I (Read - my engine) made while preparing for this course is - Black doesn't really have to deal with the potential threat of c5 yet.} 
6. Nc6
7. c5 {The most obvious move in the position - but it fails tactically. However, if White plays something like7.Be3,defending the pawn on d4 and threatening c5, we can switch plans and go for the e5 break, e.g.7...Qf68.Nf3e5Given how rare this whole 4.b3 system is, there is probably no need to remember too much here - as they say, against all these random moves it is sufficient to 'just play chess'.} 
7. Qxd4 {The point of Black's play. Now we are threatening the rook on a1 so White is forced to take.} 
8. Qxd4
8. Nxd4
9. cxb6 {White should take the piece, otherwise we will move the knight and have two pieces in play and the target on c5. Now we have some Nc2 ideas on the horizon, but we can play even more strongly!} 
9. axb6 {A tremendous move, opening up the a-file for the rook and introducing the threat of Nxb3 in the mix as well. White's best move here is10.Na3, allowing10...Rxa311.Bxa3Nc212.Kd2Nxa3when we are clearly better with the two pawns for the exchange! A fascinating line that you probably won't encounter that often over the board, but which does showcase some typical ideas - as well as how quickly some tactics can appear in the position if White players don't play principled chess in the opening!} 
