1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. c4 {After examining all the possible deviations and sidelines by White on move three (and also two), in the previous two chapters, it is now time to start covering the more mainstream (and objectively - more dangerous options), available on move 3 (and onward).Now, for a long time, this logical move of the c-pawn, attacking the exposed knight on d5 with the gain of tempo, was considered to be the main line - and is indeed one of the main options available to White even today.However, in modern times, there is a solid argument to be made for3.d4, withholding the advance of the c-pawn for the moment. To be fair, the moves have a big transpositional value, as after the most common move3...d6(which will be the recommendation of this repertoire) White can still play4.c4and basically transpose to the3.c4move order.However, after3.d4d6, White more commonly plays without the advance of the c-pawn with4.Nf3With that being said, the move-order3.c4also has some peculiarities, most notably when White refrains from advancing the d-pawn on the next move. For simplicity's sake, I have decided to first cover all possible lines via this move-order - and then conclude the course with the coverage of 3.d4 variations. In the process, I will try my best to point out all the possible instances when 3.c4 and 3.d4 move orders transpose to each other.} 
3. Nb6 {The only sensible move by the knight.3...Nf4is bad for very obvious reasons after4.d4(development with a tempo),while some people have tried3...Nb4when after4.d4the knight will very likely end up on a6 at some point, where it is almost certainly placed even worse than on b6. Would not recommend.After3...Nb6the move4.d4is by far the most common and natural reply, which will be examined in great depth in later chapters. However, White does have a few other 4th move options available at their disposal, that are perhaps not objectively the best, but that can be very tricky and venomous if faced without any knowledge. In this chapter, we will cover them in some depth and ensure that we are not surprised when they appear in our own games.} 
4. a4 {This extravagant pawn push is named after the controversial American IM Emory Tate, who is nowadays known even outside of the chess circles as being the father to the even more controversial 'entrepreneur' Andrew Tate. I will refrain from elaborating in great detail on their horrible ideas in a chess book/course, but I will remark that seemingly, the things bearing the Tate family name very often turn out to be dubious, irrespective if we are talking about an opening variation or a human being.With that being said, this push of the a-pawn is a fairly standard idea whenever there is a knight on b6. It is also sometimes seen in some other variations of the Alekhine, say after1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.d4Nb64.a4!?So, why is this idea that is standard in one position far from optimal in another one? Well, in this given position, White has also pushed the c-pawn forward, which means that their control of the b4 square has been significantly weakened compared to variations where there is the possibility of playing c2-c3. These small details make an entire difference - especially after Black's next move.} 
4. a5 {In view of what I have written above, this is to be expected. Black pushes the a-pawn forward, takes the b4 square under control, and emphasizes its weakness.} 
5. Ra3 {This rook lift was one of Emory Tate's ideas in this position. On one hand, there is some logic in trying to follow up the push of the a-pawn with the rook lift, as rooks are known to be notoriously difficult to develop. But on the other hand, moving the rook so early in the game merely provides us with the opportunity to harass the rook even further and gain a few tempi.With that being said, after some natural move such as5.d4, we will continue in the standard Alekhine style with5...d6when White merely has a worse version of the regular Alekhine variations due to the weakness of the b4 square.} 
5. e6 {Gaining a tempo by attacking the rook ona3. This is even more ambitious than trying to play the normal Alekhine move5...d6,as we are trying to basically punish White for the provocative opening play.} 
6. Rg3 {This is the idea - developing the rook to the kingside, pressuring the g7 pawn, and claiming that the pawn on e5 is restricting Black's movement.} 
6. Nc6 {Continuing to develop the pieces with the gain of tempo as now the e5 pawn is under the attack, while the knight is also eyeing the vulnerable b4 square.} 
7. d4 {Defending the pawn in the most natural way.7.Nf3is met with the same7...d6} 
7. d6 {A great move, striking in the center and executing the core idea of the entire Alekhine defence.} 
8. exd6
8. Bxd6 {Black can already afford to play very ambitiously as we have three pieces in play now and White has only the rook on g3. We are not concerned with the capture on g7 after9.Rxg7as after9...Qf6we will win the pawn on d4. And otherwise, it is a big question of what White should do. Since the best move involves simply sacrificing the rook on g3, we can safely stop here and conclude that White's entire opening experiment has resulted in a big failure.} 
