1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. c4 {After examining all the possible deviations and sidelines by White on move three (and also two), in the previous two chapters, it is now time to start covering the more mainstream (and objectively - more dangerous options), available on move 3 (and onward).Now, for a long time, this logical move of the c-pawn, attacking the exposed knight on d5 with the gain of tempo, was considered to be the main line - and is indeed one of the main options available to White even today.However, in modern times, there is a solid argument to be made for3.d4, withholding the advance of the c-pawn for the moment. To be fair, the moves have a big transpositional value, as after the most common move3...d6(which will be the recommendation of this repertoire) White can still play4.c4and basically transpose to the3.c4move order.However, after3.d4d6, White more commonly plays without the advance of the c-pawn with4.Nf3With that being said, the move-order3.c4also has some peculiarities, most notably when White refrains from advancing the d-pawn on the next move. For simplicity's sake, I have decided to first cover all possible lines via this move-order - and then conclude the course with the coverage of 3.d4 variations. In the process, I will try my best to point out all the possible instances when 3.c4 and 3.d4 move orders transpose to each other.} 
3. Nb6 {The only sensible move by the knight.3...Nf4is bad for very obvious reasons after4.d4(development with a tempo),while some people have tried3...Nb4when after4.d4the knight will very likely end up on a6 at some point, where it is almost certainly placed even worse than on b6. Would not recommend.After3...Nb6the move4.d4is by far the most common and natural reply, which will be examined in great depth in later chapters. However, White does have a few other 4th move options available at their disposal, that are perhaps not objectively the best, but that can be very tricky and venomous if faced without any knowledge. In this chapter, we will cover them in some depth and ensure that we are not surprised when they appear in our own games.} 
4. c5 {Out of all 'strange' fourth moves available at White's disposal in the position with the pawn on c4, this one - leading to the so-called Chase variation - is definitely the most serious. White spends another tempo to attack our knight and forces it back to d5. At first glance, this merely exposes the c5 pawn and the center further, but White also increases the control of the d6 square and grabs some more space.Furthermore, just like in the1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3variation, the idea is to try and destabilize the knight on d5 by attacking it with Nc3 or Bc4 next.} 
4. Nd5 {Of course, this move is a no-brainer as the knight doesn't have anywhere else to go.} 
5. Bc4 {Apart from the move5.Nc3,which is more logical, White also has this developing move at their disposal, attacking the knight on d5. I don't think it is a particularly good option as it violates the principle of developing the knights before the bishops and merely provides Black with some additional options.} 
5. e6 {This move, defending the knight on d5, will also be our choice against 5.Nc3, so it makes sense to keep things universal. Besides, I also believe it is objectively healthier compared to some5...c6,which is also an option that has quite a good record in the databases.} 
6. d4 {The only independent option in this position worth examining. White defends the c5 pawn and refrains from moving the knight to c3 just yet.6.Nc3would transpose to the lines examined via the 5.Nc3 e6 6. Bc4 move order,while6.Bxd5is really not an option here as White doesn't really want to give up the bishop for the knight on d5. We will see that even with the knight on c3 we shouldn't really be afraid of the capture on d5, and here White merely gets an inferior version. For example, after6...exd57.d4d68.cxd6cxd69.Nf3Nc6and the variation is very similar to the mainline, but White has given up the strong light-squared bishop, which can't be in their favour.} 
6. b6 {This move, undermining White's central construction from the side, is an additional option available to Black due to White's imprecise move order involving the early bishop development. There is nothing wrong with6...d6either, but the text move is more ambitious. As long as you undermine the center in the Alekhine - you will be good to go.} 
7. cxb6 {This is the most common move according to both lichess and master databases, but it doesn't really impress or score particularly well. In the variation with the knight on c3, the 'refutation' of this flank undermining of the center consisted of taking on d5, but here after7.Bxd5exd58.Be3the situation is completely different because White has given up the light-squared bishop and significantly weakened the light-squares, which changes the evaluation from 'clearly better for White' to 'somewhat better for Black'. A sample line can be8...bxc59.dxc5Na610.Qxd5Rb8when Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn. I have intentionally refrained from making a line like this trainable because I think that memorizing it is redundant - it is sufficient to understand that Bxd5 is almost never an issue, and the rest can be figured out over the board.} 
7. axb6 {Black has a very healthy position and various ideas in the position. One possibility is to play Ba6 and exchange the light-squared bishops, the other is to play Bb4 and exchange the dark-squared bishops, while the undermining move d6 is still on the agenda. Definitely not a critical variation against the Alekhine.} 
