3. c4 {After examining all the possible deviations and sidelines by White on move three (and also two), in the previous two chapters, it is now time to start covering the more mainstream (and objectively - more dangerous options), available on move 3 (and onward).Now, for a long time, this logical move of the c-pawn, attacking the exposed knight on d5 with the gain of tempo, was considered to be the main line - and is indeed one of the main options available to White even today.However, in modern times, there is a solid argument to be made for3.d4, withholding the advance of the c-pawn for the moment. To be fair, the moves have a big transpositional value, as after the most common move3...d6(which will be the recommendation of this repertoire) White can still play4.c4and basically transpose to the3.c4move order.However, after3.d4d6, White more commonly plays without the advance of the c-pawn with4.Nf3With that being said, the move-order3.c4also has some peculiarities, most notably when White refrains from advancing the d-pawn on the next move. For simplicity's sake, I have decided to first cover all possible lines via this move-order - and then conclude the course with the coverage of 3.d4 variations. In the process, I will try my best to point out all the possible instances when 3.c4 and 3.d4 move orders transpose to each other.} 
3. Nb6 {The only sensible move by the knight.3...Nf4is bad for very obvious reasons after4.d4(development with a tempo),while some people have tried3...Nb4when after4.d4the knight will very likely end up on a6 at some point, where it is almost certainly placed even worse than on b6. Would not recommend.After3...Nb6the move4.d4is by far the most common and natural reply, which will be examined in great depth in later chapters. However, White does have a few other 4th move options available at their disposal, that are perhaps not objectively the best, but that can be very tricky and venomous if faced without any knowledge. In this chapter, we will cover them in some depth and ensure that we are not surprised when they appear in our own games.} 
4. c5 {Out of all 'strange' fourth moves available at White's disposal in the position with the pawn on c4, this one - leading to the so-called Chase variation - is definitely the most serious. White spends another tempo to attack our knight and forces it back to d5. At first glance, this merely exposes the c5 pawn and the center further, but White also increases the control of the d6 square and grabs some more space.Furthermore, just like in the1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3variation, the idea is to try and destabilize the knight on d5 by attacking it with Nc3 or Bc4 next.} 
4. Nd5 {Of course, this move is a no-brainer as the knight doesn't have anywhere else to go.} 
5. Nc3 {The most obvious and logical move, trying to undermine the knight on d5 - or inviting Black to capture on c3 and open up some files and diagonals.} 
5. e6 {The best move in the position, defending the knight on c3 and opening up the bishop's attack against the c5 pawn. Taking on c3 with5...Nxc3would lead to the inferior version of1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3Nxc3lines due to the presence of the pawn on c5 which severely restricts our counterplay with d6. With the text move, we are trying to make an argument that the early advance of the c-pawn was premature and that is has merely turned that pawn into a big target!White is now at a big crossroads!} 
6. Bc4 {First of all, White has this option of developing the bishop to c4 and sacrificing the pawn on c5. Before I started working on this repertoire, I wasn't fully aware of this move, but incidentally, in parallel to working on this file, I was also reading a book about the Soviet grandmaster Evgeni Vasiukov where this variation was featured in a couple of games.At first glance, this looks just like a blunder of the pawn, but the situation is not so simple as White has some ideas to go Qg4 in the resulting position, pressuring the kingside along the way - and even the engine doesn't think that White's idea is completely dubious.} 
6. Nxc3 {After some investigation, I have decided to recommend this capture of the knight on c3. I think it is far more practical than either6...Nc6or6...Bxc5,which are also fine, but which lead to more complicated and convoluted play. Besides, I also think that the text move has tremendous practical value if followed up with the very critical and testing variation that I am going to recommend here.} 
7. dxc3
7. Nc6 {This is the point! Black doesn't immediately capture the pawn on c5, but first develops the knight to c6 in order to attack the e5 pawn. The idea is to force a concession from White and to capture the pawn on c5 under better circumstances.The immediate capture of the pawn is not so good, in my opinion, as after7...Bxc58.Qg4is a bit unpleasant and forces us to make a concession of a sort. Unless you are a French Defence player who is used to these kinds of shenanigans, I would recommend you avoid something like this altogether - especially since the text move is far more practical.} 
8. Bf4 {The most common move that I would also very much expect to face in the majority of the games. White refrains from moving the knight as after8.Nf3the queen's path to g4 would be blocked so we would be able to snatch the c5 pawn under better circumstances after8...Bxc5The computer also suggests some strange8.Qh5move which was played in 600+ games in the lichess database, but after8...Bxc5,White again has to prove the compensation.} 
8. Bxc5 {Now we capture the pawn and claim this is a much better version for us. Note that this is where we deviate from the Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine Defence by GM Roeland Pruijssers, as the move8...Qh4was the choice there.} 
9. Qg4 {Now you might be wondering what on Earth have we gained by forcing the bishop to f4 - but the following move reveals the ingenuity of our entire concept!} 
9. g5 {A tremendous blow that was played by some strong players (e.g. a renowned theoretician and 2600+ grandmaster Michal Krasenkow). The idea is simple - diverting the bishop from the defense of the e5 pawn and forcing it to enter a pin along the g-file.} 
10. Bxg5 {There is no choice, as10.Qxg5Qxg511.Bxg5Nxe512.Bf6Nxc413.Bxh8Nxb2leads to a completely lost endgame.} 
10. Rg8 {The point of our play. White is now in a very uncomfortable pin and it is not very easy to decide how to deal with it. Eventually, they will have to take on d8 and enter an endgame where only Black will have the chances to play for the win.And even though the engine claims White has some chances for equality after either11.Nh3h612.Bxd8Rxg4and11.h4h612.Bxd8Rxg4,Black scores 58% according to the lichess database - and that is a far more significant statistic. I would personally allow this variation in my every Black game if I knew my opponent was going to go for it against the Alekhine.} 
