[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 3.c4: Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "3.c4 4.c5 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. c4 {After examining all the possible deviations and sidelines by White on move three (and also two), in the previous two chapters, it is now time to start covering the more mainstream (and objectively - more dangerous options), available on move 3 (and onward).Now, for a long time, this logical move of the c-pawn, attacking the exposed knight on d5 with the gain of tempo, was considered to be the main line - and is indeed one of the main options available to White even today.However, in modern times, there is a solid argument to be made for3.d4, withholding the advance of the c-pawn for the moment. To be fair, the moves have a big transpositional value, as after the most common move3...d6(which will be the recommendation of this repertoire) White can still play4.c4and basically transpose to the3.c4move order.However, after3.d4d6, White more commonly plays without the advance of the c-pawn with4.Nf3With that being said, the move-order3.c4also has some peculiarities, most notably when White refrains from advancing the d-pawn on the next move. For simplicity's sake, I have decided to first cover all possible lines via this move-order - and then conclude the course with the coverage of 3.d4 variations. In the process, I will try my best to point out all the possible instances when 3.c4 and 3.d4 move orders transpose to each other.} 
3. Nb6 {The only sensible move by the knight.3...Nf4is bad for very obvious reasons after4.d4(development with a tempo),while some people have tried3...Nb4when after4.d4the knight will very likely end up on a6 at some point, where it is almost certainly placed even worse than on b6. Would not recommend.After3...Nb6the move4.d4is by far the most common and natural reply, which will be examined in great depth in later chapters. However, White does have a few other 4th move options available at their disposal, that are perhaps not objectively the best, but that can be very tricky and venomous if faced without any knowledge. In this chapter, we will cover them in some depth and ensure that we are not surprised when they appear in our own games.} 
4. c5 {Out of all 'strange' fourth moves available at White's disposal in the position with the pawn on c4, this one - leading to the so-called Chase variation - is definitely the most serious. White spends another tempo to attack our knight and forces it back to d5. At first glance, this merely exposes the c5 pawn and the center further, but White also increases the control of the d6 square and grabs some more space.Furthermore, just like in the1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3variation, the idea is to try and destabilize the knight on d5 by attacking it with Nc3 or Bc4 next.} 
4. Nd5 {Of course, this move is a no-brainer as the knight doesn't have anywhere else to go.} 
5. Nc3 {The most obvious and logical move, trying to undermine the knight on d5 - or inviting Black to capture on c3 and open up some files and diagonals.} 
5. e6 {The best move in the position, defending the knight on c3 and opening up the bishop's attack against the c5 pawn. Taking on c3 with5...Nxc3would lead to the inferior version of1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3Nxc3lines due to the presence of the pawn on c5 which severely restricts our counterplay with d6. With the text move, we are trying to make an argument that the early advance of the c-pawn was premature and that is has merely turned that pawn into a big target!White is now at a big crossroads!} 
6. d4 {This move, simply defending the c5 pawn is the most common move in the Master's database and the 2nd most common in the lichess database. It is quite logical NOT to be willing to sacrifice the pawn on c5 and simply defend it, opening up the bishop on c1 in the process.} 
6. d6 {After some investigation, I have concluded that this typical and direct Alekhine move, creating tension in the center immediately, is the best move in the position. This move was also provided as the solution by NM Bryan Tillis in his course The Dark Knight rises here on Chessable.It has to be mentioned, though, that the move6...b6,undermining the center from the other side, is not too good here as White can simply take on d5 with7.Nxd5exd5and after8.Be3we are just worse. In contrast to the variation where White has taken with the bishop on d5, their light-squares haven't been weakened that much and we are unable to create sufficient counterplay.Also note that6...Nxc37.bxc3b6was Pruijssers suggestion in the Lifetime Alekhine, but I am not 100% convinced. For example, White has some dangerous ideas such as8.Nf3bxc59.d5,so I would prefer to avoid all this in favour of 6...d6.} 
7. cxd6 {The only move worth checking here, really.7.exd6cxd6allows Black to solve all the problems as White voluntarily gives up the strong pawn on e5 that secures the space advantage in the center and the central tension is still maintained.Also note that7.Nxd5is very likely to transpose to lines analyzed via 6.Nxd5 move order.} 
7. cxd6
8. f4 {When I was analyzing this position, I realized that this move, reinforcing the e5 pawn, is a very serious option that is played somewhat frequently in the lichess database. The idea is, obviously, to preserve the vast and mighty center and it is not so easy to deal with this idea if we don't know what we are doing.} 
8. dxe5 {In the majority of cases when White has the pawns on e5, d4 and f4, Black refrains from capturing on e5 as it allows White to recapture with the f-pawn and open up the f-file for the potential attack - especially if Black doesn't have the c-pawn to play c5 and reinforce the d4 pawn (as is the case here.)So why do we play this move here nevertheless? Well, the idea is very concrete - we want to open up the 4th rank in order to have the option of playing Qh4 in some positions and exploit the fact that White doesn't yet have the knight on f3.} 
9. fxe5 {Of course, White really doesn't want to play9.dxe5here as we don't really have the bishop on g7 where it would be blunted by this pawn so we have a reasonable position after almost any sensible developing move. All White manages to do is weaken the a7-g1 diagonal so this capture is not something we need to analyze too much.} 
9. Bb4 {A very concrete point of our play. We are pinning the knight on c3 and exploiting the fact that White spent a lot of time pushing the pawns.} 
10. Qd3 {It turns out there is no better way of defending the c3 knight. Say, if10.Bd2, we now have this10...Qh4resource and we win the d4 pawn. This check was the main motivation for the capture on e5 back on move 8.} 
10. Bd7 {I like this developing move. The idea is to get the bishop to c6 as fast as possible, where it would sit rather nicely. Other moves are also possible.} 
11. a3
11. Be7
12. Nf3
12. Bc6 {Mission accomplished. Black has a fairly healthy and nice position, with Nd7 coming next. We probably shouldn't hurry to castle too soon, but will probably aim to mobilize the queenside and then try to play along the light squares - especially if we manage to capture on c3 and force bxc3 under the right circumstances. Given that 8.f4 is a fairly rare option in this position, I think we can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening.} 
