6. d6 {After some investigation, I have concluded that this typical and direct Alekhine move, creating tension in the center immediately, is the best move in the position. This move was also provided as the solution by NM Bryan Tillis in his course The Dark Knight rises here on Chessable.It has to be mentioned, though, that the move6...b6,undermining the center from the other side, is not too good here as White can simply take on d5 with7.Nxd5exd5and after8.Be3we are just worse. In contrast to the variation where White has taken with the bishop on d5, their light-squares haven't been weakened that much and we are unable to create sufficient counterplay.Also note that6...Nxc37.bxc3b6was Pruijssers suggestion in the Lifetime Alekhine, but I am not 100% convinced. For example, White has some dangerous ideas such as8.Nf3bxc59.d5,so I would prefer to avoid all this in favour of 6...d6.} 
7. cxd6 {The only move worth checking here, really.7.exd6cxd6allows Black to solve all the problems as White voluntarily gives up the strong pawn on e5 that secures the space advantage in the center and the central tension is still maintained.Also note that7.Nxd5is very likely to transpose to lines analyzed via 6.Nxd5 move order.} 
7. cxd6
8. Nf3 {The most logical and natural move, developing the knight and defending the center. Once again,8.Nxd5will transpose to the lines analyzed via 6.Nxd5 move order.,While the other move8.f4was examined in the previous trainable.} 
8. Nxc3 {Now that White has developed the knight to f3 and removed the possibility of playing f4, we do indeed take on c3, as now we are able to put pressure on the pawn on e5.} 
9. bxc3
9. Qc7
10. Bd2
10. Nd7 {Increasing the pressure. Now it seems as if there is no good way to defend the e5 pawn. But White actually doesn't need to defend it - the engine suggests that the best way forward consists of simply sacrificing it for rapid development.} 
11. Bd3 {The best move in the position that was played in quite a few games according to the lichess database. It is true that White's results are abysmal, but this is objectively not so bad, and far better than either11.exd6Bxd6or11.Bb5a612.Bxd7Bxd7, trying to preserve the pawn.Note that this move wasn't covered in the course The Dark Knight Rises here on Chessable.} 
11. dxe5 {Of course, for the moment we take on e5 and wait to see what White will do.} 
12. O-O
12. Bd6 {For the moment, we are not interested in capturing on d4 ourselves as we have to catch up on the development. With this move, we place the bishop on an active post and reinforce the pawn on e5, preparing to castle next.} 
13. Re1 {White continues developing the pieces and insists on sacrificing a pawn. Of course, if they take on e5 we will gladly recapture and exchange some pieces.} 
13. O-O
14. Qe2 {Continuing in the same provocative manner, inviting us to take on d4 and maybe preparing some ideas associated with Qe4.} 
14. exd4 {Now we finally 'yield' and accept the challenge, opening up the bishop and preparing to play Nf6 to defend the kingside next.} 
15. Qe4 {More challenging than the immediate recapture with15.cxd4when after15...Nf6we have a fine game. White is currently threatening mate in one and we actually have to be very careful.} 
15. g6 {I feel this weakening move is a necessity. The most obvious move in the position is15...Nf6, but it seems to lose after16.Qh4when the threat of Bg5 is quite deadly on the next move.} 
16. cxd4
16. Nf6 {Now we get this move with a gain of tempo indeed - although our kingside has been quite weakened, which is not so ideal.} 
17. Qh4
17. Nd5 {And the situation is very tense and unclear. We have an extra pawn, but White definitely has some compensation in the form of the attacking prospects on the kingside. I don't think we are in any mortal danger yet and have ideas of Be7, Qd8 and Rd8 on the table, but we do need to be a bit careful. In any case, such a murky and unclear position is definitely what we are looking for when we are trying to play the Alekhine, so we should embrace the incoming fight with both hands.} 
