4. c5 {Out of all 'strange' fourth moves available at White's disposal in the position with the pawn on c4, this one - leading to the so-called Chase variation - is definitely the most serious. White spends another tempo to attack our knight and forces it back to d5. At first glance, this merely exposes the c5 pawn and the center further, but White also increases the control of the d6 square and grabs some more space.Furthermore, just like in the1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3variation, the idea is to try and destabilize the knight on d5 by attacking it with Nc3 or Bc4 next.} 
4. Nd5 {Of course, this move is a no-brainer as the knight doesn't have anywhere else to go.} 
5. Nc3 {The most obvious and logical move, trying to undermine the knight on d5 - or inviting Black to capture on c3 and open up some files and diagonals.} 
5. e6 {The best move in the position, defending the knight on c3 and opening up the bishop's attack against the c5 pawn. Taking on c3 with5...Nxc3would lead to the inferior version of1.e4Nf62.e5Nd53.Nc3Nxc3lines due to the presence of the pawn on c5 which severely restricts our counterplay with d6. With the text move, we are trying to make an argument that the early advance of the c-pawn was premature and that is has merely turned that pawn into a big target!White is now at a big crossroads!} 
6. Nxd5 {This obvious recapturing, doubling the d-pawns, is the most obvious and common move in the position - even though I do believe it is not necessarily the best/most ambitious. (Although you could make an argument that playing the Chase variation is not the most ambitious attempt to punish the Alekhine to begin with.)} 
6. exd5 {Even though we have the doubled-pawns, we are not at all concerned as we will be able to play d6 next and get rid of them, while we are also currently attacking the c5 pawn.} 
7. d4 {Of course, White has to defend the pawn on c5.} 
7. d6 {A logical and thematic undermining move of the chapter. Once again, trying to play on the flank with7...b6is not so good in this particular position as it doesn't undouble our pawns, so after8.Be3bxc59.dxc5White has a clear advantage as now our d5 is indeed very weak.} 
8. cxd6 {Once again - taking with the e-pawn is nothing to worry about as then White gets rid of the strong pawn on e5. Also - White has to react here as we were threatening to take on c5 twice.} 
8. cxd6
9. Nf3 {But now, White doesn't capture on d6, which would merely let our bishop to enter the game, but rather continues developing and tries to preserve the pawn on e5.} 
9. Nc6 {There is something to be said about the immediate capture on e5, but this move figures in our plans all the same - so why not play it at once. Black increases the pressure on the e5 pawn and makes a useful developing move.} 
10. Bd3 {A useful developing move, placing the bishop on its lawful diagonal. On the other hand, the move10.Bb5- that was played more than 13 THOUSAND times in the lichess database (!!!) loses the bishop on the spot with10...Qa5,since now there is no knight on b1 to come and defend the bishop from c3.} 
10. dxe5 {Now is a good moment to clarify the situation in the center and capture on e5, since we really don't want to delay the development of our kingside any more, while we also don't want to move the bishop to e7, as we can hope to develop it to a better square after we remove the obstacle on d6.} 
11. Nxe5 {Recapturing with the knight is less popular than recapturing with the pawn, but it is also played fairly frequently, so it needs to be checked at least a bit. White is trying to induce us to capture on e5 and grant them the pawn on e5 without the knight on f3. This would not only prevent our Bg4 idea we will see mentioned in the main line, but it also frees the f-pawn to roam to f4 and protect the pawn on e5, if required.} 
11. Bd6 {Of course, now that there is no pawn on e5, we can comfortably develop the bishop to this active square. Note that11...Bb4is possible here, but after12.Bd2Bxd213.Qxd2O-OWhite can saddle us with a backward pawn on the c-file with14.Nxc6.It might still be playable, but I would rather avoid it and play more ambitiously with the text move.Also note that11...Nxd4doesn't really win a pawn due to12.Qa4} 
12. O-O
12. O-O {And this is a good moment to stop the variation, as both sides have managed to complete the development. Due to the symmetrical structure, the position is a little bit dry, but it is still possible to play for the win. Our next move is very likely Qf6, increasing the pressure on the e5 point and trying to induce White to take on c6, while Qh4, trying to create some pressure against the h2 and d4 pawns, also comes into consideration.Note that we are not really afraid of White taking on c6 as the pawn can be easily defended with the bishop on d7 or rook on c8. We are too well-developed for such a simple positional measure to cause us any significant problems.} 
