6. Bf5 {After some contemplation, I have decided to recommend this move, developing the bishop to the natural square and not yet determining the position of the knight on b8. The downside of this move is that now it makes no longer sense to pin the knight on g4, but I personally don't think it is such a huge loss - because even if we don't move the bishop White wouldn't allow us to play Bg4 in one go. On the other hand, as we will soon see, there are some variations where it is super useful to not block the pawn on c7 and keep the option of playing c5, if required.I think this is the most flexible move and that its point might not be fully familiar to your opponents. For example, it was not at all considered by Adhiban in his 1.e4 LifetimeRepertoire, although ever-so-diligent Anish Giri did include it in his.With that being said, the main move here is the move6...Nc6Here, the idea is to be able to reply to7.Nf3with7...Bg4in one move, pressuring the center.However, after6...Nc6White will not oblige so easily and will play something like7.Be3when we hardly have anything better than to transpose to the main variation after7...Bf58.Nc3e69.Nf3with9...Be7, because in this exact position,9...Bb4has no purpose with the c-pawn blocked, and the variation with9...Qd7, intending long castling, is just too risky for Black (although there are some tricks that might work well - especially in faster time controls.).As we will see, against a very specific move order by White, even after6...Bf5we will transpose to the very same, main variation of the line. However, with 6...Bf5, we do land some mines along the way, which is why I ultimately decided to prefer it over 6...Nc6.- As for some other possibilities, the variation after6...c57.d5g6actually does super well in the lichess database, as Black wins 55% of the games. However, I do think that this is objectively quite dubious and I couldn't bring myself to recommend it in this course.} 
7. Be3 {One of the reasons why I am quite attracted to the variation with 6...Bf5 is this natural development of the bishop, defending the d4 pawn. As we have seen in the notes above, this move is the main response to 6...Nc6, as it makes a lot of sense to reinforce the center there. However, in this particular instance, this move is not very good as it allows Black to demonstrate why the knight was not developed in front of the c-pawn back on move 6.} 
7. e6 {A typical Alekhine move, opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop! Usually, this piece goes to e7 in these lines, but as we will see, here we have more ambitious plans! Also note that in some cases, now the Qh4 check might be on the agenda - especially if White plays a slow, non-developing move.} 
8. Nf3 {As we will see in the main line with8.Nc3,Black's idea is not to transpose to the mainline of the variation but to pin that knight with a Bb4 check. A sensible question, therefore, is - what if White doesn't yet develop the knight to c3 but moves the other knight to f3 now that the bishop has already been placed on f5?This is a better way of preventing Bb4 than, say, a slow passive move like8.a3, which can be met forcefully with either the same8...c5, or even8...Qh4,since now the h4 and e4 squares are not covered at all!} 
8. c5 {A powerful reply that once again demonstrates why it was a good idea not to move the knight from b8 to c6. White doesn't have sufficient control over the d5 square to meet this in a convincing way.} 
9. Nc3
9. Nc6 {Increasing the pressure on the center!} 
10. d5 {What else? It seems logical to kick the knight away not that the knight is on c3, but it transpires that in this particular line, the knight is quite comfortable on b4.} 
10. Nb4 {Black is now threatening Nc2 and White will very likely have to give up the d5 pawn in order to deal with that threat, after which they will have some compensation, but a pawn is a pawn. If playing in this style is not for you, you can always transpose to the mainline back on move 8 instead of going for this whole c5 stuff.} 
