7. Be3 {One of the reasons why I am quite attracted to the variation with 6...Bf5 is this natural development of the bishop, defending the d4 pawn. As we have seen in the notes above, this move is the main response to 6...Nc6, as it makes a lot of sense to reinforce the center there. However, in this particular instance, this move is not very good as it allows Black to demonstrate why the knight was not developed in front of the c-pawn back on move 6.} 
7. e6 {A typical Alekhine move, opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop! Usually, this piece goes to e7 in these lines, but as we will see, here we have more ambitious plans! Also note that in some cases, now the Qh4 check might be on the agenda - especially if White plays a slow, non-developing move.} 
8. Nc3 {A standard Alekhine move, developing the knight and not yet committing the other knight to f3. White also adds more control to the d5 square, so advancing the c-pawn would now be met with d5.} 
8. Bb4 {At this point, Black can transpose to the mainline of the variation with either8...Be7or8...Nc6.However, I think that the text move, pinning the knight on c3, threatening to double the pawns and intending to play c5 next, is not only better, but also much more practical, as in the resulting position Black will end up having a considerable pressure on the White center. Furthermore, since now the e4 square is once again available to Black, Qh4 is an idea once again.} 
9. Nf3 {A natural developing move that also covers the h4 square. If9.a3then9...Bxc310.bxc3Qh4is very annoying for White. Remember this Qd8-Qh4 idea as it often comes useful in these positions if White is foolish enough to allow it.} 
9. c5 {The entire point of Black's play! Instead of moving the knight in front of the pawn, Black strikes in the center with c5 at the moment where White has insufficient control over the d5 square due to the pin on the knight on c3. In the Alekhine, Black has to try and undermine the center and here it is done in a very energetic and brutal fashion!} 
10. a3 {The best reply for White in this position, posing an immediate question to the bishop and prompting an exchange on c3, when the d4 pawn will acquire some additional protection. Moving the d-pawn is once again not particularly good, while not doing anything and continuing the development with something like10.Be2allows Black to take on d4 after, say,10...O-O11.O-Ocxd4when after12.Nxd4Bg6we have a very non-standard position in which White has the open f-file and more space due to the e5 pawn, but at the same time that e5 pawn is isolated and weak. I think Black is very close to full equality, but more importantly - I feel the position is much easier to play in practice - which is exactly what the Alekhine player is looking for.} 
10. Bxc3+ {Black is more-or-less forced to take, because after10...Ba5the pressure on the White center is significantly reduced because the c-pawn can virtually never capture on d4 due to b4, winning the piece. Black would have to lose time to move the knight from b6 and then potentially capture on d4, but this is obviously not very desirable.} 
11. bxc3
11. Nc6 {And now we have a very non-standard position where White has the bishop pair and more space, but where we have considerable pressure on the center and the structural advantage. Next, we want to castle and then try to pressure the pawns on the c-file with moves such as Na5-Rc8-cxd4-Nxc4. The engine still prefers White, but I don't think that this evaluation necessarily corresponds to practical play as Black has a clear plan ahead while White is the one who has to be creative and solve non-standard problems.Just in case, I did examine two continuations. The more natural12.Be2is apparently not particularly problematic due to12...O-O13.O-OBg6when Black is ready to start going for the aforementioned plan with Rc8, Na5 and so on.On the other hand,12.Bd3seems to be a better move, although it is really strange for a human to offer this exchange when they have the bishop pair and more space. However, the idea is to get the queen into play in one go and potentially eliminate the important defender of the kingside, so Black should not oblige and go for12...Bg4instead, pressuring the center and intending to capture on d4 next. White has some ultra-sophisticated prophylactic move in the form of13.Bf2here, with the idea of13...cxd414.cxd4Nxd415.c5!when Black can't really attack the bishop one3.Nevertheless, after13.Bf2Black can continue pursuing the plan with13...Rc8and suddenly the next move for White is not at all so obvious. I definitely wouldn't mind having this position in a practical game.} 
