11. Bxf6 {No other recapture comes into consideration, as11...Rxf6is bad due to12.Bg5Rf813.Bxe7when White has actually managed to exchange the bishop that helps us pressure the d4 pawn and obtain an even better control over the e5 square, which is hugely in their favour.11...gxf6is even worse, as after12.Bh6Rf713.Nh4our kingside is desperately weakened, our bishop on e7 passive, the knight on b8 undeveloped, and White advantage is of gargantuan proportions.} 
12. Be3 {Developing the bishop on a natural square, defending the d4 pawn and preparing Qd2.} 
12. Nc6 {Finally developing the knight, which we have been delaying to do since the start of the game.} 
13. d5 {Aside from moving the queen to d2, this move is very common in the lichess database - but it is not particularly good, as it scores only 43% for White and 50% for Black, with 7% of the games ending in a draw. It looks logical to try and exploit the position of the knight on c6 and open up the d4 square for the knight - especially since White is almost completely developed. But alas, as often in the Alekhine, this premature aggression turns out to be not 100% correct.} 
13. Na5 {Even though we are taught that 'the knight on the rim is dim', here the knight are performing a very good task of pressuring the center and the pawn on c4 - and White doesn't have a convenient way of dealing with it.} 
14. Bxb6 {The only way to try and defend the c4 pawn, but we are obviously happy to eliminate the opponent's bishop pair.} 
14. axb6
15. Nd4 {Now it seems as if we are in some trouble due to the pressure on e6 and f5, but it turns out to be an illusion.} 
15. Qe7 {A very calm move, evacuating the queen and preparing to go Rad8 next. It turns out that the pawn on f5 is immune as after16.Nxf5exf517.Rxf5we have17...Bd4+If White doesn't capture and plays, say,16.Kh1then we can calmly play either16...Be5or even16...Rad817.Nxf5exf518.Rxf5Bxc3!?19.Rxf8Rxf820.bxc3Rf4when our activity and better pawn structure more than compensate for the missing pawn. All in all, I think Black is more than fine in this position and I think the practical results in the database are the best evidence in support of that claim.} 
