14. Rad8 {Also a very natural move, bringing the rook to the open d-file and increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn. The diagram position is reached almost 'automatically' in the majority of cases where White choses the Four Pawns Attack (especially if Black doesn't try to be too clever with the move order in the initial phases of the game) and is arguably one of the critical positions of the Four Pawns Attack - and of the entire Alekhine Defence.Given its importance, the fact that it was analyzed in several Chessable courses from the White perspective, AND that White has a wide array of options, we will analyze it a little bit deeper than perhaps customary/expected from a 100 Repertoire.} 
15. b3 {This move, defending the c4 pawn and restricting the knight on b6 even further, is quite logical and as popular as15.Qe1,so we should definitely devote at least one trainable to it.} 
15. Nb4 {Similarly as in the 15.Qe1 lines - this thematic knight jump, intending Nc2 and preparing c5, has a lot of merits here.15...Rd7is much more common, according to the lichess database, but after16.Kh1Rfd817.Qe1I don't see how Black can create any meaningful pressure on the d4 point. In general, this frontal attack doesn't quite work out in these lines, so we should try to play in a more subtle manner.} 
16. a3 {The most obvious and logical reaction, trying to kick the knight away. The move16.Bg5,trying to avoid Nc2 tempo is apparently stronger, but given it is very counterintuitive and that this is a relatively unexplored position, I think it is okay to cover it in clickable form. Here Black can demonstrate another point of the previous knight move and strike with the c-pawn:16...c517.Bxf6Qxf618.Qf4Nd7and Black is perhaps objectively marginally worse, but the position is very complicated and tense, which means that all three results are possible in a practical game.} 
16. Nc2 {Jumping into the lion's den, gaining a tempo on the bishop on e3, increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn and also attacking the a3 pawn.} 
17. Bf2
17. Qxa3 {Taking the pawn and asking White to demonstrate the compensation. It is also possible to strike in the center with17...c5In any case, Black is by no means worse in this complicated and non-standard position where White has seemingly overextended the forces. And even if White has an objective way to maintain the balance, it is not so easy to find it in a practical game. This kind of murky and unclear position where precise and demanding play is required from White is exactly what we are looking for as Alekhine players and we can, therefore, be extremely pleased with the outcome of the opening.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) The Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "Four Pawns Attack: Mainline with 7.Nc3 #10"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {When it comes to the Four Pawns Attack which will be examined in this chapter, it is completely irrelevant whether White moves the c-pawn or the d-pawn first, as the same position is also reached after3.c4Nb64.d4d65.f4} 
3. d6
4. c4
4. Nb6
5. f4 {After we have covered some early deviations in earlier chapters, it is now time to turn our attention to more mainline options. We will start by examining the so-called Four Pawn Attack, featuring the early advance of the f-pawn on move 5.White's intention is clear - since we are refraining from contesting the center, they are trying to secure as much space as possible by fortifying their big and massive pawn chain, with the aim of using that very space advantage to slowly suffocate us - or even launch a direct attack on our king, depending on how we react.This attempt to basically directly refute the Alekhine defense has always been regarded as very dangerous - but this is especially so in our modern times, due to the following:   A) The variation is generally quite forcing and direct which makes it quite suitable for very deep computer analysis   B) The variation is objectively quite good and approved by these modern engines, essentially giving White a clear plus in almost all variations.It is not coincidence that no less than five Chessable authors - Giri, Adhiban, Mihajlov, Gajewski and till ( A community author and a master-level player ) give it as the main recommendation in their respective courses.On the other hand, even though it is a very challenging variation from the theoretical viewpoint, it has to be said that its practical results are far less impressive. According to the lichess database, Black has a positive score almost irrespective of the choice on move 5. Sure, any sort of statistic like this has to be taken 'cum grano salis' as it doesn't control for any sort of variable (say, the strength of the player). But I do think a lot of it has to be attributed to the character of the whole variation - such sharp and critical variations definitely involve some risk for the first player. Unless you are super-well prepared or a super-strong player, you can very easily slip and make the wrong move - which is often all Black needs to take over the initiative and punish you for your brave opening choice.Thus, working on this chapter lead to some sort of conundrum - on one hand you are constantly looking at computer evaluations that are very much in White's favour, but on the other hand, I knew that the majority of these evaluations are not 100% relevant for practical play ( Something similar happened as I was working on my course on the Modern defence, although you could make an argument that the Four Pawns Attack is a more narrow battlefield than 1.e4 g6 ). I tried to take this into account when choosing my recommendation in this chapter and I have tried to find a good balance between what is objectively the best - and what I think can pose significant practical problems!} 
5. dxe5 {After very long consideration, I have decided to go for this typical 'Alekhine' capture on e5. However, whereas in other variations of the Alekhine defence this move is very helpful when it comes to destabilizing the White's center, this is not the case here as White has moved the f-pawn forward and the center is reinforced. Furthermore, once we capture on e5, White will not be forced to take with the d-pawn or the knight from f3, but can actually utilize the pawn on f4, open the f-file and keep the central pawn chain intact.With all that being said, you might be wondering - but why do we then take on e5 after all? That is a very good question that can't be explained very simply. The main point behind the early capture is to open up the d-file and make the pawns on e5 and d4 a little bit loose. Black subsequently wants to move the knight to c6, and after the exchange on e5, it is very hard for White to play d5 as the e5 pawn is hanging.For example, if Black tries to play with the immediate5...Bf5then6.Nc3e67.Nf3Nc6?!is faulty, as White has the option of going8.exd6cxd69.d5An idea like this one wouldn't have been available if the pawn was on e5 and unprotected, but here it works like a charm.That is why after5...Bf56.Nc3e67.Nf3, Black probably doesn't have anything better than transposing to our variation with7...dxe5With that being said, the line involving the capture on e5 is not the only way for Black to handle the Four Pawns Attack. In his Lifetime Repertoire, GM Roland Pruijssers recommended a very interesting variation starting with5...g6!?, with the main idea being6.Nc3Bg77.Be3Be6!?It is definitely a little bit less standard and creative, although the engine is not very optimistic about Black's chances after8.d5Since I personally never played this variation myself, I didn't feel like I have that much to add to Pruijssers' analysis anyway, so feel free to investigate this on your own if you are searching for an alternative!Last but not least, one hobby horse of mine that I like to play in blitz games is the move5...g5- which was employed by Magnus on a few (trolling) occasions - but needless to say, such a move is definitely not solid enough and way too crazy to be a serious recommendation in any repertoire.} 
6. fxe5 {Of course, recapturing with the f-pawn is THE main point of White's entire aggressive play. Going for6.dxe5is very faulty as Black would very much love to exchange the queens in a position with a lack of space. Moreover, after6.dxe5Qxd17.Kxd1White also loses castling rights and we are already winning after the natural move like7...Bf5,due to our major lead in development. The fact that White only advanced the pawns works against them as the brave peasants have left a lot of weaknesses behind!} 
6. Bf5 {After some contemplation, I have decided to recommend this move, developing the bishop to the natural square and not yet determining the position of the knight on b8. The downside of this move is that now it makes no longer sense to pin the knight on g4, but I personally don't think it is such a huge loss - because even if we don't move the bishop White wouldn't allow us to play Bg4 in one go. On the other hand, as we will soon see, there are some variations where it is super useful to not block the pawn on c7 and keep the option of playing c5, if required.I think this is the most flexible move and that its point might not be fully familiar to your opponents. For example, it was not at all considered by Adhiban in his 1.e4 LifetimeRepertoire, although ever-so-diligent Anish Giri did include it in his.With that being said, the main move here is the move6...Nc6Here, the idea is to be able to reply to7.Nf3with7...Bg4in one move, pressuring the center.However, after6...Nc6White will not oblige so easily and will play something like7.Be3when we hardly have anything better than to transpose to the main variation after7...Bf58.Nc3e69.Nf3with9...Be7, because in this exact position,9...Bb4has no purpose with the c-pawn blocked, and the variation with9...Qd7, intending long castling, is just too risky for Black (although there are some tricks that might work well - especially in faster time controls.).As we will see, against a very specific move order by White, even after6...Bf5we will transpose to the very same, main variation of the line. However, with 6...Bf5, we do land some mines along the way, which is why I ultimately decided to prefer it over 6...Nc6.- As for some other possibilities, the variation after6...c57.d5g6actually does super well in the lichess database, as Black wins 55% of the games. However, I do think that this is objectively quite dubious and I couldn't bring myself to recommend it in this course.} 
7. Nc3 {This is the first important moment. Developing the queenside knight and not yet determining the positioning of either the bishop on c1 nor the knight on g1, is objectively the most precise move-order that eliminates most of the tricks associated with the 6...Bf5 move order. Now Black has nothing better than transposing to the main tabiya of the entire variation.} 
7. e6 {This is a standard Alekhine move that is very typical of this variation. Black opens up the diagonal for the bishop on f8 and also for the queen to potentially go to h4. Once again, for the moment we are refraining from touching the knight on b8 as we want to keep the c-pawn unblocked.} 
8. Nf3 {Alas, this move-order for White where they refrain to place the bishop on e3 early is the best for them as it prevents us from going for the Bb4-c5 plan and essentially forces us to transpose to the absolute mainline of the Four Pawns Attack that can be reached via different move orders.I should perhaps also mention that starting with8.Bd3is not possible here as it hangs the d4 pawn to8...Qxd4,while the alternative and rare developing move8.Be2allows Black to transpose to the mainline once again with8...Nc6when White doesn't have anything better than going for9.Nf3Be7transposition.Alternatively, after8.Be2Bb49.Nf3c5is once again possible and it scores 51% for Black in the lichess database, but I am not 100% sure whether this Bb4-c5 idea is fully viable when White refrains from placing the bishop on e3 early in the opening.} 
8. Be7 {Alas, with a somewhat heavy heart, I have to recommend this move, transposing back to the absolute mainline of the Four Pawns Attack variation. Black continues the development and prepares to castle short, after which the idea will be to try and undermine the center with the help of the timely f6 move. I personally consider this particular variation to be the critical test of the entire Alekhine defence (which is why I tried to avoid it whenever possible with the 6...Bf5 move order), so we should definitely study it in some detail.I really tried making the alternative8...Bb4work, but it is simply a bad move as after9.a3Bxc310.bxc3we don't have the important check on h4 with the queen (as the knight is on f3) and the counterplay with c5 is much less effective now that the d4 pawn is heavily fortified.Not to mention that8...Bb4can also be met with9.Bd3which is also quite good for White.Allow me to mention once again that you can also try going for8...Qd7here, preparing Nc6 and castling long, but in my opinion this is simply too risky of a variation in this modern engine day (even for Alekhine standards).} 
9. Be2 {The most natural developing move, moving the bishop to a place where it doesn't obstruct the queen's defence of the d4 pawn, prevents any Bg4 pins and prepares castling. White can also start with9.Be3when we are very likely to transpose after9...Nc6} 
9. O-O
10. O-O {Both sides complete their development and bring their respective kings to safety. But now the question is - what should Black do next?} 
10. f6 {This is a very logical move, trying to undermine White's center and the pawn on e5. Black has to do it in the Alekhine defences, even though in this specific position, it leaves the pawn on e6 isolated and weak. However, Black's argument is that the weakness of this pawn will not be so easily exploited and that the emergence of the bishop on f6 will create some counter chances due to the pressure on the d4 pawn.Note, btw, that Black can also delay this for a move and that10...Nc611.Be3f6leads to the same thing.} 
11. exf6 {This is by far the most common and obvious move, simply capturing on f6 and virtually forcing Black to isolate the pawn on e6.} 
11. Bxf6 {No other recapture comes into consideration, as11...Rxf6is bad due to12.Bg5Rf813.Bxe7when White has actually managed to exchange the bishop that helps us pressure the d4 pawn and obtain an even better control over the e5 square, which is hugely in their favour.11...gxf6is even worse, as after12.Bh6Rf713.Nh4our kingside is desperately weakened, our bishop on e7 passive, the knight on b8 undeveloped, and White advantage is of gargantuan proportions.} 
12. Be3 {Developing the bishop on a natural square, defending the d4 pawn and preparing Qd2.} 
12. Nc6 {Finally developing the knight, which we have been delaying to do since the start of the game.} 
13. Qd2 {Another very natural move, developing the queen and connecting the rooks - and by far the most common move in the position.} 
13. Qe7 {The main move in the position, developing the queen, connecting the rooks, and vacating the d-file. It looks a bit weird to put her majesty on e7 and not on d7 as now it is not attacking the d4 pawn and can also be prone to some potential Re1-d5 ideas much later in the future.One sample line that illustrates why it is better to have the queen on e7 could continue13...Qd714.Rad1Rad815.Kh1h616.h3Bh717.Bg1and now, with the queen on e7, we would have the trick Nxd4 and e5 due to the pin along the d-file, but here17...Nxd4simply blunders the piece.I should also probably mention that now the move13...Qe8doesn't quite work due to14.Bg5Bxg515.Qxg5When the queen is very active on g5.} 
14. Rad1 {The most natural move, developing the rook, placing it on an open file and potentially preparing to remove the queen to c1 to avoid potential pin along the d-file. This is by far the most common move played in the position and is also the first choice of the computer.} 
14. Rad8 {Also a very natural move, bringing the rook to the open d-file and increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn. The diagram position is reached almost 'automatically' in the majority of cases where White choses the Four Pawns Attack (especially if Black doesn't try to be too clever with the move order in the initial phases of the game) and is arguably one of the critical positions of the Four Pawns Attack - and of the entire Alekhine Defence.Given its importance, the fact that it was analyzed in several Chessable courses from the White perspective, AND that White has a wide array of options, we will analyze it a little bit deeper than perhaps customary/expected from a 100 Repertoire.} 
15. h3 {Before we get to the main move15.Kh1,let's examine a very similar idea - a quiet waiting move, covering the g4 square and placing the ball back into Black's court. Alas, moving the king into the corner is more useful as having the Bg1 resource is a key idea in several lines - and this move is not really possible here.} 
15. Bg6 {A nice move, preparing the tactical idea of capturing on d4 and playing e5. Doing so immediately with15...Nxd4doesn't quite work as after16.Nxd4e5White has17.Nxf5It is precisely this resource that we are aiming to avoid with the text move.} 
16. c5 {The only real way to avoid the idea of Nxd4 and e5, although White is not really willing to make this move voluntarily and allow the knight to d5. I think advancing the c-pawn is particularly difficult to make for a human player, as it is never very practical to provide your opponent with some nice squares and outposts for their pieces.With that being said, it is kinda difficult to say what White should do instead, given that16.Kh1is met with16...Nxd4And16.Qc1e5is very similar to the lines studied under 15.Qc1.} 
16. Nd5 {Placing the knight on a nice square and gitting the bishop on e3.} 
17. Bf2 {Here we can see why it is nicer to have the king on h1 - the setup with the bishop on g1 instead of f2 is much more harmonious.} 
17. Ndb4 {Now we remove the knight and introduce the idea of Nxd4 once again. White can apparently prevent it with18.Bc4, pinning the pawn one6and preventing Nxd4-e5 resource, but after18...Na5!?19.Qe2Nxc420.Qxc4Nd5we have managed to exchange a dangerous bishop and establish a nice blockade on the light squares with the knight on d5. It is true that our pawn structure is still inferior, but with the bishop pair and the nice outpost on d5, we can never be worse. A complicated battle is still ahead, of course, but we can definitely play for three results here. Some potential ideas include taking on c3 and/or undermining the queenside structure with a timely b6.} 
