14. Rad1 {The most natural move, developing the rook, placing it on an open file and potentially preparing to remove the queen to c1 to avoid potential pin along the d-file. This is by far the most common move played in the position and is also the first choice of the computer.} 
14. Rad8 {Also a very natural move, bringing the rook to the open d-file and increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn. The diagram position is reached almost 'automatically' in the majority of cases where White choses the Four Pawns Attack (especially if Black doesn't try to be too clever with the move order in the initial phases of the game) and is arguably one of the critical positions of the Four Pawns Attack - and of the entire Alekhine Defence.Given its importance, the fact that it was analyzed in several Chessable courses from the White perspective, AND that White has a wide array of options, we will analyze it a little bit deeper than perhaps customary/expected from a 100 Repertoire.} 
15. Kh1 {Last but not least, we arrive to this quiet move, simply tucking the king in the corner. White essentially tries to make an argument that Black doesn't have a good active plan and that White has some time for precautionary measures that involve safeguarding the king AND vacating the g1 square for the bishop.Even though it is not the most obvious move for a human in the given position, it is the first suggestion of the modern engine. It is not a coincidence that this move was recommended in several Chessable repertoires, such as:   - Giri's 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire Part 2   - Adhiban's 1. e4 Lifetime Repertoire   - The Energetic 1.e4 by Sebastian Mihajlov   - Beat The Alekhine: Four Pawns Attack by Till   - Gajewski's 1.e4 Lifetime part 2.  This move was definitely the one that provided me with the most difficulties when working on this course. I spent a long time analyzing various possibilities and comparing the lines with the lines given in aforementioned courses and have ultimately settled for a very creative, daring, and - let's be frank - computerish idea that might breathe some new life in this very tough and complex position.} 
15. h6 {After a long and painstaking analysis, I have decided to settle on this move. The idea is quite simple - since White made a useful waiting move, Black does the same. The idea is to vacate the h7 square for the bishop and cover the g5 square, which can be surprisingly relevant in some variations.As we will soon see - this is a better waiting move than a move like15...Kh8due to very specific reasons that can only be explained on the basis of some concrete variations.Given that it is the first choice of the engine and that it is the main option considered in almost all of the aforementioned courses, you might be wondering what did I spend that much time on. Well, this position is quite difficult to understand, as the engine gives a stable +0.5-0.7 advantage for White in almost all of the lines - at least initially. I, therefore, spent a long time clicking around, trying to understand the nuances and differences between different lines and why certain logical moves are not that optimal. I also did a lot of manual input, trying to make different ideas work until I finally stumbled on a very creative move that will constitute the mainline of my analysis.With that being said, let's take a look at some other possibilities by Black and what exactly I disliked about them. I hope the reader will excuse me for this lengthy detour from the main line - I wouldn't go so deep if I didn't consider this position to be extremely important and crucial for the viability of the entire Alekhine defence.A) So first of all, Black can't really try to attack the knight onf3and put pressure on thed4pawn because after15...Bg416.Ne4, hitting the bishop onf6is extremely unpleasant.B) Secondly, the move15...Rd7,trying to double on the d-file and attack the d4 pawn, looks sensible, but doesn't quite work as after16.Qc1Rfd8White already has17.d5with a clear advantage.C) Thirdly, the idea of15...Nb4which was viable in some other lines is not too good here because after16.a3Nc217.Bg1we see one of the points behind Kh1 - the bishop is very harmonious on g1.Also, we can't really go for17...Nxd418.Bxd4c5due to19.Bxf6.D) On the other hand, the move15...Bg6might be considered, but as we will soon see - the bishop is not really that ideal on this square. The idea of Bh5 is not particularly attractive, the bishop can be exposed to some Ne5 jumps and there is also16.Qc1now, when16...e5idea doesn't quite work with the king on h1, due to17.d5Nd418.Nxd4exd419.Bxd4Bg520.Qa1c521.Bg1!in this particular case, White doesn't have any problems on the dark squares and the a7-g1 diagonal, so we are essentially just a pawn down.E) Last but not least, I put very high hopes on the move15...Kh8and considered giving it as a main line. However, after16.h3Bg617.Qc1I was unable to find a good continuation. Once again - going for the Bh5 plan, pinning the knight, is never efficient due to Ne4 jumps - while in some other cases, the bishop is not ideal on g6 as it is exposed to Ne5 jumps - as we will soon see.} 
16. h3 {Another useful waiting move, covering the g4 square and once again placing the ball back into Black's court. This move was given in almost all of the aforementioned Chessable repertoires - apart from the Beat The Alekhine: The Four Pawns Attack, which preferred the move16.Qc1. However, in this case, we can again go for the same16...Bh7when it is hard for White to avoid the transposition for too long, say after17.Bg1Kh8they should sooner or later decide on the move18.h3Given that this is way too deep and nuanced and that the transposition is most likely anyway, I have decided not to cover this possibility in greater detail, since this chapter is on the verge of getting out of hand even without it.} 
16. Bh7 {After long consideration, I have decided to settle on this flexible retreating move, removing the bishop from a potentially exposed position on f5 and tucking it on a very safe square, utilizing the fact that h6 has been played on the previous move. It may seem a bit weird to retreat the bishop to h7 and not on g6, but it turns out that the bishop is less exposed here - as we will soon see.Aside from the fact that I genuinely believe that his move is objectively the best, I was also attracted to it because it was not mentioned at all by Baskaran Adhiban or Sebastian Mihajlov in their respective courses. On the other hand, ever-so-thorough Anish Giri did cover it in his Lifetime Repertoire, but he only provided it in clickable and not trainable form. Thus, there are high chances that even well-prepared opponents might not be fully familiar with it once they encounter it over the board.A) With that being said, let's once again make a quick survey of the alternatives and explain what exactly I dislike about them. First of all, the move16...Rd7is quite common and logical - and actually scores quite decently for Black in practice (55% for Black in the lichess database on the basis of 20 games). It was even seen in some correspondence games which continued17.Qc1Kh8However, I am not 100% sure convinced about Black's position in that line,as well as in the line arising after16...Rd717.c5Nd518.Bg1Rfd819.Bb5Perhaps it is a matter of taste, but I somehow figured my choice is more practical - although I would urge diligent students to do their own analysis and draw their own conclusions about 16...Rd7B) While we are at correspondence games,16...Kh817.Bg1was also seen in quite a few of them, but I once again felt that what works on the correspondence level might not be most viable on a practical level.C) On the other hand, you might be wondering why exactly the bishop goes to h7 and not to g6 instead. Well, the reasoning can be revealed in the line after16...Bg617.Qc1Kh818.b3Now if Black tries to follow the same continuation as will be seen after 16...Bh7 it is not as good as after18...a619.Bg1Nc820.c5b521.cxb6cxb622.Bxa6Nb423.Be2Nd624.Ne5!comes with the tempo on the bishop on g6, which completely changes the evaluation of the position. This is the deep reasoning why it is better to place the bishop on h7 back on move 16.D) Last but not least, it is also possible to go for the exotic16...g5here. This aggressive lunge is definitely not unreasonable and is worth investigating further, although I wasn't 100% convinced with the position that arises after17.d5!This is why I have ultimately decided to settle for the text continuation. White now has two viable continuations.} 
17. c5 {Aside from the typical move17.Qc1,avoiding the pin on the d-file, White can also advance the c-pawn and attack the b6 knight. This move was provided in the clickable form in Anish Giri's Lifetime Repertoire: 1.e4 - Part 2.Note, by the way, that White can't play17.Bg1as now with the bishop on h7 we do indeed have the tactical17...Nxd4shot.} 
17. Nd5
18. Bg1 {Once again we see this typical maneuver, exploiting the fact that the g1 square has been vacated earlier. Giri stops the clickable here, saying White intends Bb5 but it is not at all so clear cut.} 
18. Nxc3 {Exchanging the knight in order to be able to play e5 on the next move.} 
19. bxc3
19. e5 {A thematic central strike. Black is not trying to create pressure on d4 given that it is very well protected with the pawn on c3. But the idea is rather to gain even more space by pushing e4 and forcing the knight on f3 away.} 
20. d5 {A logical advance that definitely needs to be checked in this position.} 
20. e4 {The knight on c6 is not under immediate danger due to the pin on the d-file, so Black takes a moment to attack the knight on f3 and vacate the e5 square.} 
21. Nh2
21. Ne5 {And even though White is probably objectively better in this position, Black also has some trumps in the form of the d3 outpost for the knight. Once the knight appears there, the central pawn on d5 might become weak and the outcome of the game is definitely not 100% clear.With the price of each move being quite high, White needs to continue playing with computer-like precision to obtain a tangible advantage - and it is a big question whether they would be able to do so in a practical game. Given that a lot of knowledge is required to even get here to begin with, it is a risk I am personally prepared to take.} 
