16. h3 {Another useful waiting move, covering the g4 square and once again placing the ball back into Black's court. This move was given in almost all of the aforementioned Chessable repertoires - apart from the Beat The Alekhine: The Four Pawns Attack, which preferred the move16.Qc1. However, in this case, we can again go for the same16...Bh7when it is hard for White to avoid the transposition for too long, say after17.Bg1Kh8they should sooner or later decide on the move18.h3Given that this is way too deep and nuanced and that the transposition is most likely anyway, I have decided not to cover this possibility in greater detail, since this chapter is on the verge of getting out of hand even without it.} 
16. Bh7 {After long consideration, I have decided to settle on this flexible retreating move, removing the bishop from a potentially exposed position on f5 and tucking it on a very safe square, utilizing the fact that h6 has been played on the previous move. It may seem a bit weird to retreat the bishop to h7 and not on g6, but it turns out that the bishop is less exposed here - as we will soon see.Aside from the fact that I genuinely believe that his move is objectively the best, I was also attracted to it because it was not mentioned at all by Baskaran Adhiban or Sebastian Mihajlov in their respective courses. On the other hand, ever-so-thorough Anish Giri did cover it in his Lifetime Repertoire, but he only provided it in clickable and not trainable form. Thus, there are high chances that even well-prepared opponents might not be fully familiar with it once they encounter it over the board.A) With that being said, let's once again make a quick survey of the alternatives and explain what exactly I dislike about them. First of all, the move16...Rd7is quite common and logical - and actually scores quite decently for Black in practice (55% for Black in the lichess database on the basis of 20 games). It was even seen in some correspondence games which continued17.Qc1Kh8However, I am not 100% sure convinced about Black's position in that line,as well as in the line arising after16...Rd717.c5Nd518.Bg1Rfd819.Bb5Perhaps it is a matter of taste, but I somehow figured my choice is more practical - although I would urge diligent students to do their own analysis and draw their own conclusions about 16...Rd7B) While we are at correspondence games,16...Kh817.Bg1was also seen in quite a few of them, but I once again felt that what works on the correspondence level might not be most viable on a practical level.C) On the other hand, you might be wondering why exactly the bishop goes to h7 and not to g6 instead. Well, the reasoning can be revealed in the line after16...Bg617.Qc1Kh818.b3Now if Black tries to follow the same continuation as will be seen after 16...Bh7 it is not as good as after18...a619.Bg1Nc820.c5b521.cxb6cxb622.Bxa6Nb423.Be2Nd624.Ne5!comes with the tempo on the bishop on g6, which completely changes the evaluation of the position. This is the deep reasoning why it is better to place the bishop on h7 back on move 16.D) Last but not least, it is also possible to go for the exotic16...g5here. This aggressive lunge is definitely not unreasonable and is worth investigating further, although I wasn't 100% convinced with the position that arises after17.d5!This is why I have ultimately decided to settle for the text continuation. White now has two viable continuations.} 
17. Qc1 {This typical Alekhine move is arguably more critical and human than the17.c5analyzed earlier. White removes the queen from the d-file, avoids any potential pins and asks Black to demonstrate what they want to do next.} 
17. Kh8 {For the moment, we don't have a good active idea, so we finally take the moment to tuck our king into the corner and wait to see what White will do next.} 
18. Bg1 {Continuing in the same patient and very solid style, removing the bishop from a potentially exposed square and also vacating the e3 square for the queen in some lines. Needless to say, this sophisticated maneuvering is very typical of the modern engines and top grandmaster games, but I would be quite surprised to see it on a regular basis at the club level.} 
18. a6 {This is the new, creative and unexplored idea that I stumbled upon after the lengthy analysis of this position. Black makes a useful waiting move, covering the b5 square, preparing to bring the b6 knight back into the game. The move also prepares the surprising b5 expansion.This is much better than the immediate18...Nc8when19.c5is annoying, restricting the knight on c8 and preparing Bb5 or Bc4. This is precisely what our move is trying to avoid.With that being said, the move18...e5is the alternative worth exploring. In his course, Giri mentions this move and states that White is better after either19.d5or19.dxe5- yet he doesn't really give that many variations. While I do agree with Giri's evaluation, I don't necessarily think that the situation is that obvious or clear to anyone below the super GM level, so feel free to analyze this option on your own if you are interested.} 
19. b3 {A logical move, reinforcing the c4 pawn and trying to stay as solid as possible. Given that we are on an unexplored territory, I don't think it is sensible to analyze a myriad of options for White. Let me just mention that the idea of Nc8 is quite typical in almost all variations.Say, if19.Qe3Qb420.b3Black goes for the same20...Nc8plan.The only exception is perhaps19.Rfe1,when we should be careful not to run into some d5 ideas and should therefore go for19...Qf7when we want to play Nc8 next all the same.} 
19. Nc8 {Finally embarking on the desired knight maneuver, intending to reach f5 via the d6 square. This knight on b6 is Black's worst-placed piece in these variations of the Four Pawns Attack so it makes a lot of sense to try to improve it and bring it back to the game.} 
20. c5 {Trying to prevent the activation of the knight as now White controls the d6 square. But here Black can execute a very unexpected and surprising idea.} 
20. b5 {A very computerish idea, trying to gain some space on the queenside and restrict the opponent's light-squared bishop. Black is ready to sacrifice a pawn in order to get the knight onc8back into the game. Thus after21.cxb6cxb622.Bxa6first we include the22...Nb4tempo and then after23.Be2Nd6we are ready to jump with the knight to f5. Also note that it is important to have the bishop on h7 here as24.Ne5is not a tempo and we can calmly continue with24...Nf5,pressuring the d4 pawn. The position seems quite acceptable for Black to handle in practice - and even the engine slowly converges to the eternal '0.0' evaluation.That is why it is probably better for White not to react to the advance on the queenside and go for something like21.Qe3,trying to slowly improve the position. Here Black should also try to bring the knight on c8 back in the game, this time via e7 after21...Qe8I analyzed22.Bh2N8e723.Bxc7Nf524.Qf2Rd7when Black seems to have quite reasonable compensation for the pawn.Conclusion: The Four Pawns Attack is definitely one of the critical - if not THE most critical - tests of the Alekhine defence. It is one of the lines that makes an opening such as Alekhine defence very difficult to uphold on the correspondence level - as modern engines do claim White has an objective advantage in the main tabiya of this variation.However, it is very debatable how relevant the objective state of the variation (and the opening) are at the practical, human level. In this course, I have not only tried to avoid the main tabiya whenever possible - but also tried to come up with a less-explored and computer-backed variations that might be extremely tricky to handle in practice. I do think that the variation with 15...h6 and 16...Bh7 is quite tricky - and I do feel that White's advantage is not as one-sided or definite as the computer claims - as the position is very concrete and as both sides have some weaknesses.} 
