[White "7) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange variation: 4.exd6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this chapter, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. exd6 {Capturing on d6 immediately is less flexible as it allows Black some additional options now that the knight can potentially go to f6 or even c7.} 
4. cxd6 {Of course, just like in the mainline - we recapture with the c-pawn in order to keep the pawn structure asymmetrical/imbalanced. There is nothing wrong with capturing with the e-pawn, either, but it does lead to a bit more dull positions, which I, generally, prefer to avoid.} 
5. c4 {It is not 100% clear what White can gain from reversing the move order and first capturing on d6. At a minimum, Black can transpose back to normal variation - while it is also possible to exploit the move order to place the knight on a different square.} 
5. Nf6 {With the pawn on e5, this move would not be possible, but here it is. Instead of placing the knight on b6, Black places it on f6 and claims it is better on this, more central square. Most notably because now the idea of d5 has a lot of merit, as White will be unable to play c5 with a gain of tempo - the knight is not on b6.With that being said5...Nc7is also interesting, while5...Nb6,transposing to the normal lines, might be even lazier. But why not try to take advantage of White's imprecise move order?} 
6. Nf3 {Since this is not a main variation in this repertoire, I don't think it is necessary to go into too many details and to cover every possible developing scheme for White. I will, therefore, stick to providing a sample line against the most natural setup, illustrating one of the advantages of having the knight on f6.} 
6. g6 {Just like in positions with the knight on b6, we go for the setup with the bishop on g7. Even though the knight is currently blocking it} 
7. Be2 {Continuing with the development of the bishop. As we will see in the mainlines, White doesn't necessarily have to fear the Bg4 pin, so losing a tempo to prevent it with7.h3is not really necessary. Once again, all these details will be covered and explained in the main variation with the knight on b6.} 
7. Bg7
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Nc3 {The most natural move. Now the question is - what should Black do? In positions with the knight on b6, the diagonal of the bishop on g7 is open, so Black's play most commonly revolves around executing the e5 break. In the given position with the knight on f6, the bishop's diagonal is closed, which makes e5 less desirable. On the other hand, Black does have an alternative central strike at disposal.Note, btw., that White can prevent Black from freeing themselves with the very extreme9.d5, but after9...e6Black is happy to open up the position at the expense of the slight weakening of the d6 pawn. A complicated battle will ensue.} 
9. d5 {A nice option available to Black with the knight on f6, as the typical advance of the c-pawn is now less powerful (as it doesn't gain a tempo on the knight on b6). Black will get a nice 'Grunfeldesque' position where White will very likely end up having an isolated pawn on d4.That doesn't mean Black is better by any means, but it does mean we have very easy and clear play from this point onward - Nc6, take on c4, Rc8, potentially Bf5 or Ne4 and then take it from there.} 
