8. h3 {In this position, almost any quiet move by White is met with the typical central advance.} 
8. e5 {This is very thematic and reasonable, although even here,8...Nc7with some b5 ideas is a possibility. But I think playing e5 here is much more understandable from the human perspective. Furthermore, it is very instructive to see why exactly the knight stands better on d5 than on b6 when this type of central break happens.} 
9. c4 {This now comes a bit too late as Black has some additional flexibility with the knight - not only is the e7 square open, but the knight can also potentially go to f4.} 
9. Nf4 {A bit more combative than retreating to e7 which is also good. The knight is much more active on f4 than it would be on b6,  for example. Black doesn't mind the capture as it would open up the bishop on g7 and eliminate the opponent's bishop pair. After some10.Bxf4exf411.Nc3the pawn on f4 only appears to be weak and Black can even contemplate playing11...g5to reinforce it.In any case, we have achieved the dream of an Alekhine player - unclear, murky and combative positions with reasonable chances of playing for a win.} 
