3. d6
4. exd6 {Capturing on d6 immediately is less flexible as it allows Black some additional options now that the knight can potentially go to f6 or even c7.} 
4. cxd6 {Of course, just like in the mainline - we recapture with the c-pawn in order to keep the pawn structure asymmetrical/imbalanced. There is nothing wrong with capturing with the e-pawn, either, but it does lead to a bit more dull positions, which I, generally, prefer to avoid.} 
5. Nf3 {White can also try to play without the move c4 whatsoever, but it is definitely not the most challenging. Black will have the very same plan of trying to execute a quick e5, but with the knight on d5 there are some additional options - for example jumping to f4 later down the road.} 
