[Black "Exchange variation: 4.c4 and 5.Nf3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this chapter, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. Nf3 {Before we get to the main move 5.exd6, let's briefly consider this natural developing move, bringing the knight to f3 and trying to play some version of the Modern variation with the pawn on c4 and the knight on b6. This is very uncommon, but this move is not at all silly as it looks.} 
5. g6 {This seems to be the simplest, as it is hard or White to refrain from taking on d6, eventually transposing to the line that can arise via 5.exd6.It is also possible to take on e5 immediately with5...dxe5, but after6.Nxe5the resulting position is not at all so simple to handle as I initially envisioned - and practical results in the lichess database (50% win for White, 46% win for Black) indirectly confirm .While we are at practical results in the lichess database, the move5...Bg4seems to be scoring quite well for Black. However, I don't think it is particularly good as after6.exd6we find ourselves in an inferior version of the 5.exd6 lines. Even though this Bg4 move looks very logical as it eliminates the defender of the d4 pawn, it does give up the bishop for a knight and should be played only under the right circumstances - and not automatically.} 
6. Nc3
6. Bg7
7. Bf4 {Trying to overprotect the e5 pawn.} 
7. O-O {We continue developing as we know the center will come under pressure sooner or later. Black scores 56% from this position, while White only 39%, according to the lichess database.} 
8. Be2
8. Nc6 {The pressure against the d4 pawn is at its peak and White finally has to release the tension.} 
9. exd6 {This is semi-forced as White can't preserve the pawn on e5. After9.O-Odxe5there is no good way of recapturing and Black has reasonable chances of seizing the initiative.} 
9. cxd6 {Of course, we recapture with the c-pawn as in the mainline and obtain a better version, as the bishop on f4 is merely in the way of the e-pawn and is also not protecting the d4 pawn. Black has two ideas here - going for e5 at once, or even playing Bg4-d5-Bxf3 and then taking on d4.} 
10. h3 {This move prevents Bg4, but is met strongly with the advance of the e-pawn.} 
10. e5 {A very thematic strike in these positions that also works out tactically here!} 
11. Bg5 {In the variation with 10.O-O, this would be very annoying, but here a concrete variation works because White hasn't castled yet and vacated the e1 square for the knight on f3.} 
11. Qe8
12. Nb5 {This is very annoying in the 10.O-O line, but here it doesn't work due to a very precise and accurate sequence.} 
12. e4 {Hitting the knight on f3.} 
13. Nh2 {This is the difference. If White castled, the knight could have gone to e1 and c2 to defend the d4 pawn, but here it is very far away from the center so the pawn on d4 is quite exposed. Note that13.Nc7Qd7is already winning for Black.} 
13. Qd7 {Black is now threatening a6, winning the pawn on d4, while if the bishop retreats to e3 then the f-pawn can also march forward. Black is already somewhat better and can be very happy with the outcome of the opening.} 
