[White "7) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange variation with 6.Nc3 and 7.h4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this chapter, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. exd6 {The capture on d6 leads to the so-called Exchange variation. White voluntarily releases the tension in the position and gets rid of the pawn on e5 that was securing them a lot of space. On the other hand, this pawn often turns out to be Black's main source of counterplay, so White is trying to make an argument that this exchange eliminates a potential target and provides White's center with some stability.Even though this solid approach is not the most critical or ambitious, it is very annoying to face in practice because it makes it quite difficult to play for the win (I have often jokingly referred to it as the 'Alapin of the Alekhine').} 
5. cxd6 {This is a big and important crossroad as it is possible to capture ond6with both pawns. The move5...exd6is generally regarded as the soundest and most solid way to deal with the exchange variation, but I have always found the resulting positions a bit dull, due to the symmetrical pawn structure. In this course, I will be, therefore, recommending the more ambitious, combative and risky approach, involving the capture with the c-pawn, simply because it leads to a more imbalanced position with an asymmetrical pawn structure.Also note that we can't really capture on d6 with the queen in 'Scandi' style, since5...Qxd66.c5Qe67.Be2is not very pleasant as our pieces are not really standing very well.} 
6. Nc3 {In this position, White has a vast choice, as there are many possible move orders available at our opponent's disposal. However, most commonly, White decides either to start by developing the kingside pieces and castling quickly or by developing the queenside pieces and trying to prevent Black's counterplay on that side of the board before proceeding with the kingside operations.Sure, these two plans/ schemes can be mixed and there are many move orders that lead to transpositions, but in principle, we will be focusing our attention on the moves6.Nc3and6.Nf3Not only because they follow the golden opening principle (Knights before bishops) or because this is the 100 Repertoires - but also because other moves such as6.Be3,6.Bd3or6.Be2are very likely to transpose.With that being said, you might be wondering - what exactly is the point of the text move? What are the benefits of starting with the queenside development? Well, as we will soon see, Black does have some ideas that involve generating counterplay in the center and on the queenside, so White quickly tries to mobilize the c1 bishop, the knight on b1 and the rook on c1 to avoid any issues. This is a very legitimate and serious way of handling this asymmetrical variation of the Exchange variation, so we should know what to do about it and how to handle it.} 
6. g6 {Of course, fianchettoing the bishop is the central theme of this entire chapter and we indeed go for it here, as well. Now White has quite a few options at their disposal.} 
7. h4 {First of all, in the era of neural chess engines and Leela Zero, we need to consider the advance of the h-pawn in almost any position. Here, this idea has a lot of sense because Black's knight is far away on the queenside and Black lacks control of the critical h5 square.} 
7. h5 {I think stopping the h-pawn in its tracks is not only objectively the strongest - but also much more practical than allowing the advance to h5. After, say,7...Bg78.h5White has a positive score in the lichess database (51% wins, 44% loses, 5% draws), while after the text moves the statistics are eschewed into Black's favour (53% wins, 43% losses, 4% draws). It is true that the move 7...h5 allows our opponent to occupy the g5 square, but this is of less significance than allowing the h-pawn further. Now White has quite a few options at their disposal, but I will examine the two most common ones.} 
8. Nf3 {The most natural move, developing the knight and potentially aiming to get it to the g5 square. But this allows us to demonstrate that White's early advance of the h-pawn also had its drawbacks and exploit the weakened g4 square.} 
8. Bg4 {A very thematic and strong move. Not only do we pin the knight and prevent the potential Ng5 jumps, but we also threaten to eliminate the important defender of the central d4 pawn. Next, we want to play Bg7, O-O and Nc6 and pressure the d4 pawn.} 
9. Be2 {A logical move, dealing with the pin and preparing to castle.} 
9. Bg7 {Fianchettoing the bishop, targeting the d4 pawn and preparing to castle, too.} 
10. Bg5 {This is the strongest move according to the engine. It makes a lot of sense, optically speaking, to place the bishop on the weakened g5 square and create some potential pressure against the e7 pawn, but given that it basically forces White to give up the d4 pawn later down the road, it is debatable how human and natural it is.- With that being said, it is not easy to suggest and alternative. For example,10.Be3does protect the d4 pawn, but runs into the standard d5 issue, e.g. after10...O-O11.Rc1d5White can also try to get the knight to g5 via10.Ng5, but then after10...Bxe211.Nxe2Nc6Black again has an annoying pressure against the center and the prospect of playing d5, gaining some space and central control.Finally, if10.O-OO-OWhite is once again faced with the dilemma of where to develop the bishop and how to deal with the bishop on g4.} 
10. Nc6 {Continuing to develop and pressuring the d4 pawn.} 
11. O-O {The most natural move in the position. The engine suggests that11.Rc1is better as the rook gets away from the long diagonal and prepares d5, but then Black has11...Bxf3True, after12.Bxf3Nxc413.O-Othe engine claims White has sufficient compensation - but would a human evaluate it so precisely?Secondly, after11...Bxf312.Bxf3Black can also capture on d4 via12...Nxd413.Bxb7Rb8when we get a strong and centralized knight on d4. The engine gives a slight preference to White after14.Be4but I think Black is very comfortable in a practical game.} 
11. O-O {Now that White is not really threatening d5, we don't hurry to capture on f3 and d4 and continue developing instead.} 
12. Re1 {Preparing a potential discovered attack on the e7 pawn.} 
12. Re8 {Simply defending the e7 pawn and asking White what they want to do. If they play something like13.d5, trying to preserve the pawns, then13...Bxf314.Bxf3Ne5is very inconvenient as15.b3is met strongly with15...Nexc4Instead, White should probably go for something like13.Rc1when we can again win a pawn with13...Bxf314.Bxf3Nxc4and White's compensation is again not very obvious. All in all, I think Black has more natural and obvious ideas in these lines due to the pressure against White's center - and it is precisely what an Alekhine player is looking for.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange variation with 6.Nc3 and 7.h4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this chapter, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. exd6 {The capture on d6 leads to the so-called Exchange variation. White voluntarily releases the tension in the position and gets rid of the pawn on e5 that was securing them a lot of space. On the other hand, this pawn often turns out to be Black's main source of counterplay, so White is trying to make an argument that this exchange eliminates a potential target and provides White's center with some stability.Even though this solid approach is not the most critical or ambitious, it is very annoying to face in practice because it makes it quite difficult to play for the win (I have often jokingly referred to it as the 'Alapin of the Alekhine').} 
5. cxd6 {This is a big and important crossroad as it is possible to capture ond6with both pawns. The move5...exd6is generally regarded as the soundest and most solid way to deal with the exchange variation, but I have always found the resulting positions a bit dull, due to the symmetrical pawn structure. In this course, I will be, therefore, recommending the more ambitious, combative and risky approach, involving the capture with the c-pawn, simply because it leads to a more imbalanced position with an asymmetrical pawn structure.Also note that we can't really capture on d6 with the queen in 'Scandi' style, since5...Qxd66.c5Qe67.Be2is not very pleasant as our pieces are not really standing very well.} 
6. Nc3 {In this position, White has a vast choice, as there are many possible move orders available at our opponent's disposal. However, most commonly, White decides either to start by developing the kingside pieces and castling quickly or by developing the queenside pieces and trying to prevent Black's counterplay on that side of the board before proceeding with the kingside operations.Sure, these two plans/ schemes can be mixed and there are many move orders that lead to transpositions, but in principle, we will be focusing our attention on the moves6.Nc3and6.Nf3Not only because they follow the golden opening principle (Knights before bishops) or because this is the 100 Repertoires - but also because other moves such as6.Be3,6.Bd3or6.Be2are very likely to transpose.With that being said, you might be wondering - what exactly is the point of the text move? What are the benefits of starting with the queenside development? Well, as we will soon see, Black does have some ideas that involve generating counterplay in the center and on the queenside, so White quickly tries to mobilize the c1 bishop, the knight on b1 and the rook on c1 to avoid any issues. This is a very legitimate and serious way of handling this asymmetrical variation of the Exchange variation, so we should know what to do about it and how to handle it.} 
6. g6 {Of course, fianchettoing the bishop is the central theme of this entire chapter and we indeed go for it here, as well. Now White has quite a few options at their disposal.} 
7. h4 {First of all, in the era of neural chess engines and Leela Zero, we need to consider the advance of the h-pawn in almost any position. Here, this idea has a lot of sense because Black's knight is far away on the queenside and Black lacks control of the critical h5 square.} 
7. h5 {I think stopping the h-pawn in its tracks is not only objectively the strongest - but also much more practical than allowing the advance to h5. After, say,7...Bg78.h5White has a positive score in the lichess database (51% wins, 44% loses, 5% draws), while after the text moves the statistics are eschewed into Black's favour (53% wins, 43% losses, 4% draws). It is true that the move 7...h5 allows our opponent to occupy the g5 square, but this is of less significance than allowing the h-pawn further. Now White has quite a few options at their disposal, but I will examine the two most common ones.} 
8. Bd3 {Apart from developing the knight to f3 and allowing the Bg4 pin, the text move is also very popular. It makes a lot of sense to develop the bishop and prepare the development of the knight to e2 in order to avoid the Bg4 pin. But on the other hand, with the bishop on d3, the pawn on d4 is not protected by the queen.} 
8. Bg7 {Continuing with the natural developing move and slowly starting to pressure the center.} 
9. Nge2
9. Nc6 {And now again White is faced with a dilemma - how to deal with the pressure against the d4 pawn.} 
10. d5 {The most logical move, hitting the knight on c6 in the process. Note that10.Be3is by far the most common move in this position, but it would once again be met with the thematic Alekhine strike10...d5Since we will be seeing this typical idea in different shapes and forms later in this chapter, I would refrain from including it as trainable at this particular juncture - even if it is the most common.} 
10. Ne5 {In contrast to the previous variation, White is not as vulnerable along the long h8-a1 diagonal as the knight on e2 is protecting the knight on c3, but on the other hand, we are able to get the bishop pair and eliminate the one on d3.} 
11. b3
11. Nxd3+
12. Qxd3
12. Nd7 {Retreating the knight immediately as there is no future for the steed on the queenside. Next, Black wants to play Ne5 and O-O and then seek to open up the position on the queenside with the thematic a6-b5 break. It is true that White has more space (which is the main reason why the engine gives the first player preference in this position), but Black's position is fairly solid and we have a long-term asset in the form of the bishop pair. Given that this whole variation is quite rare, I think this is an acceptable outcome of the opening!} 
