12. dxe5 {A better move than moving the d-pawn forward.} 
12. dxe5 {White's argument is that this version of the 'endgame' pawn structure is better for them due to the fact Black has moved the bishop to g4 where it doesn't really belong.} 
13. O-O {Here, it is not that beneficial for White to exchange queens as Black's heavy pieces on the back rank are connected, so after something like13.Qxd8Raxd8Black has a very harmonious setup. Instead, White invites Black to take on d1 which would land them the control over the only open file.I would also mention that13.h3should be met with13...Bxf314.Bxf3f5when we will get in e4 next. Since this is played much more rarely than 13.O-O, I would refrain from giving it as a trainable.} 
13. h6 {We take the g5 square under control in preparation of Be6 and f5 plan.} 
14. c5 {Once again we see this idea. Without this move, White can hardly count on an advantage.} 
14. Nd7
15. Ne4 {A logical move, aiming to get the knight to the weakened d6 square. The engine gives some15.b4, but it is really not very human to just give up a pawn in this position. Besides, Black's chances are not inferior in the resulting complications. I will give the main line that continues15...Nxb416.Qa4a517.Rfd1Qe718.a3e4} 
15. Nf6 {Challenging the knight, controlling the d5 square and opening up the 7th rank so that the queen can protect the b7 pawn. This is safer than15...f5,which is also possible.} 
16. Nd6
16. Qe7 {And Black has completed the development, defended the weaknesses and has a very solid pawn structure and obvious next moves in the form of Be6, Rfd8 and then Ne8, challenging the annoying knight on d6. White is perhaps slightly better, but we definitely have our trumps here and it is possible to imagine Black taking over at some point in the later stage.} 
