8. Rc1 {The point behind White's setup. White realizes that Black's idea is to play some sort of 8...d5 and 9...Nc4 combo (as is usually the case when White plays Be3 in the Alekhine) and takes measures against it.Moves such as8.Nf3or8.Be2are barely played and are also most likely to transpose to 6.Nf3 lines, so they will not be examined separately.} 
8. O-O {We have to castle here before doing anything else. In case you are wondering, the immediate8...d5doesn't quite work as after9.c5Nc410.Bxc4dxc4White has11.Qa4,picking up the pawn on c4 with a gain of time.} 
9. b3 {This move, covering the c4 square and preventing the d5 idea, is by far the most common move in the position and only one really worth considering. If White refrains from playing it, then Black gets a good position with the help of the thematic d5-Nc4 combo.For example,9.Be2d510.c5Nc4or9.Nf3d510.c5Nc4After the text move, the c4 square is covered and Black obviously doesn't have the same Nc4 idea, so the question is - what do we do instead?} 
9. e5 {After some consideration, I have decided to recommend this thematic central strike as the main option in this repertoire. This move was mentioned by both Roland Pruijssers and Bryan Tillis in their respective Alekhine repertoires here on Chessable, but it was dismissed as a bit too dry/non-combative. And while it is true that this allows White to exchange the pawns on e5 and essentially go for an endgame, I will try to make an argument that this endgame is not at all so simple or 'dry' as it looks at first glance.Besides, I am not 100% sure whether Black has a worthy alternative in this position. Both Tillis and Pruijssers gave9...Bf5as their main recommendation, but it seems to me that10.h3borderline refutes this attempt, as the main idea of10...d5is now met with11.g4Bd712.c5It is true that this whole h3-g4 is not the most easy to find over-the-board, but it is not that difficult to find at home when analyzing with the engine.On the other hand, the most common move in the position according to the lichess database is9...Nc6, but after10.d5White simply obtains a fantastic position and scores extremely well in practice (61% wins).On the other hand, when I analyzed this position some time ago, I discovered the amazing line that goes9...d510.c5e5Alas, even though it is extremely beautiful, it is not 100% sound, so I couldn't bring myself to give it as my main recommendation in this position (I have to mention that Pruijssers also gave it in his repertoire with a very similar verdict). However, I couldn't make a course on Alekhine and omit it completely, so this line will be provided as the alternative.} 
10. dxe5 {Last but not least, this exchange on e5 is the main reason why 9...e5 is considered a bit meek/non-combative. And while it is true it allows White to exchange queens and reach an endgame with the queenside pawn majority, I don't necessarily think that White has such a big advantage - nor that Black has zero chances of playing for a win.} 
10. dxe5
11. Qxd8
11. Rxd8
12. c5 {The only try to play for the advantage. White realizes that the knight can't really jump to d5 and therefore forces it to an inferior spot on d7, while gaining some space and opening up the diagonal for the bishop from f1 to come to c4. This move was the main recommendation by Christof Sielecki in his Keep It Simple 1.e4, Vol 1. here on Chessable.Note that White has to try this move in order to fight for the advantage, as otherwise, Black will simply get Nc6-Nd4 jump, e.g. after12.Nf3Nc613.Be2Nd4,when the second player is already to be preferred.} 
12. N6d7 {We have to go here as12...Nd513.Rd1is a rather embarrassing way to lose a game of chess.} 
13. Bc4 {A natural developing move, placing the bishop to a newly opened c4 square.13.Nf3is very likely to transpose.} 
13. Nc6 {Of course. This knight belongs to c6 in these structures. Black's general idea is to play h6 - Kh7 - f5, Na5 if required, move the knight from d7 and then develop the bishop on c8. I am not 100% sure what exactly White can do to prevent this harmonious development, which is why I am very doubtful of White's claims that they have an easy game/advantage in this variation.} 
14. Nf3
14. h6 {Taking the g5 square under control and creating a square for the king on e7 is quite useful and natural.} 
15. O-O {The most common move. What can be more natural than castling? In Keep It Simple 1.0, IM Christof Sielecki analyzed15.Nb5, but after15...Bf8we are intending to play Be6 nevertheless and capture the knight if it ever jumps to d6.} 
15. Nf8 {A very fine maneuver, preparing to play Be6 next and deal with the pin on the f7 pawn. Note that here15...Na5is not as good as the knight is still on c3, so after16.Be2f517.Nd5is somewhat inconvenient.} 
16. Rfd1
16. Be6 {Black will go f5 and potentially f4 next. All our pieces are developed, rooks are connected, we have the potential d4 outpost and even if the enemy knight comes to d6 it will not be the end of the world. The engine thinks this position is equal and I also think it is quite possible to win this position once the kingside pawn mass starts moving. In any case, the outcome of the opening is more than acceptable and I don't see any reasons for Black to fear this variation with 10.dxe5.} 
