9. d5 {As mentioned in my comments to9...e5,when analyzing this position in the past I stumbled on this idea, challenging the center immediately. The move in itself is not that fascinating, but the follow-up is simply amazing as it involves a completely unexpected piece sacrifice. And even though this variation is not completely unknown and also not completely sound, it is extremely interesting and fun to play, which is why I had to include it in this course, if only as the alternative option.} 
10. c5 {Of course, White advances the pawn and attacks our knight.} 
10. Nc6 {This move, striking in the center immediately and simply leaving the knight on b6 en prise, is the whole point of Black's play. We essentially want to play e5 next, open up the position and create pressure against the d4 pawn. At first glance, it looks ludicrous to give up a piece, but considering that we are somewhat ahead in development and that White's king is still in the center, this idea definitely has some logic. Furthermore, it is bound to come as a shock/surprise to your opponent. I played it in some rapid games online and almost inevitably my opponents would take a few minutes to figure out whether to take the piece or not.} 
11. cxb6 {Of course - who could possibly resist such a tempting offer. Besides, if White doesn't do it, their center collapses and Black obtains a very good position.} 
11. e5 {The point behind Black's play. With this thematic central pawn strike, we create tremendous pressure against the d4 pawn and also seek to exploit the position of the White king in the center. Now White has to defend the d4 pawn.} 
12. Nge2 {The best move, avoiding any sort of Bg4 pin, as would be the case after12.Nf3Bg4} 
12. exd4
13. Nxd4 {The more logical and natural recapture, not giving up the dark-squared bishop. After13.Bxd4Nxd414.Nxd4Qxb6,Black only has a pawn for the piece, but due to the massive lead in development and the threat of playing d4 next, the situation is completely unclear and Black has big practical compensation.} 
13. Bxd4 {A surprising capture, but the point is to draw the bishop out and play Qh4 next without allowing some Bxg7 in return.} 
14. Bxd4
14. Qh4 {Hitting the bishop on d4 and activating the queen.} 
15. Bc5 {A natural move and the one that has been played against me in practice. White can also play15.Ne2, but after15...axb6it is not easy to complete the development and Black has some compensation, even if the engine does claim the material advantage gives White some objective edge in the position.} 
15. Re8+
16. Be2
16. axb6 {For the moment, we only have a pawn for the piece, but all our pieces are in play, we have some pressure along the e-file and also ideas of playing d4. For example, after the most natural17.Bxb6we go17...d418.O-Odxc319.Rxc3Qb4!?and we are definitely not worse.Unfortunately, White can include17.g3when after17...Qh318.Bxb6Bg419.Be3our compensation is running out of steam. The best we can get is19...Bxe220.Nxe2d421.Nxd4Nxd422.Qxd4Qg223.Rf1Rxa2when we have some compensation, although White is a full piece up. It is a variation such as this one, together with 15.Ne2 or even 12. Nce2 that has dissuaded me from recommending this whole 8...d5 line as the main option. I do think White is objectively better and I also don't like that all of their moves are kinda forced and obvious.Still, it is a fascinating variation that is also very fun to play, so I wanted to have it in the course in case someone wants to try it in their own practice. Do play at your own risk.} 
