7. Bd3 {Aside from the more natural7.Be2,this move is also quite commonly played, according to the lichess database. At first glance, I thought it is just ridiculous as it seemingly makes zero sense to place the bishop here as now the knight on f3 can be pinned and the pawn on d4 is not defended, but a closer analysis revealed things are not at all that simple, even if the practical results are overwhelmingly in Black's favour, according to the lichess database.} 
7. Bg7 {Alas, it turns out that7...Bg4doesn't really achieve anything due to8.Nbd2when White is ready to play h3 next. Hence, we start by fianchettoing the bishop.} 
8. O-O {The main reason why White's results are rather poor in the lichess database is the fact that this move is by far the most common one in this position. But as usual in these Alekhine positions, playing natural-looking moves without a specific purpose doesn't really lead to anything too good for the first player and allows Black to start the fight for the initiative.} 
8. Bg4 {This is already highly annoying for White as now the d4 pawn is under considerable pressure.} 
9. Be3
9. Nc6 {And it is hard to suggest a good move for White here. Relatively the best is10.h3Bxf311.Qxf3Nxd412.Qxb7, but after12...O-OBlack is more than okay after trading the b-pawn for the central pawn. Our pieces are more active, we have some Rb8 ideas and the second player is already to be slightly preferred.} 
