[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {In this chapter, we will cover the very popular Exchange variation that involves White releasing the tension in the center by capturing on d6 at virtually the very first opportunity. Just like all the main variations in this course, it will be examined via the 3.d4 move order, although it has to be mentioned that this variation can also be reached via3.c4Nb64.d4d65.exd6move order!} 
3. d6
4. c4 {The most common move order, chasing the knight to b6 before deciding on a capture on d6.} 
4. Nb6
5. exd6 {The capture on d6 leads to the so-called Exchange variation. White voluntarily releases the tension in the position and gets rid of the pawn on e5 that was securing them a lot of space. On the other hand, this pawn often turns out to be Black's main source of counterplay, so White is trying to make an argument that this exchange eliminates a potential target and provides White's center with some stability.Even though this solid approach is not the most critical or ambitious, it is very annoying to face in practice because it makes it quite difficult to play for the win (I have often jokingly referred to it as the 'Alapin of the Alekhine').} 
5. cxd6 {This is a big and important crossroad as it is possible to capture ond6with both pawns. The move5...exd6is generally regarded as the soundest and most solid way to deal with the exchange variation, but I have always found the resulting positions a bit dull, due to the symmetrical pawn structure. In this course, I will be, therefore, recommending the more ambitious, combative and risky approach, involving the capture with the c-pawn, simply because it leads to a more imbalanced position with an asymmetrical pawn structure.Also note that we can't really capture on d6 with the queen in 'Scandi' style, since5...Qxd66.c5Qe67.Be2is not very pleasant as our pieces are not really standing very well.} 
6. Nf3 {Last but not least, even though the setup with Nc3-Be3-Rc1-b3 is very popular and testing, this natural developing move, aiming to mobilize the bishop and castle as quickly as possible, is still the most common move in the position - and arguably the most challenging. Some White players hesitate to make this move because it allows Black to pin the knight with Bg4, but as we will soon see, White doesn't really have to fear this early bishop move just yet.} 
6. g6 {Just like in the 6.Nc3 variation, we will aim for the fianchetto setup, aiming to bring the bishop to g7 from where it can influence the central e5 and d4 squares. It is important to mention that the pinning move6...Bg4is made automatically by many Alekhine players, but it really doesn't achieve anything in this position. For example, after7.h3Bh58.Nc3Black doesn't really have a reasonable continuation. For example, if8...e6then9.d5is already quite strong.While if7...Bg48.h3Bh59.Nc3Nc610.d5Bxf3(which is a standard idea in a number of Alekhine positions) then10.Qxf3Ne511.Qe4and White has everything protected, the bishop pair, more space and a completely winning position. We can conclude that the move Bg4 is much more powerful once the bishop has been developed to e2, because then White will have to recapture on f3 with the bishop and remove one of the defenders of the c4 pawn.After 6...g6, White has a wide array of options at their disposal.} 
7. Be2 {Apart from the move7.h3,which will be examined slightly later, White can also just continue developing and claim that Bg4 is not problematic for the moment. More often than not, this will transpose to the lines examined via 7.h3 move order, but there are some variations that have unique value.} 
7. Bg7 {As I mentioned several times in this chapter, Black shouldn't go for the Bg4 move too early in this chapter. To be fair, at this particular moment, it is not entirely clear why7...Bg4is not as good, but it transpires that White has a very annoying move8.a4The idea is that after8...a59.h3Bxf310.Bxf3Nc611.d5Ne5White has12.b3as now after12...Bg7the rook on a1 has some space and after13.Ra2White has a clearly better position.Similarly, after7...Bg48.a4Nc6is not particularly good due to9.a5when White has an advantage. I understand these lines might seem a bit computerish, but they are a good illustration of why it is not good to rush with Bg4 too early in these positions.} 
8. O-O {The only move that has some independent value, given that 8.h3 O-O transposes to lines examined via 7.h3 move order,while8.Nc3O-Owill transpose to the text after9.O-OBg4,or to the 7.h3 lines after9.h3} 
8. O-O
9. Nc3 {This is not good as it finally allows Bg4 under good circumstances, but9.h3Nc6is another transposition to 7.h3 lines.} 
9. Bg4 {Here Black can also try to transpose to the 7.h3 lines via9...Nc610.h3,but we can play more ambitiously and start pressuring the center.} 
10. Be3 {What else?10.h3Bxf311.Bxf3Nc6is the Alekhine's player dream as Black has a lot of pressure against the center.} 
10. Nc6 {Developing the knight and increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn, while now Bxf3 and Nxc4 is also a threat. Note that this position is an exception from the 'meet Be3 with d5 rule' because we have already moved the light-squared bishop.Thus, after10...d511.c5Nc412.Bxc4dxc413.h3Bf514.Qa4Bd315.Rfd1White achieves a more harmonious setup compared to some other variations as they are much better developed due to our loss of tempo.} 
11. b3 {Protecting the vulnerable c4 point.} 
11. d5 {Now we finally strike in the center even though the c4 square is not available to us, mainly because White has weakened the long h8-a1 diagonal and also lost a tempo in b3 (since it makes the queenside expansion with b4 slower).} 
12. c5
12. Nc8
13. b4
13. a6 {This position has been reached more than 100 times in practice, and Black has very reasonable results. Our next few moves are fairly simple - play e6, take on f3, place the knight on f5 via e7 and pressure the center.} 
