11. d5 {Last but not least, this move is not the most common, but it does have some logic. It is not so much about attacking the knight on c6 as about freeing the d4 square for the knight. White wants to exploit Black's last move and immediately hit that bishop on f5.} 
11. Na5 {A typical response to d5. Now we can see the downside of White's idea - it does involve a pawn sacrifice.} 
12. Nd4
12. Naxc4 {It is better to take with this knight as otherwise the knights on a5 and c4 would be somewhat 'hanging in the air'.} 
13. a4 {Apart from the more obvious move13.Nxf5which will be examined next, this subtle advance of the a-pawn also needs to be considered - especially since it was recommended by IM Christof Sielecki in his course Keep It Simple 2.0 here on Chessable.The immediate threat is a5, winning the knight. But it transpires that Black has some issues when it comes to finding a good reply to this as all the potential responses have some drawbacks.} 
13. a5 {After some analysis, I have decided to settle on this move, stopping the advance of the a-pawn in its tracks. At first glance, it is not entirely clear why this would be a concession, but it turns out that the weakened b5 square and the possibility of playing Ra3 is relevant in some variations.Black's main problem is that the desirable move13...Ne5is met strongly with14.a5when we can't go14...Nbd7because15.g4wins a piece.Alternatively, you can consider playing13...Na5to stop the pawn, but it turns out that this leads to a worse version of 13.Nxf5 lines after14.Nxf5as our knight is 'dim' on a5 and not nicely centralized on e5.} 
14. Nxf5 {Now White finally captures the bishop on f5 and ruins the structure.} 
14. gxf5 {This is one of those positions where the engine will give a nice advantage for White (from 0.7-1.0, depending on the engine and the depth you are using), although it is not 100% clear why. Yes, Black does have a bad structure, but Black also has some fairly active pieces. It is not immediately clear how White continues, while Black does have a very clear idea of playing e6 at some point.I checked the approximate line14.Re1Re815.Bd3e6and concluded that the line is fully playable considering that the engine gives16.Rb1and16.Qh5as the best moves - neither of which is that obvious for a human player. Obviously, entering this position involves a certain risk, but given that we are a pawn up, that 11.d5 is still very rare AND that Black's results in practice are not at all so bad, I think this is a risk worth taking.} 
