[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.d4: Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "3.d4 4. g3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {So far in this course, we have covered all the possible variations that can arise via the 3.c4 move order (Which can in many cases transpose to the variations that arise via the 3.d4 move order, as we have seen in the case of the Four Pawns Attack or the Exchange Variation). Starting from this chapter we will begin our coverage of the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine defence where White refrains from moving the c-pawn early in the game and instead opts for the natural looking 3. d4. This is by far the most common variation you will encounter - both according to the lichess and masters' databases.The logic is simple - White refrains from advancing too many pawns early in the opening and overextending the forces, but tries to develop in a more harmonious and natural fashion, keeping the option of advancing the c-pawn in reserve. For a while, this has been regarded as the most critical test of the Alekhine defence. And even if the modern engines prefer the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I am also more afraid of, personally), 3.d4 is a very big and important line that needs to be taken seriously and studied in some detail.} 
3. d6 {The standard Alekhine response, creating the tension in the center and 'attacking' the e5 pawn. Now White can play4.c4and transpose to the Exchange Variation after4...Nb65.exd6or to the Four Pawns Attack after4...Nb65.f4, although the most common continuation is4.Nf3leading to the starting point of the Modern Variation. 4. Nf3 will be analyzed in the final chapter of this course, but before we get there, it is necessary to complete the picture by mentioning other, rare 4th moves available to White in this position. They will be the subject of the current chapter.} 
4. g3 {This advance of the g-pawn, intending to fianchetto the bishop to g2, is sometimes played, according to the lichess database, but that is not particularly good.This is not the only outlandish option at White's disposal in this particular position. Initially, I included three additional ones as trainables, but after some additional thinking and conversation with beta testers, I have decided to include them as clickables.A) The first option I considered was4.Nc3when4...Nxc3is the simplest solution, simply taking on c3, doubling the pawns and intending to take on e5 next. Note that this is not the same as when White plays Nc3 on move 3 as with the pawns on d6 and d4 the situation is different. After5.bxc3dxe5Black manages to exchange the queens after6.dxe5Qxd1And Black is much better in this endgame due to the better pawn structure and the fact we will develop our pieces with the gain of time with Nc6, O-O-O, and so on. At some point, we will blast open the position with the f6 break and we have every reason to be extremely happy about the outcome of the opening.B) I also checked4.Qf3but4...e6is even better than taking on e5 as we want to keep the pawn on d4, since it is now not protected and a potential target. c5 is our next move almost irrespective of what White does.5.c4Nb4!6.Qb3dxe57.dxe5N8c6Black is almost winning here - not only is the e5 pawn under the attack, but Nd4 is also a huge threat and we already have two pieces in play. Not to be recommended for White.C) Last but not least,4.c3is sometimes played, protecting the pawn on d4 and trying to erect some sort of the pawn chain from c3 to e5 in the style of the French Advance variation makes little sense here as Black is able to destroy that pawn chain immediately by executing the thematic dxe5 capture.4...dxe55.dxe5Bf56.Nf3e6And Black just has a very good version of the regular Alekhine lines/Caro-Kann/ Scandinavian structure as the pawn on e5 is somewhat exposed, our pieces have good squares, we have no weaknesses and we are already somewhat ahead in development. Be7, O-O, Nc6 or c7/Nd7 are all coming next and it is not 100% clear what White has achieved by placing the pawn on c3 so early in the game.} 
4. dxe5 {The same procedure as against all other dubious 4th moves seen in this chapter.} 
5. dxe5
5. Nb4 {This is by no means forced, but I really like the idea of jumping with the knight to b4 and offering the queen trade. It does look a bit strange to voluntarily offer White the opportunity to capture on d8 and lose our castling rights, but it transpires this is perfectly acceptable as our knight on b4 is creating some problems due to the very slow 4.g3 move.} 
6. Qxd8+ {Of course, it looks quite logical to capture on d8.} 
6. Kxd8 {But now it transpires that White has some issues with the c2 pawn and the light-squares in the position.} 
7. Na3
7. Bf5 {Renewing the pressure. Note that this works because there is no knight on f3, so some Nd4 jumps are never in the position.} 
8. c3
8. Nd3+
9. Bxd3
9. Bxd3 {Black has a very nice position with the bishop pair. The loss of the castling rights is quite irrelevant as White is in no position to exploit it.} 
