no weaknesses and we are already somewhat ahead in development. Be7, O-O, Nc6 or c7/Nd7 are all coming next and it is not 100% clear what White has achieved by placing the pawn on c3 so early in the game.} 
4. dxe5 {The same procedure as against all other dubious 4th moves seen in this chapter.} 
5. dxe5
5. Nb4 {This is by no means forced, but I really like the idea of jumping with the knight to b4 and offering the queen trade. It does look a bit strange to voluntarily offer White the opportunity to capture on d8 and lose our castling rights, but it transpires this is perfectly acceptable as our knight on b4 is creating some problems due to the very slow 4.g3 move.} 
6. Bg2 {Developing the bishop to g2 is arguably better than taking the queen on d8 - although I would be very surprised if anyone played this in a practical game.} 
6. Qxd1+ {Of course, we should be quite happy to capture on d1 as Black here.} 
7. Kxd1 {Now Black has some options, but I really like the following idea.} 
7. N4c6 {It looks a bit strange to retreat the knight from b4, but White was ready to kick it with the move a3 - and we would prefer to avoid ending up with the knight on a6, as would be the case, say, after7...N8c68.a3Na6when White can even contemplate9.Bxc6Instead, we retreat the knight ahead of time, attack the e5 pawn and intend to calmly continue our development with g6-Bg7 without allowing any sort of a3 Bxc6 tricks.} 
8. Nf3 {White should continue developing the pieces.8.f4can be met with the immediate8...f6,blasting the position open in Black's favour.} 
8. g6 {Not the only move, of course, but why not fianchetto the bishop to g7 and put pressure on the e5 pawn?} 
9. Re1
9. Bg7
10. Nc3
10. O-O {And Black has a very harmonious position with Rd8 coming next, after which some sort of a5-Na6, developing the b8 knight to a6 under better circumstances, will follow. The c8 bishop can also come to g4 or f5. And even though Black doesn't have any objective advantage, I suspect our position is a bit easier to handle in practice.} 
