5. c5 {Striking in the center and exploiting the fact that the knight is still on d5.} 
6. Nf3 {Another very popular move, according to the lichess database. The idea is to recapture on d4 with the queen and try to control the center with the pieces. It is not at all so silly as it look at first glance, although it is also not particularly dangerous for Black, either.} 
6. cxd4 {Of course, we happily take on d4 and remove one of the central pawns. Note that the e5 pawn is now isolated.} 
7. Qxd4 {The point! White brings the queen into the play and tries to control the center with the pieces. The idea is similar to the variation of the Sicilian that goes1.e4c52.Nf3d63.d4cxd44.Qxd4At first glance, it seems as if the exposed queen is a target, but the situation is not at all so simple.} 
7. Nc6 {Nevertheless, we make the obvious move and attack her majesty.} 
8. Bb5 {The point. White pins the knight, keeps the queen in the center and profits from the fact it is not possible to cover the pin with the bishop due to the hanging knight on d5.} 
8. Bf5 {Still, we are not too impressed with White's demonstration nor particularly worried about them capturing on c6, as that would involve giving up the bishop pair.} 
9. Nc3 {A logical move, continuing to develop and targeting the knight on d5. Otherwise we get easy play with e6, Be7 and so on. Once again, allow me to emphasize that9.Bxc6bxc6is nothing to be afraid of yet, as we get the bishop pair and the open b-file in compensation for our slightly ruined pawn structure.} 
9. e6 {Now we do take a moment to defend the knight since9...Nxc310.Bxc6bxc611.Qxc3is actually somewhat inconvenient with the bishop on f5 due to some Nd4 tricks.After the text move, we have a very solid, although a bit dry position. The game might continue10.Nxd5exd511.O-OBe712.Qf4Bg6when both sides have isolated pawns in the center and the game is roughly balanced.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.d4: Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "3.d4 4. f4 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {So far in this course, we have covered all the possible variations that can arise via the 3.c4 move order (Which can in many cases transpose to the variations that arise via the 3.d4 move order, as we have seen in the case of the Four Pawns Attack or the Exchange Variation). Starting from this chapter we will begin our coverage of the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine defence where White refrains from moving the c-pawn early in the game and instead opts for the natural looking 3. d4. This is by far the most common variation you will encounter - both according to the lichess and masters' databases.The logic is simple - White refrains from advancing too many pawns early in the opening and overextending the forces, but tries to develop in a more harmonious and natural fashion, keeping the option of advancing the c-pawn in reserve. For a while, this has been regarded as the most critical test of the Alekhine defence. And even if the modern engines prefer the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I am also more afraid of, personally), 3.d4 is a very big and important line that needs to be taken seriously and studied in some detail.} 
3. d6 {The standard Alekhine response, creating the tension in the center and 'attacking' the e5 pawn. Now White can play4.c4and transpose to the Exchange Variation after4...Nb65.exd6or to the Four Pawns Attack after4...Nb65.f4, although the most common continuation is4.Nf3leading to the starting point of the Modern Variation. 4. Nf3 will be analyzed in the final chapter of this course, but before we get there, it is necessary to complete the picture by mentioning other, rare 4th moves available to White in this position. They will be the subject of the current chapter.} 
4. f4 {Advancing the f-pawn without advancing the c-pawn first has also been played relatively frequently, according to the lichess database. In contrast to the other 4th moves analyzed previously, it is a bit more sensible as it does provide some additional protection to the e5 pawn, but it is still not too great.If White wants to play with this move, they should really go for4.c4Nb65.f4and transpose to the Four Pawns Attack.} 
4. dxe5 {Nevertheless! Even though the center has been reinforced, we are more than happy to take on e5. Even in the Four Pawns Attack, we couldn't go without making this move - and here we have a much better version! White doesn't have a particularly convincing/good way of recapturing!} 
5. dxe5 {This is probably better than recapturing with the f-pawn, but this is clearly not what White wants when they launch the f-pawn forward, as now the structure is symmetrical, the f-file is not opened and Black doesn't face any immediate problems.} 
5. Bf5 {Continuing to develop and potentially preparing Nb4.5...Nb4immediately, as in the lines with 4.g3, is possible, but after6.Qxd8Kxd87.Na3it would transpire that f4 is more useful for White compared to g3.} 
6. Bd3 {Trying to exchange the active bishop and prevent any sort of Nb4 shenanigans, as would be the case after6.Nf3Nb4} 
6. Bxd3 {We don't even have to exchange, but for the sake of simplicity, let's just do it.} 
7. Qxd3
7. e6 {Continuing the natural development.} 
8. Nf3
8. Nc6
9. a3 {Preventing Nb4, which was always in the air.} 
9. Be7 {Next, Black is ready to castle short - or even play Qd7 and castle long. Later down the road, we will definitely try to play f6 and undermine White's center. With no obvious weaknesses and three pieces in play, we have definitely equalized and can be happy with the outcome of the opening.} 
