[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {So far in this course, we have covered all the possible variations that can arise via the 3.c4 move order (Which can in many cases transpose to the variations that arise via the 3.d4 move order, as we have seen in the case of the Four Pawns Attack or the Exchange Variation). Starting from this chapter we will begin our coverage of the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine defence where White refrains from moving the c-pawn early in the game and instead opts for the natural looking 3. d4. This is by far the most common variation you will encounter - both according to the lichess and masters' databases.The logic is simple - White refrains from advancing too many pawns early in the opening and overextending the forces, but tries to develop in a more harmonious and natural fashion, keeping the option of advancing the c-pawn in reserve. For a while, this has been regarded as the most critical test of the Alekhine defence. And even if the modern engines prefer the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I am also more afraid of, personally), 3.d4 is a very big and important line that needs to be taken seriously and studied in some detail.} 
3. d6 {The standard Alekhine response, creating the tension in the center and 'attacking' the e5 pawn. Now White can play4.c4and transpose to the Exchange Variation after4...Nb65.exd6or to the Four Pawns Attack after4...Nb65.f4, although the most common continuation is4.Nf3leading to the starting point of the Modern Variation. 4. Nf3 will be analyzed in the final chapter of this course, but before we get there, it is necessary to complete the picture by mentioning other, rare 4th moves available to White in this position. They will be the subject of the current chapter.} 
4. Bc4 {Out of all the 4th moves considered in this chapter, this developing bishop move, hitting the d5 knight and also potentially eyeing the f7 pawn, is by far the most serious. It leads to a somewhat rare variation of the Alekhine defence that is not particularly dangerous, but which can be tricky to handle over the board without any prior analysis.} 
4. Nb6 {Almost an automatic move in the Alekhine defence when the bishop appears on c4 - we retreat the knight with the gain of tempo. In this particular case, since White refrained from developing the knight to f3, we will be able to capture on e5 on the very next move.} 
5. Bb3 {Of course, the bishop wasn't developed to c4 to immediately depart from the a2-g8 diagonal, so this is the only move really worth analyzing.} 
5. dxe5 {As mentioned above and as we have seen over and over agian in this chapter - since White refrained from reinforcing the e5 pawn on the previous move, we are more than happy to capture it, open the d-file and create a potential target on e5.} 
6. dxe5 {Taking on e5 is, of course, not to good and allows Black to go for a very good endgame.} 
6. Qxd1+
7. Kxd1
7. a5 {I really like this move in these positions with the bishop on b3, as it forces a reaction from White. It is also possible to continue developing normally as we have no weaknesses and our pieces can come into the came fairly quickly and fluently.} 
8. a4 {Trying to prevent the pawn from advancing even further. We will see in the analysis of the mainline how we should handle alternative pawn moves, but none of them bring White any good. Now the bishop on b3 has been a bit weakened and the pawn on a4 can become a potential target.} 
8. Bf5 {After pushing the a-pawn forward, we take a step back and return to natural development.} 
9. Be3
9. e6 {And next is Nc6/Nbd7, Be7, castling and so on. Black has better development, healthier pawn structure and some advantage out of the opening.} 
