2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4 {So far in this course, we have covered all the possible variations that can arise via the 3.c4 move order (Which can in many cases transpose to the variations that arise via the 3.d4 move order, as we have seen in the case of the Four Pawns Attack or the Exchange Variation). Starting from this chapter we will begin our coverage of the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine defence where White refrains from moving the c-pawn early in the game and instead opts for the natural looking 3. d4. This is by far the most common variation you will encounter - both according to the lichess and masters' databases.The logic is simple - White refrains from advancing too many pawns early in the opening and overextending the forces, but tries to develop in a more harmonious and natural fashion, keeping the option of advancing the c-pawn in reserve. For a while, this has been regarded as the most critical test of the Alekhine defence. And even if the modern engines prefer the Four Pawns Attack (a variation I am also more afraid of, personally), 3.d4 is a very big and important line that needs to be taken seriously and studied in some detail.} 
3. d6 {The standard Alekhine response, creating the tension in the center and 'attacking' the e5 pawn. Now White can play4.c4and transpose to the Exchange Variation after4...Nb65.exd6or to the Four Pawns Attack after4...Nb65.f4, although the most common continuation is4.Nf3leading to the starting point of the Modern Variation. 4. Nf3 will be analyzed in the final chapter of this course, but before we get there, it is necessary to complete the picture by mentioning other, rare 4th moves available to White in this position. They will be the subject of the current chapter.} 
4. Bc4 {Out of all the 4th moves considered in this chapter, this developing bishop move, hitting the d5 knight and also potentially eyeing the f7 pawn, is by far the most serious. It leads to a somewhat rare variation of the Alekhine defence that is not particularly dangerous, but which can be tricky to handle over the board without any prior analysis.} 
4. Nb6 {Almost an automatic move in the Alekhine defence when the bishop appears on c4 - we retreat the knight with the gain of tempo. In this particular case, since White refrained from developing the knight to f3, we will be able to capture on e5 on the very next move.} 
5. Bb3 {Of course, the bishop wasn't developed to c4 to immediately depart from the a2-g8 diagonal, so this is the only move really worth analyzing.} 
5. dxe5 {As mentioned above and as we have seen over and over agian in this chapter - since White refrained from reinforcing the e5 pawn on the previous move, we are more than happy to capture it, open the d-file and create a potential target on e5.} 
6. Qh5 {The main move in this position, eyeing the f7 pawn and also adding some control to the e5 square.} 
6. e6 {Dealing with the threat to the f7 pawn and restricting the bishop on b3. It is true that this also locks our bishop on c8, but there is no better way to deal with the threat to the f7 pawn. Besides, since White has violated the opening principles and moved the queen this early in the game, we can afford to play 'suboptimally' too, as we will have time to develop the bishop via d7 later in the game.} 
7. dxe5 {Recapturing on e5 with the pawn is the only sensible move, as7.Qxe5Nc6is not to be recommended.} 
7. a5 {As I mentioned in my notes to the 6.Qxd1 and 6.Qf3 variations, with the bishop on b3 and the knight on b3, I really like this thematic advance of the a-pawn, trying to gain some space on the queenside while harassing the bishop on b3 at the same time. a4 is now a very serious threat and White has to react to it.} 
8. a4 {The most common reaction in this position. White stops the a-pawn in its tracks and refuses to give Black more ground on the queenside. This is very sensible, but the problem is that now the pawn on a4 is a potential target. Black can start exploiting this immediately with the following knight move.} 
8. Na6 {Slightly more flexible than going via the d7 route as it doesn't lock the bishop on c8 in, although both moves are more than fine. The knight is immediately heading toward the c5 square to put pressure on White's vulnerable queenside.} 
9. Nf3 {The most natural and arguably the best move in the position. White ignores the 'threat' of Nc5 and just continues the development, intending to give up the bishop on b3 and castle on the next move.} 
9. Nc5 {Executing the desired idea and jumping to c5.} 
10. Bg5 {According to the lichess database, this developing bishop move is also sometimes played. It makes some sense to try and bring more forces toward the kingside and try to exploit the gain of space provided by the pawn on e5, but in reality, White is in no position to mount an attack and exchanging pieces will actually help Black as we have a bit less space.} 
10. Be7
11. O-O
11. Nxb3 {Eliminating the bishop on b3 and executing the core idea behind the entire Na6-Nc5 maneuver.} 
12. cxb3
12. Bxg5
13. Nxg5
13. Qe7 {Defending the pawn on f7 and preparing to remove the knight on g5 with a timely h6.} 
14. Nc3
14. Bd7 {Not yet hurrying with the h-pawn and developing the bishop, taking the b5 square under control and preparing the future Bc6, potentially keeping the option of castling long, if required. Next, we will go with h6 next and take it from there. Black has a very healthy position without weaknesses and with some potential of outplaying the opponent (although it is debatable whether there is any 'objective' advantage).} 
