7. dxe5 {Recapturing on e5 with the pawn is the only sensible move, as7.Qxe5Nc6is not to be recommended.} 
7. a5 {As I mentioned in my notes to the 6.Qxd1 and 6.Qf3 variations, with the bishop on b3 and the knight on b3, I really like this thematic advance of the a-pawn, trying to gain some space on the queenside while harassing the bishop on b3 at the same time. a4 is now a very serious threat and White has to react to it.} 
8. a4 {The most common reaction in this position. White stops the a-pawn in its tracks and refuses to give Black more ground on the queenside. This is very sensible, but the problem is that now the pawn on a4 is a potential target. Black can start exploiting this immediately with the following knight move.} 
8. Na6 {Slightly more flexible than going via the d7 route as it doesn't lock the bishop on c8 in, although both moves are more than fine. The knight is immediately heading toward the c5 square to put pressure on White's vulnerable queenside.} 
9. Nf3 {The most natural and arguably the best move in the position. White ignores the 'threat' of Nc5 and just continues the development, intending to give up the bishop on b3 and castle on the next move.} 
9. Nc5 {Executing the desired idea and jumping to c5.} 
10. O-O {Continuing the development and ignoring Black's demonstration on the queenside.} 
10. Nxb3 {Getting rid of the bishop pair and worsening White's pawn structure on the queenside.} 
11. cxb3
11. Qd3 {Another very thematic idea in these position we have already seen. The queen plants itself to the d3 square, hits the b3 pawn and also intends to go to g6 to reduce the queenside pressure, if required. Note that Black refrains from moving the g-pawn in all these variations as we don't really want to create some dark-square weaknesses for no reason. Let's follow the variation for a bit more just to see how play could typically continue from here.} 
12. Nc3 {A logical move, dealing with the threat to the b3 pawn and developing a piece.} 
12. Bd7 {Also a very useful move, covering the b5 square just in case White gets some ideas of jumping there with the knight.} 
13. Rd1 {Hitting the queen while placing a rook on the open file can hardly be too bad.} 
13. Qg6 {The desired maneuver I have mentioned above, challenging the queen and reducing the pressure on the kingside.} 
14. Qxg6 {Kinda forced, since14.Qh4Be7would simply provide Black with more tempi for development, and15.Qd4O-O-Odoesn't lead anywhere.} 
14. hxg6 {Black has a very healthy position with the bishop pair and slightly better structure. White does have some ideas such as Nb5 or Bg5-Rac1 with some pressure on the queenside, so the position is objectively balanced, but long-term I feel Black has a bit more potential, at least in a practical game. At the very least, we are not worse and can be reasonably satisfied with the outcome of the opening.Conclusion: Even though White has multiple options on move 4 after 1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6, none of them are particularly good and Black can obtain an easy game by simply capturing on e5 and taking it from there. The only exception is the variation with 4.Bc4 which is a bit more complicated and tricky to handle, but even there after the capture on e5 Black should be fine - especially if we remember the typical idea of a5. All in all, I don't think the variations presented in this chapter can be regarded as a critical test of the Alekhine defence by any means - especially when compared to variations presented in some other chapters.} 
