7. exd6 {White can also try taking on d6 at this exact moment, transposing to some sort of exchange variation where the bishop has been developed to b3 via c4. Even though the bishop is relatively active on this square, I am not sure if this is a major improvement for White as now going for the standard c4 plan makes less sense as it would block the bishop. Furthermore, the bishop can potentially be vulnerable to some Na5 attacks.} 
7. cxd6 {Naturally, we recapture with the c-pawn in order to keep the position asymmetrical - just like we did in the case of the 'pure' Exchange variation.} 
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. h3 {This natural move, covering the g4 square, is the one which White players make almost automatically in these positions and will therefore constitute our mainline. However, without the pawn on c4, it is not entirely clear whether White needs to worry about any Bg4 pins as it is easier to deal with the pressure on the d4 pawn with the help of the move c3.Say, if9.Re1Bg4there is10.c3and it is not 100% clear how effective the pin with the bishop is.Instead, after9.Re1Nc6should be the move, intending to go for either Na5 or the e5 pawn push. Say if10.c3,making room for the bishop on b3, then already10...e5is very thematic and okay for Black. This idea was also thematic in the exchange variation. Next, Black plays Qc7 and then probably tries to go Na5-Nxb3 or Na5-Nc4, trying to exercise control on the light squares on the queenside. The position is close to being equal, but is also very imbalanced, which provides us with a reasonable chance of playing for the win.} 
9. Nc6 {Black continues developing normally and intends to play either Na5 or e5 next.} 
10. Re1 {I think this natural rook move is a little bit trickier to handle because it directly fights against our idea of playing e5 by not yet moving the c-pawn forward. The immediate10.c3is met with the thematic pawn push10...e5We will see very shortly why keeping the c3 square open can be very relevant.} 
10. Na5 {After some analysis, I have concluded that this knight move is very logical in the situation where White refrained from making some room for the bishop on b3 with c3. We are not only pressuring the bishop, but we are also eyeing the c4 square and potentially intending to plant a knight there, depending on how White reacts. Black also keeps the option of playing more naturally with Bd7/Bf5, Re8, simply bringing more pieces into the action and awaiting further events.Now, you might be wondering - but what is wrong with the immediate10...e5,which was so thematic in other variations? Well, it appears that without c3 played, this advance is not as good due to11.dxe5dxe512.Nc3!when White exploits the fact that c3 hasn't been played in order to develop the knight on a very active square from where it can jump to d5. It might not be the end of the world, but computer really dislikes this position for Black and I think it is better to avoid it.On the other hand, the semi-waiting10...Bf5was played in an old game between Grischuk and Bortnyk back in 2016. The idea is to develop the bishop and wait for White to play11.c3in order to strike with11...e5and it is also very sensible. The text move seems a little bit more creative, unexplored and combative, which is why I decided to prefer it over Bortnyk's choice.} 
11. Bg5 {This very logical move, attacking the e7 pawn and developing with tempo, is arguably the main move played in this position.11.Nc3is an alternative, but here there aren't any direct threats, so Black can continue with natural play, say with11...Bd712.Qe2Re8when we want to play Rc8, Bc6, Qc7, etc. and then either take on b3, jump to c4 or play e5 at the opportune moment, depending on what White does.} 
11. Re8 {Naturally, we defend the e7 pawn and place the rook on an ideal square, where it helps with the subsequent pawn push. I do think Black is perfectly fine in a position like this since we have no weaknesses, reasonable development and good piece play to compensate for our lack of space.Since we have entered a typical Alekhine middlegame, this seems like a good spot to end the trainable variation as the play will be non-forcing from this point onward and since it is more important to be aware of some typical ideas and simply play well, rather than to memorize moves. Black has ideas of capturing the bishop on b3, jumping with the knight to c4, simply developing with Bd7, Rc8 and Bc6, kicking the bishop away with h6 and eventually playing e5.In order to help you with that task, let's take a look at some potential continuations and how the play might typically proceed.  A) First of all, the natural12.c3is probably best met with taking the bishop with12...Nxb313.axb3and then kicking the other bishop away with13...h614.Bf4Nd5!?15.Bg3and then playing the extravagant-looking15...b5!?,trying to restrict the pawn mass on the queenside, develop the bishop to b7 and secure the knight on d5.B) If White develops the knight with12.Nc3,we can perhaps keep some flexibility and not hurry with the capture on b3 as we don't have the same Nd5 jump available later in the line. Instead, we can play something like12...h613.Bf4Bf5with the idea of playing g5, Rc8, Qd7 and just playing very naturally next and emphasizing that the knight is not really that good on c3.C)12.Qe2trying to increase the pressure on e7, is another logical move, but it doesn't really threaten to capture the pawn on e7 as the bishop would end up in a deadly pin, so Black has great freedom of choice. I think the most reasonable is to kick the bishop again with12...h613.Bh4Bf5,when we still retain all the possibilities of g5, Qd7, Nxb3 and so on.D) Last but not least, apparently the best move in the position is12.Qd2,preventing Black from playing h6. Against this, the best is probably to change plans and jump to c4 with12...Nac4and then after13.Qc1to play13...Bd7,continuing the natural development and intending Rc8 next. At some point, we might want to reinforce our knight on c4 with d5 and so on. The engine does give a slight preference to White, but given that it is just a small edge and that the whole idea Qd2-Qc1 looks very strange, I wouldn't be too concerned with this particular variation, as I believe even in the worst-case scenario we get a very playable and imbalanced position.} 
