[White "9) Modern Line: Alburt Variation with 4...g6"]
[Black "4...g6 5. Bc4 with 7.a4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3 {Finally, after examining all the other possibilities available to White up to this point, in this, final, chapter, we will examine this natural developing move of the knight, leading to the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. White's idea is simple - they are trying to keep the tension while developing a piece, intending to recapture on e5 with the knight, if allowed. They are also refraining from moving the c-pawn too early in order to prevent the overextension that can be so typical of the Alekhine Defence.For a long time, this was considered to be the best and most reliable way of meeting the Alekhine Defence. For example, if you enter these moves into lichess, you get an entry from Batsford Chess Openings/Wikipedia which states that 'While 4. c4 is tempting, the modern variation 4. Nf3 gets better results, making it harder for Black to equalize.'.There is no denying that 4.Nf3 is a variation that provides White with objective chances of seizing the advantage and that needs to be taken very seriously. However, in contrast, to, say, Four Pawns Attack, where the path is very narrow, the Modern Variation does offer Black a lot of flexibility in terms of possible setups. As we will soon see, there are many different possibilities available to Black starting from the very next move. In order for White to get an advantage against all these setups, they do need to be well-prepared and know a lot of details - which is not always the case, especially at lower levels.Therefore, even though the Modern variation is very solid, objectively very good and still very popular, I am personally a little bit less concerned about it compared to the Four Pawns Attack examined in the previous chapter (a variation I do consider as the critical test of the Alekhine, as I mentioned there already).} 
4. g6 {As mentioned in my comment to White's previous move, there are many possibilities available to Black against the Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. After some consideration, I have decided to recommend the text move, leading to the so-called Alburt variation, named after the famous Ukrainian chess player and a great Alekhine specialist, Lev Alburt (who immigrated to the United States in 1979). The idea of this move is simple - Black decides to keep the tension, develop the bishop to g7, castle quickly and then play against White's center.I decided to go for this line because it is the most combative variation available to Black against the Modern variation, simply because it keeps the pawn structure asymmetrical. It is true that it involves some risk and that it might be less solid than some of the other options, but I do think it requires a bit more precision, concreteness, and knowledge from White. Besides, given that I have previously written a course on the Modern defence, it was only natural to try and develop the bishop to g7 at the first opportunity.With that being said, let's take a look at some of the other options available to Black on move 4.A) First of all, the old mainline is4...Bg4,pinning the knight on f3 and intending to play e6 next, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain. I have played this in some classical games in the past and recently in some high-rated rapid online games, but I am never too thrilled with the positions I get. Not only do I consider the mainline after5.Be2problematic for Black irrespective if we try5...e6or even5...c6,but I also feel that4...Bg45.c4Nb66.exd6cxd67.h3leads to a version of the exchange variation which is very reasonable for White, where I feel our development of the bishop to g4 was premature (as explained in the chapter dedicated to the Exchange variation).B) The other big variation that actually constitutes the mainline involves releasing the tension in the center with the move4...dxe5Then after the typical5.Nxe5, keeping the center fluid and activating the knight, Black again has quite a few options at the disposal.  B1) First of all, the move5...Nd7,immediately challenging the knight on e5, is played by some brave and bold Alekhine warriors. However, the problem is that it more or less loses by force to6.Nxf7It is true that this refutation is not at all that simple and that many White players don't actually go for it, after which Black's knight move is fully justified, but recommending a line that is objectively losing would be a little bit too hardcore even for an author of my standards who loves to go against the evaluation of the engine.B2) Secondly, after4...dxe55.Nxe5there is also the move5...g6,leading to the so-called Kengis variation, named after another great Alekhine expert Edvins Kengis, was recommended by Roland Pruijssers in the course Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. It is a very solid line, as exchanging on e5 removes the annoying pawn on e5 which often provides White with some nasty attacking opportunities, as we will see in our lines. However, the exchange on e5 also invites the knight on e5 - and also leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure. I am not even sure whether Black has full equality after, say,6.Bc4c67.O-OBg78.Re1,but more importantly - I feel it is very difficult to play for a win in a position like that one.B3) Last but not least, after4....dxe55.Nxe5the solid move5...c6,opening the potential c7 square for the knight on d5, overprotecting it, and also preparing to play with Bf5 and e6 next, is arguably the most reliable variation available to Black. It was recommended as the main option in the course The Dark Knight Rises by NM Bryan Tillis here on Chessable (with the move 4... g6 being recommended as the alternative). It is also the variation that is the choice of the strongest Alekhine practitioner, GM Oleksandr Bortnyk when he faces the Modern variation. I was considering recommending it, as well, but here again, I thought that Black has very little chance to play for a win in the main tabiya of the variation that arises after6.Be2Bf57.O-ONd78.Nf3e69.c4N5f610.Nh4Bg611.g3Still, this is a very solid setup, so if you want to keep things flexible and mix it up every now and then - I can only recommend you to check this variation in greater detail.} 
5. Bc4 {This is by far the main - and arguably the most dangerous move in the position. White develops the bishop to a very active diagonal, attacks our knight on d5 and also potentially eyes the pawn on f7. We will see that this early attack against the weakest point in the Black's pawn structure is actually quite relevant and venomous.} 
5. Nb6 {The most common and also natural move, retreating the knight and gaining a tempo for an attack on the bishop. Trying to preserve the knight on d5 doesn't work that well, say after5...dxe56.dxe5c6asnow the bishop is very active on c4 and some nasty ideas appear in the position, such as7.Nc3when7...Nxc3is not possible due to8.Bxf7winning on the spotOn the other hand, reinforcing the knight immediately with5...c6is sometimes played, but I really don't like the fact that this allows White to take on d6 with6.exd6at the moment when we are unable to recapture with the c-pawn, so we basically have to accept the transposition to some sort of symmetrical/Kengis variation where White has placed the bishop quite actively on c4.} 
6. Bb3 {Of course, White didn't bring the bishop all the way to c4 in order to retreat it to e2, and therefore retreats it to the active square b3, from where the bishop eyes the f7 square and exerts some pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.6.Be2would be very similar to the line with 5.Be2 after6...dxe57.Nxe5Bg7when the idea of c5 is already looming in the position.Also, note that6.Bxf7Kxf77.Ng5Kg8does lead to an extra piece for Black. There are minor inconveniences with the king, but objectively such a sacrifice shouldn't work and we are objectively winning.} 
6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. a4 {Before I started working on this particular chapter, I wasn't fully aware that the advance of the a-pawn is particularly dangerous. However, it is not only very logical to try to exploit the position of the knight on b6 by advancing the flank pawn - it is also objectively quite tricky to handle AND it is the 6th most popular move lichess database. Thus, even though I have encountered it very rarely, if ever, in my own games, I still think some idea of how to handle it is required.} 
7. dxe5 {I think capturing on e5 and exploiting the fact White's last move didn't develop a piece is the way to go. I also investigated the more natural move7...a5,preventing the further advance of the a-pawn, but it transpired that there are some variations where White can benefit greatly from the fact that the a-pawn has been advanced. Most concretely, in the variation after8.Qe2O-O9.e6d510.exf7Rxf711.Be3c512.dxc5Bxb2if the pawn wasn't moved, White would lose the rook on a1, but here they have13.Ra2and are completely winning.Of course, it is very debatable whether your opponents who play 7.a4 will actually know this detail, but even if they don't it is not yet 100% clear whether the mutual advance of the a-pawns has been in Black's favour (since here we were unable to remove the d-pawn and gain access to the c5 square for the potential Na6-Nc5). Thus, I have ultimately decided to recommend the text move even though it does allow our opponent to go for a forced draw if they want to.} 
8. a5 {Of course, this is the whole point of White's previous play, as both8.Nxe5Bxe59.dxe5Qxd1and8.dxe5Qxd1guarantee Black at least an equal endgame. Now we have to move the knight and there is seemingly only one good square for it.} 
8. N6d7 {This is the best place for the knight as it defends the e5 pawn.8...Nd59.dxe5leads to a very cheerless position after9...c610.O-Oas White has gained some space on the queenside with the gain of time, the knight is not ideal on d5 and it is hard for us to generate pressure against e5. But after the text move, you might be wondering - what on Earth is White doing? Haven't they just lost a pawn for nothing, since we are protecting e5 twice?} 
9. Bxf7+ {Well, first of all, White is not even forced to lose a pawn.9.dxe5has been played in some games, when after9...Nxe510.Qxd8Kxd811.Nxe5Bxe512.Bxf7White regains the pawn, even though the position after any sensible move for Black, say12...Nc6,is just dead equal. However, this bishop pseudo-sacrifice is the true point behind White's previous play as they are trying to exploit the fact that the knight on d7 is blocking the bishop on c8, which makes our e6 square quite exposed.} 
9. Kxf7
10. Ng5+ {A very annoying check.} 
10. Kg8 {The only move, given that10...Ke811.Ne6loses the queen and10...Kf611.Qf3the king.} 
11. Ne6 {Attacking our queen and exploiting the weakness of the e6 square.} 
11. Qe8 {Our majesty has only one square to go to.} 
12. Nxc7 {Forking the rook and the queen. Now the critical position of this entire line has been reached.} 
12. Qd8 {It appears that this move is a must in this position. It is important for the queen to keep the c7 square under control and also to eye the a8 corner, in order to be able to capture the knight on a8 faster in the future. The drawback of this move is that it allows White to repeat the moves and force a draw.I did take a look at12...Qf713.Nxa8exd4At first glance it looks as if now the knight can escape with14.Nc7, but it transpires that the line after14...Be515.Nb5Qd5!16.Nxa7Qxg217.Rf1Kg7is not at all so clear as Black has quite some compensation for the exchange in the form of activity and strong central pawns.However, what worries me after12...Qf713.Nxa8exd4is the simple14.O-Owhen we are suffering from the fact that our queen is not on d8, say after14...Nc615.c3Nc516.cxd4Nxd417.Be3With the queen on d8, our knight on d4 would not be threatened, but here we need to lose more time to deal with this threat and we are also still very far away from capturing the knight on a8, which means our position is just dead lost. Of course, if you are desperate to avoid a draw, you might still risk this idea as it is far more likely that a human opponent will play 14.Nc7, but if you suspect your opponent might go for this drawing line and you are desperate to win, it is probably better to play a different line of Alekhine - or another opening altogether.} 
13. Nxa8 {Taking the rook is quite natural and more ambitious than13.Ne6which leads to the aforementioned draw by repetition.} 
13. exd4
14. O-O
14. Nc6 {This position is highly unclear, although Black has a nice center and lead in development in compensation for the exchange and the loss of castling rights. The knight on a8 is also trapped for the moment and it is not so easy to see how it will extricate itself. Surprisingly, the engine already gives zeroes here, which is a good sign for us given that we are down in material.A sample line might continue15.c3Nc516.cxd4Nxd417.Be3but here we have the queen on d8 so we can continue developing with17...Bf5,when we have some Bc2 and Kf7 ideas and the position, is completely unclear.} 
