7. Qe2 {This queen move, stepping away from the d-file and reinforcing the e-pawn is also quite common and sensible. White fights against Black's idea of capturing on e5 and also introduces the potential idea of playing e6.} 
7. O-O {Alas, we have to castle before undergoing anything else, given that7...dxe58.dxe5is bad for Black now that we can't exchange the queens ond1,while7...Bg4would be desirable were it not for the simple tactic8.Bxf7Kxf79.Ng5when we lose the unfortunate bishop - and with it the game.} 
8. e6 {This advance of the e-pawn is actually quite logical with the queen on e2 and the bishop on b3. Yet even though it is the 3rd most common move in the lichess database, it is still played comparatively rarely compared to the mainlines with8.h3or8.O-O(which each have 2000+ games in the lichess database, compared to ~200 featuring 8.e6) Still, it is a very serious - maybe even a critical option of the7.Qe2complex, so we should definitely take a look and analyze it to some extent.} 
8. d5 {This move, simply restricting the bishop on b3, seems to be the best in the position. It looks a bit strange to weaken the e5 square and to allow White to capture on f7 and ruin our structure, but it transpires that Black can afford this weakening due to the lead in development.} 
9. exf7+
9. Rxf7 {A critical position for the evaluation of this line - and one that is a bit tricky to analyze for a course, given that only a handful of games have reached it and that the majority of the games saw White players not continuing in the best possible manner. Thus, I have decided to focus on the main move seen in actual practical games and provide the other, better possibilities mentioned by the computer as clickables.} 
10. Ne5 {The most common move, but the one that scores horribly for White. It looks logical to activate the knight, utilize the new weakness on e5, and gain a tempo on the rook, but this is met very forcefully with a counterintuitive bishop exchange.The other knight move,10.Ng5is not much better since Black has the active10...Rf5and everything is under control. Instead of these active ideas, the engine prefers to play in a somewhat more restricted manner, develop the pieces, fortify weak spots and fight against Black's active ideas of e5 and c5 in a different manner.Since this is a rare line, I felt it is sufficient to keep the number of trainables low - especially in a 100 Repertoire. Still, for full picture, allow me to list some other tries for White and potential sample continuations.  A) First of all, the quiet move10.h3preventing Ng4 is met very forcefully with10...Nc611.Be3e5!?when after12.dxe5Nxe513.Nxe5Bxe5Black manages to liberate the position since the tactic14.Bxb6axb615.Qxe5doesn't work due to15...Re7, winning the queen.B)10.c3makes a lot of sense, too, but here we can go for10...Bg411.Nbd2e5again, when after12.dxe5Nc613.h3Bxf314.Nxf3Nxe515.Nxe5Bxe5we manage to liberate our position somewhat, at the expense of giving up the bishop pair.C) Last but not least, the engine's top move here is10.Be3, when we can try to attack the center from the other side and play10...c5when after11.dxc5Bxb212.Bd4Bxd413.Nxd4Na414.Qb5Qc7we have a very crazy and complicated position.When you are analyzing this lines at home with the engine, it is easy to get scared and think Alekhine is not viable, but I genuinely think the lines presented here have very little to no significance for human play - there is a reason why this particular line scores very well for Black in practice.} 
10. Bxe5 {A surprising exchange, giving our proud bishop, but forcing another concession on White's behalf.} 
11. dxe5 {Taking with the queen with11.Qxe5is arguably better, but it is quite understandable that White doesn't want to give us more tempi for development after11...Nc6After12.Qe3Nc4is another annoying move and the situation is completely unclear.} 
11. c5 {This is the drawback of taking with the pawn on e5. Now Black obtains a nice and mobile pawn duo in the center and this position is objectively better for Black already.} 
12. c3
12. Nc6 {Continuing with the natural development.} 
13. O-O
13. Bf5
14. Re1
14. c4 {And Black had a very good position in the game Ganguly,S (2631) - Gerzhoy,L (2399) , Edmonton 2008. Next on the cards is e6, Nd7 and so on. Even though that game ended in a draw, the fact that a 2400 player was able to obtain a good position against a strong 2600 Grandmaster and one of Anand's seconds is a good testament to the practical viability of this entire line.} 
