6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. O-O {Before we get to7.Ng5,a move that I consider to be the mainline of the variation, let's first check out this natural and logical developing move. Castling on move 7 is actually the most common move in the lichess database - and it is also objectively not such a bad move.} 
7. O-O {For the moment, we also follow suit and castle our king. One might be tempted to play7...Bg4here, but first of all, as I explained earlier - with the pawn still on c2 and not on c4, it is debatable how effective our play against the center and the pawn on d4 is. Secondly and more importantly - without our king castled, this move simply blunders8.Bxf7tactic. Now White has two sensible options at their disposal.} 
8. Re1 {This rook move is equally sensible and common as the main move8.h3which will be examined slightly later. The rook is placed on the open file and the idea of e6 once again appears in the position - similarly as in the lines with 7.Qe2.Other 8th move possibilities don't have that much independent value.For example,8.exd6cxd6transposes to lines examined via 7. exd6 move order,while8.Bf4- a move that is seen quite often in the lichess database, is not particularly inspiring, and is met with the simple8...Nc6,developing a piece, increasing the pressure on the center, and threatening to simply take on e5.} 
8. Nc6 {I feel this developing move is the most logical and straightforward. We simply bring the knight into the game, increase the pressure on the center and threaten to take on e5, virtually forcing White to take a decision in regard to their e-pawn.I also analyzed8...Bg4, but here I am a bit worried about9.e6as after9...d510.exf7Rxf711.Nbd2the engine insists Black has to start finding some unconventional moves such as11...Bh6It is true that the text continuation also leads to some complications, but I felt that it at least forces White to play more energetically and give up some material.} 
9. e6 {The most logical follow-up to the previous move.9.exd6cxd6would once again transpose to lines analyzed via7.exd6while the timid9.c3allows Black to take on e5 with9...dxe5and obtain a dream scenario for an Alekhine player.} 
9. fxe6 {Of course, we capture the pawn first and think later.} 
10. c3 {This is already a necessary move. White reinforces the d4 pawn and prepares to jump Ng5 next. The dangers facing White are illustrated after the immediate recapture of the pawn on e6 with10.Bxe6Bxe611.Rxe6Here we have a thematic exchange sacrifice at our disposal with11...Rxf312.gxf3when after12...Nxd4we have a tremendous position and are already virtually winning.} 
10. Kh8 {Now, we take a moment to sidestep the bishop on b3 and are preparing the move e5 next.} 
11. Ng5 {A logical follow-up, attacking the e6 pawn and also eyeing the f7 square.11.Bxe6Bxe612.Rxe6Qd7leads to a fine position for Black, as we will get to move our other rook to the e-file and eventually play e5.} 
11. e5 {A surprise! Black removes the hanging pawn and achieves a desirable central advance. This move seemingly blunders an exchange - but it turns out White can't accept the gift.} 
12. dxe5 {The best move!12.Nf7Rxf713.Bxf7runs into13...e6when the bishop is trapped and Black is winning.} 
12. Nxe5 {The knight on e5 covers the f7 square.} 
13. f4 {Now seemingly Black is again in trouble as White wants to win an exchange with Nf7 next, but we have a solution here.} 
13. Bg4 {A very nasty intermediate move, forcing the queen to a suboptimal square. This is stronger than the immediate jump of the knight to c4 as the bishop is developed with a gain of tempo.} 
14. Qd2 {The only sensible square as14.Qc2Bf515.Qd1Nd3is horrible for White.} 
14. Nec4 {And now the knight jumps on c4 with a gain of tempo, deals with the Nf7 threat, and blocks the bishop on b3. The position is very sharp and complex. The engine insists it is close to dynamic equality, but I wouldn't have anything against playing this position with Black, given that we are currently up a pawn and that White is quite underdeveloped.It is also worth mentioning that the most obvious continuation15.Bxc4Nxc416.Qd5Nb617.Nf7Rxf718.Qxf7e6is actually perfectly fine for Black as we have a strong light-squared bishop and a very healthy pawn chain in return for the missing exchange.} 
