6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. Ng5 {Last but not least, this knight jump, attacking the f7 pawn and making the way for the queen to join the action. It is true that this move violates the basic principles of the opening play (Don't move the same piece twice), but White claims it is justified because it creates immediate threats.This is a very serious option and arguably the main move in this position. Even though it is 'only' the 2nd most popular move in the lichess database, it is the 1st most popular move according to the masters' database - and is also the move that is often recommended as the 'refutation' of the Alburt line. It was, for example, recommended by Chessable author chessforlife in his course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian here on Chessable.Now, even though this move is theoretically very challenging, the fact that it is one of the main options for White in this variation was one of the reasons why I decided to recommend the Alburt variation with 4...g6 to begin with. I do think this move leads to some very sharp and combative lines where the price of a move is quite high and where Black can definitely get their fair share of winning chances. I also think very energetic and concrete play is required from White which makes the position somewhat difficult to handle - especially at lower levels. And even though White has relatively favourable results according to the lichess database (52% wins, 41% losses, 7% draws), in the very specific line I am going to recommend with 7...e6 and 8...Qe7, the situation is less clear (with wins for White and Black being tied at 47%, with 6 % draws).} 
7. e6 {This move, blocking the bishop onb3and preventing any sort of e6 nonsense is almost a must here, given that7...O-Oruns into8.e6which is very bad for Black. Now again White is at a crossroads and has to choose between two big options.} 
8. f4 {This relatively logical push of the f-pawn, reinforcing the e5 pawn and trying to hold on to the strong center in the style of the Four Pawns Attack, is not at all so silly or harmless as it looks. Since the knight has moved away, White tries to utilize the fact that the f-pawn is free. I faced this move for the first time in a rapid game online just as I started working on this course and immediately realized this is a relatively sensible option that does require some coverage. So let's take a look at how we should react.} 
8. dxe5 {When White places the pawns on d4, e5 and f4, it is better not to capture the pawn on e5 with the d-pawn, as after White almost certainly recaptures with the f-pawn, the f-file will be opened and our f7 pawn might come under pressure after White castles and places the rook on f1. However, with the bishop on g7, sometimes it is also very desirable for White to capture with the d-pawn, in order to maintain a strong point on e5 that restricts the fianchettoed bishop severely.In the given position, my suggestion is to capture on e5 at this particular moment when the opponent's queen is on d1, in order to 'force' White to capture with the f-pawn. The reason we want to keep the pawn on d4 is counterplay - after we castle, we want to play c5 and start undermining White's center, while claiming that the opening of the f-file is not at all so fatal, provided we do know what we are doing.It is also possible to castle, but I dislike the fact that8...O-O9.Qf3gives White some additional options, e.g. after9...dxe5they can play10.dxe5when the queen exchange has been avoided. It may not be the end of the world, but I would like to narrow their choice a little bit.} 
9. fxe5 {The most obvious and logical recapture. As I mentioned above,9.dxe5is not particularly desirable as after9...Qxd1we manage to exchange a pair of pieces - and queens no less - which is very much in our favour, given that we have less space in the position.} 
9. O-O {Now we finally castle and intend to start playing against the center with the c5 strike. But also - somewhat surprisingly - with the f6 pawn push, which turns out to be quite viable in this position.} 
10. O-O
10. c5 {Now we finally start chipping away at White's center and try to distract our opponent from attacking us on the kingside.} 
11. c3 {The only sensible move, reinforcing the d4 pawn and trying to maintain the long pawn chain. Taking on c5 is not desirable for White as after11.dxc5Qxd112.Rxd1N6d7both c5 and e5 are hanging and Black will regain a pawn with at least an equal position - although one that is much more pleasant to play in practice.} 
11. cxd4 {I think taking on d4 immediately is the most precise. Many games in the Lichess database saw11...Nc6but after12.Ne4cxd413.Bg5White gets a very strong - probably already winning - attack, e.g.13...Qd7?already fails to14.Nf6Bxf615.Bxf6when the weaknesses of the dark-squared complex turn out to be fatal, with Qc1-Qh6 incoming.} 
12. cxd4
12. Nc6 {Now we see one of the points of Black's idea - pressure against the d4 pawn.} 
13. Nf3 {This retreat of the knight is arguably the best move. Instead of playing for some sort of attack, White switches to calmer, more positional, waters and tries to defend the center and develop behind it. I have to mention that this move is relatively rare in practice and that the inferior way of defending the d4 pawn with13.Be3is more common. However, getting the bishop on e3 allows us to play13...Nd5with a gain of tempo, forcing14.Bxd5exd5when we have gained a nice pawn in the center and eliminated White's bishop pair. It is true that their strong center and the open f-file give them a positional edge, but we will blasts things open with f6 next and obtain a clear equality - with the potential for playing for more due to the bishop pair.} 
13. f6 {Continuing in the spirit of the Alekhine defence and undermining the center further. It looks a little bit risky to do so due to the weakness of the e6 pawn, but since White moved the knight back and forth, we have some lead in development, so this opening of the position is fully justified.} 
14. exf6
14. Qxf6 {Even though we have a very ugly pawn structure, our lead in development, piece activity and pressure against d4 compensate for it.} 
15. Be3 {The only way to defend the d4 pawn, but it allows the knight to come to d5.} 
15. Nd5
16. Bf2
16. Nf4 {Now the knight is very active and Nh3 is a threat. At some later point, we can consider playing b6-Ba6 and White has to keep an eye on the d4 pawn. Even if we lose the pawn on e6, we are not necessarily worried. The position is very complex and dynamic and both sides have their chances - and a mess like this is one of the reasons why I have decided to give the Alburt variation with 4...g6 as my main recommendation.} 
