11. Nf6+ {The most obvious move, exploiting the weakness of the f6 square.} 
11. Kf8 {Of course, we don't really want to give up our important dark-squared bishop. Our idea here is that the e5 pawn is exposed and that White has made many moves with the knight to get it to f6 - so these lost tempi compensate for our loss of castling rights. When I first checked this position, I was a bit worried because I saw that the engine gives White some objective advantage, but when I started digging I realized White's play is not at all so simple - and even in the worst-case scenario is not so bad for Black.} 
12. Qc3 {This move is the first choice of the engine, the recommendation of GM Wesley So in his Lifetime 1.e4 Repertoire and also the most common move in the lichess database (although it only appeared in 12 games, which probably means these players who entered this line have analyzed it at home with the engine). White realizes that Black wants to play N6d7 next and challenge the knight on f6, so they eye the c7 pawn - and also the c5 square.} 
12. Nd5 {This move, which was played in a single correspondence game on lichess, was the move that convinced me that this entire line might be playable for Black. Since the queen is now on c3, Black decides to take the opportunity to jump with the knight to d5 with a gain of tempo, simultaneously challenging the knight on f6 and not minding the capture on d5 since it would expose the pawn on e5.Note that it is hard to find another satisfactory move, since12...Nc613.f4leaves Black somewhat without counterplay,12...N8d713.Be3is just bad for Black as the knight can never move due to Bc5 threats and the c7 pawn is also hanging, while12...N6d713.Qxc7Nc6is playable, but it leads by force to an inferior endgame after14.Nxd7Qxd715.Qxd7Bxd716.f4where Black can perhaps hope for a draw, but hardly more.White now has a choice - with which piece do they want to capture on d5.} 
13. Bxd5 {This is the strongest move that was, in fact, played in the afore-mentioned correspondence game, although it is by no means an obvious one for a human to make.} 
13. exd5
14. Be3 {White continues to develop normally and currently threatens Bc5, while the pawn on d5 is still exposed. This move also covers the e-file, so any potential capture of the pawn on e5 would not come with a check.Note that14.Nxd5is not a problem since after14...Qxe5we exchange queens and protect the e5 with a check.} 
14. Na6 {The best move, not only protecting the c5 square, but also the c7 pawn. This is relevant because after something like14...b615.Nxd5Qxe5thec7pawn would be hanging and after16.Nxc7White would be completely winning.} 
15. O-O {A natural developing move, getting the king out of the way and waiting to see what Black will do. Note that15.Nxd5Qxe5is again not a problem - the c7 pawn is now protected by the knight.} 
15. c5 {A nice move, gaining some space and threatening d4, virtually forcing White's reply.} 
16. Nxd5
16. Qxe5
17. Bxc5+ {White wins a pawn, but allows us to eliminate the strong dark-squared bishop.} 
17. Nxc5
18. Qxc5+
18. Kg8 {This whole variation was given by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire on 1.e4 here on Chessable. In return for the missing pawn, we have a strong bishop pair in an open position and a monster dark-squared bishop and we, therefore, have definite compensation. Wesley continued the line a bit further, but even after the best19.Nbc3Kh720.Rfe1Qf5,Black probably has a better chance of drawing this endgame than White winning it.I would much rather play this position than the endgame that arises in the line after 12... N6d7 because I do think Black has quite realistic drawing chances - and even some hopes of taking over if White is not careful. And remember that White had to know a lot to even get there.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Modern Line: Alburt Variation with 4...g6"]
[Black "4...g6 5. Bc4 with 7.Ng5 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3 {Finally, after examining all the other possibilities available to White up to this point, in this, final, chapter, we will examine this natural developing move of the knight, leading to the so-called Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. White's idea is simple - they are trying to keep the tension while developing a piece, intending to recapture on e5 with the knight, if allowed. They are also refraining from moving the c-pawn too early in order to prevent the overextension that can be so typical of the Alekhine Defence.For a long time, this was considered to be the best and most reliable way of meeting the Alekhine Defence. For example, if you enter these moves into lichess, you get an entry from Batsford Chess Openings/Wikipedia which states that 'While 4. c4 is tempting, the modern variation 4. Nf3 gets better results, making it harder for Black to equalize.'.There is no denying that 4.Nf3 is a variation that provides White with objective chances of seizing the advantage and that needs to be taken very seriously. However, in contrast, to, say, Four Pawns Attack, where the path is very narrow, the Modern Variation does offer Black a lot of flexibility in terms of possible setups. As we will soon see, there are many different possibilities available to Black starting from the very next move. In order for White to get an advantage against all these setups, they do need to be well-prepared and know a lot of details - which is not always the case, especially at lower levels.Therefore, even though the Modern variation is very solid, objectively very good and still very popular, I am personally a little bit less concerned about it compared to the Four Pawns Attack examined in the previous chapter (a variation I do consider as the critical test of the Alekhine, as I mentioned there already).} 
4. g6 {As mentioned in my comment to White's previous move, there are many possibilities available to Black against the Modern variation of the Alekhine Defence. After some consideration, I have decided to recommend the text move, leading to the so-called Alburt variation, named after the famous Ukrainian chess player and a great Alekhine specialist, Lev Alburt (who immigrated to the United States in 1979). The idea of this move is simple - Black decides to keep the tension, develop the bishop to g7, castle quickly and then play against White's center.I decided to go for this line because it is the most combative variation available to Black against the Modern variation, simply because it keeps the pawn structure asymmetrical. It is true that it involves some risk and that it might be less solid than some of the other options, but I do think it requires a bit more precision, concreteness, and knowledge from White. Besides, given that I have previously written a course on the Modern defence, it was only natural to try and develop the bishop to g7 at the first opportunity.With that being said, let's take a look at some of the other options available to Black on move 4.A) First of all, the old mainline is4...Bg4,pinning the knight on f3 and intending to play e6 next, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain. I have played this in some classical games in the past and recently in some high-rated rapid online games, but I am never too thrilled with the positions I get. Not only do I consider the mainline after5.Be2problematic for Black irrespective if we try5...e6or even5...c6,but I also feel that4...Bg45.c4Nb66.exd6cxd67.h3leads to a version of the exchange variation which is very reasonable for White, where I feel our development of the bishop to g4 was premature (as explained in the chapter dedicated to the Exchange variation).B) The other big variation that actually constitutes the mainline involves releasing the tension in the center with the move4...dxe5Then after the typical5.Nxe5, keeping the center fluid and activating the knight, Black again has quite a few options at the disposal.  B1) First of all, the move5...Nd7,immediately challenging the knight on e5, is played by some brave and bold Alekhine warriors. However, the problem is that it more or less loses by force to6.Nxf7It is true that this refutation is not at all that simple and that many White players don't actually go for it, after which Black's knight move is fully justified, but recommending a line that is objectively losing would be a little bit too hardcore even for an author of my standards who loves to go against the evaluation of the engine.B2) Secondly, after4...dxe55.Nxe5there is also the move5...g6,leading to the so-called Kengis variation, named after another great Alekhine expert Edvins Kengis, was recommended by Roland Pruijssers in the course Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. It is a very solid line, as exchanging on e5 removes the annoying pawn on e5 which often provides White with some nasty attacking opportunities, as we will see in our lines. However, the exchange on e5 also invites the knight on e5 - and also leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure. I am not even sure whether Black has full equality after, say,6.Bc4c67.O-OBg78.Re1,but more importantly - I feel it is very difficult to play for a win in a position like that one.B3) Last but not least, after4....dxe55.Nxe5the solid move5...c6,opening the potential c7 square for the knight on d5, overprotecting it, and also preparing to play with Bf5 and e6 next, is arguably the most reliable variation available to Black. It was recommended as the main option in the course The Dark Knight Rises by NM Bryan Tillis here on Chessable (with the move 4... g6 being recommended as the alternative). It is also the variation that is the choice of the strongest Alekhine practitioner, GM Oleksandr Bortnyk when he faces the Modern variation. I was considering recommending it, as well, but here again, I thought that Black has very little chance to play for a win in the main tabiya of the variation that arises after6.Be2Bf57.O-ONd78.Nf3e69.c4N5f610.Nh4Bg611.g3Still, this is a very solid setup, so if you want to keep things flexible and mix it up every now and then - I can only recommend you to check this variation in greater detail.} 
5. Bc4 {This is by far the main - and arguably the most dangerous move in the position. White develops the bishop to a very active diagonal, attacks our knight on d5 and also potentially eyes the pawn on f7. We will see that this early attack against the weakest point in the Black's pawn structure is actually quite relevant and venomous.} 
5. Nb6 {The most common and also natural move, retreating the knight and gaining a tempo for an attack on the bishop. Trying to preserve the knight on d5 doesn't work that well, say after5...dxe56.dxe5c6asnow the bishop is very active on c4 and some nasty ideas appear in the position, such as7.Nc3when7...Nxc3is not possible due to8.Bxf7winning on the spotOn the other hand, reinforcing the knight immediately with5...c6is sometimes played, but I really don't like the fact that this allows White to take on d6 with6.exd6at the moment when we are unable to recapture with the c-pawn, so we basically have to accept the transposition to some sort of symmetrical/Kengis variation where White has placed the bishop quite actively on c4.} 
6. Bb3 {Of course, White didn't bring the bishop all the way to c4 in order to retreat it to e2, and therefore retreats it to the active square b3, from where the bishop eyes the f7 square and exerts some pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.6.Be2would be very similar to the line with 5.Be2 after6...dxe57.Nxe5Bg7when the idea of c5 is already looming in the position.Also, note that6.Bxf7Kxf77.Ng5Kg8does lead to an extra piece for Black. There are minor inconveniences with the king, but objectively such a sacrifice shouldn't work and we are objectively winning.} 
6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. Ng5 {Last but not least, this knight jump, attacking the f7 pawn and making the way for the queen to join the action. It is true that this move violates the basic principles of the opening play (Don't move the same piece twice), but White claims it is justified because it creates immediate threats.This is a very serious option and arguably the main move in this position. Even though it is 'only' the 2nd most popular move in the lichess database, it is the 1st most popular move according to the masters' database - and is also the move that is often recommended as the 'refutation' of the Alburt line. It was, for example, recommended by Chessable author chessforlife in his course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian here on Chessable.Now, even though this move is theoretically very challenging, the fact that it is one of the main options for White in this variation was one of the reasons why I decided to recommend the Alburt variation with 4...g6 to begin with. I do think this move leads to some very sharp and combative lines where the price of a move is quite high and where Black can definitely get their fair share of winning chances. I also think very energetic and concrete play is required from White which makes the position somewhat difficult to handle - especially at lower levels. And even though White has relatively favourable results according to the lichess database (52% wins, 41% losses, 7% draws), in the very specific line I am going to recommend with 7...e6 and 8...Qe7, the situation is less clear (with wins for White and Black being tied at 47%, with 6 % draws).} 
7. e6 {This move, blocking the bishop onb3and preventing any sort of e6 nonsense is almost a must here, given that7...O-Oruns into8.e6which is very bad for Black. Now again White is at a crossroads and has to choose between two big options.} 
8. Qf3 {The most common and obvious move, utilizing the fact that the knight has created some space for the queen to join the action and currently threatening mate on f7.} 
8. Qe7 {This very provocative move is, in my opinion, the most combative and challenging option available at Black's disposal. Black defends the pawn on f7 and intends to play h6, kicking the knight from g5 away and also protecting the g5 square, which is important since White wants to play some sort of Ne4 and Bg5 combo next.In my distant youth, I once played8...O-O9.Qh3h6in a game against young and talented Croatian junior player and future IM Jadranko Plenča, but not only did I get absolutely crushed in that game - but this variation is also objectively very bad, irrespective if White decides to play the aggressive10.Ne4or more positional10.Nf3} 
9. Ne4 {This knight move, preparing Bg5 next and trying to utilize the dark squares on the kingside, is the only serious attempt for an advantage worth analyzing, as Black was threatening to take on e5, play h6, play Nc6 and castle. If Black obtains all that and gets a harmonious setup, then White's aggressive opening with Ng5 and Qf3 will make little sense - so the first player has to try and utilize their initiative while they still can. This is one of the critical positions of the entire Alburt variations and Black needs to be quite careful and knowledgable here in order not to lose at once.On a side note, maybe it is worth mentioning that9.exd6cxd610.Bf4,trying to invert the move order compared to the main line of the variation, doesn't quite work as after10...Nc6Black is ready to play e5 next and grab the initiative.} 
9. dxe5 {This is a very critical position for the entire variation with 4...g6 and I spent some time trying to decide which variation to recommend. Ultimately, I have decided to go for the most obvious move involving the capture on e5 as my main recommendation, mainly because it leads to sharp and irrational positions where both sides have to play accurately and have chances to win.However, since this continuation does force Black to play a non-standard and rugged position that can be tricky to navigate, and since White might objectively be better if they find all the best moves, this line might not be everybody's cup of tea. This is why I also decided to include the 'safer', but less exciting 9...h6 as the alternative in this course.} 
10. Bg5 {This developing move, temporarily sacrificing a pawn, is the most common move in this position. White attacks the queen on e7 and gets access to the f6 square. The downside is that Black now gets the opportunity to give a check on b4 and keep the e5 pawn protected, although Black shouldn't really aim to keep it and play this line too greedily, as we will soon see.} 
10. Qb4+ {This check is virtually the only move in this position, as the queen's best square is the one on a5.} 
11. Nbd2 {This surprising move was recommended by Indian Grandmaster S.P. Sethuraman in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. It is hard to explain this move in simple terms as it seemingly blunders a pawn on d4. But White develops another piece and claims that Black is significantly behind in development - especially if the second player spends another tempo to capture the pawn on d4.} 
11. exd4 {The most obvious move. Black simply grabs another pawn and asks White to show the compensation. I think this is a better choice than the alternative11...f5which leads to some crazy complications after12.Nf6Kf7- simply because after 11...exd4 the ball is in White's court and they have to find the right sequence - as otherwise they might end up being significantly worse.} 
12. a3 {An important move for White which is not super obvious or easy to find with all the cloud storms gathering on the kingside. The point is to kick the queen away from the d4 pawn in order to capture that pawn later in the variation.} 
12. Qa5
13. Bf6 {Once again the only move to try and fight for the advantage. After13.Nf6Kf8Black is already winning as we are simply too much material up and White doesn't really have a good follow-up to keep the flare of his initiative.} 
13. O-O {The best move! Black simply ignores the piece on f6 and castles the king to relative safety. It turns out that White doesn't have a mating attack going despite the dark-square weaknesses. Note that we really want to play the move Qf5 next which kinda forces White's hand.} 
14. Bxg7 {Again the only move to try and fight for the advantage, as otherwise we get in Qf5 and are already better.} 
14. Kxg7
15. Qf6+ {White kinda has to give up any hopes of mating Black. With the text move, White not only gives a check - but also attacks the pawn on d4, intending to capture it on the next move.} 
15. Kg8
16. Qxd4 {Not only capturing the pawn on d4 but also creating a deadly threat of Nf6 which looks quite devastating. Still, there is no need to panic.} 
16. N8d7 {A calm move, covering the f6 square and also preparing to play Qe5 next.16...Qf5is also worth investigating.} 
17. O-O-O
17. Qe5 {Challenging the queen ond4and also centralizing the Black queen. This seems like a good moment to stop this variation as we have reached a complicated middlegame where we are somewhat uncoordinated, but we are up a pawn. It is not 100% obvious how White should continue the initiative. I analyzed the best line18.Qd3f519.Ng5Nc520.Qh3Qg721.Qe3Nxb322.Qxb3Bd7where it turns out White retains the initiative with the best play, but objectively Black should be able to hold a draw.This is one of those positions where the computer will always give White some edge, but which is extremely difficult for a human to handle. Considering that the whole variation with 11.Nbd2 is extremely rare, I wouldn't be too worried about White actually knowing all the best moves and getting here. After all, when we play 4...g6 (or the Alekhine altogether) we are willing to take some risk to begin with.} 
