12. Bf6 {Planting the bishop to f6 is better than planting the knight, but it is also not objectively the most dangerous move at White's disposal in this position.} 
12. Bxf6 {Here, we are happy to give up our dark-squared bishop because we also exchange the opponent's dark-squared bishop, which makes it more difficult for our oppponent to exploit the weakness of our dark-squares.} 
13. Qxf6 {Apart from the recapture with the knight, it is also possible to capture with the queen. At first glance, it looks very scary for Black to allow the queen so close to the king, but it turns out it is not that dangerous.} 
13. O-O {The simplest reply. Now that White refrained from giving the disturbing check on f6, we are more than happy to castle, since White is not really in the position to attack. Not only do they not have enough pieces on the kingside - but their center is also on the verge of collapse.} 
14. Qxe5 {The best move, going by force into an equal endgame.14.dxe5is much worse since after14...N8d7Black wins the e5 pawn with a gain of tempo.} 
14. Qxe5
15. dxe5
15. a5 {In the endgame, the space advantage is less significant and Black has some ideas of gaining space on the queenside. If White prevents it with a4, then this pawn might become a target after Black plays Bd7, Na6 and Nc5. Otherwise, Black wants to play a4, Bd7-Bc6 and N8d7 and deploy the pieces in a very harmonious fashion. The position is objectively equal and we can be very happy with how the opening went.} 
