6. Bb3 {Of course, White didn't bring the bishop all the way to c4 in order to retreat it to e2, and therefore retreats it to the active square b3, from where the bishop eyes the f7 square and exerts some pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.6.Be2would be very similar to the line with 5.Be2 after6...dxe57.Nxe5Bg7when the idea of c5 is already looming in the position.Also, note that6.Bxf7Kxf77.Ng5Kg8does lead to an extra piece for Black. There are minor inconveniences with the king, but objectively such a sacrifice shouldn't work and we are objectively winning.} 
6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. Ng5 {Last but not least, this knight jump, attacking the f7 pawn and making the way for the queen to join the action. It is true that this move violates the basic principles of the opening play (Don't move the same piece twice), but White claims it is justified because it creates immediate threats.This is a very serious option and arguably the main move in this position. Even though it is 'only' the 2nd most popular move in the lichess database, it is the 1st most popular move according to the masters' database - and is also the move that is often recommended as the 'refutation' of the Alburt line. It was, for example, recommended by Chessable author chessforlife in his course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian here on Chessable.Now, even though this move is theoretically very challenging, the fact that it is one of the main options for White in this variation was one of the reasons why I decided to recommend the Alburt variation with 4...g6 to begin with. I do think this move leads to some very sharp and combative lines where the price of a move is quite high and where Black can definitely get their fair share of winning chances. I also think very energetic and concrete play is required from White which makes the position somewhat difficult to handle - especially at lower levels. And even though White has relatively favourable results according to the lichess database (52% wins, 41% losses, 7% draws), in the very specific line I am going to recommend with 7...e6 and 8...Qe7, the situation is less clear (with wins for White and Black being tied at 47%, with 6 % draws).} 
7. e6 {This move, blocking the bishop onb3and preventing any sort of e6 nonsense is almost a must here, given that7...O-Oruns into8.e6which is very bad for Black. Now again White is at a crossroads and has to choose between two big options.} 
8. Qf3 {The most common and obvious move, utilizing the fact that the knight has created some space for the queen to join the action and currently threatening mate on f7.} 
8. Qe7 {This very provocative move is, in my opinion, the most combative and challenging option available at Black's disposal. Black defends the pawn on f7 and intends to play h6, kicking the knight from g5 away and also protecting the g5 square, which is important since White wants to play some sort of Ne4 and Bg5 combo next.In my distant youth, I once played8...O-O9.Qh3h6in a game against young and talented Croatian junior player and future IM Jadranko Plenča, but not only did I get absolutely crushed in that game - but this variation is also objectively very bad, irrespective if White decides to play the aggressive10.Ne4or more positional10.Nf3} 
9. Ne4 {This knight move, preparing Bg5 next and trying to utilize the dark squares on the kingside, is the only serious attempt for an advantage worth analyzing, as Black was threatening to take on e5, play h6, play Nc6 and castle. If Black obtains all that and gets a harmonious setup, then White's aggressive opening with Ng5 and Qf3 will make little sense - so the first player has to try and utilize their initiative while they still can. This is one of the critical positions of the entire Alburt variations and Black needs to be quite careful and knowledgable here in order not to lose at once.On a side note, maybe it is worth mentioning that9.exd6cxd610.Bf4,trying to invert the move order compared to the main line of the variation, doesn't quite work as after10...Nc6Black is ready to play e5 next and grab the initiative.} 
9. dxe5 {This is a very critical position for the entire variation with 4...g6 and I spent some time trying to decide which variation to recommend. Ultimately, I have decided to go for the most obvious move involving the capture on e5 as my main recommendation, mainly because it leads to sharp and irrational positions where both sides have to play accurately and have chances to win.However, since this continuation does force Black to play a non-standard and rugged position that can be tricky to navigate, and since White might objectively be better if they find all the best moves, this line might not be everybody's cup of tea. This is why I also decided to include the 'safer', but less exciting 9...h6 as the alternative in this course.} 
10. Bg5 {This developing move, temporarily sacrificing a pawn, is the most common move in this position. White attacks the queen on e7 and gets access to the f6 square. The downside is that Black now gets the opportunity to give a check on b4 and keep the e5 pawn protected, although Black shouldn't really aim to keep it and play this line too greedily, as we will soon see.} 
10. Qb4+ {This check is virtually the only move in this position, as the queen's best square is the one on a5.} 
11. c3 {By far the most popular move in this position. It is very logical to prevent the check with the gain of tempo and defend the d4 pawn at the same time. But quite surprisingly, there is an alternative.} 
11. Qa5 {The key position of the entire 4...g6 variation. At first glance it looks crazy to allow a piece to jump to f6, but it turns out that this is not at all the end of the world for Black. And even though the computer claims some advantage for White, Black's practical results are actually quite good - Black scores 49% wins, 44% losses, with 7% of the games being drawn, according to the lichess database.White has some options here and we will examine them one by one.} 
12. Bf6 {Planting the bishop to f6 is better than planting the knight, but it is also not objectively the most dangerous move at White's disposal in this position.} 
12. Bxf6 {Here, we are happy to give up our dark-squared bishop because we also exchange the opponent's dark-squared bishop, which makes it more difficult for our oppponent to exploit the weakness of our dark-squares.} 
13. Nxf6+ {The more obvious recapture.} 
13. Kf8 {Just as in the variation with12.Nf6, we move the king to f8. Here it has even more point because the g7 square is available to the king. On the other hand, it does allow White to go for a semi-forced variation that virtually leads to a forced draw, so if you feel bold you can also consider going for13...Ke7here, as it doesn't have an immediate refutation.} 
14. d5 {Once again, we see this thematic advance of the d-pawn, trying to open up the position and include the bishop from b3 into the game. Since we have given up the bishop on g7, the knight on f6 is not under attack, so we don't have the same e4-h6-g5 idea we had in the variations where the bishops were on g5 and g7.} 
14. exd5 {As mentioned above, here there is no point in pushing the e-pawn because the knight on f6 is not under threat, so there is no reason for the queen to be defending it from f3.} 
15. Nxd5
15. Nxd5
16. Bxd5 {And this position looks dangerous for Black because both f7 and b7 are under the attack, but actually, there is an amazing variation here leading to a forced draw.} 
16. f5 {Dealing with the threat to the f7 pawn and intending to play Kg7 and e4 next.} 
17. Bxb7 {The critical attempt that leads to a forced draw. Something like17.Nd2Kg7leads to a complicated game with chances for both sides.} 
17. e4 {Now it seems as if White has simply blundered the bishop, but it is not really the case.} 
18. Qd1 {A saving move, threatening the check on d8. This is the line that one can prevent if they place the king on e7 instead of f8 back on move 13.} 
18. Bxb7
19. Qd8+
19. Kg7 {And the game ends up in a perpetual check after20.Qd4Kg821.Qd8It is very debatable whether a variation like this will appear in your games (White does need to be aware of the whole d5 idea), but if you are not really happy with allowing something like this, you can consider going for 13...Ke7 instead (Or playing a completely different Alekhine line whatsoever).} 
