after the typical5.Nxe5, keeping the center fluid and activating the knight, Black again has quite a few options at the disposal.  B1) First of all, the move5...Nd7,immediately challenging the knight on e5, is played by some brave and bold Alekhine warriors. However, the problem is that it more or less loses by force to6.Nxf7It is true that this refutation is not at all that simple and that many White players don't actually go for it, after which Black's knight move is fully justified, but recommending a line that is objectively losing would be a little bit too hardcore even for an author of my standards who loves to go against the evaluation of the engine.B2) Secondly, after4...dxe55.Nxe5there is also the move5...g6,leading to the so-called Kengis variation, named after another great Alekhine expert Edvins Kengis, was recommended by Roland Pruijssers in the course Lifetime Repertoires: Alekhine Defence here on Chessable. It is a very solid line, as exchanging on e5 removes the annoying pawn on e5 which often provides White with some nasty attacking opportunities, as we will see in our lines. However, the exchange on e5 also invites the knight on e5 - and also leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure. I am not even sure whether Black has full equality after, say,6.Bc4c67.O-OBg78.Re1,but more importantly - I feel it is very difficult to play for a win in a position like that one.B3) Last but not least, after4....dxe55.Nxe5the solid move5...c6,opening the potential c7 square for the knight on d5, overprotecting it, and also preparing to play with Bf5 and e6 next, is arguably the most reliable variation available to Black. It was recommended as the main option in the course The Dark Knight Rises by NM Bryan Tillis here on Chessable (with the move 4... g6 being recommended as the alternative). It is also the variation that is the choice of the strongest Alekhine practitioner, GM Oleksandr Bortnyk when he faces the Modern variation. I was considering recommending it, as well, but here again, I thought that Black has very little chance to play for a win in the main tabiya of the variation that arises after6.Be2Bf57.O-ONd78.Nf3e69.c4N5f610.Nh4Bg611.g3Still, this is a very solid setup, so if you want to keep things flexible and mix it up every now and then - I can only recommend you to check this variation in greater detail.} 
5. Bc4 {This is by far the main - and arguably the most dangerous move in the position. White develops the bishop to a very active diagonal, attacks our knight on d5 and also potentially eyes the pawn on f7. We will see that this early attack against the weakest point in the Black's pawn structure is actually quite relevant and venomous.} 
5. Nb6 {The most common and also natural move, retreating the knight and gaining a tempo for an attack on the bishop. Trying to preserve the knight on d5 doesn't work that well, say after5...dxe56.dxe5c6asnow the bishop is very active on c4 and some nasty ideas appear in the position, such as7.Nc3when7...Nxc3is not possible due to8.Bxf7winning on the spotOn the other hand, reinforcing the knight immediately with5...c6is sometimes played, but I really don't like the fact that this allows White to take on d6 with6.exd6at the moment when we are unable to recapture with the c-pawn, so we basically have to accept the transposition to some sort of symmetrical/Kengis variation where White has placed the bishop quite actively on c4.} 
6. Bb3 {Of course, White didn't bring the bishop all the way to c4 in order to retreat it to e2, and therefore retreats it to the active square b3, from where the bishop eyes the f7 square and exerts some pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.6.Be2would be very similar to the line with 5.Be2 after6...dxe57.Nxe5Bg7when the idea of c5 is already looming in the position.Also, note that6.Bxf7Kxf77.Ng5Kg8does lead to an extra piece for Black. There are minor inconveniences with the king, but objectively such a sacrifice shouldn't work and we are objectively winning.} 
6. Bg7 {Of course, here we continue with the development of the bishop, as with the bishop on b3 taking on e5 is no good as after6...dxe57.Nxe5the f7 pawn is hanging and we have to go for something ugly such as7...e6,severely weakening the dark-squares on the kingside and shutting our bishop on c8. Not to be recommended.Some Alekhine players like to go for6...d5here,but I personally have my doubts about playing d5 in the Alekhine defence in almost any kind of position - but especially here where we have already moved the d-pawn previously and where White has developed the bishop to b3 and forced our knight on b6. After the simple7.h3,preventing Bg4 ideas, Black will have a bad French defence where the fianchetto with g6-Bg7 usually doesn't fit the picture.After6...Bg7,we have reached a very important theoretical position of the entire Alburt variation where White has quite a few options at their disposal. And even though the variations with7.O-Oand7.Ng5are by far the most common and arguably the only variations you can reasonably expect to meet up to a certain level, I will be also devoting some coverage to7.Bf4,7.exd6,7.Qe2and7.a4} 
7. Ng5 {Last but not least, this knight jump, attacking the f7 pawn and making the way for the queen to join the action. It is true that this move violates the basic principles of the opening play (Don't move the same piece twice), but White claims it is justified because it creates immediate threats.This is a very serious option and arguably the main move in this position. Even though it is 'only' the 2nd most popular move in the lichess database, it is the 1st most popular move according to the masters' database - and is also the move that is often recommended as the 'refutation' of the Alburt line. It was, for example, recommended by Chessable author chessforlife in his course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian here on Chessable.Now, even though this move is theoretically very challenging, the fact that it is one of the main options for White in this variation was one of the reasons why I decided to recommend the Alburt variation with 4...g6 to begin with. I do think this move leads to some very sharp and combative lines where the price of a move is quite high and where Black can definitely get their fair share of winning chances. I also think very energetic and concrete play is required from White which makes the position somewhat difficult to handle - especially at lower levels. And even though White has relatively favourable results according to the lichess database (52% wins, 41% losses, 7% draws), in the very specific line I am going to recommend with 7...e6 and 8...Qe7, the situation is less clear (with wins for White and Black being tied at 47%, with 6 % draws).} 
7. e6 {This move, blocking the bishop onb3and preventing any sort of e6 nonsense is almost a must here, given that7...O-Oruns into8.e6which is very bad for Black. Now again White is at a crossroads and has to choose between two big options.} 
8. Qf3 {The most common and obvious move, utilizing the fact that the knight has created some space for the queen to join the action and currently threatening mate on f7.} 
8. Qe7 {This very provocative move is, in my opinion, the most combative and challenging option available at Black's disposal. Black defends the pawn on f7 and intends to play h6, kicking the knight from g5 away and also protecting the g5 square, which is important since White wants to play some sort of Ne4 and Bg5 combo next.In my distant youth, I once played8...O-O9.Qh3h6in a game against young and talented Croatian junior player and future IM Jadranko Plenča, but not only did I get absolutely crushed in that game - but this variation is also objectively very bad, irrespective if White decides to play the aggressive10.Ne4or more positional10.Nf3} 
9. Ne4 {This knight move, preparing Bg5 next and trying to utilize the dark squares on the kingside, is the only serious attempt for an advantage worth analyzing, as Black was threatening to take on e5, play h6, play Nc6 and castle. If Black obtains all that and gets a harmonious setup, then White's aggressive opening with Ng5 and Qf3 will make little sense - so the first player has to try and utilize their initiative while they still can. This is one of the critical positions of the entire Alburt variations and Black needs to be quite careful and knowledgable here in order not to lose at once.On a side note, maybe it is worth mentioning that9.exd6cxd610.Bf4,trying to invert the move order compared to the main line of the variation, doesn't quite work as after10...Nc6Black is ready to play e5 next and grab the initiative.} 
9. dxe5 {This is a very critical position for the entire variation with 4...g6 and I spent some time trying to decide which variation to recommend. Ultimately, I have decided to go for the most obvious move involving the capture on e5 as my main recommendation, mainly because it leads to sharp and irrational positions where both sides have to play accurately and have chances to win.However, since this continuation does force Black to play a non-standard and rugged position that can be tricky to navigate, and since White might objectively be better if they find all the best moves, this line might not be everybody's cup of tea. This is why I also decided to include the 'safer', but less exciting 9...h6 as the alternative in this course.} 
10. Bg5 {This developing move, temporarily sacrificing a pawn, is the most common move in this position. White attacks the queen on e7 and gets access to the f6 square. The downside is that Black now gets the opportunity to give a check on b4 and keep the e5 pawn protected, although Black shouldn't really aim to keep it and play this line too greedily, as we will soon see.} 
10. Qb4+ {This check is virtually the only move in this position, as the queen's best square is the one on a5.} 
11. c3 {By far the most popular move in this position. It is very logical to prevent the check with the gain of tempo and defend the d4 pawn at the same time. But quite surprisingly, there is an alternative.} 
11. Qa5 {The key position of the entire 4...g6 variation. At first glance it looks crazy to allow a piece to jump to f6, but it turns out that this is not at all the end of the world for Black. And even though the computer claims some advantage for White, Black's practical results are actually quite good - Black scores 49% wins, 44% losses, with 7% of the games being drawn, according to the lichess database.White has some options here and we will examine them one by one.} 
12. dxe5 {Last but not least, we need to check this rare and seemingly strange recapture on e5. Even though it is played extremely rarely and mostly in correspondence chess, it is mentioned by the engine and it was also given as the main recommendation in the course Crush the Scandinavian and Alekhine by the community author chessforlife here on Chessable.Even though White seemingly loses the pawn on e5 immediately, the situation is not so simple because it turns out Black can't comfortably recapture on e5 - at least for now. And even if Black does so later, White's argument is that this will provide them with enough time to develop the rest of the pieces and get a decisive initiative.} 
12. Nc6 {This is an important moment. Black shouldn't be tempted with the e5 pawn just yet, since both12...Bxe513.Nf6and12...Qxe513.Bf4are quite bad for the second player. By developing the knight first, we avoid any immediate tactical issues and intend to capture on e5 with this piece, gaining a tempo on the queen along the way.} 
13. Nbd2 {The best move in the position and the main line of chessforlife's analysis. White shouldn't get tempted by exploiting the f6 square again, since after either13.Nf6Kf8or13.Bf6Bxf614.Nxf6Kf8there is no real advantage, similarly as in the lines examined earlier.} 
13. Nxe5 {Black finally snatches a pawn and gains the tempo on the queen on f3.} 
14. Qg3 {The queen sidesteps the threat and creeps closer to the dark-square complex on the kingside. It also creates space for the march of the f-pawn. White's plan is to castle queenside next, kick the knight away from e5 with f4, play Nc4 with the gain of tempo and overrun Black with the pieces. This is actually a very dangerous position for Black and we do need to remember the following important move.} 
14. f5 {At first glance, seems as if White's previous move was a major blunder, because the knight on e4 is now short on squares. However, White has an amazing, very engine-like idea at their disposal.} 
15. O-O-O {This amazing move, simply leaving the knight on e4 hanging, is chessforlife's main recommendation in the aforementioned course. It is a legitimate attempt to refute this entire line and strive for a decisive advantage. But I am personally not too scared of it, mainly because I think it is impossible for a human to find unless they are specifically acquainted with chessforlife's analysis. There is a reason why this entire continuation with 12.dxe5 is extremely rare and utilized mainly on the correspondence level. Besides, even if White players do know this line, it is still not the end of the world for Black, as we will soon see.} 
15. O-O {Probably the safest move. Black shouldn't get tempted and capture the knight on e4, as after15...fxe416.Nc4!is a strong blow, since after16...Nexc417.Rd8Black is getting mated. Instead, Black gets the king into safety and begs White to demonstrate the compensation.} 
16. f4 {Again the only move and the main recommendation of chessforlife. Even though he is an excellent analyst and Chessable author, I often find his recommendations a bit too computerish to be practical - and this is a very clear example of one such line. Not only does White leave the knight on e4 hanging on the previous move, but now they do so again and counterattack the knight on e5 instead.} 
16. fxe4 {Not the only move, but I feel the most practical one, simplifying the position a bit and making it a bit easier to navigate. Although it is not immediately obvious why something like16...Nc6would be so bad, but probably after17.Nf2White has a long-lasting compensation due to Black's weakened structure and problems with the development.} 
17. fxe5
17. Qxe5
18. Qh4 {Of course, White doesn't want to exchange the queens in this position. Next, they want to capture on e4 and continue the initiative. But Black has a strong reply available in this position.} 
18. a5 {A very strong move, intending to play a4 and a3 and then weaken the White's king position.} 
19. a4 {This is probably the best move, since19.Nxe4a420.Bc2a3gives Black serious counterplay, while19.a3e320.Nf3Qb5is even worse and just winning for Black, as we suddenly get a decisive attack out of nowhere.} 
19. Bd7 {Now Black finally develops the bishop and targets the a4 pawn and should have sufficient counterplay to maintain the balance, despite being two pawns up. One correspondence game continued20.Rhe1h621.Bxh6Qh522.Qxh5gxh523.Bxg7Kxg724.Nxe4Bxa425.Bxa4Nxa4and Black had to fight a bit for the draw, but ultimately he got it in Roebuck D, Schmidt L, ICCF Email, 2019. I am highly skeptical about the probability of encountering this variation over the board, but it is good to know that Black objectively has chances to maintain the balance even against White's best play. Once again, if all these lines are too murky for you, I would definitely suggest checking the alternative variation back on move 9.Conclusion: The Modern variation of the Alekhine defence is, together with the Four Pawns Attack, arguably the most serious and critical variation available to White. My proposed solution - the Alburt variation with 4...g6 - seems to be the most combative and sharp variation Black can employ against the Modern variation. Even though it does involve some degree of risk and even though White should objectively be better provided they are super-well prepared, in practice it is reasonable to expect that our opponents will not be as acquainted with all the details - and that we will have good chances of punishing them in typical Alekhine style.Besides, even if they do know all the moves, in the worst-case scenario we will end up in a somewhat worse - but by no means lost - position, where we have considerable practical chances.} 
