8. Qe7 {This very provocative move is, in my opinion, the most combative and challenging option available at Black's disposal. Black defends the pawn on f7 and intends to play h6, kicking the knight from g5 away and also protecting the g5 square, which is important since White wants to play some sort of Ne4 and Bg5 combo next.In my distant youth, I once played8...O-O9.Qh3h6in a game against young and talented Croatian junior player and future IM Jadranko Plenča, but not only did I get absolutely crushed in that game - but this variation is also objectively very bad, irrespective if White decides to play the aggressive10.Ne4or more positional10.Nf3} 
9. Ne4 {This knight move, preparing Bg5 next and trying to utilize the dark squares on the kingside, is the only serious attempt for an advantage worth analyzing, as Black was threatening to take on e5, play h6, play Nc6 and castle. If Black obtains all that and gets a harmonious setup, then White's aggressive opening with Ng5 and Qf3 will make little sense - so the first player has to try and utilize their initiative while they still can. This is one of the critical positions of the entire Alburt variations and Black needs to be quite careful and knowledgable here in order not to lose at once.On a side note, maybe it is worth mentioning that9.exd6cxd610.Bf4,trying to invert the move order compared to the main line of the variation, doesn't quite work as after10...Nc6Black is ready to play e5 next and grab the initiative.} 
9. h6 {Aside from the very ambitious and combative move9...dxe5that constituted our mainline, I have also decided to mention this quieter move, simply covering the g5 square and preventing the annoying Bg5 move, as the alternative in this course. The downside of this move is that it gives White a tempo to resolve the pressure on the e5 and basically allows them to go for a position where they will be able to snatch our bishop pair and prevent our king from castling.Still, due to the nice  central structure and relatively closed nature of the position, I don't think  that this is the end of the world, although I do think White is objectively  somewhat better and that it has fewer chances to go wrong compared to the 9...  dxe5 line - which is why this line is given as the alternative.} 
10. exd6 {The only reasonable move. White can no longer ignore the attack on the e5 pawn as after10.O-Owe can now afford to grab it since the g5 square is covered:10...dxe511.dxe5Bxe5Also, note that trying to preserve the pawn on e5 is not as problematic, say after10.Bf4dxe511.dxe5White doesn't have a direct attack anymore and we can obtain a normal-looking position after either11...Nc6when we have some pressure against the e5 pawn and want to castle next.} 
10. cxd6
11. Bf4 {This move, attacking the d6 pawn, looks a little bit uncomfortable, as Nd6+ can't seemingly be prevented, but we are not too concerned about that check. Note that11.Qg3d5would be very similar.} 
11. d5 {Advancing the pawn is the only way to preserve it.} 
12. Nd6+ {This knight check might seem a little bit annoying, but remember that this knight made many moves, while our bishop on c8 is bad and hasn't moved yet, so we don't necessarily mind the exchange, which is more or less inevitable.} 
12. Kf8
13. Nxc8 {Capturing the bishop at once.13.c3as the move order recommended in chessforlife's aforementioned course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian, but sooner or later White will have to capture on c8 so it merely transposes to the text after13...Nc614.O-Og515.Nxc8} 
13. Nxc8
14. c3 {Defending the d4 pawn which was hanging.} 
14. Nc6 {And this seems like a good moment to stop the trainable variation as the forcing stage is over and we obtained a static position that needs to be evaluated! We have a relatively standard pawn structure - the popular Carlsbad structure (with reverse colours).White is definitely somewhat better due to the existence of the bishop pair and the fact our king can't castle. But since the pawn structure is relatively stable and it is hard to open it up without creating some weaknesses, these advantages shouldn't be overestimated.Knights are quite decent minor pieces in such positions, our king can easily walk to h7 or g7 and we even have the option of playing Bf6-Bg5 and exchanging one of our opponent's bishops.I felt going for a position like this one, while laying some mines along the way, is a good practical approach that creates some chances, but doesn't cross the risk threshold. If you are not 100% content with ending up in a position like this, I can definitely recommend you to investigate the line with 9...dxe5 a bit deeper - or to play a different variation of the Alekhine back on move 4 (to be honest, if you intend to be a lifelong Alekhine player, I would suggest you do it nevertheless, in order to be flexible and avoid the opponent's preparation, but that is a discussion for a different day).} 
