 {The first game we are going to examine will be a game by the man after whom the entire opening is named - the fourth World Champion Alexander Alekhine. According to stories, Alekhine saw the opening employed in some amateur tournament.The move intrigued him, so he spent some time analyzing at home and ultimately employing it in tournaments - starting with the Budapest tournament held in 1921. According to the quick research I did on the Internet, the following game was the first game in which Alekhine played his own opening.} 1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Bg5 {This move - which is a sign of times and the class of Alekhine's opponent - was not covered in the course. But not because the author of these words was superficial - the move is as bad as it is strange.} 
4. dxe5
5. dxe5
5. Nc6 {Continuing with the natural development.5...h6It was worth considering this move to force the bishop to an inferior square and potentially follow up with g5, but let's not scrutinize a game from 1921 too deeply.} 
6. Bb5 {This pin looks somewhat annoying, but White is violating some basic principles, which can't be too good.} 
6. Bf5 {Getting the bishop out of the pawn chain. The immediate6...Ndb4was worth considering, too.} 
7. Nf3 {7.Qf3Qd7Is not at all problematic for Black. Still, it does prevent this whole Ndb4 idea that happened in the game, so it is probably better for White than the game continuation.7.Bxc6+Is also better than the text move.} 
7. Ndb4 {A typical move for the Alekhine defence that now has a lot of merit. Black protects the knight on c6, attacks the pawn on c2 and doesn't mind the potential queen exchange at all.} 
8. Na3 {Very passive, but it is kind of hard to say what White should do instead.8.Bxc6+Nxc69.Qe2Is mentioned by the engine as comparatively the best, but White doesn't really want to give up the bishop pair without ruining the structure on the queenside.} 
8. Qxd1+ {This is a little bit imprecise.8...a6It was much better to attack the bishop on b5 at once and ask it to declare the intentions.9.Ba4b5This is the point. Black forces the bishop on a passive b3 square before exchanging queens.10.Bb3Qxd1+11.Rxd1e6And this is a much better version of this queenless middlegame/endgame compared to the variation analyzed in the notes to White's next move.Also note that after8...a69.c3Now doesn't work due to9...axb510.cxb4Nxb4When White can't really capture on b5 as the rook is not on d1 so Nc2 is a massive threat.} 
9. Rxd1
9. Nxc2+ {But this move is a little bit too materialistic. Black does win a pawn, but falls behind in development, providing White with more than sufficient compensation.9...a6Chasing the bishop away was much better, even though the lines are no longer that simple.10.c3axb511.cxb4e612.O-OBxb413.Nxb5Ba5And Black retains the advantage in the endgame due to the bishop pair, but White should probably be able to hold with the best play as the position is quite solid and quiet.} 
10. Nxc2
10. Bxc2
11. Rc1 {11.Rd4Was stronger, as it prevents Be4. White has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn here with Ke2-Rc1 coming.} 
11. Be4 {Defending the knight on c6.} 
12. Nd4 {Trying to get the pawn back, but losing the pawn on g2.} 
12. Bxg2
13. Rg1
13. O-O-O {A very strong intermediate move which was probably overlooked by Alekhine's opponent.13...Be4Retreating the bishop actually gives White some advantage, say after14.Nxc6bxc615.Rxc6} 
14. Nxc6 {14.Rxg2Nxd4Is of course, completely won for Black as there is no compensation for two missing pawns.} 
14. Bxc6 {Now Black can capture with the bishop since the rook is no longer on a8 so Rxc6 is not an option any more.} 
15. Bxc6
15. bxc6
16. Rxc6 {Now Black has an extra pawn, but some problems with development, so the game should be equal. Still, let's take a look at how Alekhine managed to outplay his opponent from this position.} 
16. Rd5 {Activating the rook and removing it from the pin of the bishop on g5.} 
17. Bf4 {17.e6Is maybe more resillient than the text move, although that is very modern defensive move.} 
17. e6 {Opening up the path for the bishop.} 
18. Ke2 {Threatening Rgc1.} 
18. Bc5 {Threatening to capture the rook on c6, but overlooking a brilliant reply.18...g619.Rgc1Is not good for Black, e.g.19...Rd720.Be3Bg721.R6c5And White is very active and has definite compensation for the pawn.18...Kb7Was objectively better, since after19.Rgc1Rd7Black hasn't committed the bishop to g7 and his king is defending the a7 pawn. Still, it is very hard to convert this position as White is extremely active.} 
19. b4 {A very nice tactical shot, diverting the bishop in order to gain time to capture on g7.19.Ra6Is insufficient, because after19...g6Black has managed to develop and is now a clean extra pawn. up.} 
19. Bxb4
20. Rxg7 {Now White should have more than enough activity to hold.} 
20. Rd7
21. Be3
21. a5
22. Rc4 {22.Ra6Would have led to an immediate draw since the threat of Ra8 can only be met with22...Kb723.Ra7+And now23...Kc6Is a bit risky as after23...Kb824.Ra6Leads to an immediate draw.24.Rg1Kb525.Rc1White is very active and Black should probably accept some repetition such as25...Rc826.Rb7+Ka627.Ra7+Kb528.Rb7+since28...Ka429.a3Kxa330.Ra1+Kb331.Rxa5Is very risky. It is not clear who is playing for a win here. Admittedly, not so easy to see all of it from afar.} 
22. h5
23. Rh4 {But this is an imprecision as it allows Black to attack the e5 pawn and activate some of the pieces.} 
23. Bc3
24. Rg5 {24.f4Would kinda cut the rook on h4 from the game.24...Kb725.Kf3Kc6And Black is actually quite better here. The a2 pawn is quite weak.} 
24. Rd5
25. f4
25. f6 {This is typical Alekhine, but this cute tactical shot is not really necessary.25...Rhd8Is much better. It transpires that after26.Rhxh5Bd2Is a very annoying move. Black has managed to activate and can hope to win the pawn on a2 and then promote, although with the passed h-pawn the game should still end in a draw.} 
26. Rgxh5 {This is a must, but it does lead to a holdable endgame for White.26.exf6Bxf627.Rxd5exd5And Black is winning because White didn't have time to capture the pawn on h5.} 
26. Rxh5
27. Rxh5
27. fxe5
28. fxe5
28. Bxe5 {It transpires that this endgame with a single rook is less favourable for Black than the double rook endgame mentioned in the earlier notes. With the passed h-pawn and limited material, White should be able to hold the balance with correct play.} 
29. Rh7 {The first imprecision.29.a4Depriving the rook of the b5 square and keeping the pin, was more accurate.29.h4Pushing the h-pawn and maintaining the pin along the 5th rank was also more accurate. if Black tries to go to the bishop endgame White will avoid it, e.g.29...Bf630.Rh6} 
29. Rb5 {Now the rook is being activated on b2.} 
30. Kf3 {The second imprecision.30.Rh5Admitting the mistake and activating the rook on the 5th rank again, was better.} 
30. Rb2 {Returning the favour. It looks logical to attack two pawns, but this allows the rook to go back to h5.30...Bd6Preventing Rh5 and only then going to b2, was a bit more accurate.} 
31. Rh5 {Of course!} 
31. Bxh2
32. Rxa5 {Now without the a-pawn, the win shouldn't be possible. Still, Black does have two passed pawns and is playing for two results. In a practical game, it is very much possible to win this position - and it is precisely what happens here.} 
32. Bd6
33. Ke4
33. Kd7
34. Bd4
34. Rd2
35. Be3 {35.a4White should probably start pushing the a-pawn in order to bring it closer to the promotion square.} 
35. Re2
36. Kd3
36. Re1
37. Bd4
37. Rc1
38. Be3
38. Rd1+
39. Ke4
39. Re1
40. Kd3
40. e5 {While White has been marking time, Black has improved the position significantly, and now it is no longer so easy.} 
41. Bf2 {This is probably a decisive mistake of the game. With this move, White misses the last opportunity to activate the forces and obtain a better defensive setup. Furthermore, this move ruins the coordination of White's pieces as it places the bishop on a silly square on f2.41.Ra8There were many good moves that still held, but trying to activate the rook and preparing for some checks from behind, while also making room for the a-pawn, was probably the best.41...Ke642.Bd2Rh143.Kc4Preventing Kd5. It seems White should be able to hold, e.g.43...Rh4+44.Kb3Kd545.a4The king is not in the way of the pawns and the a-pawn should provide sufficient counterplay. Once again, not very easy to figure it all out over the board - especially back in 1921.} 
41. Rf1
42. Be3
42. Ke6
43. Ke4 {43.Ra8Now comes too late as after43...Rh144.a4Kd545.Ra5+c5Black is completely winning.} 
43. Rh1
44. Bf2
44. Rh2
45. Be3
45. Rh4+
46. Kd3
46. Bb4 {A very powerful move, preparing to play c5 next.} 
47. Ra7
47. c5 {Now Black is completely winning as the pawns are too strong, the king is in the way and the counterplay with the a-pawn comes too late.} 
48. a3
48. c4+
49. Ke2
49. Bd6
50. Ra8
50. Rh2+
51. Kd1
51. Rh3
52. Kd2
52. Kd5
53. Rd8
53. c3+
54. Ke2
54. Ke4
55. Rxd6 {55.Bf2Rd3Is equally hopeless.} 
55. Rxe3+
56. Kf2
56. Rd3
57. Rc6
57. Rd2+
58. Ke1
58. Kd3
59. Rd6+
59. Kc2
60. Re6
60. Rd5
61. Ke2
61. Kb2
62. Rc6
62. c2 {Perhaps not the most remarkable and high-quality game, but one that is very important from the historical viewpoint. I also think this is a very interesting and instructive game featuring a very complex endgame where it is very hard to say where one side went wrong, so I don't feel any guilt for including this in the Model Games chapter!} 
