[Result "*"]

 {Let's fast forward 39 years in the future. In the following game, we are going to examine a heavyweight battle between two famous Soviet Grandmasters, Efim Geller and Viktor Korchnoi. I could spend ages talking about their respective careers, but it would go beyond the scope of this course. If you are not familiar with either of these names, I definitely urge you dive into their careers as they are an integral part of the rich chess history.} 1. e4
1. Nf6 {Korchnoi is known for his contributions to the field of the French Defence. But at a certain point in his career, he did adopt the Alekhine defence and played it on a semi-regular basis. Such provocative opening was very well suited for his defensive/counterattacking style.} 
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. c4
4. Nb6
5. f4 {Geller has been widely regarded as an opening theoretician and he was also a very principled player. Thus, the choice of the four pawns attack is not at all that surprising.} 
5. Bf5 {In the course, it was recommended to capture on e5 first, but we will end up transposing into the mainline anyway.} 
6. Nc3
6. dxe5
7. fxe5
7. e6
8. Nf3
8. Be7 {Alas, against this move order with knights on f3 and c3, Black is forced to go into the absolute mainline.8...Bb4As mentioned in the theoretical part, this pinning move is a bit too risky without the bishop on e3 and White has a big advantage in several lines. The most testing of which seems to be9.Bd3} 
9. Be2
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. f6
11. Bf4 {The opening has worked, even against someone as theoretically sound as Geller. This is a bit of a strange move. White does overprotect the e5 pawn, but the bishop simply doesn't belong to f4 in this position, as the d4 point is far more vulnerable.11.exf6Is by far the mainline - and it is analyzed very extensively in the theoretical chapter.} 
11. Nc6 {Now the center is under a lot of pressure and Black is intending to take on e5, so White is forced to capture on f6 nevertheless.} 
12. exf6
12. Bxf6 {Now the d4 pawn is under the attack and White is forced to do something about it.} 
13. d5 {Not a move made willingly.13.Be3Can also be considered, but then White is a full tempo down compared to the mainline, which is obviously significantly in Black's favour after13...Qe7} 
13. Na5 {Pressuring the c4 pawn and the queenside in a very typical Alekhine style. Black already has some initiative and White has to be very careful here. The opening was a very big success!} 
14. Ne5 {Defending the pawn on c4 for the moment and provoking Black into capturing it by giving up the bishop.} 
14. Bxe5 {This is not strictly necessary and possibly not even the best, but very typical of Korchnoi, who was known for his tendency to snatch material and for his defensive skills.} 
15. Bxe5
15. Naxc4
16. Bxc4
16. Nxc4
17. Bxg7 {This was the point of White's play. Now the game enters a wild tactical phase which is highly fascinating and interesting - and which was one of the main reasons why I decided to pick this particular game and include it in the Model Games chapter.} 
17. Ne3 {A nice intermediate and counterattacking move, typical of Korchnoi.17...Kxg718.Qd4+Was White's idea, winning back the material and leaving Black with a very weakened king.} 
18. Qe2
18. Nxf1
19. Bxf8
19. Nxh2 {The tactical melee continues. With this desperado, Black snatches a pawn before losing the knight.} 
20. Bc5 {The best move, keeping the strong dark-squared bishop and forcing Black to defend the knight.20.Kxh2Capturing the piece is bad because it allows Black to activate all the pieces after20...Qh4+21.Kg1Qd4+22.Kh1Rxf8Black is completely winning here, not only because of the extra pawn but because the weakness of White's king is now much more relevant than the weakness of the Black king.} 
20. Ng4
21. dxe6 {Now the material balance is restored and Black is on the verge of precipice.} 
21. Qh4 {Not only strong, but strictly necessary. Black has to create counterplay against the opponent's king before the e7 pawn decides the game.} 
22. e7
22. Qh2+
23. Kf1
23. Qf4+
24. Kg1 {Now the logical end of the game would be the repetition of moves - but the word 'repetition' was never within the vocabulary of Viktor The Terrible.} 
24. Re8
25. Qf3
25. Qh2+
26. Kf1
26. Qh5 {Threatening Nh2 and provoking White into trying to play for the win.} 
27. Qd5+ {A very attractive move, forcing the Black king up the board, although it does involve a certain risk for White.27.Kg1Qh2+Would indeed force the repetition.} 
27. Kg7
28. Qd4+ {But this is a mistake because the queen leaves the protection of the g2 pawn, turning Qh1 into a devastating threat. White probably thought the repetition of movs is forced, but now Black stumbles on an amazing concept.28.Re1Bringing the last piece into the game was necessary. Here the game would be roughly balanced. One attractive engine variation is28...Kg629.Qd8Kf730.Qd5+=Also note that after28.Re1Qh1+29.Ke2The queen is defending the g2 pawn!} 
28. Kg6 {An amazing concept and typical of Viktor Korchnoi. The king goes up the board and it transpires that there aren't any drawbacks to it - and that White king is the one who is actually less safe.} 
29. Ne2 {29.Re1Qh1+30.Ke2Qxg2+Is now completely winning.} 
29. Qh1+
30. Ng1 {The final mistake!30.Qg1Was the only way to stay in the game, when White would probably have to suffer in some endgame such as30...Qxg1+31.Kxg1b632.Ba3Ne3Opening up the bishop's control of h333.Rc1c5When Black will collect the e7 pawn and probably be objectively winning.} 
30. b6 {A very invonient move, forcing White to ruin the coordination of the pieces even further.} 
31. Qd8 {A last desperate attempt.31.Ba3Qh4And now the queen on d4 is unprotected, Nh2 and c5 are both coming and White is dead lost.} 
31. Nf6
32. Ba3
32. Be4
33. Qd2
33. c5
34. b4
34. c4
35. b5
35. Bd3+ {And here White finally resigned as heavy material losses are required in order to prevent mate. A beautiful, fascinating game very typical of Viktor Korchnoi's style, which demonstrates vividly the practical value of playing the Alekhine - even against the world's very best.} 
