 {While we are at heavyweight battles - next game we are going to analyze is game eight of the match between Mikhail Tal and Bent Larsen in the 1969 World Chess Championship cycle. It was a match for the third place in the Candidates cycle and the winner would advance directly into the Interzonal tournament of the next cycle. At this moment in match, Larsen did have a commanding 4.5-2.5 lead and here he decided to finish the match in style be employing our favourite Alekhine defence.} 1. e4
1. Nf6 {Larsen was known for his unconventional and creative approach to chess, so it is not such a big surprise to see him employ the Alekhine defence. It might seem as a risky opening choice against the attacking genius like Tal, but I do think it is actually quite smart to provoke such a player - especially since Tal was not in his peak form in this particular match.} 
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3
4. Nc6 {This is a very provocative - and objectively dubious variation - that allows White to obtain a big initiative with the help of a pawn sacrifice.4...g6You might recall this fianchetto move was what I recommended in the theoretical part.} 
5. c4
5. Nb6
6. e6 {This pawn sacrifice is sound and strong. Black is unable to recapture with the bishop so Larsen is forced to ruin his pawn structure.} 
6. fxe6 {Forced.6...Bxe67.d5Is of course, a big problem for Black.} 
7. h4 {A nice idea. White is anticipating that Black will have to play g6 to develop the dark-squared bishops, so he lunges the h-pawn forward immediately.} 
7. e5 {Trying to undouble the pawns immediately - even at the cost of a pawn.} 
8. d5 {Of course, keeping the position closed!8.dxe5Bf5Is not at all so bad for Black as now it is possible to develop fluently.} 
8. Nd4
9. Nxd4
9. exd4
10. Bd3 {Again very strong and patient play. White doesn't recapture the pawn at once, but simply continues developing and claiming that Black can't easily complete his own development.10.Qxd4e5Is also better for White, but here at least Black has some breathing room to develop.} 
10. Qd7 {A bit of an artificial move. The idea is to play e5 next and take on e6 with the queen. The added benefit is that the king can now go tod8, too.10...e5Is not good here due to11.Qh5+} 
11. Bg5 {But this is a mistake! The bishop doesn't belong here and this only runs into a tempo move.11.O-ONatural developing move like castling was much better. True, now the lunge of the h-pawn looks a bit strange but nevertheless after11...g612.Nd2Bg713.a4White retains a serious avantage on both sides of the board.} 
11. h6
12. Bd2 {12.Qh5+Kd8And suddenly Black has no problems and e5 or Qg4 come next, e.g.13.Bd2e5A typical way in which the provocative choice of opening can pay off.} 
12. Qg4 {Probably not the best, but still possible.12...e5Was arguably even better!} 
13. Be2
13. Qe4 {Of course, Black can't take the g2 pawn. But now once again e5 is on cards and White can't castle without losing the h4 pawn.13...Qxg214.Bf3Would lose the queen after14...Qg615.Bh5} 
14. O-O
14. Bf5 {Also probably not the best.14...Qxh4was possible at once.14...g5Opening lines on the kingside was also worth considering.} 
15. Na3
15. Qxh4 {This is a bit too brave, tho.15...a6Preventing the knight jump to b5, was probably safer. The game is complicated but probably balanced.16.g3O-O-OAnd it is not clear whose king is less safe.} 
16. Nb5 {A very nasty jump that tips the scales into White's favour.} 
16. d3 {Trying to enter some tactical complications - which actually works quite well.16...O-O-Ois met with the strong17.Be1Attacking the d4 pawn. Black doesn't have a good way to create some threats and White's pieces are soo much better that he is just completely winning, despite having two pawns less.} 
17. Nxc7+ {Probably not a necessary move.17.Bf3Stepping away from the threat, was arguably simpler. Now again after17...O-O-O18.Rc1White has a big initiative, with c5, Nxa7, a4-a5 all being on cards. Black is still struggling to finish the development and the attack on the kingside is long in the making.} 
17. Kd8
18. Nxa8
18. dxe2
19. Qxe2
19. Nxa8 {Now the situation is much more murky and unclear. Not only does Black have two pieces for the rook - but with the reduced material the danger to Black's king and lack of space are less pronounced.} 
20. c5 {Nevertheless, with this strong move White does keep the initiative going. The idea is obviously to get the queen to b5.} 
20. Qe4 {But this is objectively a losing move. Black should have attacked the c5 pawn instead.20...Qd4Was much more resistant defense, as now the bishop on d2 is also under the attack.} 
21. Qb5
21. Qxd5
22. Ba5+ {Clearing the d-file for the rook.} 
22. b6
23. Rfd1 {Amazingly, this is the wrong rook - although it is really hard to understand why at first glance.23.Rad1Was much better because after23...Qe524.Rfe1The other rook comes to e1 and Black is just being slaughtered with the king in the center.} 
23. Qe5 {Now the situation is much less clear and it is not easy to find the right continuation.} 
24. a4 {Defending the queen and trying to orchestrate some attack along the a-file and open up the rook later down the road, but this is actually too slow.24.Rac1Including the rook via the c-file was the best. Black is left without a good reply, e.g.A)24...Be425.Qb3And again Black is helpless against all the threats. The king is too weak on d8.B)24...bxa525.Qb8+Kd726.cxd6exd627.Re1And Black is getting mated.} 
24. Bd7 {Returning the favour, but it is hard to criticize the players in this mind-boggling encounter.24...Be4Was the right move. The idea is to meet25.cxb6Qxb526.b7+Qxa5And the bishop on e4 protects the knight on a8. Not an easy line to calculate.} 
25. cxb6 {A fantastic combination in typical Tal style.} 
25. axb6 {This is the only move, strictly!25...Qxb526.b7+Is also winning for White as now the knight on a8 is not protected by the bishop.25...Bxb526.b7+Kd727.bxa8=QIs completely won for White as now he has gained a full piece and the attack is still raging.} 
26. Bxb6+
26. Ke8 {Still, the game continues going and White's task is not at all so easy.} 
27. Qa6 {It looks logical to try and keep the attack going, but actually, it was time to transition into an endgame.27.Qxe5dxe528.Be3Is actually completely won for White as the two passed queenside pawns are too strong.} 
27. Nxb6
28. Qxb6
28. g5 {Now suddenly, Black is completely back in the game as with the queens on the board, some attacking chances against White's king can also appear.} 
29. Re1
29. Qf4
30. a5
30. Bg7 {Threatening the nasty Bd4 idea, as well as Be5.} 
31. Qb8+ {The moment when the game starts to shift into Black's favour.31.a6Bd4And here we see one such variation where White ends up in trouble32.Qb8+Kf733.Qb3+Kg634.Re2Rf831.Rad1Is not sufficient due to31...Be532.g3Qf3When White's king is very weak and White is in some trouble.31.g3Was the only move, with the point that now31...Qf3is met with32.Qxd6Therefore, after 31.g3 Qd4is, the only move. Now it is not good for White to go for an endgame as Black has managed to develop and coordinate but after32.Qb8+Kf733.Qb7The outcome of the game is still very unclear.} 
31. Kf7
32. Qb3+
32. e6
33. Qb7
33. Ke7 {The Black king is surprisingly safe in the center behind the pawns.} 
34. Re4 {The only move dealing with the Bd4 threat and trying to include the rook into the game.} 
34. Qd2
35. Rae1
35. Be5 {Black's minor pieces have some nice outposts and the queenside pawns are not that relevant.} 
36. a6
36. Qxb2 {Maybe a bit premature?36...Rf8Was arguably stronger, although after37.Rf1Qxb2It is still hard to say whether Black is winning or not. Probably in a practical game, he has very good chances.} 
37. Rb4 {Another mistake in this complex position.37.Rb1was better, in order not to allow the tempo-gaining move Qc3.} 
37. Qa2 {Returning the favour and missing a tactical trick.37...Qc3Attacking the e1 rook with a gain of tempo and keeping the e5 bishop protected, was important. Here Black is objectively winning, although there is still a long way forward.} 
38. a7 {Missing a nice opportunity to save the game.38.Rxe5Would have actually drawn the game on the spot since the a7 pawn provides sufficient counterplay, e.g.38...Qa1+39.Rb1Qxe540.a7Qa541.Qb2Rg842.Ra1Qd543.a8=QRxa844.Qg7+Kd845.Rxa8+Qxa846.Qf8+Be847.Qxd6+And White is probably able to save this position despite a significant material deficit. Amazing.} 
38. Bc3 {A deadly blow, winning the exchange under much better circumstances.} 
39. Rbb1 {39.Reb1runs into39...Bxb440.Rxb4Rc841.Rb1Qd5And there is no time to promote the a-pawn, while42.Qb2e5also doesn't help.} 
39. Bxe1
40. Rxe1
40. Rf8 {Now Black is completely winning and the rest doesn't require any specific commentary.} 
41. Qb6
41. Qd5
42. Rc1
42. Rc8
43. Rxc8
43. Bxc8
44. Qc7+
44. Bd7
45. f3
45. g4
46. Kf2
46. gxf3
47. gxf3
47. e5
48. Kg3
48. h5
49. Qc1
49. h4+
50. Kxh4
50. Qxf3 {A fantastic, mind-boggling game. It is perhaps not the best advertisement for the Alekhine given that Black was worse out of the opening and clearly lost at a later stage, but you should also remember that Black did obtain a clearly better position at some point and won the game in the end.In any case, due to its beauty and the result, I thought it is justified to include it in the Model Games chapter and I hope you have enjoyed going over it as much as I did.} 
