 {While it is not that unexpected that the likes of Korchnoi and Larsen employed the Alekhine in their careers, the fact that the 11th World Champion Robert James Fischer also used it in a handful of games is arguably much more surprising.His name is much more commonly associated with openings such as the Najdorf and the King's Indian, but a closer inspection shows that Fischer was not at all immune to using the Alekhine as a psychlogical weapon, despite has claim that he 'doesn't believe in psychology'.Fortunately for us Alekhine lovers, n the 1970-1972 World Chess Championship Cycle, Fischer employed it five times - three times in the Interzonal Tournament in 1970. and twice in the 'Match of the Century' against Boris Spassky in 1992. In the Model Game section, I have decided to analyze the first instance of Fischer using it against Spassky, which happened in the 13th game of the match.} 1. e4
1. Nf6 {At the moment this game was played, Fischer had a commanding lead in the match of 6-3. However, in his previous Black game, he lost badly in the Posioned Pawn Variation of the Najdorf, so he probably thought this is a good moment to unleash the Alekhine and hope that the Soviet team hasn't devoted that much attention to it. So much about 'I only believe in good moves'. Yeah, right.} 
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3
4. g6 {And here we have it - the sharp Alburt variation, as advocated in this course.} 
5. Bc4
5. Nb6
6. Bb3
6. Bg7
7. Nbd2 {And almost immediately Spassky goes for a non-confrontational, safer move, which immediately justifies Fischer's opening choice.} 
7. O-O
8. h3 {Trying to play it ultra safe and fight against Bg4, but White can't hope for a big edge with such quiet moves early in the opening.} 
8. a5 {A thematic advance of the pawn in this variation.} 
9. a4
9. dxe5
10. dxe5
10. Na6 {The knight is heading for c5.} 
11. O-O
11. Nc5
12. Qe2
12. Qe8 {Typical Fischer. He recognizes that the a-pawn is unprotected, and simply goes for it and asks White to demonstrate the compensation. This is fully correct, although not the only way to handle this position.} 
13. Ne4 {Another natural-looking move that is apparently not the best.13.Nd4Was seemingly much better. The idea is that after13...Ncxa414.Nb5Wins on the spot.Therefore, after13.Nd4Black probably has to play something like13...Bd7when after14.Ba2Bxa415.f4White has definite compensation for the pawn and a much better position than in the game.} 
13. Nbxa4
14. Bxa4
14. Nxa4 {Fischer just snatches the pawn, as he - very much like Korchnoi - liked his pawn grabs if he thought he could get away with them. In some sources I have read, his 'materialism' was quoted to be one of his weaknesses, although who am I do give my verdict on that matter?} 
15. Re1
15. Nb6 {Still, White does have some activity in the center and a bit more space, so there is definitely some practical compensation for the pawn.} 
16. Bd2 {It is hard to say whether it is beneficial or not to force the pawn to advance to a4, but oh well.} 
16. a4
17. Bg5 {It is also hard to say whether this bishop move achieves anything.17.Rad1or17.Bb4are alternatives worth considering.} 
17. h6
18. Bh4
18. Bf5
19. g4 {But this is a bit too much and a further weakening of the position.19.Nd4Is more normal, although after19...Bxe420.Qxe4Black exchanges another pair of minor pieces and simplifies the position further.} 
19. Be6 {19...Bxe4Is again worth considering, but now that the kingside and the light squares have been weakened - why not keep the bishop?} 
20. Nd4
20. Bc4
21. Qd2
21. Qd7 {A bit too safe, even.21...Bxe5Was actually a reasonable pawn grab. It looks scary to allow some counterplay along the e/file but after22.Nc5Bxd423.Qxd4g524.Bg3Rd8Nothing terrible for Black is apparent. Of course, it is not very natural for a human to play this way, but it has to be mentioned how differently the engines see chess than us.} 
22. Rad1
22. Rfe8 {But this is also a bit too safe, almost.22...a3or again22...Bxe5or even22...Bd5was preferable, although it is not easy to navigate this position.} 
23. f4 {23.b3Was a strong inclusion that works out tactically. For example:23...axb324.cxb3Bd525.Nc5Qd826.e6And White does obtain a very strong initiative.Thus, after23.b323...c5Seems to be virtually the only move, freeing the c7 square for the queen after24.Nxc5Qc7When the situation is highly unclear.} 
23. Bd5
24. Nc5
24. Qc8
25. Qc3 {Very meek, allowing Black to consolidate.25.e6Now isn't that strong as the knight has the c4 square:25...Nc426.Qe2Ra527.b4And here Black's best seems to be27...Rxc528.bxc5fxe6Still, the situation is highly unclear and I am amazed that Spassky refrained from going e6 - especially since that kind of attacking chess is very much his element. A clear sign he was not his usual self in Reykjavik.} 
25. e6 {Now the e6 advance has been prevented and suddenly White is struggling to find compensation.} 
26. Kh2
26. Nd7 {A good move, challenging the active pieces and improving the knight that wasn't doing too much.} 
27. Nd3 {A final mistake, allowing his pieces to get pushed away.27.Nxd7Qxd7Was more resistant, although here also Black should be objectively winning in the long run.} 
27. c5
28. Nb5 {Otherwise Black plays b5 and gains a lot of space on the queenside.} 
28. Qc6 {Another strong move, forcing the following transformation of the position.} 
29. Nd6 {29.Na3b5Is just horrible for White.} 
29. Qxd6 {Exploiting the pin and transforming the advantage.} 
30. exd6
30. Bxc3
31. bxc3 {This endgame is now completely winning. Not only does Black have an extra pawn, but also a superior structure. Still, it is not easy to convert and Fischer even lets the advantage seriously slip at some moment.} 
31. f6 {Taking the e5 square away.} 
32. g5 {Fighting for that square.} 
32. hxg5
33. fxg5
33. f5
34. Bg3
34. Kf7 {This is apparently not necessary and just a loss of tempo.34...a3Pushing the pawn at once was better. After35.Ne5Nxe536.Bxe5Red837.c4Is not really that powerful and Black is just winning.37...Bxc4} 
35. Ne5+
35. Nxe5
36. Bxe5
36. b5 {But this suddenly allows White to completely get back into the game.36...Red8Was necessary. Then after37.c4Bxc4White doesn't have the same d7-Bf6 combo at disposal and Black should still be winning.} 
37. Rf1 {Missing the chance! Spassky tries to go for the Rf4-Rh4 idea, but it is just too slow.37.c4Was a very strong tactical shot, fairly typical of opposite-coloured bishop endgames, where the material doesn't really matter. Black is kinda struggling now as37...Bxc438.d7Red839.Bf6Will win the exchange under good circumstances and it is not clear whether Black will be able to win the resulting position or not.It should also be noted that after37.c4bxc4Opens up the b-file for White and also the bishop now controls the a1 square, making it very difficult to win just by pushing the a-pawn.} 
37. Rh8 {A sound positional idea, but wrongly timed.37...a3Black should have pushed the a-pawn first and only played Rh8 in response to Rf4, e.g.38.Rf4Rh8Also,37...a338.c4Is no longer so good as after38...Bxc4The rook on f1 is under attack.} 
38. Bf6 {Spassky believes his opponent and doesn't take the exchange.38.Bxh8Rxh8Looks unpleasant for White, but it is not directly losing and the engine does claim White should be able to resist after, say39.Rfe1Rd840.Kg3This endgame seems quite holdable due to40...Rxd641.c4} 
38. a3
39. Rf4 {But this is a losing move. Spassky does intend to play c4 eventually, but it just doesn't work as well.} 
39. a2 {39...Bc4Is also quite winning, e.g.40.d7a2} 
40. c4
40. Bxc4 {The bishop on f6 does control the a1 square, but Black's queenside pawn chain is now intact.} 
41. d7 {Another critical moment in the game.} 
41. Bd5 {This seems to be wrong, although it is not obvious why without deep analysis.41...e5It was necessary to include this pawn push first. The idea is to open up the e6 square for the king.42.Bxe5Rhd843.Bf6Ke644.Bxd8Rxd845.Rf3f4And Black will eventually get the d7 pawn and obtain a won position while being an exchange down - the a2 pawn is too strong.} 
42. Kg3 {Now all of a sudden it is hard to make progress.} 
42. Ra3+
43. c3
43. Rha8
44. Rh4 {A very annoying move with the idea of Rh7, preventing queening for the moment.} 
44. e5 {The only chance to play for the win.44...a1=Q45.Rh7+Leads to an immediate repetition.} 
45. Rh7+
45. Ke6
46. Re7+
46. Kd6
47. Rxe5 {A highly complex and mind boggling position.} 
47. Rxc3+ {47...a1=QEven loses to48.Rexd5+Kc649.Rd6+Kb750.Rxa1Rxa151.d8=Q} 
48. Kf2
48. Rc2+
49. Ke1
49. Kxd7 {Black is forced to do this and give up the bishop on d5.} 
50. Rexd5+
50. Kc6
51. Rd6+
51. Kb7
52. Rd7+
52. Ka6 {Still, in the remaining position, Black does have three connected passed pawns for the piece and a strong soldier on a2, so White is the one who needs to be careful and try to find a way to draw the game.} 
53. R7d2 {A good defensive move, exchanging the active rook and keeping the pawn on a2 under control. For now.} 
53. Rxd2
54. Kxd2
54. b4
55. h4
55. Kb5
56. h5 {Very good defensive play. White can't wait passively for the pawn avalanche to suffocate him, so Spassky creates a passed pawn of his own on the g-file.} 
56. c4 {Threatening c3 and forcing the reply.} 
57. Ra1
57. gxh5
58. g6
58. h4
59. g7
59. h3 {The culmination of this fascinating game.} 
60. Be7 {Intending to play Bf8 and then queen, forcing the reply.} 
60. Rg8
61. Bf8
61. h2
62. Kc2
62. Kc6
63. Rd1 {A good move, cutting the king along the d-file.} 
63. b3+
64. Kc3
64. h1=Q {Sacrificing the h-pawn to try and get the king across the d-file and promote the f-pawn is the only way to try and win.} 
65. Rxh1
65. Kd5 {Now the king breaks in, although the game should still be holdable for White.} 
66. Kb2 {Making the task a tiiiiny bit more complicated by moving the king away from the c3 square.66.Re1Was 'easier. The idea is to place the rook on a1 and collect all the queenside pawns if Black tries to bring the king to the kingside - and to the second rank!66...f467.Rd1+Ke468.Re1+Kf369.Rf1+Kg370.Rg1+Kf2The king has to step to the 2nd rank to try and make progress, but then here comes:71.Ra1f372.Kxc4Kg273.Kxb3f274.Rxa2Kg175.Rxf2Kxf2With a draw.} 
66. f4
67. Rd1+
67. Ke4
68. Rc1
68. Kd3
69. Rd1+ {A blunder that throws away the game. Spassky finally cracks under the tension and commits a decisive mistake.69.Rf1There were two ways to save the game, none of which was too trivial. The first one involved attacking the f4 pawn, e.g.69...Ke270.Rxf4c3+71.Ka1c272.Rc4Kd2A)73.Ba3loses at once to73...Rxg7B) This is why it is necessary to release the rook and give a bishop check, e.g.73.Bb4+Kd174.Ba3Rxg775.Rc3It is absolutely necessary to have the square for the rook. The b3 pawn will fall or the rook will have to go passive and White should be able to hold, e.g.75...Ra776.Bb2Rb777.Rc869.Rc3+Was also drawing, e.g.69...Kd470.Rf3c3+71.Ka1c272.Rxf4+Kd373.Rf1Kc374.Rf3+Kd275.Ba3With an immediate draw. Of course, these variations are very difficult to calculate and figure out over the board, with massive tension and with the clock ticking. This is why Spassky's 66th move was not the best from the practical standpoint - it made the defensive task immensely more difficult.} 
69. Ke2 {Now it is all over - the pawns are too strong!} 
70. Rc1
70. f3
71. Bc5
71. Rxg7
72. Rxc4
72. Rd7
73. Re4+
73. Kf1
74. Bd4
74. f2 {And here Spassky resigned as one of the pawns will promote. A grandiose struggle, fully worthy of a World Chess Championship match. From the perspective of an Alekhine player, the opening of this game should be regarded as a massive success since Fischer simply came out with an extra pawn.The fact that the resulting middlegame was extremely double-edged and complicated shouldn't be something to discourage us. After all, obtaining double-edged and complicated positions is the reason why we play the Alekhine to begin with.It should be encouraging to see that it worked perfectly in a World Championship Match, even if it was played 'only' in 1972.} 
