 {While even the World Champions sometimes dare to play the Alekhine, at that level the opening is nevertheless a rare guest. However, if we go just one tier below, we can alraedy discover some grandmasters who play/used to play the Alekhine on a very regular basis and who virtually single-handedly developed the theory in certain variations. It would be unjust to their legacy if I didn't include at least some of their games in this course.In the first game, we will get acquainted with grandmaster Lev Alburt, a former Soviet grandmaster who defected to the United States in 1979 and then won three US Championships. It is impossible to talk about the Alekhine without including him in the conversation because Alekhine was his main weapon against 1.e4.} 1. e4 {Alburt's opponent was 2343 FIDE rated player called Viktors Pupols. I don't know too many details about him and to be completely honest - I didn't really bother to research too much either.} 
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3
4. g6 {If you paid attention in the theoretical part of the course, you might remember that this variation, which was my main recommendation, is named precisely after Alburt!} 
5. Bc4
5. Nb6
6. Bb3
6. Bg7
7. Ng5
7. e6
8. f4 {Not the main line, but not a move to be underestimated. As mentioned in the theoretical part, this move is probably less dangerous than the main move8.Qf3} 
8. dxe5 {If you recall, this capture on e5 in order to open up the d-file and soften up the d4 pawn, was my recommendation in the theoretical chapter.} 
9. fxe5 {9.dxe5Qxd1+Is, of course, very good for Black.} 
9. c5
10. O-O
10. O-O
11. c3
11. cxd4
12. cxd4
12. Nc6 {Black absolutely has to pressure the center in the Alekhine defence.} 
13. Nf3
13. f6 {And now this thematic move, undermining the pawn on e5 when the pawn on d4 is protected. Black accepts the ugly pawn structure, but claims that the piece activity will more than compensate for it.} 
14. Nc3 {But this is a little bit strange, to be completely honest, as White does allow Black to capture on e5. The idea is to try and get with the knight to e4 as soon as possible.14.exf6Qxf615.Be3Nd5Was the line analyzed in the theoretical chapter.} 
14. fxe5
15. Bg5 {I guess this was White's idea, trying to inconvenient the Black queen.} 
15. Qd7 {The right square, not running into any sort of Ne4 tricks. It does look a little bit strange to block the bishop on c8, but Black is winning a pawn on e5 after all and White is the one who has to demonstrate the compensation.} 
16. dxe5
16. Nxe5
17. Nxe5
17. Rxf1+ {Very accurate exchange. The idea is to either force the king to f1, or to follow things with a nice check on d4.17...Qxd118.Rfxd1Bxe519.Rd3Leaves White with a big compensation for the pawn. It does make a lot of sense for Black to exchange some of the opponent's active pieces in this position to reduce the pressure.} 
18. Qxf1 {18.Kxf1Does look a little bit strange. The point is that after18...Qxd1+19.Rxd1Bxe5An exchange of one pair of rooks has greatly alleviated Black's position. At least according to the computer, because it is not 100% obvious to my human eye, frankly.} 
18. Qd4+ {This nice check, intending to recapture on e5 with the queen, was the point. Not only is the bishop not exposed on e5, but the queen would also gain a tempo on the bishop on g5.} 
19. Kh1
19. Qxe5
20. Be7
20. Bd7 {Now Black has managed to develop and White has to start being accurate. It is true that the extra pawn on e6 is not the prettiest extra pawn of all time. But hey, it is an extra pawn after all.} 
21. Re1
21. Qf5
22. Qe2 {Of course, White is not interested in exchanging queens, since Black's king is much weaker.} 
22. Re8
23. Bd6
23. Qf6 {Maybe a slight inaccuracy - at least according to the computer.23...Nd5Bringing in the knight into the game, was apparently better, although it is a bit counterintuitive to think about some potential captures on d5.} 
24. Ne4 {But this now justifies Black's previous move as the pawn grab on b2 is relatively safe.24.Rf1Some move such as this rook move, trying to force the queen away from the diagonal and then playing Ne4, was far stronger. But again, very difficult for a human to play such a position in the best possible manner.} 
24. Qxb2 {Now Black wins another pawn and asks White to demonstrate the compensation. Note that being willing to provoke your opponent is very important when playing an opening such as the Alekhine defence.} 
25. Qf3 {But this seems to be a mistake because the knight will be now pinned by the bishop. The engine offers two solutions. The first one is a very quiet one, moving the queen with25.Qf1and intending to play Nc5 next when White has significant compensation for the two pawns.The other is to go to the endgame with25.Qxb2Bxb226.Rb1Bg727.Nc5When once again White will probably regain one of the pawns and then probably be able to draw. Still, not very easy to decide on such measures and especially exchange queens.} 
25. Bc6 {Now the knight can't go to c5 so easily and Black has also gained an important tempo to improve the bishop, which turns the evaluation in his favour.} 
26. Rf1 {Apparently also not the best, but it is already kinda hard to offer a good advice. Now the knight on e4 is a bit undefended and it will soon become very relevant.} 
26. Kh8 {Avoiding any potential checks on f7.} 
27. Qg4 {A final mistake in a tough position. Other moves don't lose a piece directly, but Black is just two pawns up anyway.} 
27. Qd4 {A nasty attack, exploiting the fact that the knight on e4 has to protect the bishop on d6. Now Black wins a piece and the rest is elementary.} 
28. Bc2
28. Bxe4
29. Rd1
29. Bf5 {A simple refutation.} 
30. Rxd4 {What else?30.Qxf5Qxd1+-+30.Qxd4Bxd431.Rxd4Bxc2-+} 
30. Bxg4
31. Rxg4
31. Rc8 {And finally, due to the weakness of the back rank, White resigned as he loses a piece. A strong performance by Alburt and a very typical way in which one wins games with the Alekhine.I would definitely urge you to check some of Alburt's other games if you are serious about playing the Alekhine.} 
