 {While we are talking about 'Alekhine greats', we should definitely mention the name of Latvian Grandmaster Edvins Kengis, who also used to play 1.e4 Nf6 throughout his career on a regular basis. In the following game, he employed it in the Chess Olympiad(!)against the strong and experienced grandmaster Larry Christiansen.} 1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3
4. dxe5
5. Nxe5
5. g6 {You might recall that this variations also bears the Black's player name and is known as the Kengis variation. While it was not recommended in this course, it was the main choice of Roland Pruijssers in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable.} 
6. Bc4 {Why not to develop the bishop very actively on the c4 square? Now Qf3 is a very serious threat.} 
6. c6 {Reinforcing the knight in order to avoid any sort of Bxf7 or Qf3 problems.} 
7. O-O
7. Bg7
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. Bb3
9. Be6 {A very typical position for this variation. The bishop goes to e6 to challenge the opponent's counterpart. Black wants to play Nd7 to challenge the knight on e5 next, while a move like Nc7 is also a potential idea. On the other hand, Black does need to be careful about typical Rxe6 ideas here.} 
10. Nd2
10. Nd7
11. Nef3 {A typical Alekhine move. Since White has more space, they really don't want to trade pieces and help Black to get some breathing room.11.Nxd7is very wrong in most positions of this type (this pawn structure can also arise via Caro Kann or Scandi, for example). We will see in the game between Topalov and Carlsen later in this chapter why this is not very principled - and how Black can exploit it.} 
11. Nc7 {Executing the typical idea and offering the bishop trade.} 
12. c3 {This is probably a bit meek. It is not entirely clear how helpful this c3 move is. Now Black immediately strikes in the center.12.Ne4Is slightly better, making it more difficult to go for the c5 break. Then after some12...a513.c3b5Is a typical idea, seizing some space on the queenside and ensuring that the knight on d5 won't be so easily kicked out with c4. White is always better in these types of positions, but Black is very solid.} 
12. c5
13. Bxe6
13. Nxe6 {Of course, the downside of the move c5 was that it allows the d-pawn to advance now. But will it be a strength or a weakness? Typical provokation.} 
14. d5
14. Nc7
15. Ne4 {A good move, defending the d5 pawn and intending d6 next. Note that15.c4is met with15...b5You should always be ready to switch from positional to dynamic mindset in the Alekhine and search for your pawn breaks. Here White is not coordinated enough so Black is already fighting for the initiative.} 
15. Nf6
16. c4 {Solidifying the center, but now allowing a different undermining.} 
16. Nxe4
17. Rxe4
17. e6 {Very thematic play. Black is not afraid of the advance of the d-pawn. And if the pawn doesn't advance, Black will very happily capture on d5 or place the knight on e6.17...b5Is not so good here due to18.Bg5Re819.Qe2when Black has issues with the e7 pawn.} 
18. Bg5 {A good move, inconveniencing the queen. Be mindful of this move in different positions where your bishop is fainchettoed.} 
18. f6 {There is nothing else but to violate Ben Finegold's principle.18...Qd619.Bf4Is definitely not desirable, e.g.19...Qb620.Bxc7Qxc721.dxe6Bxb222.Rb1Needless to say, this looks a bit unsafe. Only White can be better here.} 
19. d6 {This was the point behind White's previous move, as now the e6 pawn will be weak. But it turns out that White can't take it due to the bishop on g5.19.Be3Was objectively safer, as after19...exd520.cxd5Qxd521.Qxd5+Nxd522.Bxc5The endgame is objectively balanced.} 
19. Ne8 {Returning the favor. Black wanted to attack the d6 pawn at once, but it turns out there was a stronger alternative.19...Na6Going to the rim was stronger as the knight here defends the c5 pawn after20.Be320.Rxe6fxg5Is even worse here as the knight is not awkward on e8 as in the game.Qd7when the pawn on d6 will very likely turn out to be a weakness rather than an asset.} 
20. Rxe6 {Objectively not fully correct, but kudos for creativity and bravery. White decides to sacrifice a piece and banks on the strong pawn on the 7th rank and Black's lack of coordination.20.Be3Was again safer.} 
20. fxg5 {Of course, we don't need to be asked twice.} 
21. Qd5 {Threatening a deadly discovery.} 
21. Kh8
22. Rae1
22. Nf6 {Getting the knight out of the way and hitting the queen.} 
23. Qxb7 {Now White has two pawns for the piece, the strong d7 passer and Black has doubled g-pawns. Enough for compensation, but not for more than that.} 
23. Qb6 {A good decision, trying to reduce the pressure by exchanging opponent's active piece.} 
24. Re7 {A good move, keeping the tension and not wishing to repair Black's pawn structure.24.Qxb6It is instructive to mention why this is a mistake. After24...axb6Black's structure is better and the rook is more active along the a-file. Very instructive for lower-rated players who often exchange at the very first opportunity.} 
24. Qxb7
25. Rxb7
25. Rfe8
26. Rxe8+
26. Rxe8 {Objectively this endgame should be equal, but Black is the one with the chances. Now the threat is g4 and Re1 mate.} 
27. h3
27. Ne4 {Acitivating the knight and hitting the d6 and b2 pawns at the same time. Also note that the bishop is going a decent job in restricting the opponent's knight.} 
28. d7
28. Rd8
29. Rxa7 {But this seems to be a bad mistake. White banks on the passed a-pawn in the resulting endgame, but this is simply winning for Black.29.b4Removing the attacked pawn, was the right approach. However, the resulting variation is not easy, since after29...cxb4White has to find.30.Rc7With the idea c5-c6 and Rc8. It transpires that Black has nothing better than giving up the knight for the c-pawn and the d-pawn and obtaining a tiny bit better endgame, e.g.30...Bf631.c5Nxc532.Rxc5Rxd733.Nxg5} 
29. Bxb2
30. a4
30. Nf6 {Simply attacking the d7 pawn which can't be defended.} 
31. Nxg5
31. Rxd7
32. Rxd7 {Keeping the rooks doesn't help as after32.Ra8+Kg733.Ne6+Kf734.Nxc5White has some problems with the king, e.g.34...Rd1+35.Kh2Be5+36.g3Bd4} 
32. Nxd7 {Now Black is clearly better, maybe even winning already. The two pawns are not a match for the piece, even though considerable technical difficulties do remain.} 
33. a5
33. Nb8
34. Ne4
34. Na6 {The pawn is stopped and the c5 pawn is defended, so White shouldn't have any hope. Still, the technical task is very difficult and Kengis actually does let the opponent off the hook in several instances. I will do my best to pinpoint them.} 
35. f4
35. Ba3
36. Nd6
36. Bb4
37. Nb7
37. Kg7
38. Kf2
38. Kf6
39. Kf3
39. Ke7 {The king goes after the a-pawn, but it might not be the best. Still, I will not bother delving too much into the technical details as they are very difficult to understand even with the engine. Let's focus on main critical points, instead.} 
40. Ke4
40. Kd7
41. Kd5
41. Nc7+
42. Ke4
42. Na6 {42...Ne8Computer wants Black to place the knight here before going after the pawn because now Nd6 is not possible.} 
43. Kd5
43. Kc7
44. Nd6 {A good decision, giving up the a5 pawn to create counterplay against the kingside pawns, which have been abandoned by the monarch.} 
44. Bxa5
45. Ne8+
45. Kd8
46. Nf6
46. Nc7+ {The wrong check, amazingly enough!46...Nb4+The idea of giving up the pawn should have been executed via b4 not c7, since now after47.Kd6there is47...Nd3} 
47. Kd6 {A move that Black probably overlooked. Now the knight is somewhat restricted, two pawns are hanging and Black loses a major chunk of the advantage.47.Kxc5Ne6+48.Kd6Nxf4Was probably what Black was hoping for, even though this is not a 100% guarantee win in my eyes.} 
47. Bd2
48. g3
48. h5 {48...Be149.Ne4Holds everything together.} 
49. Ne4 {A step in the wrong direction. White got scared of the h4-Bxf4 'threat', but now was the right time to capture on c5.49.Kxc5h450.gxh4Ne6+leads to a draw, e.g.51.Kd6Nxf452.Ke5} 
49. Be3 {Now the knight is againt protected and h4 is on the agenda.} 
50. h4 {White desperately tries to keep the structure intact and avoid any h4, but now all the pawns are fixed on the colour of the bishop.50.Nxc5h4Is now annoying since with the king on c7 the capture on f4 comes with a check, e.g.51.gxh4Bxf4+52.Kc6Ke7Still wouldn't put my money on me if I had to convert with Black here, but objectively, Black is close to winning.} 
50. Bd4 {A nice move, preventing Nf6. Note how king can't cross the barrier along the e-file.} 
51. Ng5
51. Bf2
52. Ne4
52. Be1 {But this is just wrong as Black allows the king to go to e5 and play f5.52...Bd4Going back to d4, taking the e5 square under the control and trying to figure out a way to include the king and the knight into the action, retain chances of salvation.} 
53. Ke5 {Now there is no defense against f5 push.} 
53. Ke7
54. f5
54. gxf5
55. Kxf5 {The wrong pawn!55.Nxc5It was necessary to eliminate the one on c5. The point is that after55...Bxg3+56.Kxf5White has a positional fortress on the table, e.g.56...Ne857.Kg6Nf658.Nd3It is not possible to make progress in this position.} 
55. Na6 {The wrong piece!55...Bb4It was necessary to bring the bishop to b4 to defend the pawn, in order to be free for the Ne8-Nf6 maneuver with the knight. e.g.56.Kg5Ne857.Kxh5Nf6+58.Nxf6Kxf6And even though at first glance this looks as a draw, with the king on the edge even the connected passed pawns are insufficient. A sample line:59.g4Bd260.g5+Kf561.Kh6Be362.Kh7Bxg5-+Neither does55...Bb456.Nf6Ne857.Nxh5Nd6+58.Ke5Nxc4+Help. This endgame is also objectively won for Black.} 
56. Kg6
56. Ke6
57. Ng5+
57. Ke7
58. Ne4
58. Ke6
59. Ng5+
59. Kd7
60. Ne4
60. Kc6 {Black avoids the repetition, but it is a big question how wise it is as now the situation is different with the knight on a6.} 
61. Kxh5
61. Nc7
62. Kg6 {62.g4Also leads to a draw, e.g.62...Ne663.g5Kd7Although here it is much 'harder' to lose compared to the game.} 
62. Ne8 {The knight goes to d6 to challenge the knight on e4.} 
63. h5
63. Nd6 {The culminating moment of this entire game.} 
64. Nxd6 {Capitulation! White voluntarily exchanges the knights and goes into a lost endgame. It is hard to say what Christiansen missed - maybe he simply misjudged the resulting position and cracked under pressure. It is a bit heartening to see even very strong grandmasters making blunders when put under pressure for a long period of time.64.Nf6Keeping the knight was absolutely necessary. It is true that this loses the c4 pawn, but after64...Nxc465.g4Ne5+66.Kf5White has enough counterplay to maintain the balance. Of course, the engine does point out that the line is very deep and that it continues66...c467.g5c368.g6c269.g7c1=Q70.g8=QWith equality. Maybe it was not so easy to figure out all these things and find a series of 'only' moves at the board. But mathematically speaking, this was the move that lost the game for White.} 
64. Kxd6
65. g4 {65.h6Bxg3Doesn't help.} 
65. Ke6 {The king is too close and the pawns can't really move on their own.} 
66. Kg7 {66.h6Bc3And the activity on the kingside has been stopped.} 
66. Bc3+
67. Kf8
67. Kf6
68. Ke8 {Trying to get with the king around, to the c5 pawn.} 
68. Bd2
69. Kd7
69. Ke5 {A cold shower. Now that the white king has moved, the pawns can be held solely by the bishop.} 
70. Ke7 {Trying to go back to the kingside.} 
70. Be3
71. Kd7 {Or maybe not.71.Kf7Kf4is not much better, tho.} 
71. Kd4
72. Ke6
72. Kxc4
73. Kf6
73. Kd5
74. g5
74. c4
75. g6
75. c3 {Black is much faster as he can give up the bishop for one of the pawns if required. A grandiose, majestic battle, not without its mistake. On one hand, it is not the best advertisement for Alekhine to have to play such long games and win in 75 moves.But on the other hand, I felt this is a very nice example of a typical Alekhine middlegame that also features a very interesting endgame. Given that it also provided me with the opportunity to introduce Kengis to the wider audience, I regret nothing!} 
