 {Finally, throughout this course, I have offer referenced the strong Ukrainian Grandmaster and online and blitz specialist Olexandr Bortnyk as the modern 'guru' of the variation. And indeed, he is probably the strongest grandmaster who employs it regularly - albeit mostly in blitz online games. I figured it would, therefore, be quite suitable to include one of his own games against none other but arguably the strongest online blitz player and Bortnyk's eternal 'nemesis', GM Hikaru Nakamura.I should also probably mention that Bortnyk, Alburt and Kengis are definitely not the only names with whom an Alekhine devotee should be familiar with. Unfortunately, listing all the great Alekhine players and their respective games would go way beyond the scope of this course, so I apologize if I have managed to omit one of your favourite players in this short compilation of games.} 1. e4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. e5
3. Nfd7 {The line recommended in this course. I always used to play3...d4in the past, but Bortnyk inspired me to adopt the combative text continuation.} 
4. f4
4. d4
5. Ne4
5. f5
6. Ng5
6. Nb6
7. e6
7. Qd5
8. Be2
8. Nc6
9. Bf3
9. Qd6 {All this was analyzed in the theoretical chapter in the course. I don't think this is a particularly good line for White - and Nakamura's next move makes matters even worse.} 
10. Ne2 {This simply drops a pawn.10.Bxc6+Is necessary, when after10...Qxc611.N1f3The situation is more tricky as the pawn on d4 is also loose, although Black should be objectively fine.} 
10. Bxe6
11. Nxe6
11. Qxe6
12. O-O {And just like that, Black is a healthy extra pawn after 12 moves in the opening against one of the best players in the world. I know, it was just a blitz game, but it was played in a cash competition - Titled Tuesday.12.Bxc6+Qxc613.Nxd4Loses to13...Qe4+14.Ne2Qxg2} 
12. Qf6 {Spending a tempo with the queen is probably not necessary, although it is natural to want to overprotect the d4 pawn.12...g6preparing the fianchetto, is quite reasonable. The point is that after13.Bxc6+Qxc614.Nxd4Qc515.c3Bg7Is just very good for Black as he will capture on d4 next.} 
13. a4
13. a5
14. c3 {This undermining of the structure is a bit annoying. If g6 had been played, the bishop would fight for the d4 square, but alas.} 
14. d3
15. Bxc6+
15. bxc6 {A good, although a bit unconventional decision. Black wants to avoid the Nd4 tempo and also play c5 next.15...Qxc616.Nd4And the knight is quite annoying on d4. Once again - if the bishop were closer to g7, Black could consider playing Qc5 and pinning the knight, but alas.16...Qc517.b3This doesn't lead anywhere. Ba3 is comnig.} 
16. Nd4
16. c5
17. Nf3
17. c4 {Maybe this is a bit premature. The pawns do look strong, but the following move undermines them both.} 
18. b3
18. e6
19. Ne5 {But this is faulty. White disregards the development and attacks the c4 pawn - but it turns out that Black doesn't really mind exchanging the knights.19.bxc4Was healthier, when after19...Bd620.Ne1O-O21.Nxd3Nxc4The position is roughly balanced - but very complicated and difficult to play.} 
19. Bd6
20. Nxc4
20. Nxc4
21. bxc4
21. O-O {Now Black should be much better as the bishop on d6 is superior to the one on c1. However, Black's position also has certain risks and is difficult to navigate - especially in blitz.And Nakamura is arguably the best player in the world when it comes to handling these rugged positions and putting pressure on the opponent with the help of the clock.} 
22. Qf3 {Pressuring the weak d3 pawn.} 
22. Rfd8 {Indirectly defending it due to discovered attack.} 
23. Kh1
23. Rab8
24. g3 {But this turns out to be a further weakening of the king. It is hard to explain why this is not the most precise - but in future, Black can use the weakened 2nd rank to his advantage.The move such as24.h3was preferable. Let's use the method of comparison to see what is the difference. In the variation after24...Bc525.Ba3Qe726.Bxc5Qxc527.Rae1Qxc428.Re5Qxa429.Rxe6Qa2Here White can play30.Qc6When White obtains a lot of counterplay and his king is quite safe.30...Kh831.Re7Rg832.Qxc7Rb233.Rfe1Rxd234.Rxg7} 
24. Bc5
25. Re1 {With g3 instead of h3 being played, the same variation that we analyzed in the note to White's 24th move is inferior due to25.Ba3Qe726.Bxc5Qxc527.Rae1Qxc428.Re5Qxa429.Rxe6Qa2And now there is no30.Qc6Kh831.Re7Rg832.Qxc7Rb2And now since the 2nd rank is weakened, White is in trouble. Okay, not so easy to blame Nakamura for not seeing all this, although, on general grounds, it is probably safer not to weaken diagonals and files around the king.} 
25. Qf7 {But this move allows White back into the game.25...Qe7Was required, defending the bishop on c5. The idea is to meet26.Qc6with26...Rb6} 
26. Qc6 {A simple double attack on the bishop and the pawn on e6 that forces Black to make an undesired retreating move.} 
26. Bd6
27. c5
27. Bf8
28. Ba3 {Another very strong move, protecting the c5 pawn and threatening the e6 pawn.} 
28. Rb3 {A nice active move, increasing the activity of the rook and not caring about the weak pawn on e6.} 
29. Qxe6 {It is probably better not to do this and to play some quiet, semi-waiting move, but the desire to win a pawn is understandable.} 
29. Qxe6
30. Rxe6
30. Rdb8 {White has an extra pawn, but the opponent's rooks are active and White's pawn structure is worse, so Black has definite compensation for the pawn.} 
31. Ree1
31. Kf7
32. Kg2
32. g6
33. Kf3
33. Bg7 {But this is a big blunder that throws the game on the spot. It was necessary to keep the bishop on the f8-a3 diagonal. To an extent, these blunders are very characteristic against Hikaru Nakamura, as the combined pressure of the clock and nerves is bound to have its tell sooner or later.33...c6A move such as this would have kept everything under control. Black has the better pieces and is the one pushing, despite being a pawn down.} 
34. c6 {A very nasty move, activating the bishop, threatening Re7 and completely changing the evaluation of the position.} 
34. Bf6
35. Bc5 {Removing the bishop from the attack and moving it to a square where it is virtually untouchable. Just like the c6 pawn.} 
35. Rb2
