36. Re8 {36...Be7Was more resilient here. If Black can exchange the bishop and get to the c6 pawn, maybe he will be fine, although White will of course play something else such as37.Ba7Ra838.Bd4} 
37. Rab1 {A cold shower, exchanging the most active piece in the position - and a pair of rooks.} 
37. Rxb1
38. Rxb1
38. Re2
39. Be3 {Now it is all over and the rest is elementary for a player of Nakamura's caliber.} 
39. Rxh2
40. Rb7
40. Bd8
41. Ra7
41. h6
42. Rxa5 {The a-pawn will decide the issue.} 
42. Ke6
43. c4
43. g5
44. Re5+
44. Kf6
45. Bd4
45. g4+
46. Ke3
46. Kg6
47. Kxd3
47. Rg2
48. Re3
48. h5
49. a5
49. h4
50. gxh4
50. Bxh4
51. a6
51. Bf2
52. a7
52. Bxe3
53. Bxe3 {A very interesting and combative game. If you judged it by the result, you would say it is not the best advert for the Alekhine Defence, but considering how good the opening worked for Black, I would claim otherwise!} 
