 {No modern opening course is complete without including at least one game of Magnus Carlsen. Not only does it allow Chessable copywriters to include the eternal 'play like Magnus' phrase in the marketing text - but it also allows us to see how one of the best players of all time handled our opening and the resulting positions.Magnus actually played quite a few Alekhine games - but most of them were held under blitz or rapid time control. The following game, played in the historic Linares tournament (which unfortunately no longer exists) is one of those instances where he used it in a classical game against the opponent of the highest caliber. Let's take a look at this game.} 1. e4
1. Nf6
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3
4. dxe5 {This is probably the most solid option at Black's disposal against the Modern variation of the Alekhine. You might recall I recommended the more combative - but also more risky - Alburt variation with4...g6in this course.} 
5. Nxe5
5. c6 {Black has several options at their disposal, but solidifying the knight on d5, potentially opening up the c7 square for it and aiming to get some sort of caro-kann structure with pawns on e6 and c6 later down the road is one of the main options.} 
6. Bd3 {This is a bit of a strange move, as the bishop more commonly goes to e2.6.Be2Bf57.O-ONd78.Nf3Is the main variation of this particular line.} 
6. Nd7 {Immediately challenging the knight on e5.6...g6Is also possible here, aiming to fianchetto the bishop.} 
7. Nxd7 {But this is a very strange move, in my opinion. In the Alekhine, Black is the one who has less space - and it is well-known that it is favourable for the side with less space to exchange pieces.7.Nf3Going back with the knight to f3 is a standard anti-Alekhine maneuver for White which keeps more pieces on the board. I am somewhat amazed that White didn't go for it.} 
7. Bxd7
8. O-O
8. g6 {There is a choice between the fianchetto and developing with e6 which would hem in the light-squared bishop.} 
9. Nd2
9. Bg7
10. Nf3
10. O-O {We have a typical Alekhine position featuring a pawn structure that can also arise from openings such as Caro-kann or even Scandinavian. Both sides are very solid here as neither has any particular weaknesses. There is a slight imbalance in the pawn structure, but objectively the game should be about equal after one pair of minor pieces has been exchanged.} 
11. Re1
11. Bg4 {Creating some pressure against the d4 pawn.} 
12. c3
12. c5 {Another very strong move, utilizing some tactics to undermine the position.} 
13. Be4 {13.dxc5Nxc314.bxc3Bxc3Is a strong tactical blow that works well for Black. The best line continues15.Bh6Bxe116.Qxe1Qxd317.Ne5Qd418.c6bxc619.Nxc6Qd620.Nxe7+Kh821.Bxf8Rxf8When the position is quite equal. A good example of how deep it is sometimes possible/necessary to calculate, even in very simple positions. I wonder how far Magnus saw when he pushed the c-pawn forward.} 
13. cxd4
14. cxd4 {Now Black has a very pleasant position as White has a relatively bad version of the position with the isolated pawn. As a matter of fact, it is not clear how exactly will White hold onto it.} 
14. e6
15. Qb3 {This is a bit strange as it gives the d4 pawn on the spot. But it is hard to suggest a different move.15.Bxd5Qxd5Is completely won for Black as the d4 pawn is falling in the long run.15.Be3Nxe316.fxe3Defends the pawn, but gives up the bishop pair and also leaves White with undesirable structure. Topalov hopes to save himself in an endgame with a pawn down.} 
15. Bxf3
16. Bxf3
16. Bxd4 {Just like that, White is a pawn down. Magnus made it look quite simple until now, although don't expect that Alekhine will work that well in your own games!} 
17. Bxd5 {Trying to get the pawn back, but this is a mistake - it was better to try and keep the tension in the position and maintain the bishop pair.17.Qxb7Qa5Is also very much better for Black.} 
17. Qxd5
18. Qxd5
18. exd5
19. Rd1
19. Bg7
20. Kf1 {20.Rxd5Maybe Topalov realized only now that regaining the pawn leads to a lost position after20...Rfd821.Rxd8+Rxd822.Be3Bxb223.Rb1b6Due to the back rank issues, White can't capture the bishop so Black is left in a won endgame with an extra pawn.} 
20. Rfd8 {Now Black manages to keep the pawn. It is not 100% clear whether this endgame is won or not, which is why it is very instructive to observe how Magnus converts the advantage.} 
21. Bg5
21. Rd7
22. Rd2
22. h6
23. Be3
23. d4 {Pushing the pawn as far as possible in order to make the bishop on e3 a bit dumb.} 
24. Rd3 {24.Rad1Rad8Was arguably more resillient.} 
24. Rc8 {Preparing to infiltrate the c-file.} 
25. Bd2 {25.Rc1Was more tenacious.} 
25. Rc2 {Now Black is much more active and better coordinated - on top of having an extra pawn.} 
26. Rb1
26. Re7 {Another strong move, imbolizing the king and also the bishop on d2, due to the threat of Re2.} 
27. a4 {Trying to unravel by pushing the queenside pawns, but it is debatable whether this is good or whether it creates some new weaknesses.} 
27. f5 {Gaining some more space on the kingside.} 
28. b3
28. Rec7 {Now that White has moved the queenside pawns, Black goes back to seizing the c-file. It was not yet necessary as White can hardly move, but nothing wrong with it. Black can't win this position by force, but by slowly improving the position.} 
29. Be1
29. Kf7
30. Rd2
30. Rc1
31. Rxc1
31. Rxc1
32. Ke2
32. Rb1 {Now also targeting the newly created weakness on b3. The game is virtually over and the rest doesn't require much commentary.} 
33. Rd3
33. Ke6
34. h4
34. Kd5
35. Bd2
35. Ke4
36. Rg3
36. f4 {A nice touch.} 
37. Rd3 {37.Rxg6d3Is a very pictureqsue mate.} 
37. Be5
38. f3+
38. Kd5
39. Be1
39. Bd6
40. Bd2
40. g5
41. hxg5
41. hxg5
42. Be1
42. g4
43. fxg4
43. Ke4 {The threats of Rxe1 and d3-Rxe1 are too powerful. White played one more move and then resigned.} 
44. g5 {The finish could have been:} 
44. Rxe1+
45. Kxe1
45. Kxd3 {A very powerful game by Magnus and a good example of how Alekhine can sometimes work very well even against the best players in the world - although it has to be said it was definitely not Topalov's best day.} 
