 {So far in this chapter, we have seen quite a few games where the Black side of the Alekhine defence was handled by very competent players. Before we depart, I would like to provide you with the other side of the medal and show a couple of games featuring the Alekhine defence at the club level. In order to do so, to show that I have some 'skin in the game' and to demonstrate that the Alekhine can sometimes work even in the hands of a not-so-competent player I will be showing you two of my own classical games in this opening.Even though I have played quite a few tournament games with the Alekhine in my career, for this course I thought it would be most appropriate to select the very first and the very last of them. This will not only allow me to state that I have been playing the opening every now and then for more than 10 years (Oh how the time flies), but also allow you to laugh a bit at my expense and at the level of chess I displayed back in my 'youth'.Thus, we will be starting with the game I played in the very first round of the very first classical tournament I ever played - Velika Gorica Open 2012. My opponent was Kristijan Lovreković and was rated somewhere around 2000.} 1. e4
1. Nf6 {I don't even remember how exactly I decided to start playing this opening. I believe I stumbled on the book Play the Alekhine by Valentin Bogdanov somewhere, read it briefly and just decided to roll with it. Back in the pre-Chessable days, things were much simpler :).} 
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. c4
4. Nb6
5. exd6
5. cxd6
6. Nc3
6. Nc6 {Of course, back in the day my knowledge of theory was very minimal. Needless to say, this move is premature - Black should go for the fianchetto of the bishop first.6...g6Is the move recommended in the course, in case you forgot!} 
7. Be3 {7.d5Is already significantly better for White. Oh well...} 
7. g6
8. Nf3 {8.d5Is again quite unpleasant for Black.} 
8. Bg7
9. d5 {This move is still quite unpleasant to face. The consequence of my silly 6th move.} 
9. Ne5 {9...Bxc3+This move, ruining the structure, is worth considering. But I would be hesitant to play like this even in 2023, let alone back in 2012.} 
10. Nxe5
10. Bxe5
11. Bd4 {A good move by my opponent, forcing me to take a very unpleasant decision.} 
11. Nd7 {Probably the best move in the position, trying to keep the structure intact and some control over the dark squares. The alternatives are way worse.} 
