13. Qxd4
13. Nf6
14. Ne4 {But this is a bad move, violating several opening principles. White is not developed enough to be able to go for some direct attack.14.Bd3Any natural developing move such as this one, would have retained a clear advantage for White.} 
14. Qa5+ {A good reaction, exploiting the drawback of White's last move at once!14...Bf5I also contemplated during the game, concluding that after15.Nxf6+exf6I also have no reasons to complain - which is perfectly true.} 
15. Kd1 {But this is way too much. One can sense that my opponent underestimated me significantly. It also says something about the level of an average 2000 player in Croatia.15.Nc3It was objectively best to admit the mistake and go back with the knight.} 
15. Bg4+ {A natural and obvious move - but perhaps not necessary?15...O-OProbably it was better to castle first and think later, since White can't really go for the f6 pawn.16.Nxf6+exf617.Qxf6Bf5White's king is too weak and Black is completely winning, despite the missing pawn.} 
16. Be2
16. Bxe2+
17. Kxe2 {During the game, I misjudged that the king will not be so unsafe on e2, strangely enough. Not so surprising for my first-ever tournament game.} 
17. O-O {Still, this is a good move as I really don't care about my pawn on f6.} 
18. Nxf6+ {It was probably better not to take this and open the e-file, but alas..} 
18. exf6
19. Rhe1 {Wisely trying to get the king to safety. Of course, taking the pawn would lose at once to19.Qxf6Rfe8+} 
19. Rfe8+ {This move is natural, but maybe not the strongest.19...Rac8Is quite interesting, with the idea of playing for b5.20.Kf2b5!?19...Kg7Defending the f6 pawn and keeping the flexibility of the rooks is also interesting. Game might continue20.Kf2b5} 
20. Kf2
20. h5 {This was a bit cheeky and unnecessary. One can sense the excitement of young Vjeko.20...Rxe121.Rxe1Qxa2Was possible but after22.Re7White has definite compensation for the pawn.20...b5!?was once again quite interesting.} 
21. a3 {21.Qxf6It was tempted with this pawn grab, when after21...Qc5+22.Kg3Qxc4I thought I am much better. This is not only untrue, but it is also quite naive to expect your opponent to fall into your wishes.} 
21. Kg7 {Finally defending the f6 pawn.} 
22. b4 {This whole a3-b4 was probably not a necessary weakening.} 
22. Qa4
23. Qc3
23. Qd7 {Not a bad move, trying to improve the queen. Black should be somewhat better as White has meany weaknesses, but White should be able to hold the balance with best play.} 
24. Rxe8
24. Rxe8
25. Re1
25. Rxe1 {Typical mistake - exchanging when you have the opportunity.25...Rc8Of course, Black should keep the rooks on the board to make the defensive task more difficult.} 
26. Qxe1
26. Qf5 {At first glance, it seems as if this queen endgame is much better for Black, but actually, it is just dead equal.} 
27. Qc1 {Why go to the passive c1 square? He was maybe hoping to get in some c5 advance but it shouldn't really work.27.Qd2Seems more reasonable to me.} 
27. Qd3
28. h3
28. h4
29. Kg1
29. f5 {I don't know why I decided to make this move. Lack of patience still haunts me to this day. Literally, any other improving move would have been significantly better.} 
30. Kh1
30. f6 {This move weakens the queen even further, although it is already hard to talk about even practical advantage for Black at this point. Now the endgame is just dead even.} 
31. a4
31. b6
32. a5
32. Qd4 {32...bxa5Not even allowing33.c5} 
33. axb6
33. axb6
34. Kh2
34. Kh6
35. Kh1
35. Kg7
36. Qf1
36. Qd2
37. b5 {37.c5I think I wanted to tempt my opponent to push c5 - which is actually also sufficient to maintain the balance e.g.37...dxc538.bxc5bxc539.Qa1Once again - Black's king is way too weak.} 
37. Qe3
38. Qg1 {Now this simply transposes into a drawn pawn endgame.} 
38. Qxg1+
39. Kxg1
