 {After seeing my first game in the Alekhine Defence, let's fast forward 10+ years in the future and check my most recent one. It was played in the 7th round of the Groningen Open tournament. I faced a young Dutch FM who has been enjoying quite a reasonable tournament(he was winning in some game against the top seed and a GM and was, in general, playing quite well). In my preparation, I noticed he is very well prepared against a number of mainstream openings, but I estimated that he might not be as booked up against the Alekhine. Since I already started working on the course back in December 2022, I thought I might just roll with it and see what happens.} 1. e4
1. Nf6 {Since I played all kinds of openings prior in the tournament, I figured his prep would be difficult anyway.} 
2. Nc3 {And already here, when he decided to avoid the mainlines, I was kinda happy as I knew that the Four Pawns Attack was not about to happen.} 
2. d5
3. e5
3. Nfd7 {In Bortnyk's footsteps!} 
4. d4
4. c5
5. Nxd5 {A big surprise. If you remember the theoretical chapter, this is just bad for White.} 
5. cxd4
6. e6 {But this move, which I didn't quite check before the game in any depth, came as a surprise here and here I was on my own.6.Qxd4Nb6Is the trick worth remembering, as I recently had it in one of my blitz games online and couldn't remember it. White loses a piece by force, e.g. afterA)7.c4e6B) Or7.Bb5+Nc6} 
6. Qa5+ {I thought it is quite clever and also practical to simply give this check and take the knight on d5.6...fxe67.Nf4Nf6Seemed very messy during the game. I also thought my opponent would enjoy a more tactical position. And indeed, the computer claims White is better after the precise8.Bb5+Nc69.Qe2Furthermore, Black's position is very difficult to play with such an ugly pawn structure.} 
7. c3
7. Qxd5 {Quite practical. I realized I would get a reasonable position against the isolani and just decided to roll with it.7...fxe68.Qh5+Kd89.Nf4also seemed to messy for my taste. And the text move is better indeed.} 
8. exd7+
8. Bxd7 {And just like that, I am better as Black against a 2300 FM on move 8. This is the reason why I think it is worth having the Alekhine as a surprise weapon in your repertoire.} 
9. cxd4 {But now I suddenly started thinking as I wasn't 100% sure what is the best way to proceed.9.Qxd4Qxd410.cxd4Nc6I thought would lead to an easier play for me without the queens on the board - and it is indeed so. The side with the isolated pawn, in principle, doesn't want to exchange too many pieces - especially not the queens.} 
9. Nc6 {This natural developing move seemed quite sensible to me.9...e6I didn't want to lock my bishop, but he computer thinks this is not at all so bad.9...e5I contemplated for some time, but I wasn't 100% sure about the repercussions.10.dxe5Qe4+This seemed not 100% necessary to me, although the engine does point out it might be the strongest, giving the lines such as11.Be211.Be3Bb4+-+Qxg212.Bf3Qg613.Bxb7Bc614.Bxc6+Nxc6Needless to say, I didn't see any of it during the game.} 
10. Nf3
10. Bg4 {I wanted this bishop out of the pawn chain, but maybe it wasn't too good. I guess it just lead to a loss of tempo and my bishop turned out to be prone to some attacks here in the end.10...g6Was an alternative scheme of development, but I wanted to go for the e6-Bd6 setup.11.Be2Bg712.O-OO-O13.Be3I thought later I would get Rc1-Bc4-d5, although I understood this was maybe a better piece composition. The computer gives a solid plus for Black here with natural moves such as Rfd8, Rac8, Be6 incoming.10...Bf5!?Placing the bishop on a less exposed square to e6-Ne5 stuff, was arguably better.} 
11. Be2
11. e6 {Still, not that what I did was too wrong and I still have a fairly healthy position. But I missed the opportunity to squeeze the maximum out of my position.} 
12. O-O
12. Be7 {A natural developing move.12...Bd6was the other move I considered, but didn't like the fact it is taking squares away from the queen. And indeed, it does feel a little clumsy and it is not clear what the bishop is doing here.} 
13. Be3
13. O-O
14. h3
14. Bh5 {I thought it is logical to preserve the pin, but this is maybe superficial as the bishop was quite vulnerable in many variations.14...Bf5Only later did I regret that I didn't play this (Be4 is on cards). Stockfish confirms this is indeed the better move and thinks I have lost quite some advantage after my move in the game.} 
15. a3 {Not sure if this is necessary, but my opponent wanted to take the b4 square under control just in case.15.Ne5I expected, when after15...Bxe216.Nxc6Qxc617.Qxe2I thought I have a very pleasant endgame. The computer doesn't share that enthusiasm and gives only a small plus to Black. Still, in practice, once can squeeze this for million of moves.} 
15. Rfd8
16. Rc1
16. Rac8 {This was a kind of prophylaxis against Ne5. For example, after a move such as16...a6I was worried about the move17.Ne5Bxe218.Nxc6And here I got scared of some Nxe7 tricks. However, there is a dual solution to this.A) First of all,18...Qxc6is pretty much playable. I forgot about this resource and that his queen would also be hanging.A1)19.Rxc6Is bad due toBxd120.Rc7Bd6A2)19.Qxe2Qd7Leads to that stable structure with the isolated pawn, which is nevertheless quite dry. I vastly overestimated the importance of the isolated pawn in this position.B) Secondly,18...bxc6is not at all so bad for Black, although it does ruin the structure.} 
17. Qa4
17. a6 {A) I was a bit struggling to find a move here, so I just moved a pawn that can potentially be exposed. I didn't want to allow the rook to c5 after something like17...Bf618.Rc5B)17...Qd618.Qb5Was also bothering me as I lose the pawn - again that exposed bishop on h5! This was the move I was trying to prevent!C) I also considered17...Qa5but after18.Qxa5Nxa519.Rxc8Rxc8I saw the thematic advance of the d-pawn20.d5I thought this is not ideal for me. And indeed, after20...exd521.Bxa7Black is on the 'worse side of equality'.} 
18. Rfd1
18. Qd6 {Again I was struggling to find moves here. I decided to move the queen to sidestep any Rc5. It is hard to say what else to do.} 
19. Rc5 {This is perhaps a bit too simplistic. I was trying to calculate, but couldn't figure out the consequences of19.d5I didn't consider at all. The idea is19...exd520.Qb3b5I thought I would be quite fine here, but the computer disagrees and says that White has compensation. Still, I feel this is very difficult for a human to evaluate as nothing obvious is apparent.21.Bb6And White has compensation?21...Rd722.Be3Very hard idea for humans to see, in my opinion.19.Qb3Preparing d5, is also possible - and leading to relatively similar lines.} 
19. Bg6 {Preparing to move the bishop to e4.19...Bxf320.Bxf3Felt - and is - very wrong. No reason to give up the bishop.} 
20. Rdc1 {Creating the threat of Bxa6. Or so I thought.20.Ne5Be4Was my plan - and this is indeed the best move according to the engine. The position is fairly equal, according to the engine. But at least I get the blockade on the d5 square and can take it from there.I was contemplating20.d5and it bothered me quite a bit. After20...exd521.Rcxd5A) And here I only considered.21...Qb8when Black is indeed on the back foot suddenly.22.Bf4Qa823.Rxd8+Rxd824.Rxd8+Bxd825.Nd4B) Alas, I forgot I could simply play21...Qxd5As pointed out after the game by my opponent. After22.Rxd5Rxd5The two rooks should be superior to the queen.} 
20. Qb8 {Attacking the rook and avoiding theBxa6threat was so sensible, that I barely considered anything else.20...Bf8Is the move mentioned by the compy, as after21.Bxa6I always have21...Ra8} 
21. R5c3
21. Be4 {Executing the desired bishop maneuver after all.} 
22. Ne5 {A good move, simplifying the position significantly. Due to the fact I had the advantage out of the opening, I wanted to try and play for the win, but I couldn't find a way here.} 
22. Nxe5 {This leads to massive simplification and an equal position. One possibility to keep more life in the position was the natural retreating move22...Bd5I didn't consider this properly. I thought this fails to Bxa6, but it actually keeps the game going as23.Bxa6??Nxe524.dxe5bxa6Just wins for Black. A simple calculation is sometimes the best calculation.} 
23. Rxc8 {Of course, not23.dxe5Rxc324.Rxc3Qxe5-+} 
23. Rxc8
24. Rxc8+
24. Qxc8
25. dxe5
25. Qc6 {Maybe this is a bit too non-combative. Here I offered a draw, which is a bit of a pity, as I feel there was some play left in the position if I didn't exchange queens. But I mentally accepted I can't win this position - which is a very bad mentality.It is not a coincidence my play from this point onward is quite weak and that I experienced serious psychological difficulties in the resulting endgame.} 
26. Qxc6
26. Bxc6
27. f4
27. f5 {Here I started playing carelessly. This move is still probably fine, but not necessary, as it gives him some potential ideas. Bringing the king is probably simpler.} 
28. Kf2
28. Bd5
29. Bf1
29. Kf7
30. Ke1
30. Ke8 {30...h5!?Is probably simplest. I didn't quite anticipate my opponent going for g4.31.g3b5=} 
31. g4
31. g6 {31...fxg4I somehow didn't want to isolate my e6 pawn, but compy says it is fine, e.g.32.hxg4Bf333.Bh3g634.g5Kd7=} 
32. g5 {Here I started getting a bit worried due to h4-h5-h6-Bh5 ideas.} 
32. Kd7 {I wasn't 100% sure where my king belongs, but I figured it might be sensible to go to the queenside. I still didn't fully appreciate the dangers hiding in this position.} 
33. Be2
33. Kc6 {33...Bg234.h4Bh3During the game, I contemplated going to h3, but it felt weird to sideline my bishop or place it on g4 for no good reason.} 
34. h4
34. b5 {Here I was not really calculating lines, but kinda 'seeing' through them and playing on feeling. Fortunately, the position is very drawn, but my opponent could have set me with more complicated problems. Here my plan was to go a5-a4 and then repeat with Bc4-Bb3.} 
35. h5 {We spent a lot of time analyzing after the game. White wants some combination of h5-h6-Bh5 and Bc5. Black is in time, tho, after, say35.b4We considered after the game. In general, I felt very uncomfortable in this endgame all of a sudden, but maybe there was no BIG reason for that.35...Bc436.Bd1a537.bxa5Bxa3=There is more than enough counterplay on the queenside to lose on the kingside.} 
35. a5 {Continuing with the plan, but I remember I was sweating very much.} 
36. Kf2 {After this, I was very relieved as I saw I can now get my desired setup. I was more worried about36.h6!?with the idea of Bh5 and so on. The engine confirms this is the best try, forcing me to find a very precise defence. I will reproduce the analysis with some of my thoughts below:A)36...a4??37.Bd2Bc438.Bf3+Bd539.Bh5+-Bf840.Bxg6hxg641.Bb4+-B)36...b4Is another method - but it really needs to be calculated very well.37.axb4axb438.Kd2Bf839.Ba7Kb740.Bf2Kc641.Kc2Be742.Bh5Bf8=C)36...Bf837.Bd2Kb6Black does hold in all these lines, but it is not easy, as can be seen. I shouldn't have even found myself in this situation, but I guess I will never learn.} 
36. a4 {Now that I have this construction with Bc4-Bb3, I was much less worried.} 
37. hxg6 {37.h6Bc438.Bh5Bf8=I calculated during the game and I saw all is clear, e.g.39.Bxg6hxg640.h7Bg741.Bd2Kd742.Bb4Ke8Amazing how tricky this 'simple' endgame can be.} 
37. hxg6
38. Bd2
38. Bc4
39. Bd1
39. Bb3
40. Be2
40. Bc4 {And here we agreed to a draw and I breathed a sigh of relief, as I was really very uncomfortable in this endgame. Still, in general, I have happy memories of this game as I was quite proud of my clever prep and the decision to employ the Alekhine.Of course, I don't expect it to work like a charm in every single game, but the very fact that it can work like a charm against FM opposition is more than enough to convince me to keep trying it out every now and then in the future.I hope that this course will inspire you to do the same!} 
